const CYSA_QUESTIONS = [{"id":"q1","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Segmentation)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A ransomware incident spread from a user VLAN to server subnets using SMB and RDP. Leadership wants to reduce blast radius without breaking business workflows. Which control is MOST effective?","options":[{"text":"Create tightly scoped inter-subnet policy boundaries and force administrative access through brokered management paths.","correct":true,"why":"Segmentation + least-privilege network paths and controlled admin access (jump hosts) significantly limits lateral movement."},{"text":"Harden the server tier locally while leaving most routed paths between user and server networks unchanged.","correct":false,"why":"Server hardening alone doesn't address the open routed paths between user and server networks that let SMB/RDP lateral movement continue."},{"text":"Protect the protocols themselves but keep ordinary workstation reachability into sensitive segments available.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting the protocols without removing broad workstation-to-server reachability still leaves an open path for lateral movement."},{"text":"Give administrators safer workstations yet preserve broad east-west trust relationships inside production.","correct":false,"why":"Improving admin endpoints doesn't reduce the broad east-west trust between subnets that allowed the ransomware to spread."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q2","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Zero Trust)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A company is adopting a zero trust model. Which statement BEST represents the zero trust approach to network access?","options":[{"text":"Validate identity, device health, and request context each time before granting narrowly scoped application access.","correct":true,"why":"Zero trust emphasizes continuous verification, least privilege, and micro-segmentation rather than implicit trust based on location."},{"text":"Require strong login at session start and then rely on role membership for broad internal reachability.","correct":false,"why":"This grants broad reachability after a single login rather than continuously verifying each request, which is the implicit trust zero trust is meant to eliminate."},{"text":"Place apps behind policy gates but continue trusting an approved endpoint until its session naturally expires.","correct":false,"why":"Trusting an already-approved endpoint until its session expires still allows implicit trust between checks, rather than continuous verification."},{"text":"Recheck posture periodically while treating the authenticated session as trusted between evaluations.","correct":false,"why":"Treating the session as trusted between periodic rechecks still allows a window of implicit trust, unlike true continuous per-request verification."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q3","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Firewall Policy)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A firewall has a broad “allow any to web 443” rule above a narrow deny for a malicious IP range. Traffic from the bad range is still allowed. Why?","options":[{"text":"The general permit is evaluated first, so the later exception never gets a chance to match that traffic.","correct":true,"why":"First-match processing can cause shadowing."},{"text":"The device defers address checks until after certificate inspection, which causes the deny list to be skipped.","correct":false,"why":"Firewalls evaluate rules in order rather than deferring address checks until after certificate inspection; the issue here is rule order, not inspection sequencing."},{"text":"The session becomes stateful before address evaluation, so subsequent packets ignore the specific restriction.","correct":false,"why":"Statefulness tracks established sessions but doesn't explain why the broad permit rule matches before the narrower deny; the cause is rule ordering, not statefulness."},{"text":"Translation changes the packet identity so rule precedence no longer matters for that connection.","correct":false,"why":"NAT/translation doesn't change how rules are evaluated in sequence; the broad allow rule still matches first regardless of address translation."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q4","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (NAT Attribution)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A suspicious public connection is identified, but the company uses PAT for outbound traffic. What log data is MOST needed to map the event to the internal host?","options":[{"text":"Time-correlated port translation records that tie the inside socket to the observed public socket.","correct":true,"why":"PAT requires translation tuples (inside/outside IP:port) with time to identify which internal host owned a public session."},{"text":"Web gateway activity showing the requested destination and browser fingerprint for outbound sessions.","correct":false,"why":"Proxy/web gateway logs show destination and browser details but don't provide the translation tuple needed to map a public-facing PAT session back to the specific internal host."},{"text":"Address assignment history indicating which workstation held the private address during that period.","correct":false,"why":"DHCP lease history shows which host had a given private address, but without the PAT translation record it can't confirm which internal host generated the specific public-facing session."},{"text":"Sign-in events mapping users to endpoints during the window when the connection was observed.","correct":false,"why":"Authentication logs tie users to endpoints but don't provide the port translation data needed to attribute a specific outbound PAT session to a host."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q5","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Ransomware Behavior)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"An endpoint begins rapidly encrypting files and deleting shadow copies while attempting to contact multiple external IPs. What is the BEST immediate containment action?","options":[{"text":"Quarantine the endpoint immediately through endpoint controls so execution stops while artifacts remain available.","correct":true,"why":"Contain quickly (EDR isolation) to stop spread while preserving artifacts for scoping and root-cause analysis."},{"text":"Block common lateral channels first and allow the affected system to remain reachable during triage.","correct":false,"why":"Leaving the actively encrypting host reachable allows continued spread and destruction of evidence rather than immediately stopping the ongoing damage."},{"text":"Shut the machine off at once and begin restoration before collecting any short-lived runtime evidence.","correct":false,"why":"Powering off immediately destroys volatile memory and running-process evidence needed for scoping and root-cause analysis, unlike isolating the host while it stays powered on."},{"text":"Reset the user account and remove the suspected message source before addressing the active host behavior.","correct":false,"why":"Resetting credentials and removing the email doesn't stop the ransomware actively encrypting files right now on the endpoint."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q6","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Command-and-Control Beaconing)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"Network telemetry shows periodic HTTPS connections every 60 seconds to a rare domain with small outbound bytes and larger inbound bytes. What is the MOST likely explanation?","options":[{"text":"Periodic low-volume check-ins to a rare destination are most consistent with remote tasking traffic.","correct":true,"why":"Regular periodic connections with consistent sizes often indicate beaconing."},{"text":"A newly installed management client performing expected cloud heartbeats from a known enterprise process.","correct":false,"why":"A known, approved management client would be an identifiable, whitelisted process, not an unexplained connection to a rare, unfamiliar domain."},{"text":"A consumer synchronization service polling for notifications from a widely used content platform.","correct":false,"why":"Polling to a widely used content platform would go to a well-known, common domain, not a rare domain seen here."},{"text":"A software update component retrieving routine manifests from established vendor infrastructure.","correct":false,"why":"Routine vendor update traffic goes to established, known vendor domains, not an unfamiliar rare domain."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q7","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (IDS Placement)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"An IDS sensor only monitors the internet edge. Lateral movement between internal subnets is suspected but not detected. What change MOST improves detection?","options":[{"text":"Instrument internal transit points so east-west flows between sensitive segments are actually visible.","correct":true,"why":"Edge-only monitoring misses internal movement."},{"text":"Tune the perimeter signatures more aggressively while continuing to observe only north-south traffic.","correct":false,"why":"Tuning perimeter signatures doesn't add visibility into internal east-west traffic, which is where the undetected lateral movement is occurring."},{"text":"Rely on mirrored core links alone without designing coverage around the lateral paths of interest.","correct":false,"why":"Mirroring core links without deliberately covering the specific internal transit points leaves the lateral movement paths unmonitored."},{"text":"Shift the problem almost entirely to host logs even though the movement is occurring across network segments.","correct":false,"why":"Relying solely on host logs ignores the value of network-level visibility specifically needed to see traffic crossing internal segments."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q8","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Living off the Land)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"An alert shows powershell.exe spawning rundll32.exe with a long base64 command line. Why is this pattern concerning?","options":[{"text":"An encoded script launching a dual-use binary strongly suggests stealthy native-tool abuse requiring triage.","correct":true,"why":"PowerShell + encoded commands + LOLBins like rundll32 are common in malware tradecraft and warrant correlation and triage."},{"text":"A signed automation workflow invoking an approved library through standard administrative procedures.","correct":false,"why":"A legitimate signed administrative workflow wouldn't typically involve an encoded base64 command line, which is a hallmark of obfuscated malicious activity."},{"text":"A packaging routine registering components during a normal application deployment sequence.","correct":false,"why":"Normal application deployment doesn't typically chain PowerShell into rundll32 with an encoded command line, which is characteristic of evasive execution."},{"text":"A maintenance script handing compressed configuration data to a helper module during remote support.","correct":false,"why":"Routine remote support scripts don't typically use encoded PowerShell to launch a dual-use binary like rundll32, a pattern associated with malicious tradecraft."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (VPN vs ZTNA)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A company wants to reduce broad network access granted by VPN and move toward per-app access with continuous checks. Which solution BEST fits?","options":[{"text":"Move users behind an identity-aware broker that exposes only approved applications after ongoing posture checks.","correct":true,"why":"ZTNA is designed for per-app access and continuous verification, avoiding the “network-level trust” of traditional VPNs."},{"text":"Keep tunnel-based connectivity but reduce reachable subnets through narrower routing and access lists.","correct":false,"why":"This still grants broad network-level tunnel access rather than per-application access with continuous posture checks, which is what ZTNA specifically provides."},{"text":"Use an always-on tunnel with repeated authentication prompts while preserving routed internal connectivity.","correct":false,"why":"Repeated prompts over an always-on tunnel still preserves broad routed network access, unlike ZTNA's per-app, continuously verified model."},{"text":"Publish only selected front-end ranges through the tunnel rather than exposing the entire enterprise address space.","correct":false,"why":"This narrows the exposed network range but still relies on network-level tunnel access rather than the per-application, continuously verified access ZTNA provides."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q10","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Trojan vs Worm)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A malicious program disguises itself as legitimate software and requires a user to run it, then installs a backdoor. What malware type BEST matches?","options":[{"text":"Trojan horse delivering secondary access after the victim launches what appears to be a normal program.","correct":true,"why":"Trojans rely on deception and user execution; worms are self-propagating."},{"text":"Worm that automatically propagates between systems through reachable services without depending on user launch.","correct":false,"why":"A worm self-propagates without user action, unlike this scenario which specifically requires the victim to run the disguised program."},{"text":"Dropper whose main role is to unpack or install another stage rather than masquerade as something benign.","correct":false,"why":"A dropper's defining trait is installing a secondary stage, not specifically disguising itself as legitimate software to trick a user into launching it."},{"text":"Backdoor whose defining trait is covert remote access rather than the deceptive delivery method.","correct":false,"why":"A backdoor describes the resulting remote access capability, not the deceptive delivery method of disguising itself as legitimate software, which is the defining trait described here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q11","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (DDoS Mitigation)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A public web service is hit with a volumetric DDoS attack saturating bandwidth. Which mitigation is MOST effective at scale?","options":[{"text":"Offload the flood to upstream scrubbing or distribution providers that can absorb volume before your circuit fills.","correct":true,"why":"Volumetric DDoS requires upstream mitigation (scrubbing/CDN/ISP) since local firewalls cannot handle saturated links."},{"text":"Tighten protections on the local web tier so the servers can better withstand request bursts at the host level.","correct":false,"why":"Host-level hardening doesn't address a volumetric attack that saturates the network circuit itself before traffic ever reaches the servers."},{"text":"Scale out the application stack and cache layers so internal capacity grows with the inbound flood size.","correct":false,"why":"Adding application capacity doesn't help when the upstream circuit itself is saturated with volumetric traffic before it reaches the application tier."},{"text":"Filter apparent source regions and obvious signatures at the border while the circuit remains saturated.","correct":false,"why":"Border filtering still requires traffic to reach the local circuit first, which remains saturated in a true volumetric attack; the flood must be absorbed upstream instead."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q12","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Fileless / Memory-Resident)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"EDR shows suspicious PowerShell activity, but no malicious files are found on disk. The behavior persists across reboots via scheduled tasks. What is the BEST description?","options":[{"text":"Memory-resident abuse of native tooling with task-based persistence and minimal traditional file artifacts.","correct":true,"why":"Fileless activity can avoid disk artifacts."},{"text":"Ordinary script-based persistence that still depends primarily on dropped executables stored on disk.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario specifically describes no malicious files found on disk, which rules out persistence primarily dependent on dropped executables."},{"text":"Early-boot compromise that alters startup components before the operating system and services initialize.","correct":false,"why":"Scheduled-task persistence runs after the OS has booted, not before it initializes like an early-boot/bootkit compromise."},{"text":"A pure credential theft case driven mainly by stolen logon scripts rather than resident execution logic.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario describes persistent PowerShell execution via scheduled tasks, not primarily stolen logon scripts."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q13","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Secure Protocols)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A legacy application uses Telnet and FTP for administration and file transfers. Security wants to reduce credential exposure. What is the BEST change?","options":[{"text":"Use encrypted administrative and transfer channels with modern authentication instead of cleartext management services.","correct":true,"why":"SSH and SFTP/FTPS provide encrypted channels, preventing cleartext credential exposure typical of Telnet/FTP."},{"text":"Keep the legacy protocols but wrap them with network isolation so credentials are only exposed on trusted paths.","correct":false,"why":"Isolating the network path still transmits credentials in cleartext over that path; it doesn't eliminate the underlying protocol weakness."},{"text":"Replace the transfer mechanism only, leaving remote administration over the original plaintext service unchanged.","correct":false,"why":"Leaving Telnet for administration still exposes credentials in cleartext, so only fixing the file-transfer side doesn't fully solve the exposure."},{"text":"Add stronger passwords to the existing services while continuing to send secrets over observable sessions.","correct":false,"why":"Stronger passwords are still transmitted in cleartext over Telnet/FTP, so this doesn't address the underlying credential exposure risk."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q14","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Botnet Indicators)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"Multiple endpoints begin making outbound connections to many random IPs on uncommon ports, and the patterns are similar across hosts. What is the MOST likely concern?","options":[{"text":"Coordinated external tasking across many hosts, likely from centrally controlled malicious infrastructure.","correct":true,"why":"Coordinated similar outbound patterns across many hosts can indicate botnet C2 or scanning behavior."},{"text":"Normal peer-to-peer collaboration traffic generated by a newly approved communications platform.","correct":false,"why":"Approved collaboration platforms wouldn't typically produce similar random-IP, uncommon-port connection patterns across many unrelated hosts simultaneously."},{"text":"Network discovery by an internal inventory tool contacting a wide range of addresses on uncommon ports.","correct":false,"why":"An internal inventory tool would typically scan internal ranges from a central system, not appear as similar outbound patterns to many random external IPs from many separate hosts."},{"text":"Misconfigured software updates causing many endpoints to seek content from rotating third-party mirrors.","correct":false,"why":"Update mirrors are typically known vendor infrastructure, not random external IPs on uncommon ports as described here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q15","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (802.1X / NAC)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"An organization wants to prevent unknown devices from connecting to internal wired networks and to apply dynamic VLAN placement. Which control BEST fits?","options":[{"text":"Require identity-driven admission control at the edge and assign access dynamically based on policy results.","correct":true,"why":"802.1X with RADIUS is standard for port-based access control and dynamic VLAN assignment based on identity/posture."},{"text":"Lock access ports to remembered hardware addresses and manually place compliant devices into VLANs.","correct":false,"why":"Static MAC-based port locking and manual VLAN placement don't provide the identity-driven, dynamic policy-based VLAN assignment the requirement calls for."},{"text":"Enforce stronger switch port policies while relying on static segment assignment for authorized endpoints.","correct":false,"why":"Static segment assignment doesn't provide the dynamic, identity-based VLAN placement that 802.1X with RADIUS delivers."},{"text":"Use DHCP reservations and directory groups to decide where devices should live after they already connect.","correct":false,"why":"This determines placement only after a device has already connected, rather than enforcing identity-based admission control at the point of connection."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q16","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Rootkit Risk)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A compromised host shows suspicious kernel-level drivers and security tools fail to enumerate certain processes. What is the MOST likely malware category?","options":[{"text":"Rootkit using privileged stealth mechanisms to hide activity from ordinary operating system and security views.","correct":true,"why":"Rootkits often operate at kernel level and hide artifacts, interfering with normal enumeration and security tools."},{"text":"Boot sector malware focused on pre-OS startup compromise rather than runtime concealment of processes.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario describes hidden kernel-level processes at runtime, not a boot-sector compromise occurring before the OS starts."},{"text":"Spyware centered on user data capture without needing deep kernel manipulation to remain hidden.","correct":false,"why":"Spyware focuses on data capture and doesn't typically require kernel-level drivers to hide processes from security tool enumeration."},{"text":"Ransomware that disrupts availability but does not primarily depend on invisible kernel-level presence.","correct":false,"why":"Ransomware's defining trait is encrypting data for extortion, not hiding processes via kernel-level drivers as described here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q17","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (WAF vs IDS)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A web application is targeted by injection attempts. The security team wants a control that can enforce HTTP-level rules and block malicious requests. What is the BEST fit?","options":[{"text":"Deploy an inline control that understands web requests well enough to enforce and block application-layer abuse.","correct":true,"why":"A WAF is designed to inspect HTTP/S requests and block application-layer attacks like injection."},{"text":"Place a passive detector near the web tier so suspicious patterns are alerted on but not actively stopped.","correct":false,"why":"A passive detector only alerts on suspicious traffic; it doesn't actively block malicious requests the way an inline WAF does."},{"text":"Use a network gateway that filters hosts and ports even though the logic does not parse application semantics deeply.","correct":false,"why":"A network-layer gateway filtering by host/port can't parse HTTP-level application content needed to detect and block injection attempts."},{"text":"Rely on endpoint protection at the server so dangerous input is handled after it already reaches the application.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint protection reacts after malicious input reaches the application, rather than enforcing HTTP-level rules before it gets there."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q18","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Phishing Delivery)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"Users report an email urging them to “view invoice” with a macro-enabled document attachment. What is the BEST preventive control combination?","options":[{"text":"Layer message filtering, detonation, macro hardening, and user skepticism to reduce initial execution risk.","correct":true,"why":"Layered controls: secure email gateway, sandboxing, macro hardening, and training reduce phishing-to-malware execution."},{"text":"Depend mainly on awareness training and warning banners while allowing active content to run when requested.","correct":false,"why":"Relying mainly on training while still allowing macros to run leaves a significant technical gap, unlike layered filtering, sandboxing, and macro hardening together."},{"text":"Block executable attachments but permit office documents with embedded code from external senders.","correct":false,"why":"Allowing macro-enabled documents from external senders still leaves the primary attack vector in this scenario open."},{"text":"Quarantine suspicious mail after delivery based on endpoint alerts rather than stopping it earlier in the chain.","correct":false,"why":"Acting only after delivery misses the opportunity to stop the malicious attachment earlier at the email gateway or sandboxing stage."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q19","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (DMZ)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A company hosts a public web server and wants to reduce the risk of attackers pivoting to internal networks if it is compromised. Which architecture BEST supports this?","options":[{"text":"Expose the public-facing workload from an isolated buffer zone with tightly mediated paths inward.","correct":true,"why":"A DMZ isolates exposed services and limits pivot paths into internal networks through strict firewall segmentation."},{"text":"Keep the workload on the internal network and depend on host controls to stop pivoting after compromise.","correct":false,"why":"Placing the public server directly on the internal network removes the network-level isolation that limits pivoting if the host is compromised."},{"text":"Place the server behind the same trust boundary as application databases to simplify east-west communication.","correct":false,"why":"Sharing a trust boundary with sensitive databases increases pivot risk rather than isolating the exposed server from internal assets."},{"text":"Provide direct routed reachability to selected internal segments so support teams can administer it more easily.","correct":false,"why":"Direct routed reachability into internal segments creates exactly the pivot path this design is meant to prevent."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q20","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (IOC vs Behavior)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A SOC blocks known malicious hashes, but attackers recompile malware frequently and bypass hash blocks. What detection approach BEST increases resilience?","options":[{"text":"Prioritize execution patterns, persistence methods, and communication behaviors over brittle static fingerprints.","correct":true,"why":"Behavior/TTP-based detections are harder to evade than static IOCs like hashes, which are brittle against polymorphism."},{"text":"Lean mostly on user and entity baselining to catch outliers without anchoring detections to attacker tradecraft.","correct":false,"why":"UEBA baselining alone doesn't specifically target the execution and communication behaviors (TTPs) that remain consistent even when malware is recompiled."},{"text":"Expand static blocks continuously so repacked samples and fresh infrastructure are covered as they appear.","correct":false,"why":"Continuously expanding static hash/IOC blocks is exactly the brittle, easily evaded approach the scenario describes as failing."},{"text":"Focus on reputation and rare destinations, which helps some cases but misses local execution and persistence signals.","correct":false,"why":"Reputation-based detection alone misses the local execution and persistence behaviors that behavior/TTP-based detection specifically targets."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q21","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (TLS Inspection Tradeoffs)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"Security wants to inspect encrypted outbound traffic for malware, but legal/privacy teams are concerned. What is the BEST balanced approach?","options":[{"text":"Decrypt selectively under explicit governance, defined exceptions, and protected handling of revealed content.","correct":true,"why":"Selective inspection with governance, transparency, and strong key management balances security outcomes with privacy/regulatory needs."},{"text":"Inspect nearly everything centrally so security teams gain maximum visibility into outbound encrypted sessions.","correct":false,"why":"Decrypting nearly all traffic without defined exceptions or governance would raise exactly the privacy concerns the legal team is worried about."},{"text":"Avoid decryption entirely and depend on metadata-only analytics to stay clear of privacy concerns.","correct":false,"why":"Metadata-only analysis can't inspect encrypted payload content, leaving the security team unable to detect malware hidden in encrypted traffic."},{"text":"Apply category-based decryption broadly first and document exceptions later once issues are reported.","correct":false,"why":"Decrypting broadly before defining governance and exceptions skips the upfront privacy safeguards the legal team is asking for."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q22","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Lateral Movement Tools)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"EDR shows an endpoint running PsExec-like behavior to create a service on remote hosts and execute a binary. What is the MOST likely attacker goal?","options":[{"text":"Use one compromised foothold to execute remotely on peers and widen operational reach across the environment.","correct":true,"why":"Remote service creation/execution is a classic lateral movement technique to spread tooling or deploy malware."},{"text":"Establish long-term startup persistence on each targeted machine through newly installed background services.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario describes remote service creation and execution for movement, not establishing long-term startup persistence as the primary goal."},{"text":"Inventory remote systems and enumerate service states without intending to launch additional code.","correct":false,"why":"The described activity includes actually executing a binary on remote hosts, not merely enumerating services without launching code."},{"text":"Stage files centrally for later collection rather than using service creation for active expansion.","correct":false,"why":"Creating and executing services on remote hosts indicates active lateral spread, not passive file staging for later collection."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q23","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Port Security vs NAC)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A switch is configured with basic port security, but attackers still connect unauthorized devices by spoofing MAC addresses. What upgrade BEST mitigates this?","options":[{"text":"Authenticate endpoints with stronger machine identity at the edge instead of trusting a changeable address claim.","correct":true,"why":"MAC spoofing defeats MAC-based controls; 802.1X with certs/posture provides stronger identity and access enforcement."},{"text":"Tighten remembered-address enforcement and violation actions so spoofed hardware identities are rejected faster.","correct":false,"why":"Faster reaction to violations still relies on MAC addresses, which attackers can spoof; it doesn't provide the stronger identity verification needed."},{"text":"Improve segmentation and disable unused jacks while leaving device identity based on observed addresses.","correct":false,"why":"This limits reachable segments but still trusts spoofable MAC addresses for device identity, not resolving the underlying weakness."},{"text":"Rely on DHCP snooping and address inspection alone to infer whether the connected system is authorized.","correct":false,"why":"DHCP snooping and address inspection still infer identity from spoofable network attributes rather than strong machine identity."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q24","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Sandboxing Limits)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A suspicious file detonates cleanly in a sandbox, but later behaves maliciously on a real endpoint. Why might this happen?","options":[{"text":"The sample may wait for human-like conditions or detect analysis artifacts before revealing its real behavior.","correct":true,"why":"Evasion techniques can detect virtual environments, delay execution, or require user interaction, causing false negatives in sandboxes."},{"text":"The binary is harmless unless it receives a later update, so dynamic analysis is not useful during first detonation.","correct":false,"why":"This assumes the file is inherently benign rather than considering that it may be actively evading detection in the sandbox environment."},{"text":"Only command-line variations can unlock the payload, meaning environmental awareness is not part of the problem.","correct":false,"why":"This narrows the cause to command-line triggers only, ignoring that environment-detection evasion techniques are a well-known cause of this behavior."},{"text":"A clean detonation usually proves the file is benign, with later malicious activity pointing to a separate cause.","correct":false,"why":"A clean sandbox result doesn't prove benignity; evasive malware is specifically designed to behave differently once it detects it's no longer in an analysis environment."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q25","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Least Privilege Services)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A service account has domain admin rights “for convenience.” A malware infection steals the credentials and compromises domain controllers. What control MOST reduces impact?","options":[{"text":"Constrain service identities to only required actions and tightly limit where and how those credentials can be used.","correct":true,"why":"Over-privileged service accounts are high-risk."},{"text":"Rotate the secret frequently and store it safely even if the account continues holding broad administrative rights.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating the secret doesn't reduce the impact if the account is compromised, since it would still retain domain admin rights."},{"text":"Isolate directory infrastructure and monitor sign-ins while leaving the overpowered account design unchanged.","correct":false,"why":"Monitoring alone doesn't reduce what a compromised account can actually do, since it retains its excessive domain admin privileges."},{"text":"Reduce ordinary user privileges first because workstation accounts are usually the primary route to directory takeover.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario's root cause is the over-privileged service account itself, not ordinary user workstation accounts."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q26","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Keylogger Indicators)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A user reports random authentication failures. EDR shows a new unsigned DLL injected into browser processes and frequent outbound connections to a low-reputation domain. What is the MOST likely malware function?","options":[{"text":"The intrusion is likely harvesting browser-entered secrets and sending them to an external operator.","correct":true,"why":"Browser injection + outbound C2 is consistent with credential theft (keylogging/form grabbing) and account takeover attempts."},{"text":"The failures are most likely caused by users mistyping passwords during a temporary directory synchronization issue.","correct":false,"why":"A simple sync issue wouldn't explain the newly injected unsigned DLL and suspicious outbound traffic observed alongside the failures."},{"text":"The outbound traffic mainly indicates software telemetry, while the injected module is probably a browser extension.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate telemetry or extensions wouldn't typically be unsigned, injected directly into the browser process, and paired with low-reputation destination traffic."},{"text":"The activity points chiefly to denial of service against the authentication stack rather than theft of submitted secrets.","correct":false,"why":"The pattern described (browser injection plus outbound C2) is more consistent with credential theft than a denial-of-service attempt against authentication."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q27","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Secure Wireless)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A company wants stronger Wi-Fi security than WPA2-PSK and needs per-user authentication with central control. Which solution BEST fits?","options":[{"text":"Use enterprise wireless access with centralized authentication tied to individual identities.","correct":true,"why":"Enterprise Wi-Fi uses 802.1X/RADIUS for per-user auth and stronger control than shared PSKs."},{"text":"Adopt a stronger shared passphrase model that resists guessing while all users still rely on one secret.","correct":false,"why":"A stronger shared passphrase is still a single shared secret for everyone, not the per-user authentication the requirement calls for."},{"text":"Present a login page after association so users identify themselves even though access is not enforced at the link layer.","correct":false,"why":"A captive portal identifies users after association but doesn't enforce authentication at the wireless link layer like 802.1X does."},{"text":"Encrypt open guest access automatically without requiring each person to authenticate uniquely.","correct":false,"why":"Encrypting open access without per-user authentication doesn't meet the requirement for individual identity-based access."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q28","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Worm Propagation)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"A malware strain spreads rapidly across subnets without user interaction by exploiting a service vulnerability. What term BEST describes this behavior?","options":[{"text":"Autonomous self-spread by exploiting reachable services rather than waiting for a person to assist.","correct":true,"why":"Worms self-propagate by exploiting network-accessible weaknesses without needing user interaction."},{"text":"A remote-control network pushing commands to compromised hosts, which explains coordination but not self-spread.","correct":false,"why":"A C2/botnet describes coordinated control of already-compromised hosts, not the mechanism of autonomous self-propagation described here."},{"text":"A disguised installer that requires someone to launch it before any further activity can occur.","correct":false,"why":"This scenario specifically describes spread without user interaction, ruling out a disguised installer that requires user execution."},{"text":"An encryption-focused outbreak using stolen credentials, where propagation is secondary to extortion objectives.","correct":false,"why":"Ransomware's defining trait is encryption for extortion, not autonomous self-spread via a service vulnerability as described here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q29","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Egress Controls)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"Security finds malware repeatedly reaching new C2 infrastructure because domains change often. What network control BEST limits outbound malware communications?","options":[{"text":"Constrain outbound paths with destination controls and mediated name resolution so new command channels fail more often.","correct":true,"why":"Outbound controls (egress filtering, DNS security, proxies) reduce C2 success and provide visibility for detection and containment."},{"text":"Keep expanding deny lists for newly discovered destinations and addresses as threat intelligence catches up.","correct":false,"why":"Continuously expanding deny lists is a reactive, always-behind approach, unlike proactive egress and DNS controls that reduce C2 success more broadly."},{"text":"Centralize egress for visibility but continue permitting most encrypted outbound sessions to any destination.","correct":false,"why":"Gaining visibility without actually restricting which destinations are reachable still allows malware to reach new C2 infrastructure freely."},{"text":"Rely mainly on endpoint blocking because network controls are less useful once attackers rotate infrastructure quickly.","correct":false,"why":"Network-level egress and DNS controls remain effective against rotating infrastructure since they can restrict destinations broadly rather than by specific IOC."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q30","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Malware Response (Eradication vs Recovery)","source":"CySA Day 9.html","q":"After containment, the IR team wants to ensure malware is fully removed and access is not re-established. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Remove persistence, revoke abused access, fix the entry path, and verify the environment before returning to normal.","correct":true,"why":"Eradication includes removing persistence, fixing root cause, credential resets, patching, and validating via monitoring and retesting."},{"text":"Restore affected systems from backup first and investigate any remaining footholds after operations resume.","correct":false,"why":"Restoring before removing persistence and closing the entry path risks reintroducing or leaving active malware and access in place."},{"text":"Maintain containment boundaries while delaying cleanup steps until business services have fully recovered.","correct":false,"why":"Delaying persistence removal and root-cause fixes leaves the environment vulnerable to re-compromise even while services are recovering."},{"text":"Reimage only the visibly affected host and treat unchanged credentials or access paths as separate later work.","correct":false,"why":"Leaving abused credentials and the original entry path unaddressed allows attackers to re-establish access even after reimaging one host."}],"sub":"3.2"},{"id":"q31","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Process Tree)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"An EDR alert shows WINWORD.EXE spawning powershell.exe which then spawns rundll32.exe and initiates outbound HTTPS to a rare domain. What is the BEST next triage step?","options":[{"text":"Trace lineage, arguments, socket ownership, and logon session to validate whether the chain reflects staged execution.","correct":true,"why":"Start by validating lineage, command-line use, and which child owned the connection."},{"text":"Check whether the file originated from a recent approved workflow and compare the launch context with normal office activity.","correct":false,"why":"This is a reasonable early check but doesn't itself validate the specific process lineage, arguments, and network ownership needed to confirm the suspicious chain."},{"text":"Place the device in containment first, then defer process review until after volatile collection completes from the console.","correct":false,"why":"Deferring the actual triage of the process chain skips the immediate validation step needed to understand what's actually happening before deciding on containment."},{"text":"Block the destination globally and begin hunting for the domain before determining which child initiated the traffic.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking before identifying which process owns the connection skips the necessary triage step of confirming the chain's behavior first."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q32","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malicious Activity (Persistence)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A Windows host re-creates a suspicious executable after every reboot. Logs show a scheduled task created by a non-admin user and running with highest privileges. What technique is MOST likely?","options":[{"text":"Abuse of recurring task execution with elevated run context to regain foothold after restart.","correct":true,"why":"A recurring task created by a lower-privileged user but executing with elevated context strongly suggests scheduled-task persistence with privilege misuse."},{"text":"Installer-driven maintenance registration from an approved package that routinely stages binaries after startup.","correct":false,"why":"An approved installer process wouldn't typically be created by a non-admin user yet run with highest privileges, which is the suspicious privilege mismatch described here."},{"text":"Application self-healing through software distribution policy that restores missing components on boot.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate self-healing software distribution wouldn't typically be created by a non-admin account while running with elevated privileges."},{"text":"Service recovery behavior caused by crash handling rules that copy the file back after each failed launch.","correct":false,"why":"Crash recovery doesn't explain a scheduled task created by a non-admin user running with highest privileges, the specific persistence and privilege escalation pattern here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q33","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Linux)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A Linux server shows a new process listening on an unusual high port. The binary path points to /tmp and the process parent is a web server worker. What is the BEST response?","options":[{"text":"Collect pid, argv, cwd, open files, sockets, hash, and parent details before containment or removal.","correct":true,"why":"A web-server child running from /tmp and listening externally is highly suspicious."},{"text":"Delete the file from temporary storage immediately so the listener cannot rebind during further investigation.","correct":false,"why":"Deleting the file before collecting details destroys evidence needed for scoping and doesn't stop the already-running listening process."},{"text":"Restart the web service to terminate the child, then review logs afterward if the process fails to return.","correct":false,"why":"Restarting the service before collecting process details loses volatile evidence like open sockets and memory state needed for investigation."},{"text":"Add a host firewall deny rule for the port first and postpone artifact collection until scheduled downtime.","correct":false,"why":"Delaying evidence collection until scheduled downtime risks losing volatile process details that could disappear before then."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q34","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Credential Access)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"EDR detects a process attempting to read LSASS memory and opening many handles to lsass.exe. What attacker objective does this MOST align with?","options":[{"text":"Harvesting reusable authentication material for later pivoting and privilege expansion across the environment.","correct":true,"why":"Opening numerous handles to LSASS and reading its memory is a classic sign of obtaining credentials, hashes, or tickets for later movement."},{"text":"Inventorying local security products by touching protected memory regions used by endpoint tooling.","correct":false,"why":"Security product inventory wouldn't require reading LSASS memory specifically; that's the process responsible for storing authentication material."},{"text":"Performing crash-triage collection associated with operating system diagnostics after an application fault.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate crash diagnostics wouldn't specifically target repeated handle access to LSASS memory the way credential-harvesting techniques do."},{"text":"Validating smart-card middleware state by enumerating protected handles tied to interactive sessions.","correct":false,"why":"Smart-card middleware validation wouldn't require opening numerous handles to LSASS memory, which is specifically associated with credential extraction techniques."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q35","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malicious Activity (C2 Beaconing)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"Proxy logs show an endpoint making HTTPS connections to the same domain every 60 seconds with consistent request sizes. DNS shows the domain is newly registered. What is the MOST likely interpretation?","options":[{"text":"Periodic operator check-ins from an implanted foothold, pending host-side confirmation of the owning process.","correct":true,"why":"Regular timing, stable sizes, and a newly registered destination are classic beaconing signals."},{"text":"Routine patch compliance polling from a newly onboarded vendor platform that uses fixed heartbeat intervals.","correct":false,"why":"A newly onboarded vendor platform would typically resolve to a known, established domain rather than one that was just recently registered."},{"text":"Browser synchronization traffic from an extension that happened to deploy a new cloud endpoint this week.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate browser sync services use established, well-known domains, not a domain that was just newly registered this week."},{"text":"Expected telemetry uploads from a recently installed management agent that batches data in equal-sized posts.","correct":false,"why":"A legitimate management agent would typically communicate with an established vendor domain, not a domain registered very recently."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q36","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Windows Services)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"Security logs show a new service installed with a random name, pointing to an unsigned binary in a user profile directory. What should you check FIRST?","options":[{"text":"Creation metadata, startup mode, signer status, originating account, and adjacent process activity from that window.","correct":true,"why":"Randomly named services pointing to unsigned user-path binaries often indicate persistence."},{"text":"Whether the binary loads successfully after reboot so you can confirm the service is actually persistent.","correct":false,"why":"This only confirms the service runs again; it doesn't gather the metadata needed to determine whether the service itself is malicious."},{"text":"Enterprise change records for all software pushes before reviewing the service creation event in detail.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing broad change records first delays examining the specific suspicious service creation event, which should be investigated directly first."},{"text":"Other autorun locations across the host first, because services rarely matter unless multiple footholds exist.","correct":false,"why":"The suspicious service itself, pointing to an unsigned binary in a user directory, is the immediate priority to examine, not other autorun locations first."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q37","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Defense Evasion)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A process disables Windows Defender using PowerShell and modifies registry keys related to security settings, then clears event logs. Which technique category BEST matches?","options":[{"text":"Suppressing protective controls and removing traces to reduce visibility on the endpoint.","correct":true,"why":"Disabling security controls and clearing logs fits defense evasion and indicator removal, not discovery or privilege escalation."},{"text":"Expanding privileges by modifying local policy areas commonly touched during administrative role changes.","correct":false,"why":"The described actions (disabling Defender, clearing logs) reduce visibility rather than expand the attacker's privilege level."},{"text":"Surveying the host security posture to decide which controls exist before choosing later actions.","correct":false,"why":"This scenario describes actively disabling controls and clearing logs, which goes beyond passive surveying of what controls exist."},{"text":"Executing a scripted maintenance workflow that changes configuration and rotates local diagnostic records.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate maintenance wouldn't typically disable security tooling and clear logs together, a combination specifically indicative of evading detection."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q38","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (Triage)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"An endpoint alert triggers on “encoded PowerShell.” IT confirms scripts are used widely. What is the BEST way to separate benign from malicious?","options":[{"text":"Compare launch context, parentage, signer trust, decoded behavior, and outbound activity against known-good baselines.","correct":true,"why":"Encoded PowerShell can be legitimate."},{"text":"Treat any use of obfuscation as hostile because administrative automation should never require transformed content.","correct":false,"why":"IT confirmed encoded scripts are used widely for legitimate purposes, so treating all obfuscation as automatically hostile would create excessive false positives."},{"text":"Suppress the alert for the entire enterprise and rely on users to report anything that looks suspicious.","correct":false,"why":"Suppressing the alert entirely removes visibility needed to distinguish genuinely malicious activity from legitimate encoded scripts."},{"text":"Focus only on whether the script was signed, because trusted signing eliminates the need for context review.","correct":false,"why":"Signing status alone doesn't confirm intent or behavior; broader context like parentage and outbound activity is still needed to separate benign from malicious use."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q39","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Handles/Modules)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A suspicious process injects a DLL into a browser process and then the browser starts making outbound connections to low-reputation domains. What is the BEST interpretation?","options":[{"text":"A trusted user-facing program is being used as a host for theft or traffic manipulation through injected code.","correct":true,"why":"Injection into a browser followed by suspicious outbound traffic often indicates credential theft, session hijacking, or traffic interception through that trusted process."},{"text":"A normal plugin registration event where unsigned extensions transiently load before browser policy approval finishes.","correct":false,"why":"Normal extension registration doesn't typically involve DLL injection into the browser process combined with connections to low-reputation domains."},{"text":"Endpoint monitoring hooks added by a security agent, which commonly produce unknown destinations until reputation sync completes.","correct":false,"why":"A legitimate security agent wouldn't typically inject code into the browser process and then generate traffic to low-reputation domains."},{"text":"A developer troubleshooting session in which browser memory was modified to reproduce rendering issues in the lab.","correct":false,"why":"A developer debugging session wouldn't typically produce outbound connections specifically to low-reputation domains."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q40","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Discovery)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"PowerShell history shows commands like whoami, ipconfig, net user, net group, nltest, and arp -a before lateral movement. What stage does this MOST represent?","options":[{"text":"Environment and identity reconnaissance performed to understand privileges, trust paths, and nearby targets.","correct":true,"why":"Those commands map to learning who the actor is, what the network looks like, and where trust relationships exist before moving laterally."},{"text":"Data staging because local and domain queries are routinely needed before packaging files for export.","correct":false,"why":"These specific commands (whoami, net user, nltest, arp) gather identity and network information; they don't themselves package or stage files for exfiltration."},{"text":"Direct collection of reusable secrets because account enumeration normally yields plaintext credentials for reuse.","correct":false,"why":"These enumeration commands reveal account and network information, not plaintext credentials, which is a distinct data set from what these commands provide."},{"text":"Initial payload execution because built-in utilities are often launched immediately after code runs on a host.","correct":false,"why":"These commands occur before lateral movement, consistent with reconnaissance, not the initial code execution stage itself."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q41","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Windows Event IDs)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"You see repeated log clears and then a sudden gap in Security logs on a suspected host. What is the BEST investigative action?","options":[{"text":"Rebuild the timeline from centralized and adjacent telemetry such as SIEM, EDR, Sysmon, DNS, and firewall records.","correct":true,"why":"When local logs are tampered with, reconstruct activity from centralized copies and alternate telemetry sources."},{"text":"Repair the local event database first so missing records can repopulate and reduce the need for cross-source review.","correct":false,"why":"Repairing the local database doesn't recover the deleted events; the timeline must be reconstructed from other independent sources instead."},{"text":"Assume the issue is collector instability and postpone endpoint investigation until logging health is restored.","correct":false,"why":"Repeated log clears combined with a gap strongly suggest deliberate tampering, not simply a collector health issue that should delay investigation."},{"text":"Limit review to the host itself because external copies may introduce timing skew that complicates chronology.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting review to the tampered host ignores the independent, harder-to-manipulate copies held in centralized telemetry that are needed to rebuild the true timeline."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q42","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Lateral Movement)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"Network logs show a host initiating many SMB sessions to multiple servers, followed by remote service creation events on targets. Which technique is MOST likely?","options":[{"text":"Remote execution over administrative file sharing with temporary service creation on downstream systems.","correct":true,"why":"SMB fan-out paired with service creation on targets strongly resembles PsExec-style lateral movement."},{"text":"Routine software deployment that always appears suspicious because installers commonly fan out through administrative shares.","correct":false,"why":"Routine software deployment wouldn't typically be characterized as suspicious fan-out combined with remote service creation on downstream targets; this pattern matches lateral movement tradecraft instead."},{"text":"Share enumeration only, since service creation can occur during read-only access to hidden administrative folders.","correct":false,"why":"Service creation events specifically indicate code execution was attempted on the targets, not merely read-only enumeration of shares."},{"text":"Backup agent registration in which temporary services are created on every server before nightly collection begins.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate backup agents don't typically create temporary services across many targets in the pattern of manual SMB session fan-out described here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q43","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (Indicators vs TTPs)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A defender blocks known malware hashes, but the attacker recompiles payloads frequently. Which detection approach is MOST resilient?","options":[{"text":"Behavioral hunting anchored on repeatable execution, persistence, and communications patterns across data sources.","correct":true,"why":"Recompiled payloads break static hashes."},{"text":"More frequent hash refresh cycles so the blocklist can keep pace with each rebuild of the malicious binary.","correct":false,"why":"Refreshing hash blocklists more often still relies on static signatures that recompiled payloads will continue to evade."},{"text":"Broader denial of newly seen destinations because changing payloads matter less once internet exposure is reduced.","correct":false,"why":"Broadly denying new destinations doesn't address the host-side behavior driving the attack, and would also block many legitimate new connections."},{"text":"Stricter mail filtering only, since stopping delivery removes the need to detect changing host-side behavior.","correct":false,"why":"Stricter mail filtering only addresses one delivery vector and doesn't detect the changing host-side behavior after a payload executes."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q44","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Signed vs Unsigned)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A binary is running from C:UsersPublic with a random name and no valid signature. It spawns cmd.exe with /c to run encoded PowerShell. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Capture provenance, arguments, prevalence, and related ancestry, then pivot for matching executions across the estate.","correct":true,"why":"Unknown unsigned binaries in public paths spawning interpreters should be scoped quickly through prevalence, lineage, and command-line pivots before remediation."},{"text":"Reimage the workstation immediately because host restoration should precede any effort to scope related activity.","correct":false,"why":"Reimaging immediately destroys evidence needed to determine how the binary got there and whether other hosts are also affected."},{"text":"Block transformed script execution globally before collecting details about where the binary appeared elsewhere.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking script execution globally before scoping the incident skips the investigation needed to understand where else this activity appeared."},{"text":"Send the file to sandboxing first and wait for verdicts before reviewing telemetry already available in the environment.","correct":false,"why":"Waiting on a sandbox verdict delays using telemetry already available in the environment to scope related activity right now."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q45","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Initial Access)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A user opens a macro-enabled document, and shortly afterward you see mshta.exe and rundll32.exe activity with network connections to a new domain. What is the MOST likely initial access vector?","options":[{"text":"User-targeted lure content that triggered a staged chain through built-in utilities to fetch the next component.","correct":true,"why":"A macro-enabled lure followed by LOLBAS execution and external retrieval most strongly indicates phishing with a malicious attachment."},{"text":"Direct exploitation of a browsing session, since script hosts and DLL launchers commonly appear after web compromise.","correct":false,"why":"This scenario begins with a macro-enabled document opened by the user, not direct browser exploitation."},{"text":"Ordinary application setup using helper binaries that contact the internet for localization or registration resources.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate application setup wouldn't typically chain through mshta.exe and rundll32.exe immediately after a user opens a document."},{"text":"Remote administration from help desk tooling, because document viewing often invokes external helper components.","correct":false,"why":"Help desk remote administration wouldn't be triggered by a user opening a document and wouldn't typically involve mshta and rundll32 activity."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q46","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (Containment)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"You confirm an endpoint is beaconing to suspected C2 and has created persistence via a scheduled task. What is the BEST immediate action sequence?","options":[{"text":"Stop ongoing interaction, preserve volatile artifacts, then remove the foothold and rotate exposed identities.","correct":true,"why":"Containment should halt continued operator control, preserve volatile evidence, and then address persistence plus potentially exposed credentials."},{"text":"Delete the recurring mechanism first and leave network access intact so you can watch for fallback behavior.","correct":false,"why":"Removing the scheduled task first while leaving network access intact still allows the beaconing to continue and doesn't preserve volatile evidence first."},{"text":"Only block the destination and postpone host isolation to avoid user disruption during the workday.","correct":false,"why":"Delaying host isolation to avoid disruption leaves the compromised endpoint free to continue communicating with C2."},{"text":"Restore the system from gold image immediately and decide later whether memory or credential scope mattered.","correct":false,"why":"Restoring from a gold image immediately destroys volatile evidence needed to determine memory and credential exposure before rebuilding."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q47","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Linux Persistence)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A Linux endpoint executes a suspicious binary that later reappears after login. You discover a new entry in ~/.bashrc and a new user crontab. What does this MOST indicate?","options":[{"text":"User-level re-execution anchored in shell startup and time-based invocation after interactive access returns.","correct":true,"why":"Modifications to shell startup files plus user cron entries are classic Linux persistence mechanisms."},{"text":"Routine developer environment customization because shell initialization files often launch helper programs at sign-in.","correct":false,"why":"Routine developer customizations wouldn't typically pair a new bashrc entry with a new crontab entry re-executing a suspicious binary."},{"text":"Package post-install configuration from the distribution tooling, which commonly writes into user task schedules.","correct":false,"why":"Distribution package post-install scripts don't typically write to a specific user's personal crontab to relaunch a suspicious binary."},{"text":"Backup automation deployed by operations, since personal cron entries usually govern recurring data protection jobs.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate backup automation is typically managed centrally, not through an individual user's personal crontab paired with a bashrc modification."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q48","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Privilege Escalation)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A standard user process spawns cmd.exe, then uses runas and creates a new local admin account. Which objective is MOST likely?","options":[{"text":"Gaining durable elevated access by obtaining stronger local control than the original session possessed.","correct":true,"why":"Using runas and then creating a local administrator account indicates privilege escalation combined with persistence."},{"text":"Routine workstation support preparation in which temporary administrators are added for short maintenance windows.","correct":false,"why":"Routine support preparation wouldn't typically originate from a standard user process using runas to escalate and create a new account itself."},{"text":"Pure reconnaissance of access boundaries, because new accounts are often created only to test policy responses.","correct":false,"why":"Creating a new local admin account goes beyond simple reconnaissance of access boundaries; it establishes actual elevated access."},{"text":"Application deployment staging, since installers commonly create administrative users before package execution begins.","correct":false,"why":"Installers don't typically need to create a new local administrator account from a standard user's elevated cmd.exe session before running."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q49","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (PCAP / SYNs)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"PCAP shows repeated SYN packets from a host to many random IPs with no completed handshakes. What is the MOST likely activity?","options":[{"text":"Broad reachability probing intended to map services, targets, or egress behavior without establishing sessions.","correct":true,"why":"Many SYNs to numerous unrelated IPs without completed handshakes most closely matches scanning or reconnaissance."},{"text":"Normal application retries from a flaky client that chooses random internet peers during connection backoff logic.","correct":false,"why":"A flaky client's retries would typically target the same few known peers, not many random IPs with no completed handshakes."},{"text":"Synthetic packet generation by the capture stack itself, which often emits half-open traffic during interface testing.","correct":false,"why":"Capture stack artifacts wouldn't produce a pattern of SYNs specifically directed at many random external IPs."},{"text":"Misconfigured load-balancer health polling that accidentally selected arbitrary public addresses as service members.","correct":false,"why":"A misconfigured health check would typically target a small, defined set of known service members, not many random IPs."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q50","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Exfiltration)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A host compresses large directories, then initiates long-duration outbound transfers to a personal cloud storage domain over TLS. Which evidence BEST supports exfiltration?","options":[{"text":"Time-linked file staging, byte counts, destination context, and user attribution all pointing to the same transfer event.","correct":true,"why":"To support exfiltration, correlate staging activity on the host with transfer volume, timing, destination, and the responsible user."},{"text":"Proxy categorization alone showing the site belongs to cloud storage, which is enough to prove improper data removal.","correct":false,"why":"Category alone (the site being cloud storage) doesn't itself prove data was improperly removed; it needs to be combined with the timing, volume, and attribution evidence."},{"text":"Manager confirmation that the employee lacked approval, because intent matters more than endpoint and network evidence.","correct":false,"why":"Manager confirmation of a policy violation doesn't provide the technical evidence needed to confirm exfiltration actually occurred."},{"text":"Absence of DLP alerts, since true outbound theft should always trigger content inspection when sensitive data is involved.","correct":false,"why":"The absence of a DLP alert doesn't rule out exfiltration; DLP coverage gaps are common, so its absence isn't reliable evidence either way."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q51","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (DLL Search Order)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A signed application loads an unexpected DLL from the current working directory rather than the system directory. What technique does this MOST resemble?","options":[{"text":"Trusted-process execution obtained by manipulating library resolution so attacker-controlled code loads first.","correct":true,"why":"Loading an unexpected DLL from the working directory points to DLL search order hijacking or sideloading."},{"text":"Expected plugin discovery, because signed programs normally prefer the working directory over protected system paths.","correct":false,"why":"Signed applications don't normally prefer the working directory over protected system paths for library resolution by design; this is exactly the exploitable behavior being described."},{"text":"Security instrumentation shimming, since monitoring agents routinely place unsigned modules beside user applications.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate monitoring agents don't typically rely on placing unsigned modules in the working directory to be loaded ahead of the system library."},{"text":"Updater rollback behavior where old components are loaded locally until the next maintenance cycle completes.","correct":false,"why":"Updater rollback wouldn't typically explain a signed application loading an unexpected DLL from its working directory instead of the system directory."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q52","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Command Execution / LOLBAS)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A defender sees certutil.exe downloading a file from an external URL and then executing it. Why is this significant?","options":[{"text":"A built-in utility is being repurposed to retrieve and launch content while blending into normal system tooling.","correct":true,"why":"certutil is a common LOLBAS utility."},{"text":"Certificate enrollment operations often require internet retrieval and immediate execution of support components.","correct":false,"why":"Certificate enrollment operations don't typically require downloading and immediately executing arbitrary external content."},{"text":"Only plaintext downloads matter here, because encrypted transfers through native tools are generally trustworthy.","correct":false,"why":"The concern here isn't limited to plaintext downloads; encrypted delivery through a trusted native tool is exactly what makes this technique effective for evading detection."},{"text":"This mainly indicates software installation, since native utilities rarely appear in malicious delivery chains.","correct":false,"why":"Native utilities like certutil are increasingly common in malicious delivery chains specifically because they blend in with normal system activity."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q53","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (Scope)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"One host is confirmed compromised. What is the BEST SIEM query strategy to scope related activity across the environment?","options":[{"text":"Hunt with a mix of high-confidence artifacts and repeatable patterns such as lineage, destinations, auth anomalies, and paths.","correct":true,"why":"Best scoping combines concrete indicators with behavior patterns across multiple telemetry sources and time ranges."},{"text":"Search only for the contacted domain, since process context creates too much noise when expanding from one host.","correct":false,"why":"Limiting the search to just the contacted domain misses other indicators like process lineage and authentication anomalies that could reveal related activity elsewhere."},{"text":"Pivot only on the exact file hash because broad behavioral searches usually overwhelm investigators with false leads.","correct":false,"why":"Pivoting only on the exact hash misses polymorphic or related activity that wouldn't share the same file hash."},{"text":"Constrain all queries to the known hostname first, because enterprise spread is unlikely once one device is isolated.","correct":false,"why":"Enterprise spread can still occur through other compromised hosts even after one device is isolated, so scope shouldn't be limited to just that hostname."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q54","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Windows Startup Locations)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"You find a suspicious executable referenced in HKCUSoftwareMicrosoftWindowsCurrentVersionRun. What does this MOST indicate?","options":[{"text":"User-context re-launch at sign-in through a common autorun location tied to interactive startup.","correct":true,"why":"The HKCU Run key is a classic per-user autorun location and frequently used for persistence."},{"text":"Core operating system service registration, since this area mainly governs protected components and policy refresh.","correct":false,"why":"The Run key is a user-context autostart location, not an area that governs core protected OS services."},{"text":"Temporary troubleshooting automation that exists only for a single session and disappears at next logout.","correct":false,"why":"Entries in this key persist across sessions rather than existing only temporarily for a single session."},{"text":"Application inventory metadata written by installers to record version information without affecting execution.","correct":false,"why":"This registry location controls actual program execution at logon; it isn't merely inventory metadata recorded by installers."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q55","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Data Destruction / Impact)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A threat actor deletes backups and disables recovery services after gaining admin access, but does not immediately encrypt files. What is the MOST likely objective?","options":[{"text":"Reducing the victim’s ability to recover before later coercive or destructive action is launched.","correct":true,"why":"Destroying backups and recovery paths usually prepares the environment for ransomware or other high-impact actions."},{"text":"Performing storage cleanup because old recovery points commonly interfere with normal production performance.","correct":false,"why":"Deleting backups and disabling recovery services goes well beyond routine storage cleanup, which wouldn't require disabling recovery capability entirely."},{"text":"Meeting retention policy requirements that remove legacy restore paths after a successful administrative review.","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate retention policy changes wouldn't typically follow gaining unauthorized admin access and disabling recovery services."},{"text":"Gathering documentation from backup catalogs, since disabling those services is mainly useful for environmental mapping.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling recovery services actively removes restore capability; it isn't simply a byproduct of passive environmental mapping."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q56","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (False Positive Control)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"An alert flags “rundll32 executing from user directory,” but IT has a legitimate tool that uses rundll32 for plugin loading. What is the BEST way to reduce false positives while retaining detection?","options":[{"text":"Permit only the known good implementation via strong identifiers while keeping analytics on unknown parents, paths, and unsigned modules.","correct":true,"why":"The right tuning approach is narrow allow-listing for the known tool while preserving detections on suspicious contexts."},{"text":"Disable the rule entirely because native binaries used by approved tools cannot be monitored without excessive noise.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling the rule entirely removes detection capability for genuinely malicious rundll32 activity, not just the false positives."},{"text":"Suppress all executions from user-writable locations since legitimate software commonly launches from those paths.","correct":false,"why":"Suppressing all executions from user-writable locations would also hide genuinely malicious activity from other, unapproved sources."},{"text":"Block the native binary everywhere and require exception tickets for any team that still depends on it.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking the binary everywhere would break the legitimate tool's approved use case that the scenario says must be retained."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q57","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Windows Tokens)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"EDR indicates a process launched with a high-integrity token shortly after UAC prompts were accepted unexpectedly. What is the MOST likely security concern?","options":[{"text":"An unplanned elevation event likely driven by social engineering or abuse of approval to gain stronger execution rights.","correct":true,"why":"Unexpected UAC acceptance followed by high-integrity execution can indicate consent phishing or privilege escalation."},{"text":"Routine desktop behavior, because any consent prompt automatically validates the launched process as trustworthy.","correct":false,"why":"A consent prompt being accepted doesn't automatically validate that the resulting elevated process is trustworthy or expected."},{"text":"Name-resolution problems affecting administrative resources, which commonly surface as unexpected consent prompts.","correct":false,"why":"Name-resolution issues wouldn't produce an unexpected UAC elevation prompt or a resulting high-integrity token."},{"text":"Normal updater activity that should be presumed benign whenever a user clicks through a privilege prompt.","correct":false,"why":"Assuming benign updater activity ignores that this elevation was described as unexpected, which warrants investigation rather than a default benign assumption."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q58","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Credential Access / Kerberos)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"Security sees many Kerberos service ticket requests for a service account and then offline cracking attempts are suspected. Which technique is this MOST associated with?","options":[{"text":"Obtaining crackable service-ticket material to recover an account secret without interacting with the host again.","correct":true,"why":"Requesting many service tickets for SPNs and then attempting offline cracking is characteristic of Kerberoasting."},{"text":"Trying many common passwords directly against the account until one succeeds and produces a lockout pattern.","correct":false,"why":"Online password guessing produces failed login and lockout patterns, not the offline cracking of captured service tickets described here."},{"text":"Forging universal domain access after compromise of the ticket-granting authority’s long-term secret.","correct":false,"why":"Forging tickets from the KDC's long-term secret describes a different technique (golden ticket) than requesting and cracking a specific service account's tickets."},{"text":"Reusing NTLM-derived material for authentication relay against services that do not require ticket requests.","correct":false,"why":"Reusing NTLM hashes for relay doesn't involve requesting Kerberos service tickets, which is the specific activity described here."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q59","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Analyzing Malicious Activity (Evidence Preservation)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"A suspected compromised system is still running, and you need volatile artifacts (network connections, memory-resident malware). What is the BEST approach?","options":[{"text":"Keep power intact, restrict communication, and acquire ephemeral state before any shutdown or rebuild action.","correct":true,"why":"Volatile evidence disappears on reboot or shutdown."},{"text":"Turn the system off immediately so the adversary loses access, then attempt memory recovery from the disk image later.","correct":false,"why":"Powering off immediately destroys the volatile memory-resident evidence that needs to be captured while the system is still running."},{"text":"Restart first to clear unstable processes and begin collection once the operating system returns to a clean state.","correct":false,"why":"Restarting the system also destroys the current volatile state, including active network connections and memory-resident malware."},{"text":"Prioritize disk imaging alone because transient state rarely affects malware investigations when logs are available.","correct":false,"why":"Disk imaging alone misses memory-resident malware and active network connections, which only exist in volatile state while the system is running."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q60","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Command and Control / Egress)","source":"CySA+_Day_10.html","q":"An organization blocks known malicious domains, but attackers rotate domains quickly. What control MOST reduces C2 success while maintaining business needs?","options":[{"text":"Tighter outbound governance using proxy or DNS policy, selective allow rules, and telemetry for anomaly review.","correct":true,"why":"Egress controls, DNS/proxy security, selective allow-listing, and good logging reduce command-and-control success better than simple domain blocklists."},{"text":"Permit unrestricted internet access so business traffic is never disrupted by destination-based security decisions.","correct":false,"why":"Permitting unrestricted internet access removes any destination-based control, which would make it easier, not harder, for C2 to succeed."},{"text":"Eliminate DNS logging to reduce attacker visibility into defender monitoring of new domains and lookups.","correct":false,"why":"Eliminating DNS logging removes visibility needed to detect and investigate new C2 domains, working against the defensive goal."},{"text":"Force all outbound traffic onto encrypted web ports, since command channels cannot operate once ports are standardized.","correct":false,"why":"Command channels can still operate over standard encrypted web ports; forcing traffic onto those ports doesn't prevent C2 communication."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q61","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"During a risk register review, leadership asks why a control with strong security value is still not implemented. The team notes the control increases operational latency and breaks a vendor SLA. Which risk response best aligns with maintaining business objectives while reducing residual risk?","options":[{"text":"Reduce exposure with a control alternative that preserves service commitments and lowers the practical attack path","correct":false,"why":"This describes a similar compensating-control approach in different words, but the scenario specifically calls for mitigating via a compensating control that doesn't violate the SLA, which is more precisely captured by directly implementing one."},{"text":"Shift part of the financial consequence contractually while applying an interim safeguard that preserves operations","correct":false,"why":"This introduces risk transference (shifting financial consequence contractually), which isn't what the scenario is asking for; the team specifically needs a control that reduces likelihood without breaking the SLA."},{"text":"Mitigate the exposure by implementing a compensating control that reduces likelihood without violating the SLA","correct":true,"why":"Risk mitigation reduces likelihood/impact while honoring constraints; compensating controls can satisfy control objectives without breaking uptime/SLA commitments. Compensating controls are classic mitigation when a primary control is infeasible due to constraints like SLA/latency."},{"text":"Restructure the dependent workflow so the underlying weakness no longer drives the same business interruption risk","correct":false,"why":"Restructuring the workflow is a larger architectural change than implementing a compensating control, and doesn't match the described need to keep the existing SLA-bound process while adding a safeguard."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q62","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A SOC is asked to justify adding analysts for a new logging pipeline. The CFO wants a metric that ties incident frequency to monetary impact over time. Which measure most directly supports this request?","options":[{"text":"Mean time to detect (MTTD) for high-severity alerts and associated false-positive reduction ratio","correct":false,"why":"MTTD measures detection speed, not the monetary impact of incidents over time that the CFO specifically asked for."},{"text":"Annualized loss expectancy (ALE) derived from SLE and ARO for the incident category","correct":true,"why":"ALE expresses expected annual cost of incidents and is often used for cost/benefit staffing or control investment discussions. ALE is explicitly a monetary, time-based expectation of loss."},{"text":"Risk appetite statements mapped to KRIs with qualitative heat-map scoring","correct":false,"why":"Qualitative heat-map scoring doesn't tie incident frequency to a specific monetary impact figure the way a quantitative ALE calculation does."},{"text":"Coverage percentage for telemetry sources compared to the ATT&CK technique matrix","correct":false,"why":"Telemetry coverage percentage measures visibility, not the financial impact of incidents that the CFO is asking to see."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q63","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An organization uses a third-party SaaS to process regulated data. The vendor’s SOC 2 report is current, but the contract lacks language on breach notification timelines. What should you do first to reduce legal and operational risk?","options":[{"text":"Require contract language that defines notification timing, evidence rights, and handling obligations for regulated data","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same general idea as negotiating amendments, but the most direct first step is to actually negotiate the specific amendments needed, which is the more precise and actionable answer."},{"text":"Negotiate contract amendments to add notification SLAs, right-to-audit language, and data handling requirements","correct":true,"why":"SOC 2 shows controls, but the contract governs obligations. Contract language is a direct lever for third-party risk, especially breach notification timelines."},{"text":"Map shared-responsibility gaps to enforceable obligations and monitoring expectations before changing deployment models","correct":false,"why":"Mapping responsibility gaps is a useful analysis step, but it doesn't itself add the missing contractual notification language, which is the immediate gap identified."},{"text":"Increase service oversight internally while formalizing provider obligations tied to reporting and response coordination","correct":false,"why":"Internal oversight alone doesn't fix the missing contractual notification obligation, which needs to be addressed directly with the vendor."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q64","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A risk assessment identifies a threat with low likelihood but catastrophic impact. The business cannot tolerate downtime beyond minutes. Which approach best reflects this risk posture?","options":[{"text":"Redesign the service dependency so a single failure no longer creates an intolerable business outage condition","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same general goal, but avoiding the risk specifically means eliminating the single point of failure itself, which is the more precise description of this approach."},{"text":"Avoid the risk by redesigning the process to eliminate the single point of failure and reduce impact to near zero","correct":true,"why":"Avoidance changes the architecture/process so the intolerable risk condition no longer exists, matching strict availability requirements. If downtime is intolerable and impact is catastrophic, avoidance via redesign is most aligned."},{"text":"Distribute the critical function across resilient components so no single event drives the full business impact","correct":false,"why":"Distributing across resilient components describes risk reduction/mitigation, not fully eliminating the single point of failure as risk avoidance requires."},{"text":"Add recovery planning and testing, but pair it with architectural changes that materially reduce outage concentration","correct":false,"why":"Recovery planning addresses response after an outage occurs; it doesn't eliminate the single point of failure itself the way risk avoidance requires given the near-zero downtime tolerance."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q65","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A control test shows endpoint encryption is enabled, but key escrow is misconfigured, causing some devices to lose recovery keys. Which risk concept is MOST impacted if a laptop is stolen?","options":[{"text":"Inherent risk because the threat actor’s capability increases when recovery keys are centrally stored","correct":false,"why":"Inherent risk describes exposure before any controls are applied; this scenario describes a control (encryption) that was implemented but is only partially effective, which is residual risk, not inherent risk."},{"text":"Residual risk because the implemented control is partially ineffective and may not reduce impact as intended","correct":true,"why":"Encryption with broken key management can fail to meet the control objective, leaving higher residual risk than expected after implementation. Residual risk is what remains after controls; misconfiguration reduces effectiveness."},{"text":"Transferred risk because lost keys shift liability to the device manufacturer and cloud escrow provider","correct":false,"why":"Nothing in this scenario describes a contractual transfer of liability to a manufacturer or escrow provider; the issue is the control's own partial ineffectiveness."},{"text":"Risk appetite because policy language implies encryption alone is sufficient regardless of recovery feasibility","correct":false,"why":"Risk appetite describes how much risk leadership accepts; this scenario is about a control failing to work as intended, which is residual risk, not a statement of risk tolerance."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q66","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A team maps controls to NIST CSF and discovers duplicate controls implemented differently across departments. What is the BEST next step to improve governance and reduce control drift?","options":[{"text":"Standardize control baselines with a single control owner, then measure effectiveness using consistent control test procedures","correct":true,"why":"GRC maturity improves when controls have clear ownership, common baselines, and repeatable evidence/test criteria across the enterprise. Control consolidation + ownership + consistent testing reduces drift and improves governance."},{"text":"Delete overlapping controls immediately to reduce operational burden and accept any newly introduced residual risk","correct":false,"why":"Deleting overlapping controls without any consolidation process risks losing needed protections and doesn't address the underlying governance drift."},{"text":"Increase audit frequency for each department and allow local variations to persist as long as they pass annually","correct":false,"why":"Allowing local variations to persist doesn't reduce control drift; it perpetuates the inconsistency the review identified."},{"text":"Migrate all control testing to an external assessor and rely on their report as the primary evidence artifact","correct":false,"why":"Relying solely on an external assessor's report doesn't establish the internal ownership and standardized baselines needed to prevent future drift."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q67","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An analyst sees repeated TLS handshakes where the client and server negotiate a suite with ECDHE and AES-GCM, but the certificate chain is valid. What property does ECDHE primarily provide in this context?","options":[{"text":"Nonrepudiation by binding the session key to the server’s long-term private key during negotiation","correct":false,"why":"Binding the session key to the long-term private key is the opposite of what ECDHE does; ECDHE specifically avoids depending on the long-term key for the session key itself."},{"text":"Forward secrecy by ensuring compromise of long-term keys does not decrypt previously captured sessions","correct":true,"why":"Ephemeral DH derives per-session secrets; later compromise of the server’s cert private key does not reveal past session keys. ECDHE = ephemeral Diffie-Hellman, mainly for forward secrecy."},{"text":"Integrity by generating a MAC that is cryptographically separate from the authenticated encryption mode","correct":false,"why":"MAC generation for integrity is a separate function from AES-GCM's authenticated encryption; ECDHE's specific role here is key exchange providing forward secrecy, not generating a MAC."},{"text":"Key escrow by enabling a third party to recover ephemeral keys if the server certificate is revoked","correct":false,"why":"ECDHE's ephemeral keys are specifically designed to not be recoverable by a third party; that's the opposite of key escrow."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q68","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A legacy application uses CBC-mode encryption without a modern AEAD. The team wants to address padding-oracle style issues without a full rewrite. What change MOST directly reduces this class of weakness?","options":[{"text":"Add a keyed integrity check over the ciphertext and verify it before attempting any decryption or padding checks","correct":true,"why":"Padding oracles exploit distinguishable error behavior. Encrypt-then-MAC (or AEAD) prevents oracle leakage by authenticating before decrypting."},{"text":"Increase key length from 128-bit to 256-bit to reduce brute-force feasibility against block cipher operations","correct":false,"why":"Increasing key length addresses brute-force resistance, not the padding-oracle vulnerability, which stems from how padding errors are handled, not key size."},{"text":"Switch the random number generator to a faster PRNG so IV generation is less computationally expensive","correct":false,"why":"The random number generator's speed doesn't address the padding-oracle issue, which comes from verifying padding before checking integrity."},{"text":"Disable error logging for decryption failures so attackers cannot observe differences in server responses","correct":false,"why":"Hiding error logs doesn't fix the underlying vulnerability; the padding oracle can still be exploited through response timing or behavior differences even without visible logs."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q69","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A blue team identifies that an attacker can downgrade a client to a weaker TLS version during negotiation. Which mitigation BEST addresses downgrade attempts?","options":[{"text":"Enforce strict transport security and disable legacy protocol versions and weak cipher suites at the server edge","correct":true,"why":"Downgrade protection is mainly configuration: disable older protocol versions/ciphers and enforce secure transport policy. Prevent negotiation to weak protocols/ciphers and use HSTS where applicable."},{"text":"Restrict negotiation to current protocol versions and approved suites so weaker fallback paths are never selected","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same general idea in different words, but the most complete answer specifically calls for enforcing strict transport security in addition to removing weak versions and ciphers."},{"text":"Constrain clients and servers to vetted versions and suites so older fallback combinations are unavailable","correct":false,"why":"This also restates the same concept, but doesn't explicitly mention enforcing strict transport security, which is part of the most complete mitigation."},{"text":"Enforce current transport settings and remove legacy negotiation branches rather than relying on higher-layer authentication","correct":false,"why":"This is close but omits explicitly disabling weak cipher suites alongside removing legacy protocol versions, which the best answer covers more completely."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q70","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"You are validating file integrity in a pipeline and need collision resistance more than speed. Which option is the BEST fit?","options":[{"text":"Use a modern cryptographic hash with strong collision resistance to detect intentional modification attempts","correct":true,"why":"For adversarial integrity, cryptographic hashes (or HMAC if authenticity needed) are preferred over checksums. Collision resistance is a hash function property; choose strong cryptographic hash."},{"text":"Use a non-cryptographic checksum to detect random transmission errors with low computational overhead","correct":false,"why":"A non-cryptographic checksum is designed to catch accidental errors, not resist intentional modification, which requires strong collision resistance."},{"text":"Use symmetric encryption with a shared key so the file cannot be modified without access to the secret","correct":false,"why":"Symmetric encryption protects confidentiality and requires key management overhead; it isn't the standard tool for verifying integrity via collision resistance."},{"text":"Use base64 encoding to normalize the file content and reduce accidental bit flips during transport","correct":false,"why":"Base64 encoding is just a representation format; it provides no collision resistance or tamper detection at all."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q71","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An incident report notes stolen password hashes that were unsalted and hashed with a fast algorithm. Which remediation MOST directly increases attacker workload during offline cracking?","options":[{"text":"Use per-user unique salts and a deliberately slow password hashing function to increase computation per guess","correct":true,"why":"For offline attacks, salts + slow password hashing (KDF) is the primary mitigation; lockouts help only for online attacks. Salts defeat precomputation; slow KDF raises cost per guess."},{"text":"Increase account lockout thresholds so online brute-force attempts are throttled by authentication controls","correct":false,"why":"Account lockout thresholds slow online guessing attempts, not offline cracking of already-stolen hash values."},{"text":"Replace hashes with reversible encryption so credentials can be recovered if the identity provider fails","correct":false,"why":"Reversible encryption of credentials is a security anti-pattern and doesn't address the fast-hashing weakness at all."},{"text":"Store hashes in a different database instance so attackers cannot identify the hashing algorithm used","correct":false,"why":"Moving hashes to a different database doesn't change the underlying fast algorithm or lack of salting that makes offline cracking easy."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q72","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A developer proposes using the same IV for multiple encryptions with a stream cipher to simplify debugging. What is the MOST accurate security concern?","options":[{"text":"Reusing the IV can reveal relationships between plaintexts by producing keystream reuse and enabling XOR analysis","correct":true,"why":"With stream ciphers (and many modes), IV/nonce reuse repeats keystream, allowing attackers to derive plaintext relationships and recover data. Stream cipher + nonce reuse = keystream reuse catastrophe."},{"text":"Reusing the IV increases the chance of signature forgery because IVs are mathematically equivalent to private keys","correct":false,"why":"IV reuse doesn't cause signature forgery; IVs aren't private keys and have no direct relationship to digital signatures."},{"text":"Reusing the IV only affects confidentiality if the key length is below 128 bits and is otherwise acceptable","correct":false,"why":"IV reuse is a confidentiality risk regardless of key length; keystream reuse enables analysis of the plaintexts even with a strong key."},{"text":"Reusing the IV primarily impacts nonrepudiation because the ciphertext cannot be uniquely attributed to a sender","correct":false,"why":"IV reuse primarily creates a confidentiality weakness through keystream reuse, not a nonrepudiation issue about sender attribution."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q73","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A company needs to enable mutual TLS for internal APIs. Engineers want the simplest way to prevent unauthorized service-to-service calls. Which PKI control BEST supports this goal?","options":[{"text":"Issue client certificates from an internal CA and require certificate-based auth with revocation checking on the gateway","correct":true,"why":"Client cert issuance and validation is the core of mTLS. mTLS requires client certs and validation; revocation supports quick disablement."},{"text":"Enroll each workload with an identity tied to policy so unauthorized callers can be blocked at connection time","correct":false,"why":"This restates a similar identity-and-policy idea but doesn't specifically call out the certificate-based authentication and revocation checking that directly prevents unauthorized service-to-service calls."},{"text":"Bind service trust to managed identities and revocation-aware validation rather than static per-client trust exceptions","correct":false,"why":"This is close but doesn't explicitly describe issuing client certificates from an internal CA, which is the concrete PKI mechanism needed here."},{"text":"Require managed machine identities at the gateway so segmentation and certificate validation reinforce each other","correct":false,"why":"This focuses on machine identities and segmentation generally, without specifically describing certificate-based authentication with revocation checking at the gateway."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q74","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A TLS inspection device breaks and reissues certificates on the fly. Analysts see frequent validation errors due to missing intermediate certificates. What is the MOST likely root cause?","options":[{"text":"The device is generating self-signed server certificates without distributing the required trust anchor to clients","correct":true,"why":"Interception requires a trusted enterprise CA installed on clients. If clients don’t trust the issuer, chain/intermediate issues show up as validation failures."},{"text":"The device is using elliptic curve keys, and clients do not support ECDSA signatures in the handshake","correct":false,"why":"ECDSA support is a separate compatibility concern and wouldn't specifically cause missing-intermediate-certificate errors."},{"text":"The proxy is not presenting a chain clients can build to a trusted issuer distributed in the enterprise trust store","correct":false,"why":"This restates a similar idea about chain building, but the more precise root cause is that the inspection device is generating self-signed certificates without distributing its trust anchor to clients."},{"text":"The device is enforcing OCSP stapling, and clients treat stapled responses as invalid when offline","correct":false,"why":"OCSP stapling issues relate to revocation status checks, not the missing-intermediate-certificate error described here."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q75","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A security architect wants to reduce reliance on CRLs for short-lived workloads in a container platform. Which design choice BEST supports this objective?","options":[{"text":"Issue short-lived certificates and automate rotation so compromised credentials expire quickly without heavy revocation dependencies","correct":true,"why":"If certificates expire quickly and rotate automatically, the window of misuse is limited, minimizing the need for CRLs/OCSP at scale. Short-lived certs reduce revocation reliance."},{"text":"Use a single long-lived certificate and store it in the container image to ensure identical trust across all replicas","correct":false,"why":"A single long-lived certificate baked into the image increases reliance on revocation if compromised, the opposite of reducing CRL dependency."},{"text":"Disable revocation checking and rely on network ACLs since containers are ephemeral and rarely persist","correct":false,"why":"Disabling revocation checking entirely removes a security control rather than reducing reliance on it through short-lived, automatically rotated credentials."},{"text":"Replace certificates with shared secrets and rotate them annually to reduce handshake overhead and operational friction","correct":false,"why":"Replacing certificates with shared secrets removes the benefits of PKI-based identity and doesn't address the goal of reducing CRL dependency for short-lived workloads."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q76","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An auditor asks for evidence that private keys for a root CA are protected against extraction. Which control provides the STRONGEST assurance?","options":[{"text":"Store root CA keys in a hardware security module configured to prevent key export and enforce role-based operations","correct":true,"why":"HSMs are purpose-built for key protection, enforcing non-export and controlled usage, which is stronger than OS-level controls. HSMs provide strong non-exportable key protection with controls and auditing."},{"text":"Encrypt root CA keys at rest with a symmetric key stored on the same server to maintain operational continuity","correct":false,"why":"Storing the symmetric key on the same server as the encrypted CA keys means a single compromise exposes both, unlike a hardware security module that prevents key export."},{"text":"Restrict filesystem access to the key directory and rotate administrator passwords quarterly with complexity rules","correct":false,"why":"Filesystem restrictions and password rotation are administrative controls, not the strongest technical assurance against key extraction that an HSM provides."},{"text":"Back up root CA keys to offline media and place the media in a locked cabinet managed by the PKI administrator","correct":false,"why":"Offline backup media in a locked cabinet reduces some risk but doesn't prevent extraction by someone with access to the media, unlike an HSM enforcing non-export."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q77","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A server presents a certificate that is signed by an intermediate CA, but clients intermittently fail validation depending on the device. What is the MOST probable explanation?","options":[{"text":"Some clients lack the intermediate CA certificate and the server is not providing the full chain during the handshake","correct":true,"why":"If the server doesn’t send the intermediate, clients that don’t already have it cannot build a chain to a trusted root. Chain presentation issues cause device-dependent failures."},{"text":"Some clients cannot build the chain because the issuing path is incomplete or absent during the handshake","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same idea as the correct answer but doesn't specifically identify that the server itself is failing to send the full certificate chain during the handshake."},{"text":"Validation varies by client because the presented issuing chain is incomplete rather than consistently anchored","correct":false,"why":"This also restates the same general idea without pinpointing that the server-side handshake is missing the intermediate certificate for some clients."},{"text":"Some clients reject certificates that include subject alternative names because they expect only common name fields","correct":false,"why":"Rejecting SANs in favor of only common names is a different, unrelated compatibility issue, not what's described in this intermittent validation failure."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q78","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A compromised developer workstation is suspected of signing malicious code with a legitimate certificate. What is the BEST immediate PKI action to reduce further damage?","options":[{"text":"Revoke the code-signing certificate and update validation systems so new signatures from that certificate are rejected","correct":true,"why":"If a code-signing key is compromised, revoke the cert (and rotate keys). Revocation stops future trust of that cert for signing."},{"text":"Block additional signatures from that identity and rotate trust material associated with the compromised signing workflow","correct":false,"why":"This restates a similar containment idea, but the most direct action is specifically revoking the certificate and updating validation systems to reject it going forward."},{"text":"Invalidate the abused signing identity quickly while preserving unaffected issuance paths and dependent trust relationships","correct":false,"why":"This is close, but the immediate priority action is directly revoking the specific abused certificate, not general preservation of unrelated issuance paths."},{"text":"Update validation policy to reject new artifacts from that signer while preserving evidence needed for prior trusted releases","correct":false,"why":"This focuses on preserving evidence for prior releases rather than the immediate priority of revoking the compromised certificate itself."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q79","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A project team proposes a control that reduces phishing success but requires storing additional user behavior telemetry. Privacy counsel warns this increases regulatory exposure. Which activity BEST balances security benefit with compliance obligations?","options":[{"text":"Conduct a privacy impact assessment and adjust data minimization and retention so the control objective is met with reduced collection","correct":true,"why":"Balancing security and privacy typically uses PIA/DPIA, data minimization, retention limits, and purpose limitation while still meeting control goals. PIA + minimization/retention tuning is the right governance move."},{"text":"Limit collection scope and retention using a documented privacy review so the detection goal is met with less data","correct":false,"why":"This restates a similar idea, but conducting a formal privacy impact assessment is the more complete, standard activity that directly evaluates and reduces the specific regulatory exposure raised."},{"text":"Adjust the control design through governance review so detection value is preserved without unnecessary data exposure","correct":false,"why":"Adjusting the control design through governance review is part of the process, but a formal privacy impact assessment is the more complete answer that directly addresses the counsel's specific concern."},{"text":"Apply purpose limitation and retention controls before expanding collection, even if processing remains externally hosted","correct":false,"why":"Applying purpose limitation before expanding collection is a good practice, but it doesn't specifically address conducting the privacy impact assessment the scenario calls for."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q80","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A team stores encrypted database backups. An attacker gains read access to the backup files but not to the key management system. Which security property is MOST directly being relied on?","options":[{"text":"Confidentiality because ciphertext without key material should be computationally infeasible to recover as plaintext","correct":true,"why":"Encryption protects secrecy; integrity requires authentication (e.g., AEAD/HMAC) and availability is a separate control objective. Encryption primarily provides confidentiality (without authentication)."},{"text":"Availability because backup encryption ensures restores can occur quickly even if production storage is destroyed","correct":false,"why":"Availability concerns whether backups can be restored, not whether an attacker without the key can read the ciphertext."},{"text":"Nonrepudiation because encrypted backups prove who created the files and prevent denial of authorship","correct":false,"why":"Nonrepudiation proves authorship of an action; it isn't what's being relied on when read access is blocked by lacking the decryption key."},{"text":"Integrity because encryption alone guarantees the backups cannot be altered without detection by the storage system","correct":false,"why":"Encryption alone doesn't guarantee tamper detection (integrity); it specifically protects confidentiality by keeping ciphertext unreadable without the key."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q81","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An enterprise wants to enforce that only managed devices can access sensitive web apps. They plan to use certificate-based auth on endpoints. Which operational requirement is MOST critical to make this effective at scale?","options":[{"text":"Maintain lifecycle management for device certificates including issuance, renewal, revocation, and inventory correlation","correct":true,"why":"Managed device assurance requires trustworthy issuance, enrollment, renewal, and rapid revocation tied to asset inventory and posture checks. Device cert auth lives or dies on lifecycle management and inventory mapping."},{"text":"Track certificate issuance, renewal, revocation, and asset ownership so device identity remains trustworthy over time","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same lifecycle idea in different words, but the more complete answer specifically ties revocation and renewal directly to asset inventory correlation for accurate trust decisions."},{"text":"Maintain certificate lifecycle and inventory binding so device trust decisions remain accurate at enterprise scale","correct":false,"why":"This also restates the lifecycle concept generally, without the specific rapid-revocation-tied-to-inventory detail that makes the correct answer the more precise operational requirement."},{"text":"Automate enrollment and retirement of endpoint identities so device-based access decisions stay current and enforceable","correct":false,"why":"Automating enrollment and retirement is one piece of lifecycle management, but omits the revocation and inventory-correlation elements the scenario specifically calls for at scale."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q82","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A vulnerability is exploitable only if an attacker is on the internal network. Network segmentation is planned but not yet deployed. Which factor should MOST influence the current risk rating?","options":[{"text":"Current exposure because compensating controls are not yet effective, increasing likelihood despite future segmentation plans","correct":true,"why":"Risk assessments typically consider existing controls and exposure. Risk is rated based on current state, not planned controls."},{"text":"Rate the weakness against today’s exposure and live controls, then record planned segmentation as future treatment work","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same idea using different phrasing, but the correct answer more precisely captures that current exposure and control effectiveness — not future plans — should drive today's rating."},{"text":"Use current network reachability and existing safeguards to set priority rather than assuming future segmentation already exists","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames the issue around 'reachability' rather than the specific factor of compensating controls not yet being effective, which is the more precise driver of current risk."},{"text":"Base prioritization on present access conditions and interim controls rather than on roadmap items or vulnerability age","correct":false,"why":"This focuses on excluding roadmap items and vulnerability age, but doesn't name the core reason — that compensating controls aren't yet effective — as directly as the correct answer."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q83","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An analyst observes a JWT-like token that is base64-encoded, signed, but not encrypted. The token contains user roles. What is the MOST accurate statement?","options":[{"text":"The token provides integrity and authenticity of claims, but confidentiality is not provided because the payload is readable","correct":true,"why":"A signature protects against modification and identifies issuer, but anyone can decode base64. Signed ≠ encrypted; base64 is not secrecy."},{"text":"The token provides confidentiality because the signature algorithm obfuscates claims during verification operations","correct":false,"why":"A signature does not obfuscate the payload at all; base64 encoding is trivially reversible, so confidentiality is never provided regardless of the signature."},{"text":"The token provides nonrepudiation because any party can verify the signature without trusting the issuer","correct":false,"why":"Nonrepudiation would require binding the signature to a specific identity beyond mere verifiability; the scenario doesn't establish that, and public verifiability isn't itself nonrepudiation."},{"text":"The token provides integrity only if the token is transmitted over cleartext to avoid man-in-the-middle tampering","correct":false,"why":"Integrity from a signature doesn't depend on the transport being cleartext; a signature verifies the payload wasn't altered whether the channel is encrypted or plaintext."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q84","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A CA issues certificates that include a policy OID to indicate they are valid only for client authentication. Which mechanism uses this information during validation?","options":[{"text":"Extended Key Usage constraints evaluated by the relying party to ensure the certificate is permitted for the intended purpose","correct":true,"why":"Relying parties validate intended usage using EKU (and sometimes policy constraints) to prevent misuse of a cert for an unauthorized purpose. EKU/policy constraints guide intended use checks."},{"text":"Key stretching parameters applied to the private key so it can be used for multiple purposes without reissuance","correct":false,"why":"Key stretching strengthens password-derived keys against brute force; it has no role in constraining what purpose a certificate may be used for."},{"text":"Certificate transparency logs that block certificates lacking OIDs when the chain is built during handshake","correct":false,"why":"Certificate transparency logs record issued certificates for public auditing; they don't enforce purpose restrictions like EKU during chain validation."},{"text":"Perfect forward secrecy settings that are negotiated based on OIDs to determine ephemeral key lengths","correct":false,"why":"Perfect forward secrecy concerns session key derivation during a TLS handshake; it isn't negotiated based on certificate policy OIDs."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q85","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An internal audit notes that risk treatment decisions are being made without documenting assumptions or control evidence. Which artifact MOST directly addresses this gap?","options":[{"text":"A risk acceptance memo that records rationale, assumptions, compensating controls, and sign-off by the risk owner","correct":true,"why":"Risk governance expects traceable decisions: rationale, assumptions, evidence, and formal approval from the accountable risk owner. Audit wants documented decision basis and approvals."},{"text":"A vulnerability scan report that lists CVEs with severities and provides a raw inventory of exposed assets","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability scan report lists technical findings, not the rationale, assumptions, and sign-off behind a risk treatment decision that the audit is asking for."},{"text":"A phishing simulation summary that reports click rates and highlights departments with higher susceptibility","correct":false,"why":"A phishing simulation summary measures user susceptibility; it doesn't document the reasoning or approval behind risk acceptance decisions."},{"text":"A network diagram that documents segmentation boundaries and highlights where sensitive systems are located","correct":false,"why":"A network diagram shows topology and segmentation; it contains no record of the decision rationale or accountable sign-off the audit gap requires."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q86","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A monitoring tool flags that a service uses RSA key exchange instead of (EC)DHE. What security drawback is MOST relevant to incident response when traffic has been captured?","options":[{"text":"Captured traffic may be decrypted later if the server’s private key is compromised because forward secrecy is not provided","correct":true,"why":"Without ephemeral DH, compromise of the long-term private key can expose previously recorded sessions, impacting retrospective investigations. Static RSA key exchange lacks forward secrecy."},{"text":"Captured traffic becomes unavailable for forensics because RSA prevents lawful decryption even with proper authorization","correct":false,"why":"Lawful decryption authorization is a legal/procedural matter, not something RSA key exchange technically prevents; the actual issue is that captured ciphertext can be decrypted later if the key leaks."},{"text":"Captured traffic loses integrity because RSA key exchange disables authenticated encryption modes during data transfer","correct":false,"why":"RSA key exchange doesn't disable authenticated encryption modes; integrity protection for the session data is unaffected by the key exchange method choice."},{"text":"Captured traffic cannot be replayed by attackers because RSA ensures unique nonces are embedded into each packet","correct":false,"why":"Nonce handling for replay protection is unrelated to the key exchange algorithm; RSA key exchange doesn't provide or remove nonce-based replay protection."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q87","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A security team receives reports that OCSP responses are failing during an outage, causing client connection failures. What is the BEST resilience improvement?","options":[{"text":"Enable OCSP stapling where appropriate and ensure servers present fresh stapled responses to reduce client dependency on responders","correct":true,"why":"Stapling reduces reliance on external OCSP responders and can improve connection reliability when responders are unreachable. Stapling improves availability by bundling revocation status."},{"text":"Disable revocation checking entirely because revocation is optional and should never block mission-critical services","correct":false,"why":"Revocation checking is a security requirement precisely because it blocks compromised certificates; disabling it entirely removes protection rather than improving resilience."},{"text":"Increase CRL publication frequency to hourly so OCSP responders have less work and clients do not time out","correct":false,"why":"More frequent CRL publication doesn't reduce client-side dependency on reaching an OCSP responder during an outage; stapling addresses that dependency directly."},{"text":"Replace PKI with pre-shared keys so revocation is unnecessary and certificates are no longer required","correct":false,"why":"Replacing PKI with pre-shared keys is a drastic architecture change that abandons certificate-based authentication entirely rather than improving OCSP resilience."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q88","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A SOC recommends deploying a new DLP control, but the business unit refuses due to user friction. Which statement BEST represents a mature risk decision workflow?","options":[{"text":"Escalate the exception to the accountable owner, record the basis for the decision, and schedule periodic re-evaluation","correct":true,"why":"Risk treatment requires accountable ownership. Risk owner sign-off + documentation + periodic review is mature governance."},{"text":"Route the disagreement through formal governance so business impact and exposure are weighed by the accountable owner","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same governance idea in different words, but the correct answer specifically calls out escalating to the accountable owner with documented rationale and scheduled re-evaluation as the concrete workflow."},{"text":"Preserve decision traceability through formal exception handling instead of equating resistance to elimination of exposure","correct":false,"why":"This focuses on traceability broadly, but doesn't specify the concrete steps of escalation, documentation, and periodic review that define the mature workflow."},{"text":"Document the treatment path under the accountable owner instead of shifting acceptance to a team without business authority","correct":false,"why":"This is close but doesn't mention the periodic re-evaluation step, which is part of what makes the treatment decision a mature, ongoing governance process."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q89","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"An engineer suggests using encryption to ensure integrity of messages between microservices. Which correction is MOST accurate if the design currently lacks authentication?","options":[{"text":"Encryption alone does not guarantee integrity; use an AEAD mode or add a keyed integrity mechanism to detect tampering","correct":true,"why":"Without authentication, attackers can modify ciphertext (malleability). Confidentiality ≠ integrity; add AEAD/HMAC."},{"text":"Encryption guarantees integrity as long as keys are rotated quarterly and the cipher suite uses at least 128-bit keys","correct":false,"why":"Key rotation cadence and key length don't create integrity; without a keyed MAC or AEAD mode, ciphertext can still be modified undetected regardless of rotation schedule."},{"text":"Integrity is a property of base64 encoding layered on top of encryption and therefore does not require additional controls","correct":false,"why":"Base64 is a plain encoding scheme with no cryptographic properties; it provides no integrity protection at all, layered or otherwise."},{"text":"Integrity is provided by TLS version negotiation, so message-level integrity controls are redundant and unnecessary","correct":false,"why":"TLS protects the transport channel between two points, not the message itself; it doesn't provide end-to-end integrity between microservices when messages pass through intermediaries."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q90","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A certificate is revoked, but software signed before revocation continues to validate due to trusted timestamps. What does this behavior MOST indicate?","options":[{"text":"Timestamping preserves trust for signatures created while the certificate was valid, depending on validation policy","correct":true,"why":"Many code-signing ecosystems accept a signature if it was timestamped during the cert validity period, even if the cert is later revoked. Trusted timestamps allow validation after expiration/revocation under some policies."},{"text":"Revocation is ignored for code-signing and only applies to TLS server authentication use cases","correct":false,"why":"Revocation checking applies broadly across use cases, including code-signing; it isn't limited to TLS server authentication only."},{"text":"The signature is invalid because timestamps always invalidate signatures after a certificate is revoked","correct":false,"why":"Trusted timestamping is specifically designed to let a signature remain valid for the period before revocation, so the signature isn't automatically invalidated by a later revocation."},{"text":"The certificate was never actually revoked because OCSP responders cannot return revoked status for code signing","correct":false,"why":"OCSP responders can and do return a revoked status for code-signing certificates; the certificate being revoked and the signature remaining valid are not contradictory under a timestamping policy."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q91","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A BIA identifies that a customer portal outage costs $50,000 per hour in lost revenue. The estimated maximum tolerable downtime is 2 hours. Which statement best aligns with using BIA outputs in risk management?","options":[{"text":"Use cost-of-downtime and tolerance thresholds to rank resilience work that lowers impact and meets recovery targets","correct":true,"why":"BIA informs RTO/RPO priorities and helps justify controls/resilience investments to meet business tolerance and reduce impact. BIA outputs drive prioritization and continuity targets."},{"text":"Translate business impact findings into resilience priorities and recovery expectations rather than into unrelated technical settings","correct":false,"why":"This restates the correct idea in similar words, but doesn't explicitly tie the cost-of-downtime figure to justifying and sequencing resilience investment the way the correct answer does."},{"text":"Apply downtime tolerance to continuity planning and control prioritization rather than to reduction of detection capability","correct":false,"why":"This focuses on excluding detection-capability reduction, but doesn't capture the core point of using the BIA figures to prioritize continuity investment and recovery targets."},{"text":"Use the impact estimate to justify resilience investment and sequencing, not as a reason to leave outage exposure untreated","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames the answer mainly as what not to do, rather than directly describing how the cost and tolerance figures should drive resilience prioritization."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q92","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A team wants to detect unauthorized changes to configuration files while also ensuring only approved automation can update them. Which solution BEST meets both objectives?","options":[{"text":"Use a keyed hash (HMAC) so authorized automation can generate the tag and verifiers can detect tampering","correct":true,"why":"HMAC validates content integrity and proves possession of the shared secret by the automation, meeting both tamper detection and authorized update goals. HMAC provides integrity + authenticity of the updater."},{"text":"Use a checksum so random errors are detected quickly without requiring key management overhead","correct":false,"why":"A plain checksum only catches accidental corruption; it has no secret key, so it can't prove the update came from authorized automation."},{"text":"Use symmetric encryption so files are unreadable and therefore cannot be modified by unauthorized users","correct":false,"why":"Symmetric encryption for confidentiality doesn't inherently detect tampering, and readability isn't the actual goal here — verifying authorized changes and detecting tampering are."},{"text":"Use compression so the file format changes with each update and reduces the chance of undetected edits","correct":false,"why":"Compression changes file size and format but provides no cryptographic guarantee that unauthorized edits will be detected."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q93","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A security team needs to ensure subordinate CAs cannot issue certificates for unauthorized namespaces. Which PKI control MOST directly restricts this capability?","options":[{"text":"Name constraints applied to an intermediate CA certificate to limit the permitted DNS/email namespaces it can issue for","correct":true,"why":"Name constraints are designed to constrain subordinate CA issuance, preventing it from minting certs outside approved namespaces. Name constraints restrict issuance scope for sub-CAs."},{"text":"Key usage bits set to digitalSignature so the intermediate can sign only data and not certificates","correct":false,"why":"The digitalSignature key usage bit controls whether a certificate can sign data versus other operations; it doesn't restrict which namespaces a subordinate CA may issue certificates for."},{"text":"CRL distribution points removed so subordinate CAs cannot publish revocation data to external endpoints","correct":false,"why":"Removing CRL distribution points affects how revocation status is published, not what namespaces an intermediate CA is authorized to issue certificates within."},{"text":"Subject alternative name removed from end-entity certs so namespace validation no longer applies in clients","correct":false,"why":"Removing SAN from end-entity certificates would break normal hostname validation entirely; it doesn't address restricting a subordinate CA's issuance scope."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q94","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A remediation backlog is triaged using both CVSS and asset criticality. A medium-severity vulnerability exists on a system supporting regulated data with high business impact. What is the MOST appropriate treatment decision approach?","options":[{"text":"Prioritize remediation based on contextual risk by combining technical severity, exposure, and business impact rather than CVSS alone","correct":true,"why":"CVSS is a starting point. Contextual risk beats raw CVSS for prioritization."},{"text":"Defer remediation because medium CVSS indicates the vulnerability is not urgent and likely has no practical exploitation path","correct":false,"why":"Deferring based on medium CVSS alone ignores the regulated-data and high-business-impact context that make this vulnerability more urgent than its raw score suggests."},{"text":"Ignore asset criticality to ensure objective scoring and prevent business stakeholders from influencing security priorities","correct":false,"why":"Ignoring asset criticality to preserve 'objective' scoring throws away exactly the contextual information — like regulated data and business impact — that should inform prioritization."},{"text":"Treat the vulnerability as accepted risk because regulated systems already have compliance controls that negate exploitation","correct":false,"why":"Treating this as accepted risk based on existing compliance controls assumes those controls fully mitigate the vulnerability without any actual verification."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q95","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A SOC analyst suspects a downgrade and notices the server accepts 3DES in a fallback path. What is the BEST immediate hardening step?","options":[{"text":"Disable weak ciphers and fallback negotiation paths, then validate only modern suites with strong authenticated encryption","correct":true,"why":"Hardening focuses on disabling weak suites and protocol downgrade paths; modern AEAD ciphers and current protocol versions are preferred. Remove weak cipher and fallback path immediately."},{"text":"Increase certificate validity from 90 days to 2 years to reduce renegotiation frequency and stabilize handshakes","correct":false,"why":"Extending certificate validity has nothing to do with removing weak cipher suites; it doesn't address the 3DES fallback path at all."},{"text":"Switch to a larger RSA modulus so 3DES sessions inherit stronger cryptographic properties from the certificate","correct":false,"why":"A larger RSA modulus strengthens key exchange but doesn't remove 3DES from the negotiable cipher list or prevent the downgrade fallback."},{"text":"Enable plaintext HTTP on internal routes so clients do not need to negotiate cryptographic parameters at all","correct":false,"why":"Enabling plaintext HTTP removes encryption entirely, which is a severe regression rather than a hardening step against a downgrade attack."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q96","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A PKI admin wants to reduce the blast radius if an intermediate CA is compromised. Which architecture BEST supports this objective?","options":[{"text":"Use multiple intermediates segmented by environment and purpose, with constrained issuance policies and limited validity periods","correct":true,"why":"Separating intermediates by function/environment limits impact; constraints and shorter validity help contain and recover from compromise. Segmentation + constraints reduces compromise blast radius."},{"text":"Use a single enterprise intermediate for all use cases so revocation is centralized and easier to manage","correct":false,"why":"A single enterprise intermediate for everything means a compromise affects all use cases at once, which is the opposite of limiting blast radius."},{"text":"Issue end-entity certificates directly from the root CA so chain length is shorter and validation is faster","correct":false,"why":"Issuing end-entity certificates directly from the root increases risk, since any operational compromise would then endanger the root itself rather than a replaceable intermediate."},{"text":"Disable intermediate CA keys from signing certificates and use them only for signing application data","correct":false,"why":"Disabling intermediate CA keys from signing certificates would break their core function; it doesn't achieve segmentation of risk by environment or purpose."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q97","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A threat model identifies credential stuffing as a top threat for a customer login portal. Which control selection BEST reflects reducing likelihood while preserving user experience?","options":[{"text":"Implement adaptive rate limiting and bot detection with risk-based step-up authentication for anomalous login patterns","correct":true,"why":"Credential stuffing is mitigated by throttling automation and adding step-up auth when risk signals trigger, reducing success while minimizing friction for legitimate users. Adaptive throttling + bot detection + step-up MFA is a practical balance."},{"text":"Require long complex passwords and mandatory rotation every 30 days to ensure unique credentials across all services","correct":false,"why":"Long complex passwords and frequent rotation add user friction and don't specifically throttle automated credential-stuffing attempts."},{"text":"Disable password login entirely and require users to call the help desk for one-time access codes during business hours","correct":false,"why":"Disabling password login and requiring help-desk calls creates significant friction and operational burden, which conflicts with the goal of preserving user experience."},{"text":"Allow unlimited login attempts but increase monitoring so incidents are detected quickly and handled after compromise","correct":false,"why":"Allowing unlimited attempts does nothing to reduce the likelihood of successful credential stuffing; it only adds after-the-fact detection."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q98","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A developer claims that using SHA-1 for digital signatures is acceptable because signatures are not used for password storage. What is the BEST rebuttal?","options":[{"text":"Weak collision resistance can enable signature forgery or substitution attacks, so deprecated hashes are risky beyond passwords","correct":true,"why":"Digital signatures hash the message; collision weaknesses can allow crafted messages that share a hash, undermining signature trust. Collision attacks threaten signatures, not just password hashing."},{"text":"SHA-1 is only weak when used with symmetric encryption and is safe when paired with public key algorithms","correct":false,"why":"Hash function weaknesses affect any algorithm pairing that relies on the hash, including public key signature schemes; SHA-1's weakness isn't limited to symmetric encryption use."},{"text":"Signature security depends only on key size, and the hash function choice does not affect verification integrity","correct":false,"why":"Verification integrity depends on both key size and the underlying hash function; a weak hash can be exploited regardless of key size."},{"text":"SHA-1 is acceptable if the message is short because collisions become infeasible when data length is reduced","correct":false,"why":"Collision attacks against SHA-1 are practical against various message lengths; short messages don't make crafting a colliding pair infeasible."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q99","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A company uses client certs for VPN access. They want to immediately disable access for terminated users. Which factor MOST affects how quickly that takes effect?","options":[{"text":"How revocation status is checked and cached, including CRL/OCSP refresh intervals and client behavior","correct":true,"why":"Immediate disablement depends on revocation checking mechanics and caches. Revocation propagation hinges on checking/caching behavior."},{"text":"The signature algorithm on the certificate, because ECDSA revocations propagate faster than RSA revocations","correct":false,"why":"Signature algorithm choice (ECDSA vs RSA) doesn't affect how quickly revocation status propagates; that depends on CRL/OCSP checking and caching behavior."},{"text":"The size of the public key, because larger keys allow revocation to be computed more quickly by clients","correct":false,"why":"Public key size affects cryptographic strength, not how quickly a client learns that a certificate has been revoked."},{"text":"The certificate common name format, because structured naming accelerates revocation processing on endpoints","correct":false,"why":"Common name formatting has no bearing on revocation checking speed; it's a naming convention, not a mechanism for propagating revocation status."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q100","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A policy requires encryption for data at rest. A database team claims they comply because storage is encrypted, but backups are copied to a third-party without encryption. Which assessment conclusion is MOST accurate?","options":[{"text":"The control objective is not fully met because encryption must apply across the data lifecycle, including backups and third-party storage","correct":true,"why":"Encryption-at-rest requirements generally include backups, replicas, exports, and third-party storage locations unless explicitly scoped out. Backups are still data at rest; lifecycle scope matters."},{"text":"The requirement remains unmet when derivative copies outside the protected storage path are left without equivalent safeguards","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same conclusion but doesn't explicitly identify backups and third-party storage as the specific gap driving the assessment result."},{"text":"Assess the full data lifecycle, including exported copies and hosted backups, rather than limiting scope to primary storage","correct":false,"why":"This is close but focuses on describing the assessment method broadly rather than concluding that the control objective is currently unmet because of the backup gap."},{"text":"Validate the control against all resting data locations, including third-party backup repositories and exported artifacts","correct":false,"why":"This describes a validation action to take, but doesn't state the actual conclusion that the encryption control objective is not fully met as things stand."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q101","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cryptography","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A service uses AES-GCM but developers reuse nonces due to a bug. What is the MOST likely security impact?","options":[{"text":"Confidentiality and integrity can both fail because nonce reuse can enable tag forgery and plaintext recovery in GCM","correct":true,"why":"GCM requires unique nonces per key; reuse can leak information and allow attackers to forge valid tags under certain conditions. GCM nonce reuse is catastrophic for both secrecy and authenticity."},{"text":"Only availability is impacted because nonce reuse primarily causes decryption errors and forces session renegotiation","correct":false,"why":"Nonce reuse in GCM is a cryptographic weakness, not simply a cause of decryption errors requiring renegotiation; it can silently leak plaintext data."},{"text":"Only confidentiality fails while integrity remains intact because authentication tags are independent of nonce values","correct":false,"why":"GCM's authentication tag computation depends on the nonce; reusing nonces can allow tag forgery, so integrity is also at risk, not just confidentiality."},{"text":"Nonces are optional metadata in GCM and reuse has no effect if the key is rotated on a monthly schedule","correct":false,"why":"Nonces are a required, security-critical part of GCM's construction; monthly key rotation doesn't offset the harm from reusing a nonce under the same key."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q102","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Public Key Infrastructure","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A company is migrating from an internal CA to a managed CA. They worry about trust continuity for endpoints that cannot be updated quickly. What is the BEST transitional strategy?","options":[{"text":"Cross-sign or chain through a trusted intermediate while planning staged trust store updates to preserve validation during migration","correct":true,"why":"Migration often uses cross-signed intermediates or dual chains to maintain compatibility until trust stores can be updated everywhere. Cross-signing/compat chains maintain trust while endpoints update."},{"text":"Disable certificate validation temporarily so endpoints remain connected while the migration completes in the background","correct":false,"why":"Disabling certificate validation removes a critical security control and exposes endpoints to impersonation; it doesn't preserve trust, it eliminates it."},{"text":"Reuse the old private keys with the managed CA so the same certificates remain valid without endpoint changes","correct":false,"why":"Reusing old private keys with a new CA doesn't address trust store compatibility for endpoints that can't be updated quickly, and reusing keys across CAs is poor key hygiene."},{"text":"Issue self-signed certificates for all services so endpoints do not need to trust any external or internal CA","correct":false,"why":"Issuing self-signed certificates for all services abandons the CA trust model entirely and would break validation for any endpoint expecting a chain to a trusted root."}],"sub":"1.6"},{"id":"q103","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","source":"CySA_Day 1.html","q":"A team measures the effectiveness of a new control and finds it reduces alert volume but does not reduce confirmed incident count. What is the BEST interpretation?","options":[{"text":"The control may be reducing noise rather than risk, so effectiveness testing should focus on likelihood/impact metrics tied to incidents","correct":true,"why":"Control effectiveness should be measured against risk outcomes (incidents, impact) not only operational metrics (alert volume). Less noise is good, but risk reduction must be validated by incident outcomes."},{"text":"The control is fully effective because fewer alerts always indicates fewer attacks and therefore fewer incidents overall","correct":false,"why":"Fewer alerts don't always mean fewer actual attacks; the control could simply be suppressing detections without reducing real risk, which is exactly why incident-based validation is needed."},{"text":"The control is ineffective because reducing alert volume indicates the SOC is blind to attacks and cannot detect incidents","correct":false,"why":"Reduced alert volume doesn't necessarily mean the SOC is blind to attacks; it could equally reflect the control successfully filtering noise, so this conclusion isn't supported either."},{"text":"The control proves risk is transferred because operational workload decreased and responsibility is now externalized","correct":false,"why":"Reduced operational workload isn't evidence of risk transfer; nothing in the scenario describes shifting responsibility to a third party."}],"sub":"4.1"},{"id":"q104","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Credentialed vs Non)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A vulnerability scan shows few findings on Windows servers, but patch levels are unknown and local configurations are not assessed. Which change MOST improves accuracy?","options":[{"text":"Run credentialed scans to validate patch status and configuration posture with authenticated host checks.","correct":true,"why":"Credentialed scans can check installed patches, registry/config settings, local services, and missing updates more reliably."},{"text":"Enable authenticated patch auditing using a management agent and compare results against the scan output.","correct":false,"why":"This restates a similar authenticated-checking idea but doesn't specifically call out running credentialed scans as the direct fix, instead adding an extra comparison step."},{"text":"Validate missing patches by checking installed KBs and registry evidence on a sample of affected hosts.","correct":false,"why":"Manually checking a sample of hosts doesn't scale or replace the systematic authenticated scanning needed to validate patch and configuration posture enterprise-wide."},{"text":"Augment results with configuration benchmarks and local policy checks using a trusted hardening baseline.","correct":false,"why":"Adding configuration benchmarks addresses only part of the gap; it doesn't resolve the core issue of unknown patch levels without authenticated, credentialed checks."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q105","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Rules of Engagement)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"Before beginning a penetration test, the client requires clarity on allowed attack methods, scope, and how to handle sensitive data if found. What document BEST defines this?","options":[{"text":"Rules of Engagement (RoE) and scope statement defining targets, methods, timing, and handling requirements.","correct":true,"why":"RoE/scope documents define what is authorized, what is out of scope, and the boundaries for testing and data handling."},{"text":"Statement of Work outlining deliverables, milestones, staffing, and reporting expectations for the engagement.","correct":false,"why":"A Statement of Work covers deliverables and staffing, not the specific authorized methods, scope boundaries, and data-handling rules the client is asking about."},{"text":"Master service agreement covering commercial terms, liability, and general legal conditions across services.","correct":false,"why":"A master service agreement covers commercial and legal terms broadly; it doesn't define the technical scope or permitted testing methods for this engagement."},{"text":"Change request documenting windows, approvers, and communications for the activity being scheduled.","correct":false,"why":"A change request documents scheduling and approvals for a specific activity; it doesn't establish the overall boundaries and data-handling rules for the whole test."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q106","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Prioritization)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A scanner reports 30 high CVSS findings, but only 5 affect internet-facing critical systems with known exploitation in the wild. What is the BEST prioritization approach?","options":[{"text":"Prioritize based on asset criticality, exposure, exploitability, and threat intelligence, not CVSS alone.","correct":true,"why":"Risk-based prioritization considers business criticality, internet exposure, exploit availability, and active threat context."},{"text":"Rank by base severity first, then work down the list uniformly across all affected systems.","correct":false,"why":"Ranking purely by base severity ignores that only a handful of the 30 findings are actually internet-facing with known active exploitation, which matters more than raw CVSS."},{"text":"Prioritize by platform standardization so the same remediation can be applied broadly with minimal effort.","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing for platform standardization optimizes remediation convenience, not actual risk reduction based on exposure and exploitation likelihood."},{"text":"Focus on issues with the lowest remediation effort to improve backlog metrics before deeper risk review.","correct":false,"why":"Focusing on the lowest-effort fixes first could leave the 5 actively exploited, internet-facing critical systems unpatched while easier but lower-risk items are resolved."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q107","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Authorization)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A tester discovers a new subnet during reconnaissance that was not listed in the engagement scope. What should the tester do NEXT?","options":[{"text":"Stop and request written authorization/scope update before testing the newly discovered subnet.","correct":true,"why":"Testing outside authorized scope is not permitted."},{"text":"Capture the route and limited host details for the subnet, then fold it into the engagement notes for later approval.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing details about an out-of-scope subnet and proceeding with notes still involves interacting with unauthorized systems before approval is granted."},{"text":"Treat the subnet as tentatively related infrastructure and continue with low-noise validation while awaiting guidance.","correct":false,"why":"Continuing with low-noise validation still constitutes testing against assets outside the authorized scope, which isn't permitted regardless of how subtle the technique is."},{"text":"Perform only light-touch enumeration on the subnet so the client can decide later whether to include it.","correct":false,"why":"Light-touch enumeration is still active engagement with an unauthorized target; scope violations aren't resolved by reducing technique intensity."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q108","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (False Positives)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A vulnerability scanner flags a critical RCE on a server, but the service banner suggests an older version while package updates are backported. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Validate the finding using authenticated checks, vendor advisories, and targeted verification rather than trusting banners alone.","correct":true,"why":"Banner/version checks can mislead due to backports."},{"text":"Keep the finding at high priority while awaiting host-side package evidence from the system owner.","correct":false,"why":"Keeping the finding at high priority without independent verification risks acting on a false positive caused by the misleading version banner."},{"text":"Mark the result as tentative and compare scanner logic with distribution-specific package versioning details.","correct":false,"why":"Comparing scanner logic against distribution package versions is a partial step but doesn't substitute for the direct validation the situation calls for."},{"text":"Run a second unauthenticated scan from another vantage point to see whether the banner mismatch persists.","correct":false,"why":"A second unauthenticated scan would likely see the same misleading banner information and wouldn't resolve the underlying banner-versus-backport discrepancy."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q109","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Safe Testing)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A client’s production system is fragile, and the team wants to avoid outages while still assessing security. What testing approach BEST reduces risk?","options":[{"text":"Use non-destructive validation and exploit-proof-of-concept in a staging environment when possible, with careful RoE constraints.","correct":true,"why":"Reduce risk using staging, non-destructive checks, controlled testing, and careful scheduling/limits defined in RoE."},{"text":"Limit testing in production to tightly scoped validation during a maintenance window with rollback contacts ready.","correct":false,"why":"Limiting to a maintenance window still tests directly in the fragile production environment, carrying more outage risk than validating in staging first."},{"text":"Use authenticated review and configuration inspection in production, deferring invasive validation until later.","correct":false,"why":"Configuration inspection alone, while safe, defers the actual security validation the assessment needs rather than finding a way to safely perform it."},{"text":"Schedule broader validation for a low-usage period in production and rely on change controls to manage risk.","correct":false,"why":"Relying on low-usage timing and change controls still means testing occurs in production, retaining outage risk that staging validation would avoid."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q110","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Remediation Validation)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A team claims a critical vulnerability is remediated, but leadership wants proof. What is the BEST verification?","options":[{"text":"Rescan or retest the specific finding with authenticated evidence and confirm the vulnerable condition no longer exists.","correct":true,"why":"Verification requires evidence: rescans, authenticated checks, and confirming the condition is truly mitigated."},{"text":"Review change records and closure evidence from the platform team before determining whether retesting is necessary.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing change records and closure evidence relies on secondhand documentation rather than direct, authenticated proof that the vulnerable condition is gone."},{"text":"Obtain owner attestation plus implementation notes, then sample a subset of systems for spot-check confirmation.","correct":false,"why":"Owner attestation and spot-checking a subset leaves some remediated systems unverified, which doesn't provide the complete proof leadership is asking for."},{"text":"Validate at the next scheduled scan cycle and compare results against the original affected asset list.","correct":false,"why":"Waiting for the next scheduled scan cycle delays confirmation rather than actively verifying the specific finding leadership wants resolved now."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q111","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Reporting)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A penetration test report should be actionable for both executives and technical teams. Which structure BEST supports this?","options":[{"text":"Executive summary + risk narrative, followed by technical details, reproduction steps, evidence, and prioritized remediation.","correct":true,"why":"Good reports include an executive view and deep technical guidance (steps, evidence, impact, and prioritized fixes)."},{"text":"Lead with detailed technical findings and append a short summary section for leadership at the end of the report.","correct":false,"why":"Leading with technical details and appending only a short executive note at the end makes the report harder for executives to consume quickly, the opposite of the target structure."},{"text":"Produce a high-level risk summary with impact statements and keep technical validation in a separate appendix only.","correct":false,"why":"Keeping technical validation solely in an appendix separates the evidence from the findings, making it harder for technical teams to act efficiently."},{"text":"Organize findings by asset group and service owner, leaving prioritization to remediation teams after review.","correct":false,"why":"Organizing purely by asset group and deferring prioritization to remediation teams leaves the report without the clear risk-based prioritization both audiences need."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q112","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Scope & Asset Inventory)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A quarterly scan misses several critical servers because they were not in the scanner’s target list. What program gap does this MOST indicate?","options":[{"text":"Incomplete asset inventory and scope management; integrate discovery/CMDB and continuous inventory updates.","correct":true,"why":"If systems are missing from scope, the core issue is asset inventory and scope governance, not scan frequency."},{"text":"Increase scan cadence and add recurring discovery jobs so newly active systems are noticed more quickly.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing scan cadence doesn't help if the servers were never in the scanner's target list to begin with; the root problem is scope, not frequency."},{"text":"Rely more heavily on external attack-surface scanning to identify systems before updating internal targets.","correct":false,"why":"Relying more on external attack-surface scanning doesn't fix the internal target list gap that caused these critical servers to be missed."},{"text":"Expand network ranges broadly to reduce misses, then refine the target set after reviewing the results.","correct":false,"why":"Broadly expanding ranges without fixing the underlying inventory process risks continued gaps and doesn't establish a durable, accurate asset list."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q113","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Black/Gray/White Box)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A client wants testers to simulate an external attacker with no internal knowledge, but still remain within defined targets. What test type BEST matches?","options":[{"text":"Black-box (or external) testing with limited knowledge, constrained by an explicit scope and RoE.","correct":true,"why":"Black-box simulates an outsider with minimal knowledge."},{"text":"Gray-box testing using a minimal target list and externally observable information supplied by the client.","correct":false,"why":"Gray-box testing explicitly involves giving testers some internal information; the scenario specifically calls for no internal knowledge, which points to black-box instead."},{"text":"External assessment with sanitized architecture context so testers can avoid nonessential reconnaissance steps.","correct":false,"why":"Providing sanitized architecture context still gives testers privileged information an external attacker wouldn't have, conflicting with the 'no internal knowledge' requirement."},{"text":"Adversary simulation with strict objectives and time limits designed to evaluate layered detection and response.","correct":false,"why":"Adversary simulation focuses on evaluating detection and response over time; it isn't defined by the no-internal-knowledge constraint the scenario describes."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q114","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (CVSS Limits)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"Why is CVSS alone insufficient for enterprise remediation prioritization?","options":[{"text":"CVSS lacks business context such as asset criticality, compensating controls, exposure, and active exploitation conditions.","correct":true,"why":"Risk-based decisions require more than severity: exposure, exploitability, asset value, and compensating controls matter."},{"text":"CVSS is useful for technical severity, but it does not directly rank business disruption across different assets.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames CVSS as merely lacking a business-disruption ranking, rather than the broader point that it lacks business context like exposure and compensating controls."},{"text":"CVSS normalizes vulnerability characteristics, while exposure and environmental context still require local interpretation.","correct":false,"why":"This describes CVSS as needing local interpretation but doesn't state as directly that CVSS itself lacks the business-context factors needed for prioritization."},{"text":"CVSS should be one input among several because different teams may weigh operational constraints differently.","correct":false,"why":"This frames CVSS as one input teams may weigh differently, which is true but less precise than stating CVSS specifically lacks business-criticality and exploitation context."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q115","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Social Engineering)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"The scope includes phishing simulations, but the client wants to avoid collecting real user passwords. What is the BEST approach?","options":[{"text":"Use controlled landing pages that record clicks and MFA prompts without capturing credentials, as defined in RoE.","correct":true,"why":"Phishing can measure susceptibility without collecting sensitive credentials."},{"text":"Use a full credential capture workflow against a small pilot group and immediately reset any submitted passwords.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing real credentials even briefly, even from a small pilot group, still collects sensitive data the client explicitly wants to avoid gathering."},{"text":"Provide a mock sign-in experience that records username entry only so user susceptibility can still be measured.","correct":false,"why":"Recording username entry still captures potentially sensitive account information; it doesn't fully avoid capturing user credentials as requested."},{"text":"Capture submissions into a segmented test environment with automatic purge controls after the exercise window closes.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing submissions at all, even with a later purge, still means credentials were collected and stored temporarily, contrary to the client's requirement to avoid that entirely."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q116","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Authenticated Evidence)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A scanner reports “SMB signing not required” on servers. What is the BEST way to validate and document this finding?","options":[{"text":"Confirm via authenticated configuration checks (GPO/registry) and capture evidence showing the effective SMB signing setting.","correct":true,"why":"Configuration findings are best validated with authenticated checks and evidence of effective settings (GPO/registry/policy)."},{"text":"Confirm through packet-level negotiation behavior and compare the result with a second scanner plugin.","correct":false,"why":"Packet-level negotiation behavior can reflect what a client offers, not necessarily the server's configured, effective policy; it doesn't reliably confirm the actual GPO/registry setting."},{"text":"Use the scanner evidence plus host-owner screenshots from local security policy to support the write-up.","correct":false,"why":"Host-owner screenshots alone aren't independently verified evidence; authenticated configuration checks provide a more reliable, direct confirmation of the effective setting."},{"text":"Request an administrator-provided export of the effective setting and reconcile it with scan results.","correct":false,"why":"An administrator-provided export still relies on manual reporting rather than the tester directly confirming the effective setting via authenticated checks."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q117","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Exploitation Ethics)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A tester identifies an RCE vulnerability on a critical production server. The RoE prohibits exploitation that could impact availability. What is the BEST action?","options":[{"text":"Document the vulnerability with evidence and use non-destructive validation or safe PoC in staging if approved.","correct":true,"why":"Follow RoE."},{"text":"Use the least invasive validation available on production to demonstrate exploitability while minimizing execution risk.","correct":false,"why":"Using the 'least invasive' technique in production still risks impacting availability, which the RoE explicitly prohibits regardless of how minimal the technique seems."},{"text":"Attempt controlled exploitation during an approved change window with rollback support standing by if needed.","correct":false,"why":"Attempting exploitation even during an approved change window still violates the RoE's prohibition on availability-impacting exploitation of this production server."},{"text":"Shift validation to a lower-usage period and coordinate with contacts so any instability can be handled promptly.","correct":false,"why":"Shifting to a lower-usage period doesn't remove the availability risk; the RoE prohibits this kind of exploitation on this server regardless of timing."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q118","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Compensating Controls)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A critical vulnerability cannot be patched for 60 days due to vendor constraints. What is the BEST interim risk reduction strategy?","options":[{"text":"Apply compensating controls: segmentation, WAF/IPS rules, hardening, access restrictions, and monitoring until patched.","correct":true,"why":"When patching is delayed, implement compensating controls and increase monitoring to reduce exploitability."},{"text":"Document the exception, raise monitoring coverage, and wait for the patch release before making network changes.","correct":false,"why":"Simply documenting the exception and waiting increases exposure for 60 days without taking any active steps to reduce the actual risk in the meantime."},{"text":"Increase validation frequency and threat monitoring so any attempted exploitation is detected while awaiting the fix.","correct":false,"why":"Increased monitoring alone helps detect exploitation attempts but doesn't reduce the underlying exploitability of the vulnerability while the patch is pending."},{"text":"Reduce exposure through tighter access governance and operational restrictions until the permanent remediation is available.","correct":false,"why":"Tighter access governance alone is only one compensating measure; it omits the broader set of controls (segmentation, WAF/IPS, hardening) needed for adequate interim risk reduction."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q119","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Pivoting Scope)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"During an internal test, you compromise a workstation and can reach a database subnet not listed in scope. The client’s contact is unavailable. What should you do?","options":[{"text":"Stop further actions against out-of-scope assets and document access potential, then seek formal approval to proceed.","correct":true,"why":"Even if reachable, out-of-scope assets require explicit authorization."},{"text":"Map reachable assets from the compromised host and document the path, but defer direct interaction pending clarification.","correct":false,"why":"Mapping reachable assets and documenting the path still involves actively probing an out-of-scope database subnet before authorization is obtained."},{"text":"Perform limited service enumeration only, then pause before any deeper validation against the database segment.","correct":false,"why":"Limited service enumeration is still direct interaction with an unauthorized asset; scope boundaries aren't satisfied by reducing enumeration depth."},{"text":"Validate connectivity and authentication potential without touching records, then seek retrospective authorization.","correct":false,"why":"Validating connectivity and authentication potential is still active engagement with an out-of-scope system; seeking authorization afterward doesn't make the prior action permitted."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q120","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Scanner Safety)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A legacy OT device crashes during scans. How should vulnerability assessment be performed going forward?","options":[{"text":"Use passive discovery, vendor-approved methods, maintenance windows, and a separate OT-safe assessment plan in scope.","correct":true,"why":"OT systems may be fragile."},{"text":"Use vendor-tuned scan profiles and very limited maintenance-window testing for only the most critical checks.","correct":false,"why":"Vendor-tuned profiles still involve active scanning against a device already known to crash under scan traffic, risking another crash even if scope is narrowed."},{"text":"Rely on architecture review and asset owner interviews for most systems, reserving active validation for exceptions.","correct":false,"why":"Relying mainly on interviews and reserving active validation for exceptions still risks triggering the crash whenever active checks are eventually performed on the fragile device."},{"text":"Substitute manual protocol verification and firmware review for broad scanner coverage wherever feasible.","correct":false,"why":"Manual protocol verification alone doesn't scale to replace a structured OT-safe assessment plan across the broader environment."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q121","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Tool Output Interpretation)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A web scan flags potential SQL injection, but exploitation is not confirmed. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Manually validate with safe, minimal test inputs and confirm backend behavior, logging, and parameter handling.","correct":true,"why":"Scanner findings require validation."},{"text":"Raise the confidence level and corroborate the result with additional request/response testing before final rating.","correct":false,"why":"Raising confidence and corroborating with more request/response tests still stops short of directly confirming exploitation with controlled inputs against actual backend behavior."},{"text":"Attempt broader payload variation to determine exploit depth before deciding whether manual confirmation is needed.","correct":false,"why":"Attempting broader payload variation to gauge exploit depth risks unnecessary impact before it's even confirmed the vulnerability is real; minimal validation should come first."},{"text":"Keep it as unconfirmed until developer logs or targeted retesting can clarify whether the parameter is injectable.","correct":false,"why":"Waiting on developer logs or a future retest delays the direct, controlled validation that can resolve the question now."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q122","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Remediation Ownership)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"Findings repeatedly linger because no one owns remediation and exceptions are undocumented. What is the BEST program improvement?","options":[{"text":"Implement a formal workflow: assign owners, set SLAs, track exceptions with approvals, and verify closure with evidence.","correct":true,"why":"Governance: ownership, SLAs, documented exceptions, and verification are required for effective vulnerability management."},{"text":"Tie findings to named service owners and review overdue items in a recurring governance process.","correct":false,"why":"Tying findings to named owners with recurring reviews helps but omits the SLA and documented-exception-with-approval elements that make the workflow fully governed."},{"text":"Route all findings through a centralized security operations queue so one team can track status across platforms.","correct":false,"why":"Centralizing tracking in one queue helps visibility but doesn't establish the ownership, SLAs, and exception governance actually causing findings to linger."},{"text":"Reduce noise by publishing only validated findings and let product teams pull remaining items from dashboards as needed.","correct":false,"why":"Reducing what's published to only validated findings doesn't fix the lack of ownership and undocumented exceptions driving the underlying problem."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q123","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Data Handling)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"During a test, you access a file share containing PII. The RoE states testers should minimize exposure and store no sensitive data. What is the BEST action?","options":[{"text":"Capture minimal evidence (metadata/screenshots redacted) to prove access, then stop and report per RoE.","correct":true,"why":"Minimize sensitive data handling."},{"text":"Capture a very small sample under controlled handling procedures so impact can be documented more concretely.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing even a small sample of PII files still stores sensitive data, directly conflicting with the RoE's requirement to store none."},{"text":"Collect several representative files into an encrypted evidence container to preserve a stronger audit trail.","correct":false,"why":"Collecting representative files into an evidence container, even encrypted, still means storing sensitive data the RoE prohibits retaining."},{"text":"Enumerate folder structure and classifications further so the client receives a fuller picture of data exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Further enumerating folder structure and classifications increases exposure to sensitive data beyond the minimal proof of access the RoE calls for."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q124","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Configuration Drift)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A system passes a scan after remediation, but the same vulnerability reappears next month due to configuration drift. What is the BEST long-term fix?","options":[{"text":"Use configuration management baselines (IaC/GPO) with continuous compliance checks and change control enforcement.","correct":true,"why":"Prevent recurrence by enforcing baselines via config management and continuous compliance monitoring, not repeated manual fixes."},{"text":"Increase compliance scanning frequency and trigger checks after administrative changes to shorten drift windows.","correct":false,"why":"More frequent scanning would catch drift sooner but doesn't prevent the drift from recurring in the first place."},{"text":"Simplify approval paths for security changes so hardened settings are less likely to be rolled back operationally.","correct":false,"why":"Simplifying approval paths could make hardened settings easier to change, which risks more drift rather than enforcing baselines against it."},{"text":"Maintain host-level remediation scripts and rerun them whenever future scans detect the same deviation.","correct":false,"why":"Repeatedly rerunning remediation scripts treats symptoms each time drift occurs rather than preventing drift through enforced configuration baselines."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q125","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Password Attacks)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"An internal assessment includes validating password hygiene without disrupting accounts. What technique BEST balances safety and insight?","options":[{"text":"Use password auditing with approved hashes (offline) and controlled spray tests with lockout-aware pacing per RoE.","correct":true,"why":"Safe testing uses offline hash auditing (where authorized) and careful, lockout-aware online validation with strict constraints."},{"text":"Perform a narrowly targeted online guessing exercise with carefully tuned thresholds and close lockout monitoring.","correct":false,"why":"Even carefully tuned online guessing still risks account lockouts and disruption; the safer approach favors offline hash auditing where authorized."},{"text":"Use forced resets for selected high-risk groups and compare post-reset outcomes with policy requirements.","correct":false,"why":"Forcing resets across high-risk groups is disruptive to users and doesn't provide the same insight into actual password strength as controlled hash auditing."},{"text":"Run one coordinated spray across the directory using a common seasonal pattern to measure resilience under load.","correct":false,"why":"A single coordinated spray across the whole directory carries meaningful lockout and disruption risk, conflicting with the goal of not disrupting accounts."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q126","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Scanning Frequency)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A company scans monthly, but high-change internet-facing apps are updated weekly. What is the BEST adjustment?","options":[{"text":"Increase scanning cadence or implement continuous scanning for high-risk assets and integrate scans into CI/CD for apps.","correct":true,"why":"Scan frequency should match risk and change rate."},{"text":"Keep the monthly cadence and supplement it with targeted scans after each major application release.","correct":false,"why":"Supplementing with post-release scans while keeping the base monthly cadence still leaves gaps between weekly changes and the next scheduled scan."},{"text":"Shift effort toward manual testing during release windows while preserving the existing infrastructure scan cycle.","correct":false,"why":"Shifting to manual testing during releases doesn't scale to weekly change cycles and leaves the underlying scan cadence misaligned with actual risk."},{"text":"Trigger additional scans for incident-related systems only, leaving routine cadence unchanged for normal operations.","correct":false,"why":"Limiting extra scans to incident-driven systems only doesn't address the routine weekly changes to internet-facing apps between monthly scans."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q127","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Recon)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"During external reconnaissance, you discover multiple subdomains and open services. What is the MOST important reason to document them carefully?","options":[{"text":"They define the attack surface and scope evidence, supporting risk analysis, reproducibility, and remediation guidance.","correct":true,"why":"Accurate attack surface documentation supports repeatability, scoping, and actionable remediation planning."},{"text":"Record service exposure first and summarize discovered subdomains only where they map to distinct business functions.","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing service exposure over subdomains still leaves gaps in the attack-surface picture, since undocumented subdomains are part of what needs recording."},{"text":"Emphasize reachable hosts and defer lower-confidence DNS findings until later validation confirms their importance.","correct":false,"why":"Deferring lower-confidence DNS findings risks missing entry points that could matter for a complete, reproducible scope record."},{"text":"Capture enough detail for analyst handoff, then refine the external inventory later as results stabilize.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing only enough for a handoff and refining later risks losing detail needed for full reproducibility and remediation guidance from the start."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q128","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Patch Exceptions)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A team requests a patch exception for a critical vulnerability on a customer-facing server. What is the BEST process?","options":[{"text":"Perform a risk acceptance with documented justification, compensating controls, approval, expiration date, and monitoring plan.","correct":true,"why":"Exceptions must be governed: documented risk acceptance, compensating controls, time-bounded approvals, and monitoring."},{"text":"Approve a temporary exception with periodic review while the team documents why standard remediation is delayed.","correct":false,"why":"Approving with periodic review alone omits compensating controls and monitoring, leaving the customer-facing server less protected during the delay."},{"text":"Move the item into a tracked exception backlog and revisit it during the next formal risk review cycle.","correct":false,"why":"Simply tracking the item in a backlog for the next cycle doesn't establish the documented risk acceptance and controls needed right away."},{"text":"Report the issue separately from operational dashboards while the business owner evaluates the exception request.","correct":false,"why":"Separating the report from dashboards addresses visibility, not the governance elements (approval, controls, expiration) the exception actually needs."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q129","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Post-Exploitation Boundaries)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"After gaining access to a server, you can dump credentials and pivot to other systems. The RoE allows proof of access but prohibits credential harvesting. What should you do?","options":[{"text":"Stop at proof-of-access, document the potential for escalation, and request explicit approval before any credential actions.","correct":true,"why":"Always follow RoE."},{"text":"Capture hashes into a secured evidence workflow and hold them unused until approval is obtained.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing hashes into an evidence workflow still constitutes credential harvesting, which the RoE explicitly prohibits regardless of how securely they're stored."},{"text":"Collect noninteractive account material only and document why service accounts present a distinct risk path.","correct":false,"why":"Collecting service account material is still harvesting credentials, which the RoE prohibits regardless of the account type targeted."},{"text":"Demonstrate reachable lateral paths through token or session context only, without extracting reusable secrets.","correct":false,"why":"Demonstrating lateral paths through token or session context can still cross into extracting reusable secrets, which the RoE does not permit here."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q130","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Web App Testing)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A scanner reports “missing security headers” on a web app. The app team argues it is low risk. What is the BEST response?","options":[{"text":"Explain impact and context: headers reduce exploitation likelihood (XSS/clickjacking), then prioritize based on exposure and app risk.","correct":true,"why":"Security headers are hardening measures."},{"text":"Treat the issue as lower priority unless the application threat model shows realistic browser-side abuse paths.","correct":false,"why":"Deprioritizing unless the threat model shows realistic abuse paths skips explaining the actual risk reduction headers provide before that analysis is done."},{"text":"Track the issue alongside other hardening gaps and elevate it only where exposure and exploit chains justify it.","correct":false,"why":"Tracking alongside other gaps without first explaining the impact doesn't directly address the app team's specific low-risk objection."},{"text":"Map the header findings to the application’s browser threat surface before assigning a final remediation tier.","correct":false,"why":"Mapping to the browser threat surface is a reasonable step but doesn't itself communicate the impact and exposure-based prioritization the team needs to hear."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q131","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Chain of Evidence)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"A client wants evidence that is defensible for audits. Which practice MOST strengthens test evidence quality?","options":[{"text":"Maintain detailed notes, timestamps, reproducible steps, screenshots/redactions, and proper evidence handling controls.","correct":true,"why":"Strong evidence includes detailed, timestamped, reproducible steps with proper handling and redaction where needed."},{"text":"Standardize on exported tool reports and attach analyst notes only where the workflow requires clarification.","correct":false,"why":"Relying mainly on exported tool reports with sparse notes lacks the detailed, reproducible narrative auditors expect beyond raw tool output."},{"text":"Retain primary artifacts in a restricted evidence repository and redact copies used in the final report.","correct":false,"why":"Retaining primary artifacts separately from redacted report copies is good practice but doesn't by itself ensure the detailed, timestamped, reproducible documentation needed."},{"text":"Use recorded debriefs and screen sharing to supplement the written record for client and audit stakeholders.","correct":false,"why":"Recorded debriefs supplement the record but don't replace the core need for detailed, timestamped, reproducible written documentation for audits."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q132","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Mgmt (Scanning Credentials Security)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"Credentialed scans require storing privileged credentials. What is the BEST way to reduce associated risk?","options":[{"text":"Use a secrets vault, least-privilege scan accounts, rotation, and auditing; avoid domain admin where possible.","correct":true,"why":"Secure credentialed scanning with vaulting, least privilege, rotation, and auditing reduces risk while preserving assessment accuracy."},{"text":"Use highly privileged service accounts to maximize coverage, then compensate with tighter scanner access controls.","correct":false,"why":"Using highly privileged accounts to maximize coverage increases risk exposure regardless of added access controls; least privilege should be the starting point, not a compensating step."},{"text":"Standardize on one reusable scan credential per platform tier so authentication failures are easier to troubleshoot.","correct":false,"why":"Standardizing on one reusable credential per platform tier increases the impact if that single credential is ever compromised, rather than reducing risk."},{"text":"Minimize credential changes during scan windows and review usage periodically to reduce operational interruptions.","correct":false,"why":"Minimizing credential changes to reduce interruptions works against the rotation practices needed to limit exposure from a compromised credential."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q133","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Retest / Closure)","source":"CySA_Day 11.html","q":"After remediation, the client asks how to confirm the pentest issues are resolved. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Perform a focused retest of remediated findings, validating the exploit path is closed and documenting residual risk.","correct":true,"why":"A retest confirms fixes."},{"text":"Review client-reported remediation artifacts and compare them with the original exploit path before scheduling a retest.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing client-reported artifacts against the original exploit path relies on secondhand claims rather than the tester directly confirming the fix."},{"text":"Run the same broad assessment used during the initial engagement so all controls can be measured consistently.","correct":false,"why":"Rerunning the full broad assessment is unnecessarily heavy; a focused retest of the specific remediated findings is the appropriate confirmation step."},{"text":"Wait for the next routine vulnerability cycle and verify whether the original issue no longer appears in reporting.","correct":false,"why":"Waiting for the next routine vulnerability cycle delays confirmation rather than directly retesting the specific pentest findings now."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q134","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (IAM / AuthN/AuthZ)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A cloud engineer reports that a new microservice can read objects from a storage bucket even after its access key was rotated and the attached role policy was tightened. The SOC suspects policy evaluation is still allowing access through an unexpected path. Which action MOST directly validates the *effective permissions* being applied at request time?","options":[{"text":"Review the microservice source code to confirm the SDK is using the intended role session and token chain.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing source code can reveal intended behavior, but it doesn't validate what permissions are actually being evaluated and applied at request time in the live environment."},{"text":"Evaluate the active permission path with a policy analyzer against the principal, resource, and requested action.","correct":true,"why":"A policy simulator/access analyzer evaluates identity + resource policies, conditions, and explicit denies to show effective permissions for the exact action and resource."},{"text":"Disable the bucket’s public access settings and retest by forcing TLS-only requests from the service.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling public access and forcing TLS addresses a different concern (transport and public exposure), not the specific unexpected policy-evaluation path being investigated."},{"text":"Increase object storage logging retention to reconstruct historical reads for the last 30 days window.","correct":false,"why":"Extending log retention only helps look back at what already happened; it doesn't directly validate the current effective permission path."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q135","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (Logging / Visibility)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"After a suspected credential theft, an analyst needs to determine whether API calls were made from atypical geolocations and whether requests failed due to conditional access controls. Which logging approach BEST supports this investigation across the control plane?","options":[{"text":"Enable VPC flow logs only and correlate destination ports with the object storage endpoint name resolution data.","correct":false,"why":"VPC flow logs show network-layer traffic like ports and destinations, not the control-plane details (API calls, principals, auth failures) needed for this investigation."},{"text":"Aggregate control-plane audit events in the SIEM with geo-IP enrichment and authorization result details.","correct":true,"why":"Control-plane audit logs capture API calls, principals, source IPs, response codes, and auth/authorization failures."},{"text":"Rely on hypervisor logs from the compute nodes and compare kernel messages for time-skew and login anomalies.","correct":false,"why":"Hypervisor and kernel logs from compute nodes don't capture control-plane API activity, principal identity, or geolocation needed to investigate this credential theft."},{"text":"Collect application logs from the microservices and infer API activity using request IDs from load balancer traces.","correct":false,"why":"Application logs and load balancer traces can hint at request patterns but don't reliably provide direct control-plane authorization and geolocation detail."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q136","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Settings (Segmentation / ACLs)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A company migrates workloads into a cloud VPC. A scanner shows that a database subnet can still be reached from a dev subnet despite “deny” rules in a security group. The cloud provider evaluates rules as allow-lists and uses implicit deny. What is the MOST likely misconfiguration?","options":[{"text":"An attached allow path still covers the dev source range, so the expected block never takes effect.","correct":true,"why":"Many cloud SGs are allow-list only; “deny” rules aren’t supported."},{"text":"The route table is missing a default route, which causes traffic to bypass the security group evaluation process.","correct":false,"why":"A missing default route would typically break connectivity entirely rather than allowing traffic to bypass security group evaluation specifically."},{"text":"Network ACLs are stateful, so established connections ignore all inbound filtering after the first packet passes.","correct":false,"why":"Stateful evaluation of already-established connections doesn't explain new dev-to-database access when the intended block should apply from the start."},{"text":"The database is using QUIC and therefore ignores TCP-based security group rule enforcement by design.","correct":false,"why":"The database using QUIC instead of TCP wouldn't cause security group deny rules to be ignored; cloud SGs evaluate based on defined rules regardless of protocol choice."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q137","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (KMS / Secrets)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"An incident responder finds a container image that includes an embedded database password in an environment variable inside the deployment manifest. The team wants to reduce blast radius while keeping the pipeline velocity. Which change MOST improves security with minimal operational friction?","options":[{"text":"Pull the value from a managed secrets store at runtime by using short-lived workload identity.","correct":true,"why":"A managed secrets service + workload identity (no long-lived keys) is the standard: runtime retrieval, rotation, auditability, and scoped access."},{"text":"Base64-encode the password in the manifest and restrict the cluster API to only the CI runner IP addresses.","correct":false,"why":"Base64-encoding the password only obscures it trivially and doesn't remove the long-lived secret from the manifest; restricting IPs doesn't address the embedded credential itself."},{"text":"Move the password into a sidecar container file and secure it using chmod 600 on the mounted volume path.","correct":false,"why":"Moving the password to a sidecar file with file permissions still stores a long-lived static secret on disk rather than retrieving it dynamically at runtime."},{"text":"Hardcode the password into the application binary and sign the container image with a developer certificate chain.","correct":false,"why":"Hardcoding the password into the binary embeds the secret even more permanently and signing the image doesn't protect the credential's confidentiality at all."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q138","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization (Isolation / Escape Risk)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A hypervisor host shows abnormal CPU usage. Telemetry suggests a guest VM executed a sequence consistent with a hypervisor escape attempt. Which control MOST directly reduces the impact of a successful escape?","options":[{"text":"Place guest VMs on a dedicated VLAN and restrict east-west traffic using security groups across the subnet.","correct":false,"why":"Segmenting guest VM network traffic addresses lateral movement between VMs over the network, not the hypervisor-level escape risk being investigated here."},{"text":"Reduce host attack surface, patch the platform quickly, and keep management access on an isolated plane.","correct":true,"why":"Escape is about the hypervisor boundary."},{"text":"Increase VM memory reservations so the guest cannot trigger ballooning and swap storms on the host kernel.","correct":false,"why":"Adjusting memory reservations targets resource contention issues, not the security boundary an escape attempt would be breaching."},{"text":"Disable DHCP on the VM network and require static IP configuration to prevent rogue address assignment.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling DHCP addresses rogue address assignment on the guest network; it has no bearing on limiting the impact of a hypervisor escape."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q139","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Runtime / Least Privilege)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A Kubernetes workload needs to bind to port 443 and read a config file. A security review finds the container is running as root with full Linux capabilities. Which change BEST enforces least privilege while maintaining function?","options":[{"text":"Run as non-root, remove unnecessary capabilities, and grant only the minimal privilege needed for binding.","correct":true,"why":"Prefer non-root with minimal capabilities (or a proxy)."},{"text":"Keep root but set the filesystem to read-only and restrict egress to only the configuration service endpoint.","correct":false,"why":"Keeping the container running as root still retains root-level capabilities even with a read-only filesystem, which doesn't achieve least privilege for the process itself."},{"text":"Mount the container runtime socket into the pod so it can manage ports directly and avoid privilege changes.","correct":false,"why":"Mounting the container runtime socket grants powerful host-level control capabilities, which increases privilege rather than reducing it."},{"text":"Enable host networking to bypass port binding limits and remove the need for privileged process execution.","correct":false,"why":"Enabling host networking removes network isolation entirely and doesn't reduce the excessive process privileges the review flagged."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q140","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Managing Network Settings (DNS / Exposure)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"During a cloud migration, users intermittently resolve an internal service name to a public IP. The service should be internal-only. Which configuration issue is MOST consistent with this symptom?","options":[{"text":"Private and public DNS views are misaligned, so some internal resolvers return the external record set.","correct":true,"why":"Split-horizon (private zone vs public zone) mistakes can cause internal names to resolve to public records."},{"text":"NTP drift is causing DNSSEC validation to fail, so clients default to an insecure public resolver route.","correct":false,"why":"NTP drift affecting DNSSEC validation wouldn't cause an internal name to resolve to a different (public) IP address; it would cause validation failures, not incorrect record resolution."},{"text":"The load balancer health checks are failing, so the DNS server rotates records toward public endpoints only.","correct":false,"why":"Load balancer health check failures affect which backend receives traffic, not which DNS zone (private vs. public) a resolver consults for the name."},{"text":"The VPC route table is missing a local route, so DNS returns public IPs to compensate for reachability.","correct":false,"why":"A missing local route in the VPC route table would cause connectivity failures, not a DNS resolver returning the wrong (public) IP for an internal name."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q141","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (SaaS / CASB patterns)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A security team wants to detect unsanctioned cloud app usage and enforce DLP for uploads from managed devices without blocking the entire internet. Which approach BEST matches this requirement?","options":[{"text":"Use a CASB for discovery plus inline session controls and API visibility on managed endpoints.","correct":true,"why":"CASB supports discovery (shadow IT), DLP, and policy enforcement (API + inline/session controls) without blanket blocking."},{"text":"Use only endpoint EDR and rely on process lineage to block any browser performing file uploads to unknown domains.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint EDR blocking uploads by process lineage can't provide visibility into unsanctioned SaaS usage across managed and unmanaged apps the way a CASB can."},{"text":"Implement a WAF in front of the SaaS provider and configure it to inspect uploads originating from the company ASN.","correct":false,"why":"A WAF in front of the SaaS provider isn't something the security team controls or can configure, since the SaaS provider owns that infrastructure."},{"text":"Force all cloud apps to use shared static access keys and alert on any key use outside business hours windows.","correct":false,"why":"Forcing shared static access keys and alerting on off-hours use doesn't address discovery of unsanctioned apps or DLP enforcement on uploads."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q142","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Supply Chain)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A build pipeline pulls base images from a public registry. A recent compromise replaced a popular tag with a malicious image. Which control MOST effectively prevents this specific failure mode?","options":[{"text":"Pin base images by immutable digest and require trusted signature verification before deployment.","correct":true,"why":"Mutable tags can be hijacked."},{"text":"Enable container runtime auto-updates so the nodes always pull the most recent tag at deployment time window.","correct":false,"why":"Enabling runtime auto-updates to pull the most recent tag would still trust whatever image currently sits behind that mutable tag, including a maliciously swapped one."},{"text":"Increase CI concurrency so images are pulled less frequently, reducing exposure to malicious tag swaps.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing CI concurrency doesn't reduce how often a compromised mutable tag could be pulled; it only changes pipeline throughput."},{"text":"Use a single shared service account for builds and store its token in the repository secrets for durability.","correct":false,"why":"Using a single shared service account with a stored token addresses credential management, not the core issue of trusting a mutable, hijackable image tag."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q143","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization (Snapshots / Forensics)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A VM is suspected of running a memory-resident credential stealer. The team wants a forensically sound approach with minimal downtime. Which step is MOST appropriate first?","options":[{"text":"Capture volatile memory with a controlled snapshot workflow and preserve handling records for evidence.","correct":true,"why":"Memory-resident malware requires memory capture."},{"text":"Power off the VM immediately to prevent further theft and then image the disk using a standard cloning tool.","correct":false,"why":"Powering off the VM immediately destroys the memory-resident evidence needed to investigate a credential stealer before it can be captured."},{"text":"Delete the VM and restore from a known-good template, then review the application logs for errors only.","correct":false,"why":"Deleting the VM and restoring from a template destroys all forensic evidence, and reviewing only application logs would miss memory-resident indicators entirely."},{"text":"Patch the VM OS first and then run antivirus scans to remove any artifacts before collecting evidence.","correct":false,"why":"Patching and running antivirus first would alter or remove artifacts needed for forensic analysis before evidence is properly collected."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q144","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Settings (TLS / Load Balancing)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A cloud load balancer terminates TLS. A compliance requirement mandates that backend services also use TLS and that client identity can be traced end-to-end. Which configuration BEST satisfies this?","options":[{"text":"Re-encrypt to the backend tier with mTLS and forward validated client identity context end to end.","correct":true,"why":"Re-encryption (TLS to backend) + ideally mTLS provides encryption in transit and strong service identity."},{"text":"Terminate TLS at the load balancer and send plaintext to backends to reduce CPU overhead while logging source IP.","correct":false,"why":"Terminating TLS at the load balancer and sending plaintext to backends fails the compliance requirement that backend services also use TLS."},{"text":"Disable HTTP/2 to ensure identity headers cannot be modified in transit and rely on NAT logs for attribution.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling HTTP/2 doesn't provide encryption or client identity tracing to backend services; it addresses an unrelated protocol-level concern."},{"text":"Use a single wildcard certificate on the load balancer only and rotate it monthly to satisfy traceability.","correct":false,"why":"A single wildcard certificate on the load balancer only secures the client-facing hop; it does nothing to encrypt or trace identity to the backend tier."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q145","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (Shared Responsibility)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A team assumes the cloud provider patches all components. A breach occurs through an unpatched web application framework running on a managed VM. Which statement BEST reflects the shared responsibility model?","options":[{"text":"The provider is responsible for patching guest operating systems and application frameworks within customer VMs.","correct":false,"why":"This reverses the actual IaaS responsibility split; the provider does not patch guest operating systems or application frameworks running inside customer VMs."},{"text":"The customer patches the guest stack on IaaS workloads, while the provider maintains the underlying platform.","correct":true,"why":"In IaaS, customers patch OS/app in their VMs; provider patches physical/hypervisor/infrastructure."},{"text":"Shared responsibility means both parties patch everything, but only the customer is liable for regulatory penalties.","correct":false,"why":"The shared responsibility model divides which layers each party is responsible for; it doesn't mean both patch everything, and liability isn't determined this way either."},{"text":"In IaaS, the provider patches applications; in SaaS, the customer patches the hypervisor and physical servers.","correct":false,"why":"This also reverses the actual responsibilities; in IaaS the provider patches the hypervisor and physical layer, not the applications, and SaaS customers don't patch the hypervisor."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q146","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Network Policies)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A cluster has multiple namespaces. A compromised pod in namespace A is laterally scanning services in namespace B. The team wants to contain blast radius without redesigning the network. Which control MOST directly addresses this?","options":[{"text":"Apply default-deny pod traffic rules and allow only the specific namespace-to-namespace paths that are required.","correct":true,"why":"NetworkPolicies enforce micro-segmentation at the pod level."},{"text":"Disable service discovery and require static IPs for all pods so scans cannot enumerate service names quickly.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling service discovery and requiring static IPs doesn't stop a compromised pod from directly connecting to known service IPs in namespace B; it only slows enumeration."},{"text":"Increase pod replica counts so scanning traffic is load balanced and less likely to impact service availability.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing replica counts spreads scanning traffic across more pods but doesn't restrict which namespaces can communicate with each other at all."},{"text":"Enable privileged pods only for namespace B to allow security tools to monitor namespace A from a higher context.","correct":false,"why":"Granting namespace B pods privileged access to monitor namespace A increases the attack surface rather than containing the compromised pod's reach."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q147","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization (Management Plane)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"An attacker gains access to the hypervisor management API. Which indicator is MOST concerning for imminent widespread compromise?","options":[{"text":"Repeated failed logins to guest VM SSH ports from a single internal IP across a narrow time window.","correct":false,"why":"Repeated failed SSH logins from one internal IP suggest ongoing guessing attempts, not evidence of already-established persistent control at the management-plane level."},{"text":"New high-privilege roles and broad API tokens appear in the virtualization management layer.","correct":true,"why":"Management-plane token/role creation suggests persistence and control over many hosts/VMs."},{"text":"Increased ICMP traffic between VMs as part of routine monitoring checks after a maintenance cycle.","correct":false,"why":"Increased ICMP traffic tied to routine monitoring after maintenance is expected housekeeping activity, not an indicator of privilege escalation or persistence."},{"text":"A spike in disk I/O for one VM consistent with database reindexing and log rotation housekeeping.","correct":false,"why":"A disk I/O spike consistent with routine reindexing and log rotation is normal operational behavior, not evidence of management-plane compromise."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q148","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (Data Protection / Storage)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A storage bucket contains sensitive reports. The organization requires that data be unreadable if the bucket policy is accidentally made public. Which control BEST meets this requirement?","options":[{"text":"Use object encryption that stays under customer-controlled keys so exposure of storage policy alone is insufficient.","correct":true,"why":"Encryption (especially client-side/envelope) ensures confidentiality even if access policy is wrong."},{"text":"Enable versioning so public reads can be rolled back by restoring prior object versions from history.","correct":false,"why":"Versioning allows rolling back object changes, but it doesn't prevent an already-public bucket from exposing the current sensitive data to unauthorized readers."},{"text":"Set object lifecycle rules to transition older reports to archival storage to reduce the window of exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Lifecycle transitions to archival storage change where data is stored, not whether it remains readable if the bucket policy becomes public."},{"text":"Enable CDN caching so requests are served faster and access logs can be analyzed for abnormal patterns.","correct":false,"why":"CDN caching and log analysis address performance and monitoring, not whether the underlying data stays confidential if the bucket policy is misconfigured."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q149","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Managing Network Settings (Routing / Egress)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A cloud workload must reach an external payment API, but policy requires that all egress be inspected and restricted. Which architecture BEST supports this while preserving availability?","options":[{"text":"Send outbound connections through centralized egress controls that inspect, allow-list, and log approved destinations.","correct":true,"why":"Central egress via NAT + firewall/proxy supports inspection, allow-lists, and logging while avoiding per-host public IP exposure."},{"text":"Assign public IPs to each instance and rely on host-based firewalls for egress control and local log storage.","correct":false,"why":"Assigning public IPs to each instance directly exposes them to the internet and relies on inconsistent host-based firewalls rather than centralized, inspectable egress."},{"text":"Disable outbound internet entirely and use DNS tunneling to reach the payment API without opening egress routes.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling outbound internet and using DNS tunneling is an unreliable, covert channel that doesn't provide the inspected, allow-listed egress path the policy requires."},{"text":"Use a single shared jump host with SSH dynamic port forwarding so applications can reach the payment API indirectly.","correct":false,"why":"Routing through a single shared jump host with SSH forwarding creates a fragile single point of failure and doesn't provide policy-based inspection and logging."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q150","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Admission Control)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"Security wants to block deployments that request privileged mode, hostPath mounts, or runAsUser=0, but developers want fast feedback. Which control MOST directly enforces this at deploy time?","options":[{"text":"Enforce deployment-time policy that rejects manifests requesting disallowed privileges or node-level access.","correct":true,"why":"Admission control denies bad specs before they run, giving immediate feedback."},{"text":"Enable node auto-scaling so noncompliant pods are placed on dedicated nodes with higher monitoring coverage.","correct":false,"why":"Auto-scaling onto dedicated nodes with more monitoring doesn't stop the disallowed manifest from being deployed in the first place; it only observes it after the fact."},{"text":"Deploy a sidecar IDS into every pod to watch syscalls and kill the container when privileged operations occur.","correct":false,"why":"A sidecar IDS watching syscalls only reacts after a privileged container is already running, rather than rejecting the risky manifest before deployment."},{"text":"Rely on image scanning only and block images that contain package managers and shells to reduce container misuse.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking images with package managers and shells addresses image content, not manifests that request privileged mode, hostPath mounts, or root user directly."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q151","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization (Resource Overcommit / DoS)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"Multiple VMs on a host become unstable during peak hours. Investigation shows aggressive CPU overcommit and noisy neighbor contention. Which mitigation BEST addresses availability without weakening isolation?","options":[{"text":"Apply workload reservations and placement rules so competing high-load guests are not packed onto the same host.","correct":true,"why":"Reservations/limits and placement policies manage contention while keeping isolation intact."},{"text":"Disable hyperthreading globally so cores cannot be shared, eliminating all forms of VM contention.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling hyperthreading globally reduces available compute capacity for every VM and doesn't specifically address CPU overcommit and placement causing contention."},{"text":"Enable promiscuous mode on the virtual switch so monitoring can observe and throttle chatty VMs precisely.","correct":false,"why":"Enabling promiscuous mode exposes traffic broadly for monitoring but doesn't manage or reduce the CPU resource contention causing instability."},{"text":"Move all VMs to host networking so the virtual switch cannot become a bottleneck during burst traffic windows.","correct":false,"why":"Moving all VMs to host networking removes network isolation and doesn't address the CPU overcommit issue driving the instability at all."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q152","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (Identity Federation)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A company wants to avoid long-lived cloud access keys for developers while enabling SSO with MFA. Which approach BEST meets the goal?","options":[{"text":"Use federated sign-in that issues short-lived role credentials after MFA rather than persistent developer secrets.","correct":true,"why":"Federation (SAML/OIDC) provides SSO + MFA and issues short-lived credentials (STS style), eliminating long-lived developer keys."},{"text":"Create per-developer IAM users and rotate their access keys weekly using a shared spreadsheet reminder process.","correct":false,"why":"Creating per-developer IAM users with manually rotated keys still relies on long-lived static credentials, which is exactly what the company wants to avoid."},{"text":"Use a single break-glass account for all developers and store the credentials in a password manager vault.","correct":false,"why":"A single break-glass account shared across all developers removes individual accountability and still relies on a persistent, long-lived credential."},{"text":"Disable console access and allow only static API keys because programmatic access cannot support MFA flows.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling console access and relying only on static API keys keeps long-lived credentials in place and doesn't provide the SSO/MFA flow the company wants."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q153","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Managing Network Settings (IPv6 / Filtering)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A security assessment finds host-based firewall rules are strict for IPv4, but the same hosts are reachable over IPv6 from segments that should not have access. What is the MOST likely root cause?","options":[{"text":"The hosts have a second reachable path because IPv6 filtering was not aligned with the IPv4 rule set.","correct":true,"why":"Common issue: IPv6 enabled with missing/loose rules."},{"text":"IPv6 traffic cannot be filtered by modern firewalls, so controls must rely entirely on application authentication.","correct":false,"why":"Modern firewalls can filter IPv6 traffic just as they do IPv4; the issue described is a rule misalignment, not an inherent inability to filter IPv6."},{"text":"NAT for IPv6 is required for filtering, and the environment has not enabled NAT66 on the edge router.","correct":false,"why":"IPv6 filtering doesn't require NAT to function; NAT66 isn't a prerequisite for applying firewall rules to IPv6 traffic."},{"text":"IPv6 uses mandatory IPsec, so firewall rules are ignored once encryption is negotiated between endpoints.","correct":false,"why":"IPv6 doesn't mandate universal IPsec encryption in practice, and firewall rules aren't bypassed simply because IPv6 is in use."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q154","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Runtime Monitoring)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"An analyst sees a container spawning a shell and running a network scanner. The image is supposed to be a minimal web service. Which telemetry is MOST useful to confirm malicious runtime behavior?","options":[{"text":"Runtime syscall telemetry showing process launches, socket activity, and unexpected file access from the container.","correct":true,"why":"Runtime behavior is best proven by syscall-level telemetry (process execution, sockets, file access)."},{"text":"Kubernetes liveness probe failures only, because restarts correlate directly with compromise timing windows.","correct":false,"why":"Liveness probe failures reflect restart events, which don't by themselves confirm the specific malicious shell and scanner activity observed."},{"text":"Container image vulnerability scan results, because CVEs prove the container must be actively exploited.","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability scan showing CVEs indicates potential weaknesses, not proof that a specific exploit is currently being executed at runtime."},{"text":"Node uptime graphs, because higher uptime indicates reduced administrative activity and fewer security changes.","correct":false,"why":"Node uptime doesn't indicate administrative activity levels or reveal anything about a specific container's runtime behavior."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q155","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization (VM Sprawl / Governance)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A cloud subscription shows hundreds of idle VMs with unknown owners. Cost is rising and patching is inconsistent. Which control BEST addresses the root cause long-term?","options":[{"text":"Enforce ownership tags, provisioning guardrails, and automated lifecycle cleanup for unattended instances.","correct":true,"why":"Governance needs ownership tags, guardrails, and automated cleanup/lifecycle management."},{"text":"Block all VM creation immediately and require manual approval for any future VM deployment requests.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking all VM creation and requiring manual approval addresses new sprawl going forward but does nothing to clean up the hundreds of existing idle, unowned VMs."},{"text":"Increase the patch window frequency so idle VMs are patched faster even if ownership is unknown.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing patch frequency doesn't resolve the underlying issue of unknown ownership and lifecycle governance driving the sprawl and cost growth."},{"text":"Move all workloads to containers so virtualization sprawl can no longer occur in any form at all.","correct":false,"why":"Migrating everything to containers is a drastic architectural change and doesn't directly address establishing ownership and lifecycle controls for the existing VM sprawl."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q156","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (Misconfiguration Detection)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"Security needs to continuously detect publicly exposed storage buckets, overly permissive security groups, and risky IAM policies. Which solution BEST fits this continuous posture management need?","options":[{"text":"Use continuous cloud posture monitoring to check benchmarks, detect drift, and flag unsafe configurations.","correct":true,"why":"CSPM is designed for continuous misconfiguration detection in cloud controls: IAM, networking, storage exposure, benchmarks, drift."},{"text":"Run quarterly penetration tests and treat any findings as definitive proof of current cloud security posture.","correct":false,"why":"Quarterly penetration tests provide only a periodic snapshot and can't continuously flag drift or new misconfigurations as they occur."},{"text":"Rely on endpoint antivirus on cloud VMs to detect risky IAM policies through behavioral heuristic signatures.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint antivirus on VMs is designed to detect malware behavior, not to evaluate cloud IAM policies or configuration posture."},{"text":"Enable full packet capture on all VPC traffic and manually review flows for signs of public exposure daily.","correct":false,"why":"Manually reviewing full packet captures daily doesn't scale to continuously catching misconfigurations across storage, IAM, and networking."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q157","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Managing Network Settings (MTU / Troubleshooting)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"After enabling a site-to-site VPN to a cloud VPC, certain applications fail while simple pings work. Packet captures show fragmentation and repeated retransmits. Which network setting is MOST likely involved?","options":[{"text":"Tune packet sizing for the tunnel path so encapsulation overhead does not cause fragmentation-related breakage.","correct":true,"why":"VPN encapsulation reduces effective MTU; without MSS clamping/PMTUD handling, large packets fragment and break certain apps."},{"text":"DNS TTL is too low, causing frequent re-resolution and intermittent routing changes through the VPN tunnel.","correct":false,"why":"Low DNS TTLs causing frequent re-resolution wouldn't produce the fragmentation and retransmit symptoms observed; those point to packet size issues over the tunnel."},{"text":"ARP cache timeout is too high, so stale MAC addresses persist and prevent communication across the VPN link.","correct":false,"why":"Stale ARP entries would cause local link-layer communication failures, not the fragmentation and retransmission pattern seen after enabling the VPN."},{"text":"The VPN uses asymmetric encryption, so the application payloads are not aligned to block size and are dropped.","correct":false,"why":"VPN encryption doesn't require payloads to align to a fixed block size in a way that causes drops; the symptoms described point to MTU/fragmentation issues instead."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q158","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Secrets / Service Accounts)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A pod has access to the Kubernetes API using a default service account token. The team discovers the token can list secrets cluster-wide. What is the BEST immediate fix?","options":[{"text":"Reduce the service account scope to only required actions and stop mounting tokens into pods that do not need them.","correct":true,"why":"RBAC least privilege is the core fix; also disable automount tokens for pods that don’t need them and prefer workload identity where available."},{"text":"Rotate the cluster CA certificate and restart all nodes to invalidate any cached service account tokens.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating the cluster CA certificate and restarting nodes doesn't address the actual problem, which is that the token has excessive read-secrets permissions."},{"text":"Move the pod to the kube-system namespace because system namespaces are more trusted by default policies.","correct":false,"why":"Moving the pod to kube-system doesn't reduce its permissions; namespace placement doesn't grant or restrict RBAC scope here, and system namespaces aren't inherently safer."},{"text":"Enable container privileged mode so it can locally encrypt secrets, preventing the API server from exposing them.","correct":false,"why":"Enabling privileged mode increases the container's capabilities and risk; it doesn't restrict what the service account token can access via the API."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q159","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization (Storage / Snapshot Risk)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A regulated workload uses VM snapshots frequently. Auditors worry snapshots contain sensitive data and can persist beyond retention requirements. Which control BEST addresses this?","options":[{"text":"Enforce snapshot retention, access restrictions, and customer-controlled encryption across the snapshot lifecycle.","correct":true,"why":"You need governance: retention/lifecycle enforcement, strict access controls, and encryption (preferably CMKs)."},{"text":"Disable snapshots entirely and rely only on manual disk copy operations performed by administrators on demand.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling snapshots and relying only on manual disk copies removes a useful capability without establishing the retention and encryption governance auditors are asking for."},{"text":"Enable thin provisioning so snapshots store less data and are therefore less sensitive by default to auditors.","correct":false,"why":"Thin provisioning reduces storage footprint, not the actual retention, access control, or encryption of sensitive data within snapshots."},{"text":"Store snapshots in a public bucket so they can be integrity-checked by independent parties at any time.","correct":false,"why":"Storing snapshots in a public bucket for integrity checking directly exposes sensitive regulated data, which is the opposite of what auditors want addressed."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q160","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security (WAF / API Protection)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"An internet-facing API in the cloud is receiving high-rate requests with valid authentication tokens. The traffic appears automated and is causing resource exhaustion. Which control BEST mitigates this while preserving legitimate use?","options":[{"text":"Apply identity-aware throttling and automated abuse controls at the gateway edge to slow hostile automation.","correct":true,"why":"Rate limiting, anomaly/bot defenses, and identity/behavior-based throttling at gateway/WAF mitigate token-abuse automation."},{"text":"Disable TLS to reduce CPU overhead and allow the backend to respond more quickly during the spike window.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling TLS to save CPU removes encryption in transit entirely and doesn't address the automated abuse driving the resource exhaustion."},{"text":"Move the API to a private subnet only and require all clients to connect through a corporate VPN gateway.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring a corporate VPN would block the legitimate external clients this API needs to serve, conflicting with preserving legitimate use."},{"text":"Increase container privileges so the service can drop packets faster using raw sockets and kernel bypass.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing container privileges for faster packet dropping doesn't distinguish abusive automated traffic from legitimate requests and adds unnecessary risk."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q161","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Managing Network Settings (Zero Trust / Access)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A company wants to reduce reliance on flat internal networks. Access should be granted based on identity, device posture, and application context rather than subnet location. Which approach BEST aligns to this goal?","options":[{"text":"Use identity-aware access with continuous evaluation and segmented application paths instead of network-based trust.","correct":true,"why":"Zero Trust emphasizes identity and context, with identity-aware proxies and micro-segmentation, not subnet-based trust."},{"text":"Expand the internal address space and add more VLANs so each department can have its own large trusted segment.","correct":false,"why":"Adding more VLANs still grants trust based on subnet membership, which is exactly the network-location-based model the company wants to move away from."},{"text":"Move all internal apps to a single DMZ and allow all internal users full access to reduce routing complexity.","correct":false,"why":"Consolidating into a single DMZ with full internal access removes segmentation entirely, increasing risk rather than shifting to identity-based access decisions."},{"text":"Use only MAC address filtering because it binds access to a physical device identity across network boundaries.","correct":false,"why":"MAC filtering ties access to a physical network interface, not to identity, device posture, or application context as the goal requires."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q162","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security (Pod-to-Node Boundary)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A pod is granted access to the host filesystem through hostPath mounts for “log collection.” A red team demonstrates it can read node credentials and pivot. Which mitigation is MOST appropriate?","options":[{"text":"Remove direct host filesystem mounts where possible, use constrained node agents, and deny risky mount patterns at admission.","correct":true,"why":"hostPath breaks pod isolation."},{"text":"Keep hostPath but rename mount paths and obfuscate credential files to prevent easy discovery by attackers.","correct":false,"why":"Renaming paths and obfuscating files is security through obscurity; it doesn't remove the underlying host filesystem access the red team exploited."},{"text":"Allow hostPath only in the default namespace because it is monitored more closely than other namespaces.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting hostPath to the default namespace only shifts where the risky mount is used; it doesn't remove the isolation-breaking capability itself."},{"text":"Move the pod to host networking to reduce the need for filesystem mounts and simplify log routing paths.","correct":false,"why":"Moving to host networking addresses network isolation, not the filesystem access that let the pod read node credentials."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q163","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Cloud + Virtualization (Backups / Ransomware Resilience)","source":"CySA_Day 3.html","q":"A ransomware event encrypts data inside VMs and also targets attached cloud snapshots via stolen admin credentials. The organization needs recoverability even if cloud admin accounts are compromised. Which strategy BEST supports this?","options":[{"text":"Keep recoverable copies in immutable storage under separate administrative control, with isolated vault or offline protection.","correct":true,"why":"If admin creds are stolen, same-tenant snapshots can be deleted/altered."},{"text":"Increase snapshot frequency and store all snapshots in the same subscription so restores are faster during incidents.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing frequency while keeping all snapshots in the same subscription still leaves them reachable and deletable by the same compromised admin credentials."},{"text":"Store backup encryption keys inside the same VM for convenience so operators can restore quickly when needed.","correct":false,"why":"Storing encryption keys inside the same VM means a compromise of that VM exposes the keys needed to access or destroy the backups."},{"text":"Disable logging to reduce attacker visibility, then rely on rapid redeployment from templates as a recovery plan.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling logging removes visibility into the attack and doesn't provide any actual recoverability if snapshots are deleted or encrypted."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q164","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Architecture (Log Sources)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A SOC can see endpoint alerts but misses cloud control-plane abuse and suspicious admin actions. Leadership wants faster detection of account takeover. Which data source MOST directly closes this visibility gap?","options":[{"text":"Aggregate cloud audit trails with identity, source IP, and API action context for correlation across admin activity.","correct":true,"why":"Control-plane audit logs capture admin actions, principals, source IPs, and API activity, which directly support account-takeover detection in cloud environments."},{"text":"Collect additional endpoint application logs and correlate local process launches with software inventory changes.","correct":false,"why":"Additional endpoint application logs only cover local process activity; they don't provide visibility into cloud control-plane API calls or admin actions."},{"text":"Expand wireless controller logging to capture roaming events and client authentication timing across office floors.","correct":false,"why":"Wireless controller logs track physical network roaming and authentication, not cloud administrative or API-level activity."},{"text":"Increase web proxy retention and categorize browsing destinations by risk score and content filtering decisions.","correct":false,"why":"Web proxy logs show browsing destinations, not the cloud control-plane admin actions and API calls needed to detect account takeover."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q165","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Baselining (Normal vs Anomalous)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A new anomaly rule flags “high DNS query volume” for multiple endpoints. Analysts are unsure if it is malware or a software update event. What is the BEST first step?","options":[{"text":"Compare against historical baselines and change windows, then enrich with process and user context before escalating.","correct":true,"why":"Baseline and change context help separate legitimate update behavior from suspicious activity."},{"text":"Quarantine every endpoint that triggered because unusual resolver activity is sufficient evidence of active compromise.","correct":false,"why":"Quarantining every triggering endpoint before investigating risks major disruption if the volume increase turns out to be a legitimate software update."},{"text":"Raise the DNS threshold globally so only the largest spikes alert while analysts review the trend later.","correct":false,"why":"Simply raising the alert threshold reduces visibility into genuinely anomalous activity rather than helping distinguish it from benign causes."},{"text":"Pivot immediately to external threat feeds and block the queried domains before validating internal activity patterns.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking domains from external feeds before validating internal context risks disrupting a legitimate update process based on an unconfirmed assumption."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q166","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"NetFlow (Metadata vs Payload)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Network monitoring shows large data transfers to a single external IP, but TLS prevents payload inspection. Which telemetry is MOST useful to quantify and scope the suspected exfiltration?","options":[{"text":"Use flow records with byte counts, duration, direction, endpoints, and host attribution to measure transfer scope.","correct":true,"why":"NetFlow/IPFIX is ideal for encrypted traffic because it shows volume, timing, direction, and endpoints even when payload inspection is unavailable."},{"text":"Review switch CAM tables and port-security counters to identify which access port last learned the source MAC.","correct":false,"why":"Switch CAM tables and port-security counters identify local port-to-MAC mappings; they don't measure the volume or scope of a suspected external data transfer."},{"text":"Capture wireless signal metrics over the time period to determine whether radio interference affected throughput.","correct":false,"why":"Wireless signal metrics reflect radio conditions, not the volume, duration, or endpoints involved in the suspected exfiltration."},{"text":"Audit password age and lockout settings to estimate which accounts could have initiated the transfer session.","correct":false,"why":"Password age and lockout settings don't identify which account initiated a specific transfer session or help scope the transfer's scale."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q167","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS/NDR (Placement)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"An IDS sensor is only at the internet edge. The organization experiences lateral movement between internal subnets without alerts. Which change MOST improves detection?","options":[{"text":"Deploy internal sensors or NDR at east-west chokepoints and critical segments to observe inter-subnet movement.","correct":true,"why":"Sensor placement determines visibility."},{"text":"Tune edge signatures more aggressively so they infer internal movement from internet-bound sessions and retries.","correct":false,"why":"Tuning edge signatures more aggressively still only observes internet-bound traffic; it can't directly detect movement happening between internal subnets."},{"text":"Mirror only core-switch management traffic because configuration channels best represent user-to-user traversal paths.","correct":false,"why":"Mirroring only core-switch management traffic captures configuration activity, not the actual user-to-user lateral traffic between subnets."},{"text":"Increase firewall deny logging at the perimeter to approximate which internal VLANs are communicating laterally.","correct":false,"why":"Firewall deny logging at the perimeter only reflects traffic crossing the network edge, not lateral movement occurring entirely within internal subnets."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q168","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SIEM Correlation (Identity)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A user successfully logs in to SaaS from the US, then two minutes later from Europe, both with valid MFA. What is the BEST correlation rule concept for this?","options":[{"text":"Use geo-velocity correlation across identity events with time windows, IP enrichment, and session context.","correct":true,"why":"Impossible travel or rapid geo-velocity detection is the direct analytic for this pattern."},{"text":"Alert on repeated MFA success events for the same account because valid prompts indicate persistent account misuse.","correct":false,"why":"Repeated valid MFA successes for one account are expected during normal use; this alone doesn't capture the specific impossible-travel pattern described."},{"text":"Correlate the account to endpoint CPU spikes because unusual compute load typically follows identity compromise.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint CPU spikes are unrelated to identity events and wouldn't reliably correlate with a geographically impossible login pattern."},{"text":"Track certificate renewal events on the SaaS tenant because session region changes usually accompany trust updates.","correct":false,"why":"Certificate renewal events on the tenant have no relationship to a user's login location or the timing between two logins."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q169","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"PCAP Triage (TCP Flags)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A firewall log shows many outbound connections to random IPs with short-lived sessions. PCAP indicates repeated SYNs with no completed handshakes. What is the MOST likely interpretation?","options":[{"text":"The host is likely probing or scanning for reachable services without completing full application sessions.","correct":true,"why":"Repeated SYNs without completed handshakes commonly indicate recon, blocked traffic, or attempts to discover live services."},{"text":"The host is maintaining normal browser preconnect behavior across many destinations before loading content pages.","correct":false,"why":"Normal browser preconnect behavior completes handshakes to load content; it wouldn't produce many repeated SYNs with no completed connections."},{"text":"The pattern suggests a throughput-optimized transfer where data leaves before acknowledgments are fully exchanged.","correct":false,"why":"A throughput-optimized transfer still requires completed handshakes to exchange data; it wouldn't show only SYNs without established sessions."},{"text":"The activity reflects standard name-resolution retries because recursive queries begin with repeated SYN packets.","correct":false,"why":"DNS resolution uses UDP queries, not repeated TCP SYN packets, so this doesn't match standard name-resolution retry behavior."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q170","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Log Integrity (Time Sync)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"An investigation is slowed because events from endpoints, firewalls, and SaaS logs appear out of order. Which control MOST directly fixes this?","options":[{"text":"Standardize time synchronization and timestamp formats across all log sources to preserve reliable event sequencing.","correct":true,"why":"Centralized time sync and consistent timestamp standards are essential for correlation and incident timelines."},{"text":"Increase collection frequency so the SIEM ingests records sooner and can sort them by receipt order instead.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing collection frequency affects how quickly logs arrive, not whether their timestamps are consistent enough to establish accurate event order."},{"text":"Raise log verbosity on every device so duplicate messages make cross-source ordering easier to infer manually.","correct":false,"why":"Raising log verbosity produces more messages but doesn't fix inconsistent timestamps across sources, which is the actual ordering problem."},{"text":"Shorten retention windows so analysts only review recent records that are less likely to have ordering drift.","correct":false,"why":"Shortening retention reduces the data available for investigation but does nothing to correct the underlying timestamp inconsistency."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q171","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"UEBA (Behavioral Analytics)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Analysts suspect an insider is staging sensitive files before exfiltration. Traditional signatures are quiet. Which monitoring approach BEST detects this pattern?","options":[{"text":"Apply behavior analytics to unusual file access, privilege use, and movement patterns for the specific user.","correct":true,"why":"UEBA is well suited for insider scenarios because it highlights deviations in access, staging, and privilege behavior against a normal baseline."},{"text":"Increase perimeter deny logging so outbound blocks become the primary signal for insider handling of data.","correct":false,"why":"Perimeter deny logging only shows blocked outbound traffic; it wouldn't reveal internal file staging behavior by a trusted insider with legitimate access."},{"text":"Run authenticated vulnerability scans more often to reveal whether exploitable software enabled the staging phase.","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability scans reveal software weaknesses, not behavioral patterns like unusual file access or privilege use by an insider."},{"text":"Focus on domain-generation detections because insiders usually rely on covert DNS channels during collection.","correct":false,"why":"DNS tunneling and domain-generation detections target external C2 channels; they wouldn't be the primary signal for internal file-staging behavior by an insider."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q172","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"EDR Telemetry (Process Context)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A detection shows powershell.exe spawning rundll32.exe with a long base64 command line. Which enrichment is MOST valuable to confirm malicious behavior?","options":[{"text":"Review process lineage, command-line details, signer trust, and related network connections for that execution.","correct":true,"why":"Process tree, command line, signer reputation, and network context are the most direct enrichments for validating scripting abuse and LOLBin behavior."},{"text":"Check disk health telemetry to see whether sustained read or write rates align with script-based execution.","correct":false,"why":"Disk health telemetry reflects hardware read/write performance, not the process behavior or command-line content needed to assess this specific detection."},{"text":"Compare the user’s display and idle-state history to determine whether the shell ran during active interaction.","correct":false,"why":"User idle-state history doesn't confirm whether the observed process chain and encoded command line represent malicious activity."},{"text":"Inspect print service events to identify whether document rendering preceded the encoded command invocation.","correct":false,"why":"Print service events are unrelated to a PowerShell-to-rundll32 execution chain and wouldn't help confirm malicious behavior here."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q173","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Syslog (Normalization)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A SIEM receives syslog from multiple vendors, but fields are inconsistent and correlations fail. What is the BEST fix?","options":[{"text":"Normalize records into a common schema and verify mappings for time, host, action, and severity fields.","correct":true,"why":"Normalization and field mapping are what make multi-vendor correlations reliable."},{"text":"Store all messages as raw text and rely on keyword searches so vendor formats remain untouched in the index.","correct":false,"why":"Storing raw text and relying on keyword search doesn't resolve inconsistent field formats across vendors, so cross-source correlation still fails."},{"text":"Reduce ingestion to the noisiest devices first so parsing issues become easier to diagnose with fewer sources.","correct":false,"why":"Reducing ingestion to fewer devices might simplify troubleshooting but doesn't fix the underlying field inconsistency causing correlation failures."},{"text":"Extend retention periods to increase cross-vendor history, which improves field consistency over longer timelines.","correct":false,"why":"Extending retention adds more historical data but does nothing to make field names or formats consistent across different vendor sources."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q174","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS Tuning (False Positives)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"IDS repeatedly alerts on “SQL injection” for a legitimate JSON search endpoint. Which tuning reduces false positives while maintaining coverage?","options":[{"text":"Add narrowly scoped exceptions using URI and content-type context while leaving broader injection coverage intact.","correct":true,"why":"Precision tuning is best here."},{"text":"Lower signature sensitivity on the entire sensor so structured API traffic produces fewer application-layer alerts.","correct":false,"why":"Lowering sensitivity across the entire sensor reduces detection of genuine SQL injection attempts elsewhere, sacrificing broader coverage for this one endpoint's noise."},{"text":"Move the application to a separate subnet and treat the segment as trusted for all injection-related detections.","correct":false,"why":"Treating the whole subnet as trusted for injection detections removes coverage for other services on that segment, not just the noisy endpoint."},{"text":"Suppress alerts only after analysts manually label each request pattern instead of refining the detection logic.","correct":false,"why":"Manually suppressing alerts after the fact doesn't scale and leaves the underlying detection logic untouched, so the false positives keep recurring."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q175","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Threat Hunting (Hypothesis)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A hunter suspects credential dumping is occurring. Which data is MOST directly useful to test the hypothesis quickly?","options":[{"text":"Use endpoint and security logs showing LSASS access, suspicious handles, and related credential-tool artifacts.","correct":true,"why":"Credential-dumping hunts should focus on LSASS access, handle opens, suspicious drivers, and endpoint evidence tied to memory access."},{"text":"Review email click history to find whether the suspected user recently interacted with external newsletters.","correct":false,"why":"Email click history relates to phishing exposure, not the memory access and tool artifacts that would confirm credential dumping."},{"text":"Inspect printer service activity to determine whether spooler interactions preceded the suspected account misuse.","correct":false,"why":"Printer spooler activity has no direct connection to credential-dumping techniques like LSASS access."},{"text":"Query building-access events to compare badge swipes with the timing of the endpoint detections under review.","correct":false,"why":"Building-access badge data reflects physical presence, not the technical evidence of LSASS access or credential-dumping tool activity being hunted for."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q176","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"DNS Monitoring (Tunneling)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"You observe many long, random subdomain queries to a single domain with consistent intervals. Which detection best fits?","options":[{"text":"Investigate for DNS tunneling by reviewing label entropy, query frequency, destination history, and response patterns.","correct":true,"why":"Long, high-entropy labels at regular intervals to a single destination strongly fit DNS tunneling or data-smuggling behavior."},{"text":"Classify it as content-delivery optimization because edge services often generate stable, high-entropy labels.","correct":false,"why":"Content-delivery services don't typically generate long, high-entropy random subdomains at consistent short intervals to a single domain; that pattern is unusual for legitimate CDN behavior."},{"text":"Treat it as local name-resolution churn caused by clients failing over between internal recursive resolvers.","correct":false,"why":"Resolver failover would produce inconsistent, retry-driven query patterns, not the long, high-entropy labels at steady intervals described here."},{"text":"Map it to routine patch orchestration because software updates commonly beacon through randomized subdomains.","correct":false,"why":"Routine patch orchestration doesn't typically rely on long, randomized subdomain labels at consistent intervals; that's atypical for standard update check-ins."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q177","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Controls (Alert Fatigue)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Analysts are overwhelmed by thousands of low-value alerts daily. Detection quality is dropping. What is the BEST first improvement?","options":[{"text":"Tune noisy rules, add enrichment, and prioritize workflows so analysts work higher-signal alerts first.","correct":true,"why":"Reducing noise and increasing context is the right first move."},{"text":"Enable the remaining unused detections so analysts see fuller coverage before deciding which alerts matter.","correct":false,"why":"Enabling more unused detections would add even more alert volume, worsening the fatigue problem rather than improving analyst focus."},{"text":"Shift all review to weekly batches so the queue is larger but handled in a more predictable reporting cycle.","correct":false,"why":"Shifting to weekly batches delays review without reducing the underlying volume of low-value alerts causing the fatigue."},{"text":"Require manual validation of every raw log source before an alert can be closed or triaged by the team.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring manual validation of every raw log before triage adds more analyst workload, compounding the fatigue rather than relieving it."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q178","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewall Logs (NAT Attribution)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"The SOC needs to map a suspicious public connection to the internal host behind PAT. Which log detail is MOST necessary?","options":[{"text":"Use timestamped NAT translation tuples that map inside IP and port pairs to the public session values.","correct":true,"why":"PAT attribution depends on NAT translation logs that tie internal IP:port pairs to public IP:port mappings at a specific time."},{"text":"Review the destination’s reputation category so the external service can be matched back to the initiating asset.","correct":false,"why":"Destination reputation data identifies the risk of an external service, not which internal host and port initiated the connection behind PAT."},{"text":"Correlate wireless SSID assignments to determine which user segment owned the translated internet connection.","correct":false,"why":"Wireless SSID assignments identify network segment association, not the specific NAT translation needed to map a public session to an internal host."},{"text":"Check lifecycle inventory data to see which device class was most likely to use the observed ephemeral port.","correct":false,"why":"Device lifecycle inventory data doesn't provide the specific timestamped translation record needed to attribute a particular ephemeral port to a host."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q179","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Monitoring (Resource Abuse)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Billing spikes show unusual compute consumption overnight. Logs reveal many new instances launched with the same API key. What is the MOST likely incident?","options":[{"text":"Compromised cloud credentials are being used for automated resource abuse such as cryptomining workloads.","correct":true,"why":"Unexpected instance creation tied to one API key and billing spikes strongly indicates stolen credentials being used for cloud resource abuse."},{"text":"A scheduled autoscaling policy is overreacting to traffic forecasts associated with the same service principal.","correct":false,"why":"An autoscaling policy reacting to traffic forecasts wouldn't typically launch instances tied to unexpected overnight billing spikes using one API key in this pattern."},{"text":"The environment is recycling failed instances because service discovery cannot resolve backend dependencies.","correct":false,"why":"Recycling failed instances due to service discovery issues wouldn't produce a billing spike from many new instances tied to a single API key."},{"text":"A security group change is triggering replacement of compute nodes across the account for policy alignment.","correct":false,"why":"A security group change triggering node replacement for policy alignment wouldn't explain the specific pattern of new compute tied to one API key and a cost spike."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q180","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Email Monitoring (Phish Triage)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Multiple users report a suspicious email with a link to a newly registered domain. Which action best supports rapid triage?","options":[{"text":"Enrich the URL with reputation, domain age, sandbox results, and correlate clicks with authentication activity.","correct":true,"why":"Rapid triage comes from enrichment and correlation: reputation, WHOIS/domain age, sandboxing, and evidence of user interaction."},{"text":"Purge the messages first, then investigate only if additional login anomalies appear for one of the recipients.","correct":false,"why":"Purging first and waiting for further anomalies delays gathering the reputation and sandbox evidence needed to triage the report quickly."},{"text":"Block all external links at the gateway until analysts finish comparing the campaign against known reporting trends.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking all external links at the gateway is a broad, disruptive step that doesn't itself confirm or scope the specific threat from this email."},{"text":"Forward copies to an external mailbox used for detonation so internal analysis systems stay separated from risk.","correct":false,"why":"Forwarding to an external detonation mailbox introduces unnecessary handling risk and delay compared to using internal enrichment and correlation tools directly."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q181","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Packet Analysis (Beaconing)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Network telemetry shows periodic HTTPS connections every 60 seconds to a rare domain, always with small outbound bytes and larger inbound bytes. Which interpretation is MOST plausible?","options":[{"text":"This is consistent with command-and-control beaconing and should be validated with endpoint and DNS context.","correct":true,"why":"Regular intervals and consistent small-outbound/larger-inbound patterns are classic beaconing indicators."},{"text":"The host is likely streaming media in segmented bursts that align naturally to fixed one-minute intervals.","correct":false,"why":"Streaming media typically varies in segment size and timing based on content; it doesn't produce the strict small-outbound/larger-inbound pattern at fixed one-minute intervals described."},{"text":"It reflects a scheduled backup negotiation in which remote storage polls the host before each transfer block.","correct":false,"why":"Scheduled backup negotiation wouldn't typically show this consistent small-request/larger-response pattern at short, fixed intervals to a rare external domain."},{"text":"The system is renewing infrastructure leases through encrypted service checks that happen once per minute.","correct":false,"why":"Infrastructure lease renewals don't typically involve consistent small-outbound, larger-inbound data patterns at one-minute intervals to a rare destination."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q182","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SIEM Queries (Scoping)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A ransomware alert triggers on one endpoint. What is the BEST next SIEM query to scope potential spread?","options":[{"text":"Search across hosts for matching artifacts, related process activity, lateral auth events, and SMB or RDP use.","correct":true,"why":"The best scoping query looks for the same indicators plus lateral movement evidence across other hosts."},{"text":"Query enterprise-wide CPU spikes during the day because encryption activity should dominate processor trends.","correct":false,"why":"Enterprise-wide CPU spikes are a noisy, indirect signal and wouldn't specifically reveal which other hosts share the same indicators or lateral movement evidence."},{"text":"Pull every login event for the past year so long-term user behavior can reveal the earliest compromise path.","correct":false,"why":"Pulling a full year of login events is far broader than needed and doesn't specifically target the artifacts and lateral movement relevant to this ransomware alert."},{"text":"Limit the query to antivirus quarantine actions because spread should only occur where prevention already fired.","correct":false,"why":"Limiting to antivirus quarantine actions would miss any host where the malware wasn't yet detected or blocked, undercounting the true scope of spread."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q183","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Sysmon/Security Logs (Windows)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A Windows host shows repeated event IDs for new service installation and scheduled task creation. Why is this suspicious?","options":[{"text":"These are common persistence mechanisms, so correlate creator accounts, binaries, and timing for abuse.","correct":true,"why":"Services and scheduled tasks are popular persistence mechanisms."},{"text":"The pattern mainly indicates ordinary software lifecycle activity unless it appears alongside disk health issues.","correct":false,"why":"Framing this as ordinary lifecycle activity unless paired with disk health issues misses that persistence techniques don't require any hardware symptom to be suspicious."},{"text":"It most directly suggests outbound collection of data because automation objects are preferred for transfer jobs.","correct":false,"why":"Service and scheduled task creation are primarily persistence techniques, not typically the mechanism used for outbound data collection specifically."},{"text":"The events are primarily valuable as evidence of patch rollback rather than long-term foothold establishment.","correct":false,"why":"These events are far more associated with establishing long-term footholds than with evidence of a patch rollback."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q184","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Coverage (Gaps)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A SOC realizes it has no visibility into privileged activity on network devices. Which monitoring control MOST directly addresses this?","options":[{"text":"Enable AAA accounting, centralize device logs, and correlate administrative commands with configuration changes.","correct":true,"why":"AAA accounting and centralized network-device logging directly show who performed which actions and when."},{"text":"Increase endpoint privileged-access monitoring so workstation telemetry can stand in for network device activity.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint privileged-access monitoring covers workstations, not the network devices themselves, so it can't substitute for visibility into device-level admin actions."},{"text":"Rely on quarterly configuration exports and compare checksums to identify whether privileged use likely occurred.","correct":false,"why":"Quarterly checksum comparisons only catch changes retroactively and don't capture who performed which privileged action or when in real time."},{"text":"Collect only interface utilization metrics because privileged misuse usually manifests as performance anomalies first.","correct":false,"why":"Interface utilization metrics reflect traffic load, not who is performing privileged administrative actions on the device."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q185","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Analysts spend hours enriching alerts with IP reputation, WHOIS, and sandbox lookups. Which improvement BEST reduces time-to-triage?","options":[{"text":"Build SOAR playbooks that automate enrichment and standardize triage steps with approvals where needed.","correct":true,"why":"SOAR is the natural solution for repetitive enrichment and consistent triage workflows."},{"text":"Remove the enrichment steps and let analysts decide case priority from the raw detection text alone.","correct":false,"why":"Removing enrichment steps entirely leaves analysts with less context, likely slowing accurate triage rather than speeding it up."},{"text":"Increase the number of analytic rules so more context is embedded in the alert stream by default.","correct":false,"why":"Adding more analytic rules increases alert volume but doesn't automate the manual enrichment work that's actually consuming analyst time."},{"text":"Move the SIEM searches to a slower review cycle so fewer alerts appear ready for enrichment each hour.","correct":false,"why":"Moving to a slower review cycle delays triage rather than reducing the time spent per alert on manual enrichment tasks."}],"sub":"1.9"},{"id":"q186","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Honeypots/Honeytokens (Detection)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Security plants a fake admin credential in a monitored location. Any use should be suspicious. What is this technique called?","options":[{"text":"A honeytoken, which is a decoy artifact that should trigger high-confidence alerts if it is touched or used.","correct":true,"why":"A honeytoken is a decoy artifact such as a credential or file used to generate high-confidence detections."},{"text":"Tokenization, which substitutes reference values for sensitive data while preserving application workflows.","correct":false,"why":"Tokenization replaces sensitive data with substitute values for legitimate processing; it isn't a decoy meant to trigger alerts when touched."},{"text":"Kerberoasting, which abuses service tickets to support offline password recovery against domain accounts.","correct":false,"why":"Kerberoasting is an attack technique targeting service tickets, not a term for a planted decoy credential used for detection."},{"text":"Sharding, which distributes records across partitions so a compromise cannot affect every data set at once.","correct":false,"why":"Sharding is a data distribution technique for resilience and scale; it has nothing to do with planting a decoy credential for detection."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q187","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TLS Monitoring (JA3/FP)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Encrypted traffic is hard to inspect, but analysts want to cluster suspicious clients by TLS behavior. Which technique helps?","options":[{"text":"Use TLS fingerprinting to group clients by handshake traits and highlight anomalous encrypted sessions.","correct":true,"why":"TLS fingerprinting such as JA3/JA4-style techniques helps cluster encrypted traffic without decrypting the payload."},{"text":"Rely on MAC filtering data because hardware addresses remain stable indicators across internet destinations.","correct":false,"why":"MAC addresses aren't visible or consistent across internet destinations beyond the local network segment; they can't be used to cluster remote encrypted sessions."},{"text":"Compare DNS TTL values to determine which encrypted clients belong to the same malware family cluster.","correct":false,"why":"DNS TTL values reflect caching duration, not client-specific handshake behavior, and wouldn't reliably cluster malware families."},{"text":"Track port-based allow lists only, since modern encrypted tooling tends to reuse a narrow service profile.","correct":false,"why":"Port-based allow lists reflect which services are permitted, not behavioral traits of the TLS handshake itself, and wouldn't cluster anomalous encrypted clients."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q188","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability vs Monitoring (Complementary)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"A team argues vulnerability scanning eliminates the need for continuous monitoring. What is the BEST response?","options":[{"text":"Scanning finds known weaknesses periodically, while monitoring detects active abuse and emerging behavior continuously.","correct":true,"why":"Scanning and monitoring solve different problems."},{"text":"Continuous monitoring mainly duplicates patch-status reporting, so its value depends on external audit schedules.","correct":false,"why":"Continuous monitoring does far more than duplicate patch-status reporting; it observes live behavior and active abuse that scanning alone can't detect."},{"text":"If scan coverage is broad enough, active misuse is usually captured through severity trends and asset exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Broad scan coverage still only reflects known weaknesses at a point in time; it can't capture active misuse or emerging attacker behavior as it happens."},{"text":"Monitoring becomes optional once remediation SLAs are mature because exploitation should decline with patch cadence.","correct":false,"why":"Mature remediation SLAs reduce known vulnerabilities over time but don't eliminate the need to detect active exploitation or novel attack behavior."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q189","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"DLP Monitoring (Data Movement)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"An analyst suspects sensitive data is being uploaded to personal cloud storage. Which monitoring control MOST directly helps confirm and stop it?","options":[{"text":"Use DLP at the endpoint or web gateway with content classification and SIEM logging for attempted uploads.","correct":true,"why":"DLP is the most direct control because it can both identify sensitive content and block attempted uploads while logging the event."},{"text":"Review firewall egress categories and block unsanctioned destinations while relying on user reports for validation.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking unsanctioned destinations and relying on user reports doesn't inspect the actual content being uploaded, so it can't confirm sensitive data exposure directly."},{"text":"Capture more packet data from remote users so analysts can manually determine whether uploads contain restricted files.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing more packet data for manual review doesn't scale and lacks the automated content classification DLP provides."},{"text":"Expand disk quotas and local sync controls to slow transfers long enough for analysts to investigate user activity.","correct":false,"why":"Expanding disk quotas or sync controls only slows transfers; it doesn't identify or stop sensitive content from being uploaded."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q190","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication Monitoring (Brute Force vs Spray)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"The SIEM sees many failed logins across many accounts with the same password, spaced out to avoid lockouts. Which attack pattern is this?","options":[{"text":"Password spraying, where a small password set is tried broadly across many users over time.","correct":true,"why":"Password spraying is low-and-slow across many users with one or a few passwords, unlike brute force against a single account."},{"text":"Brute forcing, where one account is tested with a long sequence of password guesses until it yields.","correct":false,"why":"Brute forcing targets a single account with many password attempts; this scenario instead spreads few passwords across many accounts, which is spraying."},{"text":"Kerberoasting, where service tickets are requested for offline cracking against service-account secrets.","correct":false,"why":"Kerberoasting targets service ticket encryption for offline cracking; it doesn't involve failed logins across many accounts with a shared password."},{"text":"Golden-ticket abuse, where forged Kerberos tickets are used to bypass repeated password validation attempts.","correct":false,"why":"Golden-ticket abuse forges Kerberos tickets to bypass authentication entirely; it wouldn't produce many failed login attempts across accounts."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q191","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Response (Containment)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"An endpoint alert indicates possible C2. What is the BEST immediate containment action while preserving evidence?","options":[{"text":"Isolate the host through EDR network containment while leaving it powered for volatile evidence collection.","correct":true,"why":"EDR network isolation contains the host quickly while preserving volatile evidence and limiting further command-and-control activity."},{"text":"Reset the user’s credentials first so any malicious process loses access before host-level action is taken.","correct":false,"why":"Resetting credentials doesn't stop an active C2 process already running on the host or contain its network communication."},{"text":"Force an enterprise firewall block on the suspect domain while keeping the host fully connected for monitoring.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking only the specific domain at the firewall still leaves the host connected and able to reach other C2 infrastructure."},{"text":"Start remote remediation scripts immediately so suspicious binaries are removed before they can disappear.","correct":false,"why":"Running remediation scripts immediately risks destroying volatile evidence and alerting the attacker before containment and evidence collection occur."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q192","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"NDR + EDR Correlation (Confidence)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"NDR detects beaconing from a host, but EDR shows no malware alerts. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Correlate the destination to process-level network telemetry and investigate proxying, tunneling, or LOLBin use.","correct":true,"why":"EDR may miss suspicious tools or not alert on them."},{"text":"Reduce confidence in the network alert until the endpoint tool produces a matching prevention or malware verdict.","correct":false,"why":"Reducing confidence in the network detection just because EDR is silent risks dismissing a real threat that endpoint tooling simply failed to catch."},{"text":"Treat the traffic as benign background application behavior unless the domain appears in multiple threat feeds.","correct":false,"why":"Treating the traffic as benign unless it appears on multiple threat feeds ignores that EDR gaps, not feed absence, are the likely explanation here."},{"text":"Close the case after documenting the discrepancy because duplicate coverage should have produced identical outcomes.","correct":false,"why":"Closing the case assumes both tools should always agree, but EDR not alerting doesn't mean the network-observed beaconing is safe to dismiss."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q193","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Program (KPIs)","source":"CySA_Day 6.html","q":"Leadership wants to measure SOC performance improvements after new tooling. Which metric BEST reflects operational detection effectiveness?","options":[{"text":"Track mean time to detect and mean time to respond using consistent incident definitions over comparable periods.","correct":true,"why":"MTTD and MTTR are strong operational metrics for detection and response effectiveness when measured consistently."},{"text":"Track total alerts generated per day because broader visibility should naturally increase case volume over time.","correct":false,"why":"Alert volume can rise simply from more visibility, not necessarily from improved detection or response effectiveness."},{"text":"Track total log volume stored because larger telemetry sets usually indicate stronger detection maturity across teams.","correct":false,"why":"Larger stored log volume reflects data retention, not whether the SOC is actually detecting and responding to incidents more effectively."},{"text":"Track firewall rule count because more policy objects generally reflect deeper operational monitoring investment.","correct":false,"why":"Firewall rule count reflects policy complexity, not how effectively the SOC detects or responds to actual incidents."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q194","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Baseline & CIS)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"After repeated incidents, leadership wants a repeatable way to reduce attack surface on new servers. Which approach BEST supports consistent hardening at scale?","options":[{"text":"Standardize approved builds as code, enforce the state automatically, and flag deviations continuously across the fleet","correct":true,"why":"Standard baselines + automation + continuous compliance prevent drift and scale hardening across fleets consistently."},{"text":"Publish a server build standard, require peer review for changes, and verify adherence during scheduled platform audits","correct":false,"why":"Peer review and scheduled audits still rely on manual processes and periodic checks, which can't prevent or continuously catch drift the way automated enforcement does."},{"text":"Refresh golden images each quarter, rebuild systems during maintenance windows, and document approved exception handling","correct":false,"why":"Refreshing golden images quarterly still leaves systems exposed to drift between refresh cycles rather than continuously enforcing the baseline."},{"text":"Use startup scripts to apply common settings, then investigate configuration drift only after scanners report material findings","correct":false,"why":"Investigating drift only after scanners report findings is reactive and allows deviations to persist until the next scan catches them."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q195","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Input Validation)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A web API concatenates untrusted input directly into a SQL query string. Which coding practice MOST directly prevents injection?","options":[{"text":"Separate user-supplied values from query logic through bound parameters and narrowly scoped database permissions","correct":true,"why":"Parameterized queries prevent user input from being interpreted as SQL code, and validation/least privilege reduces impact."},{"text":"Constrain accepted characters and formats before constructing server-side statements from approved request fields","correct":false,"why":"Input format constraints reduce some malformed input but don't stop the fundamental issue of user input being interpreted as part of the SQL query itself."},{"text":"Move data access into predefined routines and rely on audit records to identify abusive statement patterns","correct":false,"why":"Moving to stored routines with audit logging can help but doesn't prevent injection if those routines still concatenate untrusted input into dynamic SQL."},{"text":"Filter suspicious payloads at the edge and normalize requests before they reach the application database tier","correct":false,"why":"Edge-level filtering can be bypassed by encoding or novel payloads and doesn't address the root cause of unparameterized query construction."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q196","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Digital Forensics (Order of Volatility)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"You arrive at a live system suspected of memory-resident malware. What evidence should be collected FIRST for best forensic value?","options":[{"text":"Preserve ephemeral system state before shutdown by prioritizing resident process and connection artifacts over static media","correct":true,"why":"Order of volatility: collect memory and other volatile artifacts before they are lost due to shutdown/reboot."},{"text":"Disconnect the host immediately to halt remote control, then gather live artifacts once the communication path is severed","correct":false,"why":"Disconnecting the host immediately still risks losing volatile memory state, especially if it triggers any shutdown or defensive wipe behavior on the malware's part."},{"text":"Start with a full storage acquisition so the primary evidence set is secured before collecting transient operating state","correct":false,"why":"Starting with full storage acquisition first risks losing memory-resident evidence, which is more volatile and time-sensitive than static disk data."},{"text":"Export endpoint telemetry first because centrally retained records are less likely to be challenged than host acquisitions","correct":false,"why":"Centrally retained endpoint telemetry doesn't capture the same live memory-resident details as direct volatile-state collection from the host itself."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q197","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Least Privilege)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A service account is configured as domain admin “for convenience.” A compromise of the service host leads to domain takeover. What control MOST reduces future impact?","options":[{"text":"Narrow the account to only required actions, constrain where it can authenticate, and isolate privileged material from the host","correct":true,"why":"Over-privileged accounts create catastrophic blast radius."},{"text":"Keep the role assignment unchanged but prevent interactive use and rotate the credential on a tighter administrative cadence","correct":false,"why":"Keeping domain admin rights while only limiting interactive logon and rotating credentials still leaves the account with excessive privileges if the host is compromised."},{"text":"Move the workload onto a more isolated server tier and reduce inbound exposure to limit opportunities for host compromise","correct":false,"why":"Isolating the workload to a more restricted server tier reduces exposure to compromise but doesn't reduce the blast radius if the overprivileged account itself is misused."},{"text":"Require stronger administrator sign-in controls and alert on unusual directory changes initiated by service identities","correct":false,"why":"Stronger sign-in controls and change alerts help detect misuse but don't reduce the excessive privilege itself, which is the root cause of the catastrophic blast radius."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q198","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (XSS Prevention)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A web page reflects user-supplied input back into HTML without encoding. Which remediation BEST prevents reflected XSS?","options":[{"text":"Transform untrusted output for its exact browser context and reinforce the page with execution-limiting browser controls","correct":true,"why":"Encode output for the specific context (HTML, attributes, JS) and add CSP defense-in-depth."},{"text":"Allow only expected input patterns at submission time and rely on browser policy reporting to surface bad payload attempts","correct":false,"why":"Restricting input patterns at submission time doesn't prevent unencoded data already in the system from being rendered unsafely in the HTML response."},{"text":"Centralize sanitization through one reusable routine so every response path receives identical treatment regardless of sink","correct":false,"why":"A single reusable sanitization routine may not apply the correct context-specific encoding needed for different sinks (HTML body vs. attribute vs. script)."},{"text":"Return the reflected value inside structured data responses and trust the client renderer to handle unsafe characters safely","correct":false,"why":"Trusting the client renderer to safely handle unsafe characters is exactly the assumption that allows reflected XSS to succeed; the server must encode output itself."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q199","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Chain of Custody)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"Evidence may be used in legal proceedings. What practice MOST supports admissibility and integrity?","options":[{"text":"Maintain a documented custody trail with integrity verification and controlled handling at every transfer point","correct":true,"why":"Chain of custody + hashing + controlled handling establishes integrity and accountability over evidence lifecycle."},{"text":"Verify the collection set at intake and again at case closure while relying on storage access logs between those events","correct":false,"why":"Verifying only at intake and closure leaves gaps in the middle of the evidence lifecycle where tampering could occur undetected between those checkpoints."},{"text":"Place all media in restricted evidence lockers and use change tickets to reconstruct who interacted with each item","correct":false,"why":"Relying on change tickets to reconstruct custody after the fact is less reliable than maintaining a continuous, documented chain of custody in real time."},{"text":"Prioritize tamper-evident packaging and signed handoff forms, treating technical validation as secondary to physical control","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing physical packaging over technical integrity verification (like hashing) leaves digital tampering undetectable even with proper physical handling."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q200","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Patch vs Config)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A system is fully patched, but still vulnerable due to weak configurations and enabled legacy protocols. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Remove unnecessary exposure by tightening settings and retiring obsolete communication methods that expand reachable surface","correct":true,"why":"Hardening complements patching: reduce attack surface, remove insecure protocols, and enforce secure baselines."},{"text":"Reduce network reachability to the legacy services first, then retire them after the next maintenance cycle completes","correct":false,"why":"Reducing reachability while deferring retirement to the next maintenance cycle still leaves the legacy protocols enabled and exploitable in the meantime."},{"text":"Increase scanning frequency so insecure settings are reported sooner while larger platform changes are evaluated separately","correct":false,"why":"Increasing scan frequency only reports the insecure settings sooner; it doesn't actually remediate the weak configuration or legacy protocols themselves."},{"text":"Leave the configuration unchanged and depend on monitoring to identify misuse of the remaining backward-compatible features","correct":false,"why":"Leaving the configuration unchanged and relying on monitoring accepts ongoing risk rather than removing the actual exposure the weak settings create."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q201","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Secrets Management)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"Developers store API keys in source code repositories to simplify deployments. What is the BEST remediation?","options":[{"text":"Move credentials to a managed secret source, rotate what was exposed, and prevent recurrence with pipeline and commit checks","correct":true,"why":"Secrets should be stored in vaults, rotated, minimized, and monitored; code repos are not appropriate for sensitive credentials."},{"text":"Encrypt configuration files in the repository, limit who can decrypt them, and review usage patterns for abnormal access","correct":false,"why":"Encrypting configuration files still keeps secrets in the repository long-term; it doesn't remove them from source control or eliminate the exposure risk."},{"text":"Replace long-lived values with shorter-lived ones but continue storing them with the application for deployment convenience","correct":false,"why":"Shortening credential lifetime helps but still stores secrets alongside the application rather than moving them to a managed, monitored secret source."},{"text":"Keep sensitive values on build infrastructure only and trust the delivery system to inject them safely during releases","correct":false,"why":"Trusting build infrastructure to inject values doesn't address that the exposed keys were already committed to the repository and need rotation."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q202","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Disk Imaging)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"You need to acquire a forensic image of a suspect drive. What is the BEST practice to avoid altering evidence?","options":[{"text":"Interpose read-protection during acquisition, capture the entire medium faithfully, and confirm integrity before examination","correct":true,"why":"Write blockers prevent modifications."},{"text":"Perform a read-only logical collection first so urgent artifacts are preserved before deciding whether full capture is necessary","correct":false,"why":"A read-only logical collection captures only selected artifacts rather than the entire medium, risking missed evidence outside what's initially deemed urgent."},{"text":"Prioritize active case directories and verify those results, accepting that low-value space can be revisited if needed later","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing only active case directories risks leaving other areas of the drive unexamined, and revisiting later doesn't guarantee those areas remain unaltered."},{"text":"Acquire directly from the device with minimal interaction and depend on post-collection digests to show nothing changed materially","correct":false,"why":"Relying on post-collection digests alone doesn't prevent modification during acquisition; a write blocker is needed to prevent changes in the first place."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q203","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Network Segmentation)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A malware outbreak spreads via SMB/RDP across multiple VLANs. Which control MOST reduces future lateral movement?","options":[{"text":"Constrain east-west administration paths so remote management is limited to tightly governed access channels between tiers","correct":true,"why":"Segmentation and controlling admin pathways reduce lateral movement and credential reuse impact."},{"text":"Harden remote administration hosts and require stronger sign-in steps while preserving most existing network trust relationships","correct":false,"why":"Hardening admin hosts and sign-in steps still leaves broad east-west network trust intact, allowing lateral movement paths to persist."},{"text":"Retire older file-sharing versions and improve host firewalling so workstation controls shoulder most containment duties","correct":false,"why":"Retiring old SMB versions and improving host firewalls helps but doesn't directly restrict the administrative pathways attackers used to move between VLANs."},{"text":"Monitor interactive sign-ins more closely and increase review of privileged access events that precede remote administration","correct":false,"why":"Increased monitoring of sign-ins detects activity after the fact but doesn't reduce the actual pathways available for lateral movement."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q204","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (CSRF)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A web app performs state-changing actions based only on a user’s session cookie. Attackers can trick users into triggering actions. What control BEST mitigates this?","options":[{"text":"Require each sensitive request to carry proof it originated from the intended workflow rather than ambient browser state alone","correct":true,"why":"CSRF defenses include per-request tokens, same-site cookies, and origin validation to ensure requests are intentional."},{"text":"Prompt users to verify identity again for important actions and reject requests from unexpected navigation paths","correct":false,"why":"Re-verifying identity for important actions doesn't stop a forged cross-site request from silently exploiting an already-authenticated session."},{"text":"Insert a human-verification step on sensitive pages so automated cross-site submissions are less likely to succeed silently","correct":false,"why":"A human-verification step adds friction but doesn't validate that the request actually originated from the legitimate application workflow."},{"text":"Shorten session lifetime and rotate browser tokens more aggressively to reduce the window for unwanted action submission","correct":false,"why":"Shortening session lifetime reduces the exposure window but doesn't prevent a forged request from succeeding while the session is still valid."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q205","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Timeline Building)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"Local event logs appear cleared on a host. What is the BEST way to reconstruct a timeline?","options":[{"text":"Rebuild activity from independent retained telemetry sources that observed the host from outside the affected log store","correct":true,"why":"Attackers may clear local logs; centralized logging and other data sources can rebuild timelines and scope."},{"text":"Rely on endpoint telemetry plus perimeter records and accept reduced fidelity where application and name-resolution data are absent","correct":false,"why":"Accepting reduced fidelity where application and DNS data are missing still leaves timeline gaps that independent centralized sources could otherwise fill."},{"text":"Infer the sequence primarily from offline host artifacts because central observability may lag or omit short-lived events","correct":false,"why":"Relying primarily on offline host artifacts ignores that the local logs were cleared; those artifacts may also be tampered with or incomplete."},{"text":"Treat the gap as a collection failure first and attempt pipeline backfill before concluding the local record was deliberately removed","correct":false,"why":"Treating the gap as a collection failure first delays recognizing that logs were deliberately cleared and wastes time before turning to independent sources."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q206","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Application Allowlisting)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A company wants to reduce malware execution from user directories and temporary folders. What control BEST supports this goal?","options":[{"text":"Permit only approved code paths and prevent launch from user-controlled storage locations that commonly host initial payloads","correct":true,"why":"Allowlisting and blocking execution from user-writable paths reduce common malware execution vectors."},{"text":"Block common user-write locations and tighten script policy while leaving broader binary execution decisions to local controls","correct":false,"why":"Blocking user-write locations while leaving broader execution decisions to local controls doesn't establish a consistent, centrally enforced allowlist."},{"text":"Remove unnecessary administrative rights so code started from temporary paths has fewer privileges when it does execute","correct":false,"why":"Removing admin rights limits what malware can do once it runs, but doesn't prevent it from launching from user-writable folders in the first place."},{"text":"Harden email and browsing controls further because most malicious binaries reach endpoints through content delivery channels","correct":false,"why":"Hardening email and browsing controls addresses delivery vectors, not the execution-time control needed to block launches from user directories."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q207","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Error Handling)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"An API returns detailed stack traces and database errors to clients. What is the BEST secure coding improvement?","options":[{"text":"Expose only minimal failure details to callers while preserving rich diagnostics in protected server-side observability paths","correct":true,"why":"Avoid leaking internals."},{"text":"Standardize externally visible error codes and reduce internal logging to avoid leaking implementation details through operations data","correct":false,"why":"Standardizing error codes while reducing internal logging removes diagnostic detail needed for troubleshooting, rather than just limiting what's exposed externally."},{"text":"Allow privileged operators to view verbose failures directly from the production interface when authenticated for support activity","correct":false,"why":"Allowing privileged operators to view verbose failures directly from production still exposes sensitive internals through the same interface, rather than through protected observability tooling."},{"text":"Keep detailed responses in nonproduction and production alike but strip the most sensitive backend identifiers from each message","correct":false,"why":"Keeping detailed responses in both environments and only stripping some identifiers still leaks significant implementation details to any caller."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q208","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Memory Indicators)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A host is suspected of fileless malware. What artifact is MOST likely to exist only in memory and not on disk?","options":[{"text":"Resident code pages loaded through in-memory execution techniques rather than artifacts created as ordinary filesystem objects","correct":true,"why":"Fileless attacks often rely on memory injection and reflective loading, leaving minimal disk artifacts."},{"text":"Legitimate signed modules mapped by the operating system that happen to support abused runtime behavior during execution","correct":false,"why":"Legitimate signed modules mapped by the OS are expected system components; they aren't the memory-only artifact created by the fileless technique itself."},{"text":"Short-lived driver activity associated with subsystem abuse that may persist only in hardware interaction records","correct":false,"why":"Short-lived driver activity tied to hardware interaction records isn't the primary artifact associated with fileless, memory-resident execution techniques."},{"text":"Configuration changes recorded for startup extensibility points that reveal persistence even when binaries are absent from disk","correct":false,"why":"Startup configuration changes for persistence typically leave some trace in configuration data, unlike the memory-only code execution fileless malware relies on."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q209","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (MFA & Conditional Access)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A company sees multiple account takeovers from phishing. Which control MOST directly reduces successful credential replay?","options":[{"text":"Require sign-in factors that cannot be replayed by a phished secret and evaluate contextual trust before granting access","correct":true,"why":"MFA (especially phishing-resistant) and conditional access reduce replay success and add contextual controls."},{"text":"Use app-based confirmation prompts for risky locations while reserving stronger authenticators for selected privileged groups","correct":false,"why":"Reserving stronger authenticators only for select privileged groups still leaves most accounts vulnerable to phishing-based credential replay."},{"text":"Increase secret complexity requirements and depend on anomaly detections to interrupt misuse after the compromise attempt begins","correct":false,"why":"Increasing password complexity doesn't stop replay of a phished credential; anomaly detection also only reacts after compromise has already begun."},{"text":"Retire older sign-in protocols and require compliant endpoints, assuming device posture most directly blocks stolen credential use","correct":false,"why":"Device compliance requirements alone don't directly stop a replayed credential from being used if the authentication factor itself can still be phished."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q210","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Authentication)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A developer stores user passwords using unsalted MD5. What is the BEST fix?","options":[{"text":"Use a purpose-built password derivation method with unique per-user randomness and tunable cost against offline guessing","correct":true,"why":"Passwords should be hashed (not encrypted) with strong, slow algorithms and unique salts to resist offline cracking."},{"text":"Protect the stored values with centralized encryption keys and rotate them regularly to limit exposure after compromise","correct":false,"why":"Encrypting the stored values still uses a reversible scheme rather than one-way hashing, and doesn't add the per-user randomness needed to resist offline cracking."},{"text":"Replace the digest with a modern general-purpose hash plus salts because stronger primitives make dedicated password schemes unnecessary","correct":false,"why":"Switching to a modern general-purpose hash with salting is better than MD5 but still lacks the deliberately slow, tunable cost factor a dedicated password hashing scheme provides."},{"text":"Keep the current storage approach but shorten reset windows and add more account recovery checks to reduce practical abuse","correct":false,"why":"Shortening reset windows and adding recovery checks doesn't fix the weak, unsalted hashing algorithm actually storing the passwords."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q211","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Write Preservation)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"You must analyze a suspect machine but want to avoid altering its state. What is the BEST approach for analysis?","options":[{"text":"Preserve original evidence sources untouched and conduct examination against faithful duplicates within a controlled environment","correct":true,"why":"Best practice is to capture images and analyze copies, preserving original evidence integrity and minimizing contamination."},{"text":"Perform remote live triage first to minimize transport delays, then capture fuller evidence only from the most relevant systems","correct":false,"why":"Performing remote live triage first still risks altering the system's state before full evidence capture is completed."},{"text":"Rely on storage acquisition alone and use retained telemetry to stand in for transient operating context during analysis","correct":false,"why":"Relying on storage acquisition alone with retained telemetry as a substitute doesn't capture the live operating context that direct examination of the actual state would provide."},{"text":"Isolate the host and execute local collection routines carefully so the operational system changes as little as possible","correct":false,"why":"Even careful local collection routines still directly interact with and can alter the live operational system, unlike analyzing a preserved duplicate."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q212","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Secure Boot / Measured Boot)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"An organization is concerned about bootkits and tampering with bootloaders. Which control MOST directly addresses this?","options":[{"text":"Establish hardware-rooted startup trust that blocks unauthorized early-stage code and records the launch chain for validation","correct":true,"why":"Secure Boot and measured boot help prevent or detect tampering in the boot chain, reducing bootkit persistence."},{"text":"Require firmware passwords and stronger physical safeguards because startup tampering usually depends on direct device access","correct":false,"why":"Firmware passwords and physical safeguards protect against direct device tampering but don't cryptographically validate or block unauthorized code during the boot process itself."},{"text":"Encrypt workstation storage and increase endpoint monitoring so changes to early startup components are more likely to be detected","correct":false,"why":"Encrypting storage and increasing endpoint monitoring can help detect issues after boot but doesn't prevent or verify tampering in the early boot chain itself."},{"text":"Enable signed startup checks alone and depend on operating-system records to confirm what happened before the kernel initialized","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on OS-level records after the kernel has already initialized misses tampering that could occur in the earlier boot stages before the OS loads."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q213","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (SSRF)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A web service fetches a user-supplied URL server-side to generate previews. Attackers can access internal metadata endpoints. What vulnerability is this and what is the BEST mitigation?","options":[{"text":"Server-side request abuse; constrain reachable destinations through strict target validation, resolution controls, and outbound policy","correct":true,"why":"SSRF abuses server-side fetches to reach internal resources (metadata services)."},{"text":"Server-side request abuse; block the best-known internal addresses and watch for suspicious fetch behavior that evades filters","correct":false,"why":"Blocking known internal addresses is a reactive denylist approach that new or unlisted internal targets can still bypass."},{"text":"Server-side request abuse; validate only hostnames because name-based approval is sufficient to prevent access to internal services","correct":false,"why":"Validating only hostnames doesn't prevent an attacker from using techniques like DNS rebinding or alternate representations to reach internal resources."},{"text":"Server-side request abuse; require authentication before preview generation so only authorized users can invoke backend fetches","correct":false,"why":"Requiring authentication controls who can request a preview, but doesn't stop the server itself from being tricked into fetching internal resources."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q214","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Attribution vs Evidence)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"Leadership asks who “did it” during an incident. Forensics must remain defensible. What is the BEST response approach?","options":[{"text":"Frame conclusions around observed behavior, scope, and confidence while avoiding identity claims that exceed the evidence base","correct":true,"why":"Defensible forensics emphasizes evidence and confidence levels; attribution requires strong corroboration and is often uncertain."},{"text":"Offer the most likely operator set from infrastructure overlap and tactics mapping, emphasizing that certainty remains limited","correct":false,"why":"Naming a most-likely operator set still asserts an identity claim beyond what the available evidence (behavior and confidence levels) can defensibly support."},{"text":"Provide an executive narrative centered on impact and remediation while omitting most technical uncertainty from the discussion","correct":false,"why":"Omitting technical uncertainty from the discussion misrepresents the actual confidence level, undermining the defensibility the response should maintain."},{"text":"Delay answering the question until containment is complete because attribution statements are inappropriate during active response","correct":false,"why":"Delaying the answer indefinitely doesn't address that any eventual response should still be scoped to defensible confidence levels rather than firm attribution."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q215","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Logging & Audit)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A company hardens systems but incidents still occur. They lack visibility into privileged changes and authentication anomalies. What is the BEST improvement?","options":[{"text":"Centralize trustworthy activity records for sensitive actions and identity events so they can be correlated beyond the affected host","correct":true,"why":"Hardening needs monitoring."},{"text":"Collect privileged activity from each endpoint daily and keep most records local to reduce central infrastructure cost and exposure","correct":false,"why":"Keeping most privileged activity records local prevents the cross-host correlation needed to spot attacker behavior spanning multiple systems."},{"text":"Expand audit settings for administrative actions but shorten retention because fast response matters more than historical depth","correct":false,"why":"Shortening retention to save resources undermines the ability to investigate or correlate incidents that surface after the retention window closes."},{"text":"Prioritize unusual sign-in monitoring and review administrative changes through periodic compliance reports rather than event streams","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing changes only through periodic compliance reports delays detection compared to continuously correlating identity and privileged-action events."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q216","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Secure Defaults)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A new API endpoint is deployed with “debug mode” enabled, verbose logging, and permissive CORS. What secure coding principle is MOST violated?","options":[{"text":"Choose production-safe defaults so optional diagnostics and broad trust relationships are not present unless deliberately justified","correct":true,"why":"Secure defaults reduce accidental exposure."},{"text":"Reduce exposed diagnostics first but keep cross-origin openness temporarily because partner integration needs are already known","correct":false,"why":"Keeping permissive CORS open temporarily for anticipated partner needs still leaves an unnecessarily broad trust relationship enabled by default."},{"text":"Constrain who can reach the endpoint and leave deeper troubleshooting features available behind authenticated administrative access","correct":false,"why":"Restricting who can reach the endpoint doesn't remove the risky diagnostic features themselves, which shouldn't be enabled by default in production regardless of access control."},{"text":"Preserve the current launch configuration but strip only the most revealing backend details from operational and client responses","correct":false,"why":"Stripping only some backend details while keeping the same insecure launch configuration still leaves debug mode and other risky defaults active."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q217","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Hashing Use)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"Why are cryptographic hashes computed during acquisition and analysis?","options":[{"text":"They provide repeatable proof that collected material remains unchanged as it moves through examination and handoff stages","correct":true,"why":"Hashes are integrity checks: same input produces the same hash, enabling validation that evidence is unaltered."},{"text":"They show the evidence set is complete, though transfer authenticity still depends mainly on signatures and custody documentation","correct":false,"why":"Framing hashes as showing completeness while relying mainly on signatures and custody documentation understates that hashes are the direct mechanism proving content wasn't altered."},{"text":"They are needed only once after capture because later verification duplicates effort without improving evidentiary confidence","correct":false,"why":"Computing a hash only once after capture misses the ongoing value of re-verifying integrity at each subsequent handoff or examination stage."},{"text":"They confirm authenticity by themselves, so separate protection of recorded digest values is less important than media control","correct":false,"why":"Hashes don't confirm authenticity by themselves; protecting the recorded digest values from tampering is just as important as controlling the media."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q218","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Endpoint Controls)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"An attacker repeatedly abuses PowerShell and LOLBins on endpoints. Which hardening change BEST reduces this risk without breaking all admin work?","options":[{"text":"Constrain high-risk native tooling through execution policy, trusted code paths, and selective operational allowances with visibility","correct":true,"why":"Hardening scripting via policy (signing, constrained mode, allowlisting) and monitoring reduces abuse while permitting legitimate operations."},{"text":"Maximize script telemetry and content inspection, treating rapid detection as the primary safeguard against native tool misuse","correct":false,"why":"Maximizing telemetry and inspection alone still relies on detecting abuse after it happens, rather than constraining what native tools can do in the first place."},{"text":"Confine advanced shell access to management hosts while leaving similar built-in utilities broadly available on user systems","correct":false,"why":"Confining shell access to management hosts while leaving similar utilities broadly available elsewhere still leaves user systems exposed to LOLBin abuse."},{"text":"Disable only remote shell features because most living-off-the-land tradecraft depends on network-enabled interactive execution","correct":false,"why":"Disabling only remote shell features misses local PowerShell and LOLBin abuse that doesn't require network-enabled interactive execution."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q219","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Dependency Risk)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A critical vulnerability is disclosed in a widely used open-source library your app depends on. What is the BEST secure development response?","options":[{"text":"Determine exposure quickly, update the component on an informed timetable, and govern third-party risk continuously in the pipeline","correct":true,"why":"Supply chain risk requires inventory (SBOM), scanning, and timely patching with exposure assessment and validation."},{"text":"Evaluate whether the vulnerable feature is reachable and rely on compensating controls until the next planned engineering cycle","correct":false,"why":"Waiting for the next planned engineering cycle while relying on compensating controls delays addressing a critical, actively disclosed vulnerability."},{"text":"Freeze the current version and watch for exploitation attempts while waiting for a more widely adopted downstream vendor release","correct":false,"why":"Freezing the current version and merely watching for exploitation leaves the known vulnerability unpatched while risk continues to grow."},{"text":"Maintain an internal fork temporarily so behavior stays stable, accepting ongoing ownership of future security corrections","correct":false,"why":"Maintaining an internal fork creates ongoing security maintenance burden instead of adopting the vendor's timely, tested fix."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q220","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (EDR Containment vs Evidence)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A host is actively beaconing to suspected C2. You need to stop exfiltration but preserve evidence. What is the BEST action?","options":[{"text":"Cut off external communication without discarding system state, then acquire short-lived artifacts before deeper examination begins","correct":true,"why":"Contain quickly to stop harm while preserving state."},{"text":"Block the observed destination upstream and continue watching the host so additional indicators can be gathered from behavior","correct":false,"why":"Continuing to watch the host while only blocking the destination still leaves the host connected to the network, risking further communication through other channels."},{"text":"Power the system down after immediate scoping so transmission stops quickly and the storage image can be captured safely later","correct":false,"why":"Powering down after scoping still risks losing volatile memory evidence that could be captured while the system remains running before containment."},{"text":"Invalidate the associated user access immediately, relying on identity disruption to halt the malicious communication channel","correct":false,"why":"Invalidating user access doesn't stop malware-driven C2 communication, which doesn't depend on the compromised user's credentials remaining valid."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q221","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Egress Control)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"Attackers rotate domains quickly for C2. Blocking known domains is insufficient. What hardening control BEST reduces outbound abuse?","options":[{"text":"Constrain what destinations systems may reach and inspect outbound patterns so unknown infrastructure has fewer usable paths","correct":true,"why":"Egress controls (proxy + DNS security + allowlists where possible) reduce C2 success and provide detection telemetry."},{"text":"Continuously import fresher reputation feeds at the proxy because fast domain churn is primarily a timeliness problem","correct":false,"why":"Continuously refreshing reputation feeds still relies on already-known-bad domains, which doesn't help against newly registered, not-yet-flagged infrastructure."},{"text":"Normalize outbound traffic through a single common port and analyze encrypted session metadata for suspicious communication","correct":false,"why":"Normalizing traffic to a single port doesn't restrict which destinations are reachable; it primarily aids analysis, not actual outbound restriction."},{"text":"Apply strict outbound rules to server subnets first while leaving user networks flexible to avoid disrupting productivity","correct":false,"why":"Applying strict rules only to server subnets while leaving user networks flexible still leaves an easy path for C2 traffic from user systems."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q222","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Race Conditions / TOCTOU)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"A program checks file permissions and then opens the file later, allowing an attacker to swap a symlink in between. What vulnerability class is this?","options":[{"text":"A state-change race between verification and use, best addressed by operations that bind the decision to the final object","correct":true,"why":"TOCTOU arises when state changes between check and use."},{"text":"A state-change race between verification and use, best addressed by repeating the permission test immediately before opening","correct":false,"why":"Repeating the permission check immediately before opening still leaves a window, however small, where the object could be swapped between the repeated check and the open."},{"text":"A state-change race between verification and use, best addressed by general file locking because timing windows vanish under locks","correct":false,"why":"General file locking doesn't necessarily bind the specific permission decision to the exact object ultimately opened, especially across symlink swaps."},{"text":"A state-change race between verification and use, best addressed by path normalization so alternate references resolve consistently","correct":false,"why":"Path normalization addresses ambiguous path references but doesn't close the timing gap between when permissions are checked and when the file is actually used."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q223","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Reporting & Lessons Learned)","source":"CySA_Day_12.html","q":"After an investigation, leadership wants improvements that prevent recurrence. What is the BEST deliverable from a forensics perspective?","options":[{"text":"An evidence-grounded report that explains sequence, cause, impact boundaries, and prioritized changes to reduce recurrence","correct":true,"why":"Forensics should produce evidence-backed reporting: timeline, root cause, scope, and actionable improvements to prevent recurrence."},{"text":"A concise executive report centered on business impact and remediation tasks, with technical findings kept in a separate annex","correct":false,"why":"Keeping technical findings in a separate annex risks leadership missing the evidence basis connecting root cause to the recommended changes."},{"text":"A timeline-focused package that documents what happened and where, leaving causal analysis to engineering owners afterward","correct":false,"why":"A timeline-only package that defers causal analysis to engineering doesn't provide the root-cause and prioritized-improvement guidance leadership specifically asked for."},{"text":"A remediation tracker with attached supporting artifacts, minimizing uncertainty language so leadership receives a consistent message","correct":false,"why":"Minimizing uncertainty language for a cleaner message risks overstating confidence and undermines the evidence-grounded nature forensics reporting should maintain."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q224","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A SOC lead wants a daily feed that summarizes emerging adversary activity with minimal false leads. The team also needs predictable sourcing and editorial accountability. Which source type best fits this requirement?","options":[{"text":"Subscription reporting that curates findings, cites sources, and publishes on a reliable review cycle.","correct":true,"why":"For daily executive-ready threat awareness, a curated finished-intelligence product is usually the best fit because it balances timeliness with validation and accountability. A reviewed commercial-style product gives consistency, sourcing, and lower noise than raw community collection."},{"text":"Volunteer chatter streams that surface fresh claims but vary widely in validation and editorial control.","correct":false,"why":"Volunteer chatter streams vary widely in validation and accountability, which doesn't fit the need for predictable sourcing and editorial oversight."},{"text":"Closed-forum scraping that captures raw discussion yet requires extensive analyst vetting before use.","correct":false,"why":"Closed-forum scraping requires extensive analyst vetting before use, which conflicts with the need for a low-effort daily summary with minimal false leads."},{"text":"Internal case summaries that are accurate locally but too narrow to represent the wider threat landscape.","correct":false,"why":"Internal case summaries are accurate for local incidents but too narrow to represent the broader emerging adversary activity the SOC lead wants covered."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q225","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"An analyst sees a spike in suspicious domains that look like brand impersonation. The team must identify registrant patterns, hosting overlap, and passive DNS history without actively touching attacker infrastructure. What is the best approach?","options":[{"text":"Correlate registration records, passive resolution history, and certificate artifacts to map related infrastructure quietly.","correct":true,"why":"When the goal is infrastructure mapping without interaction, passive DNS, WHOIS history, and certificate transparency are safer and more defensible than active probing. Passive infrastructure correlation gives linkage without tipping off the operator or introducing collection risk."},{"text":"Perform service enumeration and banner collection across the domains to infer campaign overlap from exposed ports.","correct":false,"why":"Service enumeration and banner collection involve directly probing the suspicious domains, which risks tipping off the operator and isn't purely passive."},{"text":"Transmit controlled messages to the domains so delivery behavior can reveal whether the phishing workflow is active.","correct":false,"why":"Sending controlled messages to the domains is active interaction with attacker infrastructure, which the team specifically wants to avoid."},{"text":"File takedown requests first, then reconstruct the infrastructure from provider responses after the domains disappear.","correct":false,"why":"Filing takedown requests first would alert providers and potentially the attacker before the infrastructure mapping is complete, losing the chance for quiet passive correlation."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q226","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"Leadership asks why your intel report includes a confident attribution to a named APT group. Your evidence is primarily IP reuse and shared tooling indicators. What is the most defensible revision?","options":[{"text":"Lower attribution confidence and center the report on observed tradecraft, infrastructure overlap, and collection limits.","correct":true,"why":"Attribution is easy to overstate. The evidence supports behaviors and overlap better than a firm actor label, so the report should reflect that."},{"text":"Retain the actor label but broaden the list of candidate groups so the uncertainty appears more fully represented.","correct":false,"why":"Broadening the candidate list while keeping the same confident label still overstates certainty rather than actually lowering the attribution confidence itself."},{"text":"Keep the attribution as written and simplify caveats so decision-makers receive a cleaner, more direct narrative.","correct":false,"why":"Simplifying caveats for a cleaner narrative removes the nuance needed to accurately reflect the actual, more limited confidence level supported by the evidence."},{"text":"Replace the actor name with a malware family label because family identification is usually enough to imply sponsorship.","correct":false,"why":"Swapping in a malware family name while implying sponsorship still overstates what the IP reuse and tooling evidence can support regarding actor identity."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q227","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You need to collect IOCs from incident artifacts but must avoid contaminating evidence while still enabling rapid detection. Which workflow best supports both needs?","options":[{"text":"Preserve originals, derive indicators from working copies, and publish normalized findings with traceable provenance.","correct":true,"why":"Sound handling means keeping source evidence intact, working from controlled copies, and documenting where every IOC came from before operationalizing it. That approach protects forensic integrity while still producing usable detection content quickly."},{"text":"Upload the artifacts to a third-party analysis service first, then export the strongest matches into local controls.","correct":false,"why":"Uploading original artifacts to a third-party service first risks altering or exposing the evidence before controlled, traceable internal handling has occurred."},{"text":"Prioritize volatile artifacts exclusively and defer file-based review until after detections have been pushed broadly.","correct":false,"why":"Focusing only on volatile artifacts and deferring file-based review risks missing evidence and delays proper indicator provenance before wide distribution."},{"text":"Convert the evidence set into screenshots for sharing so teams can review the artifacts without handling live files.","correct":false,"why":"Converting evidence into screenshots for sharing loses forensic fidelity and doesn't preserve the working-copy chain needed to trace where indicators came from."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q228","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A feed provides thousands of IP indicators daily. Your environment generates alert storms and analyst fatigue. Which refinement best improves signal without losing coverage?","options":[{"text":"Weight indicators with local sightings, exposure context, and source confidence before routing them into detections.","correct":true,"why":"A large feed becomes useful only after environmental context is applied. Context-driven scoring reduces noise while preserving the indicators most relevant to your environment."},{"text":"Keep the full feed but raise alert thresholds so only the most repeated matches appear in analyst queues.","correct":false,"why":"Raising alert thresholds while keeping the full feed reduces visible volume but doesn't actually assess which indicators are relevant to this specific environment."},{"text":"Restrict usage to internally observed indicators so outside intelligence cannot distort the environment’s baseline.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting to only internally observed indicators discards potentially valuable external threat context rather than intelligently weighting it."},{"text":"Translate each address into related domains and alert only on those because names tend to be more stable than hosts.","correct":false,"why":"Translating addresses to related domains changes indicator type but doesn't add the environmental relevance scoring needed to reduce noise meaningfully."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q229","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A partner shares an IOC list via email. You must operationalize it quickly while preserving formatting and preventing ambiguity about indicator type. What is the best format to request?","options":[{"text":"A structured exchange format or strict schema file that labels each entry type and preserves source metadata.","correct":true,"why":"STIX/TAXII is ideal, but even a rigid CSV schema works far better than ad hoc lists because it preserves indicator type, confidence, and source details. Explicit typing and provenance reduce ambiguity and make automated ingestion safer."},{"text":"A formatted spreadsheet tab that groups similar entries visually so analysts can infer the field type by section.","correct":false,"why":"A visually grouped spreadsheet still requires manual inference of field types, which doesn't eliminate ambiguity about what each entry actually represents."},{"text":"A PDF export with the list locked for editing so everyone receives the same static reference during ingestion.","correct":false,"why":"A locked PDF preserves formatting for reading but isn't machine-parseable, making automated ingestion and type preservation difficult."},{"text":"A plain-text message body that keeps the transfer lightweight and lets the receiving team classify items manually.","correct":false,"why":"Plain text requires manual classification by the receiving team, reintroducing the ambiguity about indicator type the team wants to avoid."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q230","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A junior analyst proposes using only hashes for threat hunting because they are precise and reduce false positives. What is the best response in a CySA+ context?","options":[{"text":"Use hashes as one signal, then add behavior-driven pivots so hunts survive repacking, renaming, and minor variants.","correct":true,"why":"Hash matches are high confidence but easy for an adversary to evade through repacking or recompilation. Hashes are precise but fragile, so they work best as part of a broader hunting strategy."},{"text":"Favor hashes over process and network evidence because they stay more durable across malware campaigns over time.","correct":false,"why":"Favoring hashes as more durable than process and network evidence gets the fragility backwards — hashes are actually the easiest indicator type for adversaries to invalidate through repacking."},{"text":"Replace hash hunting with file-name monitoring since names better capture family-level variation than exact file fingerprints.","correct":false,"why":"Replacing hash hunting with file-name monitoring swaps one easily evaded indicator for another; names are just as trivial for an adversary to change."},{"text":"Limit hunts to reputation feeds because known-bad file identifiers are most effective when consumed from external vendors.","correct":false,"why":"Limiting hunts to reputation feeds still centers on external, easily-evaded file identifiers rather than incorporating broader behavioral hunting."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q231","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"Your intel team must brief executives on a ransomware campaign. The briefing needs decisions about backup investment and incident response readiness, not technical deep dives. Which intel product is most appropriate?","options":[{"text":"A business-focused assessment that frames operational risk, trend direction, and recommended resilience investments.","correct":true,"why":"Strategic intelligence translates a campaign into business impact, risk posture, and investment choices such as backup maturity or response readiness. Executives need strategic context tied to decisions, not technical execution detail."},{"text":"A defender package centered on blocklists, signatures, and quick-turn control changes for analyst implementation.","correct":false,"why":"A defender package with blocklists and signatures is a technical, operational deliverable, not the business-impact framing executives need for investment decisions."},{"text":"A campaign narrative describing the intrusion sequence, dwell time, and operator workflow inside victim networks.","correct":false,"why":"A campaign narrative about intrusion sequence and dwell time is technical detail that doesn't translate into the resilience investment guidance the briefing requires."},{"text":"A raw artifact bundle containing logs, malware notes, and unfiltered observations for later analytical refinement.","correct":false,"why":"A raw artifact bundle is unrefined technical material, not the business-focused risk and investment framing executives asked for."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q232","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You suspect a threat actor is staging data for exfiltration using a cloud storage provider. You need to gather evidence while minimizing privacy risk and collecting only what is necessary. What is the best approach?","options":[{"text":"Start with access patterns and object metadata, then expand to content review only when authorization and scope require it.","correct":true,"why":"For cloud data investigations, begin with the least intrusive evidence—access logs, object activity, and sharing metadata—before examining contents. That respects data minimization while still establishing whether staging activity occurred."},{"text":"Pull representative samples from every user workspace first so investigators can compare benign and suspicious file movement.","correct":false,"why":"Pulling samples from every user workspace immediately is broader and more privacy-invasive than starting with access patterns and metadata first."},{"text":"Suspend all sync activity and analyze cached endpoint copies because local artifacts are easier to review than provider logs.","correct":false,"why":"Suspending sync and reviewing cached endpoint copies skips the least-intrusive provider-side evidence and jumps straight to broader content access."},{"text":"Query only the provider’s threat dashboard because service-side alerts generally contain enough detail to establish misuse.","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on the provider's threat dashboard may miss the specific access-pattern and metadata evidence needed to establish whether staging actually occurred."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q233","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A threat feed includes confidence and severity fields, but your SOC sees many high-severity items with no local sightings. Which field should drive initial triage the most in your environment?","options":[{"text":"Environmental fit measured through local telemetry, exposed assets, and evidence that the threat intersects your stack.","correct":true,"why":"External severity can be useful, but your first question should be whether the threat is relevant to your assets, controls, and observed activity. Applicability to your environment determines whether an item deserves fast action."},{"text":"Vendor severity because externally assigned impact ratings usually generalize well across different enterprise environments.","correct":false,"why":"Vendor-assigned severity doesn't account for whether the threat actually intersects your specific assets and environment, which is the more relevant initial triage factor."},{"text":"Source confidence because high-certainty reporting should enter response queues even before local applicability is confirmed.","correct":false,"why":"Source confidence being high doesn't mean the threat is relevant to your environment; something can be reported with high certainty yet still not apply to your assets."},{"text":"Publication age because fresher reporting typically matters more than relevance when analysts must triage at speed.","correct":false,"why":"Publication age doesn't indicate whether a threat is actually relevant to your specific environment, regardless of how recent the report is."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q234","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"An analyst wants to enrich an IP with geolocation to infer attacker identity. What is the most accurate guidance?","options":[{"text":"Treat location data as light context and lean more heavily on tradecraft, hosting patterns, and corroborating telemetry.","correct":true,"why":"Cloud relays, proxies, and compromised systems make IP geolocation weak attribution evidence. Geo data can be misleading, so it should support—not drive—analytical conclusions."},{"text":"Use geolocation as the primary clue, then validate the conclusion with malware family overlap if available afterward.","correct":false,"why":"Using geolocation as the primary clue overweights an easily spoofed signal; tradecraft and hosting patterns should lead, with geolocation only as secondary support."},{"text":"Prioritize location over infrastructure history because registration and hosting data are easier for actors to manipulate.","correct":false,"why":"Deprioritizing infrastructure history in favor of location gets the reliability backwards; location is actually the weaker, more easily manipulated signal here."},{"text":"Map the address to a region and align it with likely motive because geography often clarifies who is behind an intrusion.","correct":false,"why":"Aligning geography with likely motive treats a weak, easily faked signal as if it reliably reveals who is behind an intrusion, which it doesn't."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q235","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"Your organization joins an ISAC. You want to consume indicator updates automatically and share sightings securely with peers. Which mechanism best supports this?","options":[{"text":"An authenticated sharing channel built for structured intel objects and automated collection-based exchange.","correct":true,"why":"STIX/TAXII exists specifically for machine-consumable threat intel exchange with authentication, collections, and normalized object structure. That points to standardized automated sharing rather than manual document distribution."},{"text":"A scheduled mailing list with attached reports so each participant receives the same curated package for review.","correct":false,"why":"A scheduled mailing list with attached reports delivers static documents manually, not the automated, machine-consumable exchange the ISAC integration needs."},{"text":"A private document portal where members can upload spreadsheets and download partner submissions on demand.","correct":false,"why":"A private document portal for manual uploads and downloads doesn't provide the automated, structured exchange needed for continuous indicator consumption."},{"text":"A chat workspace with pinned indicator lists that analysts can copy into tools as campaigns evolve through the week.","correct":false,"why":"A chat workspace with pinned lists still requires manual copying into tools, rather than the automated ingestion the organization wants."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q236","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You are hunting for a campaign using a specific phishing kit. You have limited IOCs but strong behavioral patterns. Which hunting strategy is best?","options":[{"text":"Pivot on message traits, redirect behavior, and downstream execution activity instead of anchoring on single artifacts.","correct":true,"why":"When IOCs are scarce or short-lived, hunts should follow stable behaviors across email, web, and endpoint telemetry rather than exact artifacts. Behavioral patterns remain useful even when individual kit indicators churn quickly."},{"text":"Focus on the few known domains first, then wait for fresh threat-feed additions before expanding the hunt further.","correct":false,"why":"Focusing only on the few known domains while waiting for feed updates leaves the hunt dependent on indicators that may already be stale or short-lived."},{"text":"Search only endpoint malware events because phishing-kit activity usually culminates in a consistent dropped payload pattern.","correct":false,"why":"Searching only endpoint malware events misses earlier-stage email and web behavior that could reveal the campaign before a payload even executes."},{"text":"Rely on mail reputation verdicts because kit-level hunts are most effective when delegated to secure email gateways alone.","correct":false,"why":"Relying solely on mail gateway reputation verdicts delegates detection entirely to one layer, missing broader behavioral patterns across web and endpoint telemetry."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q237","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A report says “the actor commonly uses PowerShell” but your environment has PowerShell used legitimately. What is the best analytic refinement?","options":[{"text":"Convert the note into specific patterns such as suspicious launch context, encoded content, and unusual execution chains.","correct":true,"why":"“Uses PowerShell” is too broad. Vague reporting becomes actionable only after it is translated into measurable conditions."},{"text":"Baseline normal administrative use, then temporarily suppress all events that resemble scripting to cut investigative volume.","correct":false,"why":"Suppressing all scripting-like events to reduce volume risks hiding genuinely malicious PowerShell activity alongside the legitimate administrative use."},{"text":"Create a high-priority alert for every script interpreter launch and tune exceptions only after incidents are confirmed.","correct":false,"why":"Alerting on every script interpreter launch generates significant noise from legitimate use, rather than refining the report into specific, measurable malicious patterns."},{"text":"Shift focus to outbound connections because network evidence is less ambiguous than command execution on user systems.","correct":false,"why":"Shifting focus to network evidence sidesteps refining the vague PowerShell claim rather than translating it into concrete, actionable execution patterns."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q238","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A SOC wants to validate whether a suspicious domain is actively serving malware. You need low-risk collection that avoids interacting with the payload directly. What is best?","options":[{"text":"Review reputation, passive artifacts, and safe analysis metadata first, then escalate to isolated detonation if approved.","correct":true,"why":"The safer workflow is to collect indirect evidence first—reputation, history, metadata, and redirects—before using an isolated sandbox. Passive review minimizes risk, and sandboxing should be controlled and authorized when needed."},{"text":"Access the site from a hardened internal workstation so analysts can compare the live experience with current proxy logs.","correct":false,"why":"Accessing the site from an internal workstation still directly interacts with potentially malicious content, carrying more risk than passive reputation and metadata review."},{"text":"Distribute the domain to a limited pilot group and collect screenshots to determine whether the content is actually harmful.","correct":false,"why":"Distributing the domain to a pilot group and having them interact with it directly exposes real users to potential malware, which the low-risk requirement rules out."},{"text":"Wait for endpoint protection to classify the site organically because direct validation can introduce avoidable legal risk.","correct":false,"why":"Waiting for endpoint protection to classify the site organically delays validation rather than actively but safely collecting evidence now."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q239","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"Your analyst writes an intel note with many IOCs but no stated confidence, sources, or assumptions. What is the most important improvement?","options":[{"text":"Add provenance, confidence, and validation context so recipients can judge trustworthiness before automating actions.","correct":true,"why":"Good intelligence is not just a list of IOCs. Without provenance and confidence, recipients cannot safely evaluate or operationalize the indicators."},{"text":"Group the entries by indicator type and count so the note reads as a more complete snapshot of adversary activity.","correct":false,"why":"Grouping entries by type and count makes the note look more complete but still doesn't tell recipients how trustworthy or well-sourced the indicators are."},{"text":"Rewrite the note into a shorter executive format because concise delivery reduces the chance of operational misuse.","correct":false,"why":"Shortening the note into an executive format addresses length, not the missing provenance and confidence information needed to safely operationalize the IOCs."},{"text":"Append a visual risk score for each entry so analysts can prioritize quickly without reviewing sourcing details.","correct":false,"why":"Adding a visual risk score helps prioritize but still doesn't provide the underlying sourcing and confidence details recipients need to trust the indicators."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q240","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You ingest a community feed and notice many indicators are stale and no longer resolve. What is the best handling approach?","options":[{"text":"Apply aging logic with periodic validation so old entries decay gracefully while reused infrastructure still retains value.","correct":true,"why":"Indicators age out at different rates. Decay and revalidation preserve useful history without letting stale artifacts dominate detections."},{"text":"Retain the full history indefinitely and move older entries into a lower-priority tier that continues to alert in background queues.","correct":false,"why":"Retaining full history indefinitely and still alerting on stale entries in the background continues to generate noise from indicators that no longer reflect current threats."},{"text":"Split the feed into active and archived sets, then disable archived matches unless another provider republishes the same entry.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling archived matches unless another provider republishes them may discard reused infrastructure that still has ongoing value without a more graduated aging approach."},{"text":"Keep only the most recent publication window since older community indicators rarely contribute meaningfully to new investigations.","correct":false,"why":"Keeping only the most recent publication window discards potentially valuable older indicators tied to reused infrastructure that could still be relevant."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q241","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A CISO asks for “intel that prevents attacks.” You must set expectations realistically. Which statement best frames how threat intel helps?","options":[{"text":"It sharpens prioritization, detection, and preparedness, reducing exposure even though it cannot guarantee prevention.","correct":true,"why":"Intel helps teams decide what matters, where to hunt, and which controls to tune. Threat intelligence is a decision-support capability, not a standalone preventive control."},{"text":"It blocks most hostile activity upstream when integrated with controls, making incidents far less likely to progress internally.","correct":false,"why":"Overstating that intel blocks most hostile activity upstream sets unrealistic expectations; intel informs decisions but doesn't itself function as a preventive control."},{"text":"It raises adversary awareness enough that many operators change plans once they know the environment consumes outside reporting.","correct":false,"why":"Claiming operators change plans simply because an environment consumes outside reporting overstates a speculative deterrent effect rather than intel's actual decision-support role."},{"text":"It closes the gap between patching and response by giving defenders earlier warning than vulnerability management alone can provide.","correct":false,"why":"Framing intel mainly as closing the patching-to-response gap undersells its broader role in prioritization and detection tuning across the program."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q242","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You need to collect threat data from endpoints but are constrained by limited storage and must avoid collecting excessive personal data. Which collection choice is best?","options":[{"text":"Capture security-focused process, authentication, and connection telemetry with scoped retention aligned to investigation needs.","correct":true,"why":"Process creation, command lines, auth records, and network connections are high-value security events. Focused telemetry gives strong value while respecting storage and privacy constraints."},{"text":"Prioritize periodic full-memory snapshots because volatile data often reveals malicious activity with less personal context than disks.","correct":false,"why":"Periodic full-memory snapshots capture broad system state, including more personal content, and don't specifically minimize data the way scoped security telemetry does."},{"text":"Standardize on DNS and browser history because those datasets are compact and usually sufficient for most host-based investigations.","correct":false,"why":"DNS and browser history alone miss process execution and authentication events that are high-value for security investigations."},{"text":"Collect all EDR event categories briefly, then downsample older data later if the storage budget becomes difficult to sustain.","correct":false,"why":"Collecting all EDR categories and downsampling later still captures excessive data upfront rather than scoping collection from the start."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q243","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"An intel vendor reports a campaign targeting a CVE in a product your org does not run. What is the best response?","options":[{"text":"Log the development for awareness, verify exposure assumptions, and focus immediate effort on risks tied to your actual stack.","correct":true,"why":"A campaign can matter strategically even if you are not directly exposed, but near-term response effort should follow applicable technologies and observed risk. Threat intel should be contextualized to real exposure before it drives urgent action."},{"text":"Tune perimeter controls for the campaign anyway so related adversary infrastructure is constrained before priorities shift later.","correct":false,"why":"Tuning perimeter controls for a campaign targeting an unused product spends effort on infrastructure not actually relevant to your exposure."},{"text":"Forward the report to vulnerability management for cataloging since adjacent products often share similar exploitation paths.","correct":false,"why":"Forwarding to vulnerability management for cataloging assumes shared exploitation paths without first confirming actual exposure to your stack."},{"text":"Use the report as a tabletop input rather than a response driver because nonresident technology can still inform resilience planning.","correct":false,"why":"Treating it only as tabletop input undersells that the report should still be logged and its exposure assumptions verified against your actual environment."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q244","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You are asked to convert a narrative intel report into actionable detection content. What is the best first step?","options":[{"text":"Map the described behaviors to available data sources, then express them as measurable logic in your tooling.","correct":true,"why":"Strong detection engineering turns narrative into testable analytics by matching TTPs to data sources such as EDR, DNS, proxy, auth, or mail telemetry. Operationalization starts by connecting report claims to telemetry you actually collect."},{"text":"Extract the embedded indicators and deploy them in monitoring mode so analysts can gather local evidence before tuning rules.","correct":false,"why":"Deploying extracted indicators in monitoring mode skips first mapping the underlying behaviors to your data sources, which is needed to build durable detection logic."},{"text":"Summarize the report by tactic area so defenders can decide which platform owner should translate it into controls later.","correct":false,"why":"Summarizing by tactic area for another owner to translate later delays actually connecting the report's claims to your available telemetry."},{"text":"Review the actor profile for consistency with prior campaigns because attribution alignment often determines detection value.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing actor-profile consistency with prior campaigns doesn't help translate the specific described behaviors into testable detection logic."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q245","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A threat report includes a YARA rule and claims it detects the malware family reliably. What is the best validation step before wide deployment?","options":[{"text":"Exercise the rule against trusted benign and malicious sample sets in a controlled environment before broad rollout.","correct":true,"why":"Before broad deployment, test detection content against known-good and known-bad samples so you understand match behavior and tuning needs. Controlled validation is the clearest way to assess both false positives and coverage."},{"text":"Pilot the rule on a small endpoint subset first, then compare alert volume with vendor expectations before changing logic.","correct":false,"why":"Piloting on a small subset and comparing volume to vendor expectations still skips deliberately testing against known-good and known-bad samples to understand actual match behavior."},{"text":"Review the strings and conditions manually, since a well-written YARA rule usually signals its own operational readiness clearly.","correct":false,"why":"Manually reviewing rule syntax doesn't reveal real-world false positive or false negative behavior the way testing against actual sample sets does."},{"text":"Deploy the rule in audit mode on malware repositories first, then decide whether endpoint use is necessary afterward.","correct":false,"why":"Deploying in audit mode against malware repositories only tests against malicious samples, missing the benign-sample testing needed to catch false positives."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q246","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You need OSINT on a vulnerability being exploited in the wild. The goal is to understand weaponization, exploitation preconditions, and observed targets. What is the best data to gather first?","options":[{"text":"Technical advisories, exploit analyses, and incident reporting that describe prerequisites, affected versions, and observed abuse.","correct":true,"why":"For an actively exploited flaw, start with authoritative descriptions of affected versions, attack preconditions, exploitation flow, and observed targeting. Those sources best answer exposure, weaponization, and real-world exploitation questions quickly."},{"text":"Recent discussion threads that compare adjacent flaws because exploitation patterns often emerge across related product weaknesses.","correct":false,"why":"Discussion threads comparing adjacent flaws offer speculative pattern-matching, not the authoritative details on this specific flaw's preconditions and observed exploitation."},{"text":"Source code references and developer issue trackers that reveal how the bug was introduced and later corrected by maintainers.","correct":false,"why":"Source code and issue trackers reveal how the bug originated, not the weaponization and real-world targeting information the analyst specifically needs."},{"text":"Exploit framework modules and proof-of-concept summaries that show how researchers are packaging the issue for repeatable testing.","correct":false,"why":"Exploit framework modules show how to reproduce the issue for testing, not the broader picture of preconditions and observed targeting in the wild."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q247","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You are producing an intel report for defenders. Which structure best improves actionability and reduces misinterpretation?","options":[{"text":"A concise summary followed by scope, confidence, mapped behaviors, recommended actions, and source-backed artifacts.","correct":true,"why":"Actionable defender reporting needs a clear summary, scope, confidence, mapped TTPs, defensive recommendations, and provenance for any included indicators. That structure gives responders context, confidence, and concrete actions without forcing guesswork."},{"text":"An actor overview with narrative detail first, then appendices containing references that responders can review if needed.","correct":false,"why":"Leading with narrative actor detail and pushing references to an appendix buries the confidence and recommended-action information defenders need upfront."},{"text":"A control-oriented layout that starts with blocklists and detections, then adds context only for items that triggered locally.","correct":false,"why":"Starting with blocklists and detections and adding context only for local hits skips providing scope and confidence framing for the broader threat."},{"text":"A campaign chronology that emphasizes victim timelines, then closes with a brief list of notable observables for defenders.","correct":false,"why":"Emphasizing victim timelines over actions and confidence leaves defenders without the clear guidance the report should lead with."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q248","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A junior analyst wants to scrape a forum for credentials to see if your organization’s emails appear. Legal requires minimizing risk and ensuring authorization. What is the best approach?","options":[{"text":"Use approved monitoring providers and legal-vetted workflows that handle exposed-data review under controlled procedures.","correct":true,"why":"Threat gathering around leaked credentials should use sanctioned sources and legal guidance rather than direct risky interaction with criminal marketplaces or forums. Authorized, approved collection is the safest and most defensible path for breach-exposure monitoring."},{"text":"Coordinate with counsel, then collect only enough forum data to verify whether the organization appears in recent credential posts.","correct":false,"why":"Coordinating with counsel first is good, but directly collecting forum data still risks unauthorized interaction with a criminal marketplace rather than using vetted monitoring channels."},{"text":"Rely on open breach-notification services first and escalate to deeper collection only if multiple sources indicate active exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on open breach-notification services and escalating later still risks eventual direct, unauthorized forum interaction rather than using approved workflows throughout."},{"text":"Task a separate red-team-style environment to observe the forum indirectly so production staff never interact with the source.","correct":false,"why":"Using a separate environment to observe the forum still constitutes direct interaction with the criminal source, rather than relying on sanctioned monitoring providers."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q249","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"Your SOC receives an IOC that later proves benign. Stakeholders ask how to reduce this recurring issue. What is the best process improvement?","options":[{"text":"Introduce validation gates with corroborating telemetry, quality scoring, and feedback loops before broad enforcement.","correct":true,"why":"The goal is not simply to delay action; it is to improve decision quality by checking source confidence, corroborating with telemetry, and feeding results back into the intake process. A validation pipeline systematically improves quality and reduces repeated benign hits."},{"text":"Shift new indicators into monitor-only mode first, then promote them after analysts review enough environmental matches.","correct":false,"why":"Simply shifting new indicators to monitor-only mode delays action but doesn't add the corroboration and quality scoring needed to actually improve future accuracy."},{"text":"Require multiple independent sources for every entry so low-quality submissions are filtered out before ingestion begins.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring multiple independent sources helps filter some low-quality submissions but doesn't establish the broader validation and feedback loop needed to reduce recurring benign hits systematically."},{"text":"Separate blocking indicators from hunting indicators so uncertain entries can still inform analysts without immediate control changes.","correct":false,"why":"Separating blocking from hunting indicators avoids immediate harm but doesn't build the validation process needed to improve indicator quality over time."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q250","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A threat report references MITRE ATT&CK techniques but your detection platform uses different taxonomy. What is the best way to use the report effectively?","options":[{"text":"Translate the described behaviors into your platform’s fields and logic by mapping framework concepts to local telemetry.","correct":true,"why":"ATT&CK is a translation layer for behavior, not an implementation language. Frameworks describe behavior; your tooling still needs concrete field mappings and platform-native logic."},{"text":"Adopt the framework labels within your content library first, then backfill field mappings once analysts confirm the hunt’s value.","correct":false,"why":"Adopting framework labels first and backfilling field mappings later risks deploying content that isn't actually tied to your platform's real telemetry."},{"text":"Use the techniques to prioritize which data sources matter most, then create detections in the platform’s native schema.","correct":false,"why":"Using techniques only to prioritize data sources without mapping specific behaviors into platform-native logic skips translating the report into usable detections."},{"text":"Anchor the report to the closest internal use cases so platform owners can preserve their existing content without major rewrites.","correct":false,"why":"Anchoring only to existing internal use cases to avoid rewrites risks missing behaviors the report describes that aren't already covered."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q251","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"An intel report suggests the adversary uses “living off the land” to reduce malware footprint. Which defensive recommendation aligns best with that insight?","options":[{"text":"Increase scrutiny on administrative utilities through baselines, parent-child analysis, and anomaly-focused command monitoring.","correct":true,"why":"Living-off-the-land activity often uses tools already present on systems. LoTL abuse is best detected through behavior around legitimate tools, not classic malware signatures."},{"text":"Expand script-control policy and application allowlisting so abuse of built-in tools becomes harder to blend into normal use.","correct":false,"why":"Expanding script-control and allowlisting policy addresses execution restriction but doesn't itself provide the behavior-focused monitoring needed to catch LOLBin abuse across baselines and anomalies."},{"text":"Tune endpoint analytics around execution context and privileged tasking rather than relying on family-based file detections.","correct":false,"why":"Tuning around execution context is close but doesn't emphasize the parent-child process analysis and baselining that best distinguishes LoTL abuse from normal admin activity."},{"text":"Review remote administration workflows so authorized maintenance patterns can be separated more cleanly from suspicious activity.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing remote administration workflows addresses one specific channel, not the broader baseline and anomaly-focused monitoring needed across all administrative utility use."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q252","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TG","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"You must gather threat intel on a suspected insider data theft case. The priority is legal defensibility and least-privilege access to sensitive content. Which action is best first?","options":[{"text":"Collect access, audit, and authentication records under chain-of-custody controls before expanding into content review.","correct":true,"why":"In insider cases, begin with the least intrusive, most defensible evidence such as file access logs, authentication records, and audit trails. Defensible logs and audit trails provide a narrow, lawful starting point before touching sensitive content."},{"text":"Coordinate with HR and legal, then preserve the user’s active sessions so investigators can reconstruct near-term actions accurately.","correct":false,"why":"Preserving active sessions after coordinating with HR and legal jumps ahead to broader content-adjacent evidence rather than starting with narrower access and audit logs."},{"text":"Snapshot the relevant collaboration spaces first because sharing activity often reveals intent faster than system-level telemetry.","correct":false,"why":"Snapshotting collaboration spaces first accesses potentially sensitive shared content before starting with the more defensible, less intrusive access and audit logs."},{"text":"Query DLP alerts and transfer logs first, then decide whether endpoint or storage-side collection is warranted afterward.","correct":false,"why":"Querying DLP alerts and transfer logs first still involves reviewing content-related activity before establishing the narrower baseline of access and authentication records."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q253","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TI","source":"CySA_Day_2.html","q":"A threat feed offers “contextual enrichment” but your analysts still struggle to decide what to do. What missing element most often turns enrichment into action?","options":[{"text":"Response playbooks that tie confidence and relevance to decisions such as monitor, hunt, patch, block, or escalate.","correct":true,"why":"Context alone does not tell analysts what to do. Enrichment becomes useful when it is connected to explicit decision paths and thresholds."},{"text":"Tighter prioritization labels so analysts can sort enriched entries faster before choosing an operational path themselves.","correct":false,"why":"Tighter prioritization labels help sorting but still leave analysts deciding the actual operational path themselves rather than providing that path directly."},{"text":"More examples of prior incidents so teams can compare current enriched items with historical campaigns before acting.","correct":false,"why":"More historical examples aid comparison but don't provide the explicit decision thresholds connecting enrichment to a specific action."},{"text":"A single environmental risk score that combines exposure and source quality into one triage-friendly value for each item.","correct":false,"why":"A single combined risk score simplifies triage but still doesn't specify which concrete action (monitor, hunt, block, escalate) analysts should take."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q254","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (MFA / Push Fatigue)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"SOC alerting shows multiple MFA push approvals occurring within seconds for a single user, followed by a successful VPN login from a new ASN. The user claims they “kept hitting deny” until it stopped. Which control MOST directly reduces the likelihood of this attack succeeding again?","options":[{"text":"Require number-matching or phishing-resistant MFA (FIDO2/WebAuthn) instead of simple push approvals for access flows.","correct":true,"why":"Push fatigue targets “approve” behavior."},{"text":"Require administrator review for repeated approval prompts before restoring remote-access sign-in capability to the account.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring admin review only after repeated approvals reacts after the fact rather than removing the underlying weakness of simple push-based approval."},{"text":"Restrict remote-access sign-in to managed devices while keeping the existing push-based approval method for users.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting to managed devices while keeping push-based approval still leaves the same approve/deny fatigue vulnerability exploitable on those managed devices."},{"text":"Lower the MFA prompt lifetime so expired approvals cannot be accepted after the user changes network location.","correct":false,"why":"Shortening the prompt lifetime reduces the window slightly but doesn't address the core weakness that a user can still be tricked into approving a malicious push."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q255","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (Kerberos / Golden Ticket)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"An internal investigation finds abnormal Kerberos TGT lifetimes and service ticket issuance after hours. The domain controller logs show unusual use of the KRBTGT account. Which compromise technique is MOST consistent with this evidence?","options":[{"text":"Golden Ticket creation using a stolen KRBTGT key to forge TGTs and extend access across services in the domain.","correct":true,"why":"Golden Tickets involve forging TGTs with the KRBTGT secret, leading to abnormal TGT properties and after-hours ticket patterns."},{"text":"Pass-the-Hash using NTLM hashes to authenticate directly to services without requesting Kerberos tickets.","correct":false,"why":"Pass-the-Hash uses NTLM authentication directly without requesting Kerberos tickets, so it wouldn't produce the abnormal TGT lifetimes and KRBTGT usage observed here."},{"text":"Kerberoasting by requesting service tickets and cracking them offline to recover service account passwords.","correct":false,"why":"Kerberoasting targets service ticket encryption for offline cracking; it doesn't involve the KRBTGT account or abnormal TGT issuance patterns described."},{"text":"DCShadow by registering rogue domain controllers and replicating objects without triggering standard logging.","correct":false,"why":"DCShadow involves rogue domain controller registration for stealthy replication, not forged TGTs tied to KRBTGT abuse as seen in this evidence."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q256","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (RBAC / Least Privilege)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A developer can access a production database even though they are not in the production group. The IAM audit shows a policy allowing “db:*” attached to a role that multiple teams can assume. Which remediation BEST aligns with least privilege and blast radius reduction?","options":[{"text":"Narrow the role policy to specific actions/resources and add conditions (tags/session context) limiting who can assume it.","correct":true,"why":"Fix the authorization path: overly broad shared role + permissions."},{"text":"Move production access into a separate break-glass role with approval while leaving the broad shared role unchanged.","correct":false,"why":"Creating a separate break-glass role still leaves the original overly broad shared role and its wildcard permissions in place for other teams to use."},{"text":"Add just-in-time approval for privileged sessions without narrowing the role permissions or trust relationships.","correct":false,"why":"Adding just-in-time approval controls who can get access but doesn't narrow the excessive wildcard permissions the role still grants once approved."},{"text":"Require stronger password complexity for the shared role while preserving the current wildcard action scope.","correct":false,"why":"Stronger password complexity addresses authentication strength, not the underlying authorization problem of an overly broad shared role with wildcard database permissions."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q257","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (Password Spraying)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A SIEM rule triggers on repeated login failures across many accounts using the same password, spread across hours to avoid lockouts. Which detection signal MOST strongly indicates password spraying rather than brute force against one user?","options":[{"text":"A low-and-slow pattern: one or few passwords attempted across many distinct usernames from the same source context.","correct":true,"why":"Spraying uses a small password set across many users to avoid lockouts, unlike brute force focused on one account."},{"text":"Repeated authentication failures tied to a small set of privileged accounts from rotating residential exit nodes.","correct":false,"why":"Failures concentrated on a small set of privileged accounts is closer to a targeted brute-force pattern, not the broad, low-and-slow spread across many accounts characteristic of spraying."},{"text":"A single successful login followed by immediate privilege escalation via a local exploit on the endpoint host.","correct":false,"why":"A single successful login followed by local privilege escalation describes a different attack stage entirely, not the credential-guessing pattern behind spraying."},{"text":"A cluster of login failures tied to legacy protocols from a subset of stale mobile clients after a certificate rollover.","correct":false,"why":"Failures tied to legacy protocols and stale clients after a certificate rollover point to an authentication compatibility issue, not a deliberate password-guessing campaign."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q258","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls (Stateful vs Stateless)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A network engineer claims inbound rules alone are sufficient to allow a web app to respond to clients. A troubleshooting capture shows SYN packets reach the server, but responses are dropped at the perimeter device. Which explanation is MOST likely?","options":[{"text":"A stateless ACL/firewall requires explicit outbound/return-path rules; stateful devices track sessions automatically.","correct":true,"why":"Stateless filtering needs return rules for ephemeral ports."},{"text":"An asymmetric routing path causes the returning flow to miss the device that evaluated the original session state.","correct":false,"why":"Asymmetric routing would cause the return path to bypass a stateful device's session table, but this scenario points to a stateless device lacking explicit return-path rules, not routing asymmetry."},{"text":"The web tier is replying from a different source address than the perimeter policy expects for the service object.","correct":false,"why":"A source address mismatch would cause the client to reject the response, not cause the perimeter device itself to drop it as observed here."},{"text":"A destination translation rule sends traffic to a listener that is not bound to the expected service on the backend.","correct":false,"why":"A misdirected destination-translation rule would prevent the server from ever receiving the request, but the capture shows SYNs successfully reaching the server."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q259","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS/IPS (False Positives / Tuning)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"An IDS generates repeated alerts for “SQL injection” on a JSON API endpoint. Application logs show the traffic is a legitimate search query with encoded characters. Which change BEST reduces false positives without losing coverage?","options":[{"text":"Tune signatures using context (URI/path, content-type) and add exceptions narrowly for the endpoint while keeping broad rules.","correct":true,"why":"Use precise tuning: path-aware exclusions, content-type checks, and thresholding, not disabling broad categories."},{"text":"Raise the alert threshold for that signature family globally so the API traffic is no longer surfaced to analysts.","correct":false,"why":"Globally raising the alert threshold for the whole signature family reduces visibility into genuine SQL injection attempts on other endpoints, not just this false positive."},{"text":"Convert the IDS rule to a full block action for that endpoint path before validating application behavior in logs.","correct":false,"why":"Converting to a full block before validating behavior in logs risks blocking legitimate user traffic based on an unconfirmed assumption."},{"text":"Exclude all requests with encoded characters from inspection so the search feature continues to accept special syntax.","correct":false,"why":"Excluding all encoded-character requests from inspection removes coverage broadly, potentially missing genuine injection attempts that also use encoded characters."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q260","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (ABAC / Tags)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A cloud platform uses ABAC with resource tags. A user can access resources outside their business unit after assuming a role through a CI pipeline. What is the MOST likely misconfiguration?","options":[{"text":"Session tags or role conditions are missing, allowing assumed roles to bypass tag-based constraints at evaluation time.","correct":true,"why":"ABAC needs consistent tag/condition enforcement during role assumption."},{"text":"The trust policy allows the pipeline role to assume a broader identity than intended, independent of resource ownership tags.","correct":false,"why":"An overly permissive trust policy on the pipeline role is a related but different issue from the specific ABAC tag/condition enforcement gap during role assumption."},{"text":"A permissions boundary permits broader actions than the resource-tag policy expects once the workload identity is assumed.","correct":false,"why":"A permissions boundary being too broad affects overall action scope, but the specific symptom described points to missing tag-based conditions during assumption, not a boundary policy issue."},{"text":"The role session inherits default attributes that do not match the project tag model used by the protected resources.","correct":false,"why":"Default session attributes not matching the tag model is a symptom of the missing tag/condition enforcement, but the root cause is the missing enforcement itself during role assumption."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q261","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (OAuth/OIDC Token Abuse)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A web app uses OAuth/OIDC. A user reports being logged in from a different device without a password prompt. Logs show a valid refresh token used from a new IP. Which action MOST directly limits this abuse scenario?","options":[{"text":"Bind refresh tokens to device/session context and implement refresh token rotation with reuse detection and revocation.","correct":true,"why":"Refresh tokens are high value."},{"text":"Require reauthentication for high-risk sign-ins while leaving long-lived refresh tokens usable across any device context.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring reauthentication for high-risk sign-ins doesn't stop a valid, unrotated refresh token from continuing to be reused from a new device."},{"text":"Shorten access-token lifetime without changing refresh-token reuse detection or device-aware session controls.","correct":false,"why":"Shortening access-token lifetime doesn't address the refresh token itself, which is what's actually being reused to obtain new access without a password prompt."},{"text":"Restrict token issuance to browser-based clients while keeping the same refresh-token handling and revocation model.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting to browser-based clients doesn't change how refresh tokens are validated or rotated, so the reuse vulnerability remains unaddressed."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q262","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls (Egress Filtering)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"IR discovers multiple hosts beaconing to random subdomains on uncommon ports. The environment has strong inbound filtering but minimal outbound controls. Which control MOST directly reduces command-and-control success?","options":[{"text":"Implement egress filtering with allow-lists and DNS/proxy inspection to restrict outbound destinations and protocols.","correct":true,"why":"C2 often relies on outbound access."},{"text":"Block newly registered external domains at the resolver while leaving direct outbound IP access broadly available.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking only newly registered domains at the resolver still leaves direct outbound IP-based C2 channels available, bypassing DNS-based blocking entirely."},{"text":"Deploy stricter web filtering categories but keep unrestricted outbound transport on high-risk destination ports.","correct":false,"why":"Stricter web filtering categories still leave unrestricted outbound transport on other high-risk ports, which C2 can use instead."},{"text":"Mirror edge traffic to an additional sensor for visibility while preserving the same permissive outbound policy set.","correct":false,"why":"Adding a mirrored sensor improves visibility but doesn't actually restrict any outbound destinations or protocols, leaving C2 channels open."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q263","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS (Network vs Host Telemetry)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"An attacker uses encrypted channels for lateral movement. Network IDS alerts drop sharply, but endpoints show suspicious process activity. Which telemetry source is MOST reliable for detection in this situation?","options":[{"text":"Host-based telemetry (EDR/sysmon-like) focusing on process creation, script engines, and credential access behaviors.","correct":true,"why":"Encryption reduces payload visibility."},{"text":"Network metadata enriched with identity context, because it improves triage even when endpoint process evidence is absent.","correct":false,"why":"Network metadata enriched with identity context still lacks the process-level detail needed to confirm the specific suspicious activity observed on endpoints."},{"text":"Decrypted proxy telemetry at the egress point, because it captures internet traffic even when east-west movement stays internal.","correct":false,"why":"Decrypted egress proxy telemetry only captures traffic leaving the network, not internal east-west lateral movement staying within the environment."},{"text":"Authentication logs alone, because they show who accessed a system even if the launching process remains unknown.","correct":false,"why":"Authentication logs alone show who logged in but don't reveal the suspicious process or script activity driving the lateral movement."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q264","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (SAML Misuse / Assertion)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A SaaS app trusts SAML assertions from an IdP. A tester demonstrates they can replay a captured assertion to log in again. Which control MOST directly prevents this replay?","options":[{"text":"Enforce assertion audience/recipient checks plus tight NotBefore/NotOnOrAfter windows and one-time use identifiers.","correct":true,"why":"Prevent replay using strict time windows, audience/recipient validation, and one-time IDs (and TLS everywhere)."},{"text":"Require signed assertions while leaving broad assertion validity windows and replayable identifiers unchanged.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring signed assertions ensures authenticity but doesn't prevent replay if validity windows remain broad and each assertion can still be reused."},{"text":"Restrict the service-provider ACS endpoint to a smaller IP range while keeping the same assertion replay behavior.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting the ACS endpoint's IP range limits where an assertion can be replayed from, but doesn't stop replay from an allowed IP range."},{"text":"Shorten the session cookie lifetime while leaving assertion uniqueness and audience validation unchanged at login.","correct":false,"why":"Shortening the session cookie lifetime affects the resulting session, not the assertion itself, which could still be replayed to establish a new one."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q265","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (Privilege Escalation / Mis-scoped Rights)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A helpdesk role can reset passwords for executives due to inherited permissions. Which access control failure is MOST apparent?","options":[{"text":"Overly broad role assignment / inheritance violating separation of duties and least privilege in the directory model.","correct":true,"why":"This is an authorization design issue: role inheritance and privilege scope are too broad for the helpdesk role."},{"text":"Weak hashing algorithm selection causing password resets to compute faster during directory replication cycles.","correct":false,"why":"Weak hashing algorithm choice for password resets is unrelated to why the helpdesk role has excessive inherited permissions to reset executive passwords."},{"text":"Insufficient network segmentation allowing helpdesk endpoints to reach the domain controller management ports.","correct":false,"why":"Network segmentation gaps are a separate infrastructure concern from the specific authorization design flaw of overly broad role inheritance."},{"text":"Lack of endpoint encryption allowing attackers to read executive passwords from disk after reset completion.","correct":false,"why":"Lack of endpoint encryption is unrelated to why the helpdesk role was granted the ability to reset executive passwords in the first place."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q266","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls (Rule Shadowing)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A firewall rulebase includes an allow rule for “Any to WebServers 443” above a deny rule for a known-bad IP range. Traffic from the bad range is still allowed. Why?","options":[{"text":"Rule ordering causes shadowing; the broader allow rule matches first, preventing the later deny from applying.","correct":true,"why":"First-match processing means earlier broad allow rules can shadow later denies; fix by moving deny above allow or tightening match criteria."},{"text":"Stateful inspection disables all deny rules once a single session has been permitted by any rule previously.","correct":false,"why":"Stateful inspection tracks session state per connection; it doesn't disable all deny rules globally once any single session has been permitted."},{"text":"The bad IP range is using IPv6, and IPv6 always bypasses firewall evaluation unless NAT66 is enabled.","correct":false,"why":"IPv6 doesn't inherently bypass firewall evaluation, and NAT66 isn't a prerequisite for filtering; this doesn't explain the observed rule-order behavior."},{"text":"The deny rule is applied only to outbound traffic, and inbound rules cannot block traffic by source IP range.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario describes inbound traffic being allowed despite a deny rule; inbound rules absolutely can and do filter by source IP range."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q267","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS/IPS (Inline Blocking Decisions)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"Security proposes switching from IDS to IPS for an internet-facing service. Operations is concerned about availability. Which deployment MOST reduces risk of unintended blocking while gaining protection?","options":[{"text":"Start in detect-only, tune to baseline, then enable selective blocking for high-confidence signatures with monitoring.","correct":true,"why":"Progressive rollout: detect-only, tuning, then selective blocking for high-confidence detections reduces outage risk."},{"text":"Enable full blocking immediately for all signatures and disable logging to prevent storage growth during peak traffic.","correct":false,"why":"Enabling full blocking immediately without any tuning phase, and disabling logging, both increase the risk of unintended outages rather than reducing it."},{"text":"Move the IPS behind the servers so it blocks only responses, which prevents false positives from impacting clients.","correct":false,"why":"Placing the IPS only behind the servers to block responses doesn't prevent false positives on inbound requests from disrupting legitimate client traffic."},{"text":"Disable TLS and decrypt all traffic on the backend to simplify IPS inspection and maximize rule matching coverage.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling TLS to simplify inspection removes encryption in transit, a significant security regression unrelated to safely rolling out blocking."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q268","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (Credential Stuffing)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A public login portal shows successful logins across many accounts from a small set of IPs, followed by immediate account setting changes. Passwords are not being guessed repeatedly. Which attack is MOST likely?","options":[{"text":"Credential stuffing using previously leaked username/password pairs, validated quickly and then monetized by changes.","correct":true,"why":"Credential stuffing uses known leaked pairs, often producing many successes with few failures and rapid takeover actions."},{"text":"Password spraying using one password across many users, attempting to avoid account lockout thresholds.","correct":false,"why":"Password spraying uses one password across many accounts specifically to avoid lockouts; the scenario describes successful logins with rapid follow-on changes, not failed spray attempts."},{"text":"Offline cracking of salted hashes from the live directory database, performed in real time during logins.","correct":false,"why":"Offline cracking of salted hashes happens outside live login attempts entirely; it wouldn't produce a pattern of successful real-time logins from a small IP set."},{"text":"Kerberoasting performed against the public portal, which uses Kerberos tickets to authenticate internet users.","correct":false,"why":"The public portal in this scenario is described as a standard login system, not a Kerberos-authenticated service, so Kerberoasting doesn't apply here."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q269","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (Policy Evaluation / Explicit Deny)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A user’s role includes “Allow s3:GetObject on *” but access to a specific bucket fails with AccessDenied. The user insists the allow is broad. What is the MOST likely cause?","options":[{"text":"A resource policy or SCP applies an explicit deny or condition that overrides identity-based allow for that bucket.","correct":true,"why":"In many policy engines, explicit deny overrides allow."},{"text":"The object is too large, and size limits cause authorization systems to deny reads for performance reasons.","correct":false,"why":"Object size limits aren't a real authorization mechanism; S3 doesn't deny reads based on file size for performance reasons."},{"text":"S3 access requires MFA for all operations by default, and MFA cannot be used with role-based access flows.","correct":false,"why":"S3 doesn't require MFA for all operations by default, and this isn't a real limitation on role-based access flows."},{"text":"The bucket’s encryption at rest prevents authorization checks until decryption occurs, causing denials to appear.","correct":false,"why":"Encryption at rest doesn't block authorization evaluation; a properly authorized and authenticated request can still decrypt and read the object."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q270","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls (NAT / Attribution)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"The SOC needs to map a suspicious outbound connection to the internal host that initiated it. The perimeter firewall performs PAT for thousands of clients. Which log data is MOST necessary?","options":[{"text":"NAT translation logs including timestamps, internal IP/port, external IP/port, and mapped public port tuples.","correct":true,"why":"With PAT, you need NAT translation tuples and timestamps to map public connections back to internal source IP/port."},{"text":"Only the destination IP reputation category because it identifies which internal host is most likely infected.","correct":false,"why":"Destination IP reputation alone doesn't identify which specific internal host initiated the connection; that requires the actual NAT translation record."},{"text":"DHCP scope configuration because it shows address pools, which uniquely identifies each endpoint permanently.","correct":false,"why":"DHCP scope configuration shows address pool ranges, not which specific internal host held the translated port at the time of the connection."},{"text":"Switch port MAC address tables because they retain historical mapping for weeks without needing timestamps.","correct":false,"why":"Switch MAC address tables show port-to-MAC mappings, not the NAT translation needed to link a specific public session back to an internal host and port."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q271","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS (Evasion / Fragmentation)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A red team evades an IDS by fragmenting packets and using overlapping TCP segments. Which countermeasure MOST directly addresses this evasion?","options":[{"text":"Enable traffic normalization and stream reassembly on the IDS/IPS so inspection occurs on reconstructed flows.","correct":true,"why":"Normalization and reassembly defeat fragmentation/overlap evasion by ensuring the IDS inspects canonical reconstructed streams."},{"text":"Disable TCP entirely for the protected service and require UDP-based transports so fragmentation cannot occur.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling TCP and forcing UDP transports is impractical for most services and doesn't address the reassembly gap that enables the evasion."},{"text":"Block all small packets because fragmentation always results in smaller packet sizes on the monitored interface.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking all small packets would disrupt significant amounts of legitimate traffic and doesn't specifically defeat overlapping-segment evasion techniques."},{"text":"Increase the IDS alert threshold so fragmented packets generate fewer alerts and reduce analyst workload today.","correct":false,"why":"Raising the alert threshold reduces alert volume but doesn't fix the underlying inspection gap that let fragmented, evasive traffic go undetected."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q272","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (RADIUS/TACACS+ Use Case)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"Network devices authenticate administrators through a central service with command authorization. The security team wants per-command accounting. Which protocol BEST fits?","options":[{"text":"TACACS+ for centralized admin auth, granular command authorization, and detailed accounting for device management.","correct":true,"why":"TACACS+ is commonly used for network device admin with command authorization and accounting granularity."},{"text":"RADIUS because it encrypts the entire payload end-to-end and provides per-command authorization by default.","correct":false,"why":"RADIUS typically encrypts only the password field, not the entire payload, and doesn't provide native per-command authorization the way TACACS+ does."},{"text":"LDAP because it natively supports device command control and logs each CLI command without additional tooling.","correct":false,"why":"LDAP is a directory access protocol; it doesn't natively provide command-level authorization or per-command accounting for network devices."},{"text":"Kerberos because it is designed for AAA on routers and switches with per-command logs built into the KDC.","correct":false,"why":"Kerberos is an authentication protocol for tickets, not a network device AAA solution with built-in per-command logging."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q273","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (Time-based / Conditional Access)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A user can access a finance app only during business hours and only from compliant devices. This is enforced by the identity platform. What control category BEST describes this?","options":[{"text":"Conditional access enforcing context-based authorization decisions using time, device posture, and identity signals.","correct":true,"why":"This is conditional/context-based access (ABAC-like decisions) rather than static RBAC or label-based MAC."},{"text":"Mandatory access control enforcing static labels that never change based on time or device conditions.","correct":false,"why":"Mandatory access control relies on static labels that don't change with time or device state, unlike the dynamic, context-based enforcement described here."},{"text":"Discretionary access control allowing users to share finance data by granting access to other users freely.","correct":false,"why":"Discretionary access control lets users grant access to others at their own discretion; it doesn't describe centrally enforced time and device-based restrictions."},{"text":"Role-based access control alone because roles inherently represent time windows and device compliance states.","correct":false,"why":"Role-based access control defines permissions by role assignment; roles don't inherently encode time windows or device compliance status."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q274","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls (Application Layer / L7)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A firewall allows TCP 443 to an internal server. An attacker tunnels non-HTTPS traffic over 443. Which firewall capability MOST directly detects and blocks this?","options":[{"text":"Layer 7 application identification/inspection that validates protocol behavior, not just port numbers, for enforcement.","correct":true,"why":"Port-based rules can be bypassed."},{"text":"Static NAT translation so the server uses a dedicated public IP and traffic is not mixed with other services.","correct":false,"why":"Static NAT changes how the server's IP is exposed but doesn't inspect or validate what protocol is actually running over port 443."},{"text":"Packet filtering with a destination port allow rule because port 443 is reserved exclusively for HTTPS by standards.","correct":false,"why":"Assuming port 443 is exclusively HTTPS by convention is exactly the assumption an attacker exploits by tunneling other traffic over that same port."},{"text":"MAC address filtering so only approved devices can send 443 traffic and tunneling becomes infeasible in practice.","correct":false,"why":"MAC address filtering controls which devices can send traffic at all; it doesn't inspect or restrict what protocol is tunneled once traffic is permitted."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q275","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS (Alert Context / Prioritization)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"An IDS generates “ET POLICY Possible External IP Check” alerts from multiple endpoints. The analyst needs to triage quickly. Which enrichment MOST increases decision quality?","options":[{"text":"Process/endpoint context from EDR (parent process, command line) correlated to the destination and user identity.","correct":true,"why":"Network alerts become actionable with endpoint context: what process initiated it, which user, and what command-line behavior."},{"text":"The IDS sensor CPU utilization because higher utilization indicates higher confidence in the alert output results.","correct":false,"why":"IDS sensor CPU utilization reflects processing load, not the confidence or legitimacy of a specific alert's underlying activity."},{"text":"The number of VLANs in the environment because more VLANs generally reduce false positives universally today.","correct":false,"why":"The number of VLANs in the environment doesn't inherently reduce false positives or provide context about a specific alert's source process."},{"text":"The physical rack location of the IDS because proximity to the core switch improves signature accuracy overall.","correct":false,"why":"The IDS sensor's physical rack location has no bearing on signature accuracy or the endpoint context needed to triage this specific alert."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q276","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (Account Lockout Strategy)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A company wants to reduce brute force but avoid easy denial-of-service by lockouts. Which approach BEST balances both?","options":[{"text":"Use risk-based throttling and progressive delays with MFA challenges rather than hard lockouts on low-confidence events.","correct":true,"why":"Progressive throttling + risk signals + MFA reduces brute force while mitigating lockout DoS potential."},{"text":"Lock accounts permanently after five failures and require helpdesk calls for every unlock to increase security.","correct":false,"why":"Permanently locking accounts after five failures with mandatory helpdesk calls creates exactly the denial-of-service risk the company wants to avoid."},{"text":"Disable password policies and rely only on IP allow-listing because IP addresses are stable identifiers for users.","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on IP allow-listing removes password-based protections entirely and doesn't address brute force attempts from allowed IPs."},{"text":"Allow unlimited attempts but log them, because logging alone prevents brute force from succeeding over time.","correct":false,"why":"Allowing unlimited attempts with only logging doesn't prevent a brute-force attack from eventually succeeding; logging alone is detection, not prevention."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q277","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (Privilege Creep)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A user has accumulated access over years across multiple projects. They can now approve invoices and also modify vendor bank details. Which governance practice MOST directly addresses this risk?","options":[{"text":"Perform periodic access reviews/recertification with separation-of-duties checks and remove unnecessary entitlements.","correct":true,"why":"Privilege creep is mitigated by access recertification and SoD reviews to remove excess entitlements and conflicting duties."},{"text":"Increase password length requirements so invoice approval actions require stronger authentication on every click.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing password length requirements strengthens authentication generally but doesn't remove the excessive, conflicting entitlements the user has accumulated."},{"text":"Disable firewall logging to reduce noise so the finance application has better performance under peak loads.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling firewall logging for performance is unrelated to reviewing and removing a user's accumulated conflicting access rights."},{"text":"Move vendor data to a different subnet so privilege creep cannot cross network boundaries by policy definition.","correct":false,"why":"Moving vendor data to a different subnet doesn't remove or review the user's actual accumulated permissions across systems and projects."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q278","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls (Micro-segmentation)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A data center breach shows lateral movement between application tiers. Leadership wants to limit east-west traffic to only required flows without redesigning IP addressing. Which control BEST supports this?","options":[{"text":"Micro-segmentation using host-based or distributed firewall policies that permit only explicit service-to-service flows.","correct":true,"why":"Micro-segmentation restricts east-west communications at workload level without IP redesign; it’s a direct lateral-movement control."},{"text":"Expand the flat network to simplify routing and reduce the number of ACLs, which lowers misconfiguration risk.","correct":false,"why":"Expanding to a flatter network to simplify routing would increase, not decrease, the lateral movement paths available between application tiers."},{"text":"Disable IDS signatures for lateral movement so analysts focus on perimeter detections and external attack vectors.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling IDS signatures for lateral movement removes detection capability entirely rather than actually restricting east-west traffic flows."},{"text":"Allow all internal traffic and rely on endpoint antivirus, because internal traffic is trusted by design standards.","correct":false,"why":"Allowing all internal traffic and relying only on endpoint antivirus does nothing to restrict which services can communicate with each other."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q279","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS/IPS (Detection Coverage Gaps)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A network IDS is placed only at the internet edge. An insider threat exfiltrates data to an internal file server. Why might the IDS miss this activity?","options":[{"text":"Placement limits visibility; east-west/internal traffic may not traverse the edge sensor, creating a blind spot.","correct":true,"why":"Sensor placement matters."},{"text":"IDS signatures work only for inbound traffic and cannot trigger on outbound or internal sessions by design rules.","correct":false,"why":"IDS signature engines can inspect traffic in either direction; the actual limitation here is sensor placement, not a rule against outbound or internal traffic by design."},{"text":"Internal servers use SMB, and IDS engines do not support inspection for SMB traffic under any circumstances.","correct":false,"why":"Modern IDS engines are capable of inspecting SMB traffic; that's not a fundamental limitation preventing detection of this exfiltration."},{"text":"The IDS is stateful, so it ignores all traffic after the first packet and cannot detect file transfers at all.","correct":false,"why":"Stateful IDS still inspects packets throughout a session, not just the first one; this doesn't explain why internal file transfers were missed."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q280","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (Certificate-based / mTLS)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A service mesh uses mTLS between services. After a compromise, the team wants to quickly revoke a service identity to prevent access. Which mechanism MOST directly supports this?","options":[{"text":"Short-lived certificates with automated rotation and a centralized revocation/deny capability in the mesh control plane.","correct":true,"why":"mTLS identity is certificate-based."},{"text":"Long-lived shared certificates stored in a repository so all services remain consistent and easier to manage daily.","correct":false,"why":"Long-lived shared certificates stored in a repository make it harder to revoke a single compromised service identity without affecting all services sharing that certificate."},{"text":"Disable TLS temporarily so troubleshooting is easier while the team investigates revocation issues in parallel.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling TLS entirely removes encryption and identity verification for all services, which is a severe regression rather than a revocation mechanism."},{"text":"Use self-signed certs per pod without a CA so compromise cannot affect other services in the mesh architecture.","correct":false,"why":"Self-signed certs per pod without a CA lack a centralized way to revoke or manage identities quickly across the mesh during a compromise."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q281","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (Token Scopes / Least Privilege)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"An API token is issued with scopes allowing read/write across all projects. A developer workstation is compromised. Which change MOST reduces potential impact?","options":[{"text":"Issue scoped tokens with least-privilege project-specific permissions and short lifetimes, plus rotation and auditing.","correct":true,"why":"Reduce scope and lifetime."},{"text":"Store the token in a hidden file on the workstation so malware cannot find it easily during typical scans.","correct":false,"why":"Hiding the token in an obscure file doesn't reduce what the token can do if it's found; it's obscurity, not a reduction in scope or lifetime."},{"text":"Allow the token only from the workstation IP so it remains usable, because workstation IPs are stable identities.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting to the workstation's IP still leaves the token with full read/write access across all projects if that IP is ever spoofed or the workstation reused."},{"text":"Disable logging for token use to prevent attackers from learning detection patterns and evasion techniques.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling logging removes visibility into misuse rather than reducing what the compromised token is actually capable of doing."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q282","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewalls + IDS (DMZ Design)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"A public web server in a DMZ is compromised. You want to minimize the attacker’s ability to pivot into the internal network while maintaining required application dependencies. Which design is BEST?","options":[{"text":"Restrict DMZ-to-internal flows to explicit required ports/services, monitor with IDS, and avoid shared credentials/routes.","correct":true,"why":"Explicit allow-only DMZ-to-internal rules + monitoring and no shared trust paths reduce pivoting while preserving necessities."},{"text":"Allow DMZ hosts full internal access so they can reach dependencies easily, then rely on antivirus for containment.","correct":false,"why":"Allowing DMZ hosts full internal access removes the very containment the design goal calls for, leaving antivirus as the only backstop against pivoting."},{"text":"Place the DMZ and internal network on the same VLAN so routing is simpler and firewall complexity is reduced.","correct":false,"why":"Placing the DMZ and internal network on the same VLAN eliminates the segmentation boundary entirely, directly enabling the pivot the design should prevent."},{"text":"Disable internal firewall logging so attackers cannot discover ports, and increase DMZ bandwidth for stability.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling internal firewall logging removes visibility into an attack rather than limiting what a compromised DMZ host can actually reach internally."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q283","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IDS (Incident Response Workflow)","source":"CySA_Day_4.html","q":"An IDS alert indicates suspicious outbound connections from a finance workstation. You need to confirm whether it’s true compromise and contain quickly. Which sequence is MOST appropriate?","options":[{"text":"Correlate IDS with endpoint telemetry, confirm process/user context, isolate host if suspicious, then preserve evidence.","correct":true,"why":"Best practice: validate with multiple sources, confirm context, contain (isolate), then collect/preserve evidence for RCA and scoping."},{"text":"Disable the IDS signature immediately to reduce noise, then wait for more alerts to determine if compromise exists.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling the signature reduces alert visibility rather than helping confirm whether this specific outbound activity represents a real compromise."},{"text":"Reimage the workstation immediately without collecting volatile artifacts, then close the incident as resolved.","correct":false,"why":"Reimaging immediately destroys volatile evidence needed to understand the incident and closing it without investigation risks missing lateral spread."},{"text":"Block the entire finance subnet at the firewall permanently, then ask users to submit tickets for exceptions.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking the entire finance subnet permanently is a disproportionate, disruptive response before the specific host has even been confirmed as compromised."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q284","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (PCI DSS)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A retailer is preparing for an assessment. The environment stores cardholder data and uses a third-party payment gateway for transactions. Which requirement is MOST directly associated with protecting stored cardholder data and limiting exposure?","options":[{"text":"Encrypt stored cardholder data and implement strong key management controls for storage systems.","correct":true,"why":"PCI DSS focuses strongly on protecting stored cardholder data using encryption and key management."},{"text":"Segment the cardholder data environment and tighten ingress and egress paths to reduce unnecessary connectivity exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Segmentation and connectivity restrictions reduce exposure but don't specifically address protecting the cardholder data that is actually stored."},{"text":"Apply quarterly external and internal scans to the environment while leaving stored data protection to separate control requirements.","correct":false,"why":"Quarterly scans validate the environment's security posture generally but don't themselves protect stored cardholder data."},{"text":"Mask primary account numbers when displayed and require role separation for administrators handling payment systems.","correct":false,"why":"Masking displayed PANs and role separation are good practices but don't specifically address the stronger requirement to encrypt stored cardholder data with proper key management."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q285","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (HIPAA / Privacy)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A healthcare organization is designing controls for ePHI access. The team needs auditability and least privilege aligned to regulatory expectations. Which control set BEST supports this goal?","options":[{"text":"Role-based access controls with unique user IDs, audit logging of access to ePHI, and regular access reviews in scope.","correct":true,"why":"HIPAA expects access controls, unique user identification, audit controls, and integrity/confidentiality safeguards for ePHI."},{"text":"Group-based access with department-wide privileges and periodic manager attestation for users handling patient records.","correct":false,"why":"Group-based, department-wide privileges conflict with HIPAA's expectation of least privilege and unique user identification for tracing individual access."},{"text":"Centralized session logging for EHR access with break-glass review procedures and after-hours activity monitoring.","correct":false,"why":"Centralized session logging and break-glass review address specific monitoring scenarios but don't establish the broader role-based access and unique-ID framework HIPAA expects."},{"text":"Field-level encryption for selected records plus multifactor authentication for remote administrative access to clinical systems.","correct":false,"why":"Field-level encryption and MFA for remote admins are valuable safeguards but don't themselves establish the role-based access and audit logging structure the scenario calls for."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q286","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (GDPR / Data Minimization)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A company collects customer telemetry and retains it indefinitely “just in case.” The legal team warns this increases regulatory risk. Which principle MOST directly applies?","options":[{"text":"Data minimization and storage limitation: collect what is necessary and retain it only for defined purposes.","correct":true,"why":"GDPR emphasizes data minimization and limiting retention to what is necessary for specified purposes."},{"text":"Purpose limitation: define approved analytics uses and restrict secondary processing that is unrelated to those purposes.","correct":false,"why":"Purpose limitation concerns restricting how already-collected data may be used, not the specific problem of collecting and indefinitely retaining more data than necessary."},{"text":"Pseudonymization: replace direct identifiers where possible while continuing to collect broad telemetry for operational analysis.","correct":false,"why":"Pseudonymization reduces identifiability of the data but doesn't address that broad telemetry is being collected and retained indefinitely regardless of necessity."},{"text":"Consent management: present clear collection choices and record user preferences for optional analytics categories.","correct":false,"why":"Consent management addresses whether users agreed to collection, not the separate issue of retaining data indefinitely beyond what's needed for a defined purpose."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q287","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (NIST / Control Families)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A security program uses NIST guidance to map controls for data confidentiality and auditing. Which reference is MOST commonly used for security and privacy controls in federal-style frameworks?","options":[{"text":"NIST SP 800-53 security and privacy control catalog used for mapping and implementation.","correct":true,"why":"NIST SP 800-53 provides the security and privacy control catalog."},{"text":"NIST SP 800-171 security requirements used to protect controlled information in nonfederal systems and organizations.","correct":false,"why":"SP 800-171 focuses specifically on protecting controlled unclassified information in nonfederal systems, not the general security and privacy control catalog being mapped here."},{"text":"NIST SP 800-37 risk management framework guidance used to authorize and monitor security controls over time.","correct":false,"why":"SP 800-37 provides the risk management framework process for authorization and monitoring, not the actual catalog of security and privacy controls."},{"text":"NIST SP 800-61 incident handling guidance used to prepare for, detect, and respond to security events.","correct":false,"why":"SP 800-61 provides incident handling guidance, not the broad control catalog needed for mapping confidentiality and audit controls."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q288","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Data Classification)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"An organization wants to apply different encryption and monitoring levels based on the sensitivity of data. What is the MOST foundational prerequisite?","options":[{"text":"Establish a data classification scheme with owners, labels, and handling requirements aligned to business risk.","correct":true,"why":"You can’t apply tiered controls without classification and ownership."},{"text":"Standardize endpoint encryption for all managed devices and apply elevated monitoring only to systems in regulated enclaves.","correct":false,"why":"Standardizing endpoint encryption and monitoring by enclave still requires a way to determine which systems belong in which sensitivity tier — the classification scheme itself."},{"text":"Build retention and deletion schedules first, then map encryption and monitoring tiers once business units approve them.","correct":false,"why":"Building retention and deletion schedules first addresses a different lifecycle concern and doesn't establish the sensitivity tiers needed to map encryption and monitoring levels."},{"text":"Define sensitivity labels, handling rules, and ownership so technical safeguards can be mapped to each category consistently.","correct":false,"why":"Defining labels and ownership without also establishing the classification scheme as the actual prerequisite restates part of the solution but omits framing it as foundational first."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q289","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Credentialed vs Non-credentialed)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A scan report misses several missing patches on Windows servers. The scanner was run from outside the subnet with only open ports detected. Which change MOST increases accuracy for patch visibility?","options":[{"text":"Run credentialed scans with least-privilege credentials to query installed patches and configurations on hosts in scope.","correct":true,"why":"Credentialed scans can interrogate patch level and configuration, reducing false negatives from port-only external scanning."},{"text":"Run an unauthenticated scan from an internal vantage point so additional services and versions are identified more accurately.","correct":false,"why":"Running an unauthenticated scan, even internally, still can't query the actual patch level and configuration data that only credentialed access can retrieve."},{"text":"Use authenticated agent-based assessment on those servers so missing updates and local configurations are enumerated directly.","correct":false,"why":"Agent-based assessment can achieve similar visibility, but the scenario specifically points to running scans without credentials as the actual root cause needing correction."},{"text":"Add version and banner checks from multiple subnets to improve network visibility while leaving host inspection unchanged.","correct":false,"why":"Adding more version and banner checks from different network vantage points still relies on external observation and doesn't query the host's actual installed patch state."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q290","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Authenticated Scanning Risk)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"Security wants credentialed scans, but operations is concerned the scanner account could be abused if compromised. Which approach BEST balances accuracy and risk?","options":[{"text":"Use dedicated least-privilege scanner accounts, store secrets in a vault, and restrict account use to scanner IPs.","correct":true,"why":"Dedicated least-privilege accounts + vaulting + network restrictions and monitoring mitigate scanner credential risk."},{"text":"Use local administrative rights on each asset class and rotate those credentials regularly through an approved privileged workflow.","correct":false,"why":"Using local admin rights on every asset class, even with rotation, still grants broad privileges beyond what a scanner needs, increasing risk if compromised."},{"text":"Create a service account limited to read-oriented remote checks and monitor its use through a centralized secrets platform.","correct":false,"why":"A read-only service account with centralized secrets monitoring is a reasonable partial step but doesn't include the network restrictions to scanner IPs that further limit abuse."},{"text":"Run agent-based configuration assessment on high-value systems while reserving network-based credentialed scans for lower-risk segments.","correct":false,"why":"Splitting between agent-based and network-based scanning by system risk doesn't itself address the credential risk of the scanner accounts being used."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q291","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Scope Control)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A vulnerability scan accidentally targets a partner’s public IP range due to a typo in the target list. Which process control MOST directly prevents this in the future?","options":[{"text":"Implement scan authorization and scope validation with change control and peer review for target lists before execution.","correct":true,"why":"Formal authorization/scope validation and peer review reduce accidental scanning of out-of-scope assets."},{"text":"Require approved target inventories to be generated from authoritative asset records before each scheduled assessment cycle.","correct":false,"why":"Generating target inventories from asset records helps accuracy but doesn't add the review and change-control step needed to catch the kind of typo that caused this incident."},{"text":"Enforce written rules of engagement that specify source ranges, approved targets, and named owners before scans begin.","correct":false,"why":"Written rules of engagement define scope but don't include the peer review and validation step that would catch a target-list typo before scanning begins."},{"text":"Use pre-scan validation jobs that compare requested targets against allowed ranges and stop execution on mismatches.","correct":false,"why":"Automated pre-scan validation against allowed ranges is a good technical control but doesn't itself capture the broader authorization and peer-review process for target lists."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q292","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (CVSS vs Risk)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A critical CVSS vulnerability is found on an internal test server that is isolated and cannot reach production. The business asks why it is not top priority. What is the BEST explanation?","options":[{"text":"CVSS is severity, but risk prioritization also considers exploitability, exposure, compensating controls, and business impact.","correct":true,"why":"CySA+ emphasizes context-based risk: exposure, exploit likelihood, controls, asset value, and impact, not CVSS alone."},{"text":"The severity score reflects technical impact, while remediation order depends on where the asset sits and how reachable it is.","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same conclusion in different words but doesn't explicitly identify the broader set of contextual factors (exploitability, controls, exposure) that determine actual priority."},{"text":"An isolated nonproduction host with strong segmentation can be scheduled behind issues that present greater business exposure.","correct":false,"why":"This focuses narrowly on segmentation and location, without capturing the fuller set of context-based risk factors that explain the prioritization decision."},{"text":"A high rating still needs context from attack paths, asset sensitivity, and available mitigations before ranking it ahead of others.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames it as needing more context generally, rather than directly explaining that CVSS reflects severity while risk also depends on exposure and compensating controls."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q293","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (False Positives)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A scanner flags an “outdated OpenSSL” vulnerability on a Linux host, but the package manager shows it is patched via backporting. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Validate with package metadata/vendor advisories and confirm running library versions, then mark as exception if applicable.","correct":true,"why":"Backported fixes can confuse version-based checks."},{"text":"Compare the package release to the vendor advisory and rescan with authenticated checks before deciding whether remediation is still needed.","correct":false,"why":"Comparing against the vendor advisory and rescanning is a reasonable step but doesn't fully resolve confirming the actual running library version against package metadata."},{"text":"Review the detection method and create a time-bounded exception for that host while preserving the check for other systems.","correct":false,"why":"Creating a time-bounded exception addresses documentation but skips first confirming through package metadata whether the vulnerability is genuinely still present."},{"text":"Verify whether the product uses backported fixes and document evidence from the distribution maintainer before closing the issue.","correct":false,"why":"Verifying backport status and documenting evidence is close, but doesn't include actually confirming the running library version, which the correct answer specifically calls for."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q294","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Encryption at Rest)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A company stores sensitive customer data in a database. They need to meet a standard requiring strong cryptography and key management. Which implementation BEST aligns?","options":[{"text":"Encrypt data at rest using strong algorithms with centralized KMS, rotation policies, and strict key access controls.","correct":true,"why":"Strong cryptography requires real encryption plus key management controls (KMS, rotation, access restrictions, auditing)."},{"text":"Apply transparent database encryption with locally managed keys stored on the same server for simpler operational recovery.","correct":false,"why":"Storing keys locally on the same server as the encrypted database means a single server compromise exposes both the data and the means to decrypt it."},{"text":"Tokenize only selected fields while leaving full plaintext values available in reporting replicas used by business analysts.","correct":false,"why":"Leaving full plaintext values available in reporting replicas defeats the purpose of protecting sensitive data, regardless of tokenizing some fields elsewhere."},{"text":"Encrypt storage volumes through the hypervisor and limit database-level controls to application permissions and role design.","correct":false,"why":"Hypervisor-level volume encryption alone doesn't provide the database-level key management and access controls the standard specifically requires."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q295","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Exploitability)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A new RCE vulnerability is reported. No public exploit exists yet, but the affected service is internet-facing and widely used. Which factor MOST increases urgency?","options":[{"text":"High exposure and probable exploit development: internet-facing, common software, and high impact encourages rapid weaponization.","correct":true,"why":"Exposure + likely exploit development are key drivers for prioritization, especially for internet-facing common services."},{"text":"The flaw affects a service role that is exposed publicly on a large portion of internet-facing deployments in the environment.","correct":false,"why":"Simply noting the service is exposed publicly restates part of the scenario without capturing the added urgency driver of likely rapid exploit development."},{"text":"Exploit activity has not been observed yet, but broad deployment and remote reachability raise the chance of rapid weaponization.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames it mainly around deployment scale rather than emphasizing that no observed exploitation combined with high exposure specifically increases the risk of imminent weaponization."},{"text":"Available mitigations are limited to monitoring and segmentation, which still leaves a high-consequence remotely reachable path.","correct":false,"why":"Focusing on limited mitigation options doesn't itself explain what's driving urgency; the urgency stems from exposure and exploit-development likelihood, not the mitigation menu."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q296","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Network Discovery)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"You’re tasked with scanning a new subnet, but documentation is outdated. What is the MOST appropriate first technical step before deep vulnerability checks?","options":[{"text":"Perform host discovery and service enumeration to build an accurate asset inventory and identify scan targets in scope.","correct":true,"why":"Asset discovery + service enumeration provides accurate target scope and reduces noise before vulnerability checks."},{"text":"Start with a fast TCP sweep of common ports only, then treat responding hosts as the complete scan scope for that subnet.","correct":false,"why":"A fast sweep of only common ports risks missing services on non-standard ports, giving an incomplete view of what's actually running before deeper checks begin."},{"text":"Use host discovery and lightweight service fingerprinting first so deeper checks can be targeted at confirmed live systems.","correct":false,"why":"Lightweight fingerprinting first is a reasonable step, but the goal described is building a complete asset inventory through fuller discovery and service enumeration."},{"text":"Begin with ARP, ICMP, and selective port discovery to identify responsive assets before running more intrusive vulnerability checks.","correct":false,"why":"Starting with only ARP, ICMP, and selective ports may miss live hosts or services that don't respond to those specific probes, giving an incomplete inventory."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q297","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Retention / Disposal)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A policy requires that sensitive records be retained for 7 years and securely destroyed afterward. Which practice BEST supports the destruction requirement?","options":[{"text":"Use documented retention schedules and secure sanitization methods aligned to NIST media sanitization guidance.","correct":true,"why":"Secure destruction requires validated sanitization (e.g., NIST SP 800-88) plus retention schedule governance."},{"text":"Expire records from active applications on schedule, then destroy the underlying media with approved sanitization or destruction methods.","correct":false,"why":"Simply expiring records from active applications addresses application-layer visibility but doesn't itself ensure the underlying media is destroyed using validated sanitization methods."},{"text":"Use encrypted archival storage with restricted access, then sanitize retired media after the retention period has elapsed.","correct":false,"why":"Encrypted archival storage protects data during the retention period but the destruction requirement still needs a validated sanitization process once that period ends."},{"text":"Retain records in immutable storage for the required period and document the end-of-life purge process for associated backups.","correct":false,"why":"Retaining in immutable storage and documenting a purge process describes retention handling but doesn't specify using validated sanitization methods for actual destruction."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q298","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Compensating Controls)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A vulnerable service cannot be patched for 30 days due to vendor constraints. Which compensating control is MOST effective short-term?","options":[{"text":"Reduce exposure via network controls (ACL/WAF), disable unneeded features, and add monitoring while planning patching.","correct":true,"why":"If patching is delayed, reduce exposure and add monitoring/controls; scanning doesn’t prevent exploitation by itself."},{"text":"Restrict access to trusted source ranges, place the service behind additional filtering, and watch closely for signs of abuse.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting to trusted source ranges and filtering helps reduce exposure but omits the monitoring and feature-disabling elements that make the compensating control more complete."},{"text":"Disable the affected module or interface if possible, narrow who can reach it, and increase alerting until a permanent fix is available.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling the affected module and narrowing access is close, but the most complete answer combines exposure reduction, feature disabling, and monitoring together."},{"text":"Move the service behind a reverse proxy or segmentation boundary that can block known attack paths while patching is deferred.","correct":false,"why":"Placing the service behind a reverse proxy or segmentation boundary addresses one layer of protection but doesn't include the monitoring needed while patching remains pending."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q299","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Web App Scanning)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A DAST scanner reports no issues, but a manual test finds an IDOR (insecure direct object reference) in the API. Why might the scanner miss it?","options":[{"text":"Logic flaws like IDOR often require context-specific authorization tests and user role modeling beyond simple crawling.","correct":true,"why":"Authorization logic issues require role-based test cases and business context; automated scanners can miss them."},{"text":"Automated crawling may exercise endpoints successfully without switching roles or object identifiers in ways that expose broken access control.","correct":false,"why":"Automated crawling succeeding on endpoints without exercising different roles or object IDs is exactly the gap that misses IDOR, but this doesn't explain why the scanner's approach falls short as clearly as the correct answer."},{"text":"The tool may have validated input handling but not the authorization decisions made when one user requests another user’s records.","correct":false,"why":"Validating input handling checks for things like injection, not authorization decisions about which user can access which object's records, which is the actual gap here."},{"text":"API business logic flaws often require authenticated workflows and multiple personas that generic scanning templates do not model well.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames the issue mainly around needing multiple personas, without capturing that these logic flaws fundamentally require role-based, context-specific test design beyond generic scanning."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q300","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (DLP)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A company must prevent sensitive data from being emailed externally and uploaded to unmanaged cloud storage. Which control BEST aligns?","options":[{"text":"Deploy DLP with content inspection, classification labels, and enforcement at email/web gateways and endpoints.","correct":true,"why":"DLP is designed to detect and prevent exfiltration based on content/classification across channels (email, web, endpoint)."},{"text":"Apply CASB policies for unsanctioned cloud uploads and mail-flow inspection rules for regulated content leaving approved channels.","correct":false,"why":"CASB and mail-flow inspection address cloud uploads and email separately but don't provide the unified content inspection and classification-based enforcement DLP offers across all channels."},{"text":"Tag regulated content through classification engines and enforce policy at endpoints, browsers, and mail gateways for matching data types.","correct":false,"why":"Tagging content and enforcing policy at multiple points is close to DLP's function but doesn't name DLP as the actual control providing content inspection and cross-channel enforcement."},{"text":"Limit unmanaged cloud storage through proxy controls and tenant restrictions while allowing monitored transfers to approved destinations.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting unmanaged cloud storage through proxy controls addresses one channel (cloud uploads) but doesn't also prevent sensitive data from being emailed externally."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q301","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Prioritization Workflow)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"You have 2,000 findings. Leadership wants the “top 20 to fix first.” Which method BEST produces a defensible prioritized list?","options":[{"text":"Risk rank by asset criticality + exposure + exploit intelligence + compensating controls, then validate with owners.","correct":true,"why":"CySA+ emphasizes risk-based prioritization using multiple inputs (asset criticality, exposure, exploitability, controls)."},{"text":"Combine technical severity with exploit maturity and exposure, then adjust ranking based on the importance of the affected assets.","correct":false,"why":"Combining severity, exploit maturity, and exposure is close but omits validating the resulting list with asset owners, which is part of producing a defensible prioritized list."},{"text":"Group issues by common root cause, but order remediation based on reachable paths, business criticality, and ease of exploitation.","correct":false,"why":"Grouping by root cause and ordering by exposure and criticality is a reasonable method but doesn't mention validating with owners, unlike the more complete correct answer."},{"text":"Use a weighted scoring model that incorporates asset value, attack surface, exploit availability, and existing mitigations before selecting the top set.","correct":false,"why":"A weighted scoring model incorporating those factors is close but, like the other options, omits the owner validation step that makes the list defensible."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q302","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Safe Scanning in Production)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A production OT-adjacent environment is sensitive to disruption. Security must scan for vulnerabilities without causing outages. Which approach is BEST?","options":[{"text":"Use safe scan profiles, throttle rates, coordinate maintenance windows, and prefer authenticated checks over aggressive exploits.","correct":true,"why":"Production-sensitive scanning needs coordination, throttling, safe profiles, and minimal-disruption checks."},{"text":"Use nonintrusive discovery during operations and reserve more thorough authenticated checks for approved maintenance periods.","correct":false,"why":"Using nonintrusive discovery during operations and reserving deeper checks for maintenance windows is close but doesn't mention throttling rates, which helps avoid disruption during any scan phase."},{"text":"Coordinate with operations, tune checks to avoid disruptive probes, and segment the target list so scanning stays within system tolerances.","correct":false,"why":"Coordinating with operations and tuning checks is a reasonable partial step but omits throttling scan rates, which further reduces disruption risk to sensitive systems."},{"text":"Favor vendor-safe checks, slower timing, and authenticated assessment methods that reduce load on fragile industrial-adjacent assets.","correct":false,"why":"Favoring vendor-safe checks and slower timing is close but doesn't explicitly mention coordinating maintenance windows, which is part of the more complete safe-scanning approach."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q303","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Tokenization)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A payment system wants to reduce the scope of sensitive data stored in internal systems while still supporting business processes. Which approach BEST supports this?","options":[{"text":"Tokenize sensitive values and store tokens internally while keeping the actual data in a secured vault/service.","correct":true,"why":"Tokenization reduces sensitive data footprint by substituting tokens while protecting the real data in a controlled store."},{"text":"Encrypt stored values with format-preserving controls while continuing to replicate the original records to multiple internal systems.","correct":false,"why":"Format-preserving encryption still keeps the actual sensitive values distributed across multiple internal systems via replication, rather than substituting tokens and centralizing the real data."},{"text":"Use irreversible hashing for selected lookup fields while keeping the underlying sensitive values in the primary application database.","correct":false,"why":"Hashing selected fields for lookups still leaves the underlying sensitive values stored in the primary database, rather than removing them via tokenization."},{"text":"Truncate the stored value where possible and isolate the remaining elements in a highly restricted vault tied to detokenization workflows.","correct":false,"why":"Truncating values still leaves partial sensitive data spread across internal systems rather than fully substituting tokens while centralizing the actual values in a vault."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q304","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Patch Validation)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"After patching, the scanner still reports the same vulnerability. The system owner insists it is fixed. What is the BEST next action?","options":[{"text":"Validate patch level and service versions, confirm the scanner plugin logic, and retest with credentialed checks.","correct":true,"why":"Confirm with evidence: installed versions/patches, service restarts, scanner credentials, and plugin expectations."},{"text":"Compare installed patch metadata to the scanner criteria and confirm any required service restart or package backport before closure.","correct":false,"why":"Comparing patch metadata against scanner criteria is a good step but omits actually retesting with credentialed checks to confirm the fix took effect."},{"text":"Review evidence from the system owner, then verify manually whether the vulnerable component is still present or merely misidentified.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing owner evidence and manually verifying the component is a reasonable step but doesn't include retesting with the scanner's own credentialed checks to close the discrepancy."},{"text":"Check whether the plugin depends on banners or package versions and determine whether authenticated validation is needed to prove closure.","correct":false,"why":"Checking plugin dependency on banners/versions is a relevant diagnostic step but stops short of actually retesting with credentialed checks to confirm resolution."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q305","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (External Scanning Requirement)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A standard requires regular scans of internet-facing systems from an external perspective. What scan type BEST fulfills this?","options":[{"text":"External vulnerability scanning against public IPs and exposed services, validated and documented.","correct":true,"why":"Some standards explicitly call for external scanning of internet-facing assets to validate exposure and patch posture."},{"text":"Internet-based scans from approved external sources against public addresses and exposed services to verify perimeter exposure.","correct":false,"why":"This restates external scanning from approved sources but omits explicitly validating and documenting results, which the standard's compliance requirement also calls for."},{"text":"Scheduled assessment of publicly reachable hosts from outside the environment, documented against the applicable compliance requirement.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames it as merely a scheduled assessment without emphasizing the validation and documentation needed to demonstrate compliance."},{"text":"External network and service scanning of exposed assets, combined with evidence retention and exception tracking for any validated issues.","correct":false,"why":"This adds evidence retention and exception tracking but doesn't as directly name external scanning against public IPs as the core scan type fulfilling the requirement."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q306","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Access Logging / Audit Trail)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A regulator asks for evidence of who accessed sensitive data and when. Which implementation BEST supports a defensible audit trail?","options":[{"text":"Centralized immutable logging with time sync, identity attribution, and retention controls aligned to compliance needs.","correct":true,"why":"Defensible audits require centralized, tamper-resistant logging with identity attribution, time sync, and retention."},{"text":"A centralized SIEM ingesting application and database events with synchronized timestamps and access controls for log integrity.","correct":false,"why":"A centralized SIEM ingesting events is a strong piece of the solution but doesn't by itself guarantee the logs are immutable and protected from tampering."},{"text":"Database activity monitoring paired with protected retention and user attribution so investigators can reconstruct access to records.","correct":false,"why":"Database activity monitoring with attribution is useful but doesn't specifically ensure the logging itself is centralized and tamper-resistant across all relevant sensitive-data systems."},{"text":"Tamper-evident audit records forwarded off-system with retention, time synchronization, and controls that limit modification rights.","correct":false,"why":"Forwarding tamper-evident records off-system is close but doesn't explicitly tie in identity attribution the way the more complete correct answer does."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q307","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Attack Surface Mapping)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A scan shows an old service listening on TCP 8080 across many servers. The asset owner says it “shouldn’t be there.” What is the BEST next step to assess risk?","options":[{"text":"Identify the service/process, map exposure paths, confirm business function, and determine if it can be removed or patched.","correct":true,"why":"You need to identify what it is, why it exists, where it’s reachable, and then decide remove/patch/segment."},{"text":"Confirm whether the listener is expected, determine which systems can reach it, and assess whether segmentation or removal is appropriate.","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same investigative steps in different order but doesn't include confirming the business function tied to the service, which the more complete answer covers."},{"text":"Investigate the process owner and package source first, then evaluate exposure and remediation options before making broad network changes.","correct":false,"why":"Starting with the process owner and package source narrows the investigation prematurely before mapping the full exposure picture across all affected servers."},{"text":"Correlate the service to business purpose, software inventory, and reachable paths so treatment decisions are based on actual exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Correlating to business purpose and reachable paths is close but omits actually deciding whether the service can be removed or patched, which completes the assessment."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q308","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Agent vs Agentless)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A scanner cannot reach endpoints on laptops that are frequently off-network. The team still needs vulnerability visibility. Which approach BEST addresses this?","options":[{"text":"Use endpoint agent-based vulnerability assessment that reports over the internet with policy controls and encryption.","correct":true,"why":"Agent-based tooling provides continuous visibility even when devices are off-network, with centralized reporting."},{"text":"Deploy an agent that reports software and configuration posture whenever the device has internet access outside the corporate network.","correct":false,"why":"This restates the reporting mechanism but doesn't mention the centralized policy control aspect that helps manage the fleet of roaming endpoints consistently."},{"text":"Use cloud-connected endpoint telemetry so mobile assets remain visible even when they are not reachable through on-premises scanners.","correct":false,"why":"Cloud-connected telemetry is a related concept but doesn't specifically describe deploying an actual vulnerability assessment agent capable of scanning the endpoint."},{"text":"Adopt agent-based assessment with centralized policy and encrypted reporting to maintain visibility for roaming endpoints.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but doesn't explicitly describe reporting over the internet, which is the specific mechanism that solves visibility for off-network laptops."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q309","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (FIPS / Crypto Modules)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A federal-aligned contract requires validated cryptography for certain systems. Which statement BEST fits common compliance language?","options":[{"text":"Use FIPS-validated cryptographic modules for required systems and document configuration and validation boundaries.","correct":true,"why":"Many federal contracts require FIPS-validated crypto modules (validated implementations) and documented boundaries."},{"text":"Select approved implementations that have completed formal validation and ensure the covered operating mode matches the deployment.","correct":false,"why":"This focuses on matching operating mode to deployment but doesn't mention the documentation of configuration and validation boundaries the correct answer specifically covers."},{"text":"Use validated modules where required and maintain evidence showing how those modules are configured within the system boundary.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but doesn't explicitly name using FIPS-validated modules, focusing instead on general configuration evidence."},{"text":"Document the cryptographic boundary and verify that required services use modules operating in their validated configuration mode.","correct":false,"why":"This addresses documenting the cryptographic boundary and operating mode but doesn't as directly state the requirement to use FIPS-validated modules themselves."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q310","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Risk Acceptance)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A critical vulnerability exists on a legacy system that cannot be patched and is required for business operations. Leadership accepts the risk. What is the BEST documentation outcome?","options":[{"text":"Create a formal risk acceptance with compensating controls, expiration date, owner sign-off, and a retest plan.","correct":true,"why":"Risk acceptance must be formal, time-bounded, with ownership, compensating controls, and a plan to revisit."},{"text":"Record the decision in the risk register with business justification, review date, and the controls used to reduce likelihood or impact.","correct":false,"why":"Recording in the risk register with business justification is a reasonable step but omits the formal owner sign-off and retest plan that make the acceptance fully governed."},{"text":"Approve a documented exception that names the owner, duration, compensating measures, and trigger points for reevaluation.","correct":false,"why":"Documenting an exception with owner, duration, and compensating measures is close but doesn't explicitly include a retest plan to revisit the risk later."},{"text":"Track the issue formally with sign-off, review cadence, and conditions that would require remediation if the risk picture changes.","correct":false,"why":"Tracking with sign-off and review cadence is close but doesn't explicitly establish an expiration date the way the more complete formal risk acceptance does."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q311","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Credentialed Windows Checks)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"Credentialed scans against Windows hosts are failing. The scanner shows “access denied” even though the account is valid. What is the MOST likely cause?","options":[{"text":"Required remote management settings/services (WMI/WinRM/SMB) or firewall rules are blocked for the scanner context.","correct":true,"why":"Credentialed scans depend on remote management channels and permissions."},{"text":"Remote checks may be blocked by missing WMI, WinRM, or SMB permissions even though the supplied account can log on locally.","correct":false,"why":"This restates the same root cause but focuses only on local logon capability, without capturing that remote management services themselves may be blocked at the firewall."},{"text":"A valid account still needs the right services, firewall exceptions, and administrative context for the scanner to collect host data.","correct":false,"why":"This acknowledges the needed services and context but is less precise than directly identifying that remote management channels or firewall rules are blocking the scanner specifically."},{"text":"Credentialed assessment can fail when remote administration paths are filtered or the account lacks the privileges expected by the plugin.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but frames it as a general privilege issue rather than specifically pointing to blocked remote management services or firewall rules as the likely cause."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q312","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Integrity / Hashing)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A team needs to detect unauthorized changes to sensitive configuration files and produce evidence for audits. Which control BEST supports integrity verification?","options":[{"text":"Implement file integrity monitoring with cryptographic hashes, protected baselines, and alerting for changes in scope.","correct":true,"why":"FIM uses hashes and protected baselines to detect changes and provide audit evidence for integrity control."},{"text":"Use signed configuration baselines and compare current files against known-good hashes to alert on unauthorized modification.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but doesn't mention alerting on detected changes, which is part of what makes file integrity monitoring a complete audit-evidence control."},{"text":"Store approved baseline hashes securely and monitor protected paths so unexpected changes generate an auditable record.","correct":false,"why":"Storing baseline hashes and monitoring paths is close but omits the alerting component that notifies the team when changes actually occur."},{"text":"Pair change monitoring with privileged access control so configuration edits are attributable and deviations from baseline are detected.","correct":false,"why":"Pairing change monitoring with privileged access control addresses attribution but doesn't center on the hash-based integrity verification the scenario specifically needs."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q313","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (Reporting & Remediation)","source":"CySA_Day_5.html","q":"A vulnerability report is going to executives. They want clarity on what to fix first and why, plus measurable follow-up. Which report element is MOST valuable?","options":[{"text":"A prioritized remediation plan with risk rationale, owners, due dates, compensating controls, and retest verification criteria.","correct":true,"why":"Execs need prioritization + rationale + accountability and measurable verification (retest criteria), not raw scanner dumps."},{"text":"A treatment roadmap that groups related issues, explains business impact, and assigns accountable owners for verification.","correct":false,"why":"This restates a similar roadmap concept but doesn't explicitly include the retest verification criteria the correct answer specifies as important to executives."},{"text":"An executive summary that ranks actions by business risk, shows deadlines, and defines how remediation success will be confirmed.","correct":false,"why":"This is close but doesn't mention compensating controls, which the correct answer includes as part of the complete prioritized picture executives want."},{"text":"A concise remediation tracker linking each major issue to rationale, responsible teams, timing, and the planned validation step.","correct":false,"why":"This tracker links issues to teams and timing but doesn't explicitly call out compensating controls, which round out the complete remediation picture requested."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q314","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP Foundations (BIA)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A business continuity program is being launched. Leadership asks which systems must be restored first after an outage and what maximum downtime is acceptable. Which activity MOST directly produces this information?","options":[{"text":"Conduct a business impact analysis to rank critical processes, dependencies, and recovery targets.","correct":true,"why":"A BIA determines criticality, dependencies, and defines recovery requirements like RTO and RPO for business processes."},{"text":"Review outage tickets to see which systems have generated the most historical downtime.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing historical outage tickets shows past downtime frequency, not the business criticality and recovery targets a BIA is specifically designed to establish."},{"text":"Classify systems by data sensitivity so regulated assets automatically recover before others.","correct":false,"why":"Classifying by data sensitivity addresses regulatory risk, not the operational dependencies and acceptable downtime that determine recovery order."},{"text":"Patch externally exposed hosts first so the least secure services become the first restored tier.","correct":false,"why":"Patching order based on external exposure addresses security risk, not the business-criticality-based recovery sequencing the BIA is meant to establish."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q315","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP Metrics (RTO vs RPO)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A CFO asks why a database needs expensive replication. The business can tolerate losing up to 10 minutes of data but needs the service back within 2 hours. Which statement correctly maps these requirements?","options":[{"text":"RPO is 10 minutes for tolerable data loss, and RTO is 2 hours for service restoration.","correct":true,"why":"RPO = maximum tolerable data loss; RTO = maximum tolerable downtime to restore service."},{"text":"RTO is 10 minutes for allowable downtime, and RPO is 2 hours for restoring service data.","correct":false,"why":"This swaps the definitions: 10 minutes of tolerable data loss is the RPO, and the 2-hour restoration window is the RTO, not the reverse as stated here."},{"text":"RPO is 2 hours because it measures how long the application can remain unavailable after disruption.","correct":false,"why":"RPO measures tolerable data loss, not how long an application can remain unavailable; that describes RTO instead."},{"text":"RTO is 2 hours and RPO is not applicable because replication eliminates the data-loss metric entirely.","correct":false,"why":"RPO doesn't become inapplicable just because replication is used; the 10-minute data loss tolerance is still the RPO, and RTO is the 2-hour restoration target."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q316","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR Strategy (Backups)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A ransomware incident encrypts production data and attempts to delete online backups. Which approach BEST supports recoverability even if admin credentials are compromised?","options":[{"text":"Use immutable backups with a separate control plane and an offline recovery copy.","correct":true,"why":"Immutable + separated control plane + offline copies resist deletion/encryption by attackers with stolen creds."},{"text":"Rely on frequent snapshots stored in the same tenant with the same administrator roles.","correct":false,"why":"Frequent snapshots stored in the same tenant under the same admin roles remain reachable and deletable by the same compromised credentials."},{"text":"Keep backup repositories mounted so recovery jobs can write directly to production storage.","correct":false,"why":"Keeping backup repositories mounted for direct write access to production storage means a compromised admin account could reach and destroy those backups too."},{"text":"Centralize backup credentials in the domain vault so all restore operators use the same account.","correct":false,"why":"Centralizing backup credentials in the domain vault under one shared account increases the impact if that single account is compromised, rather than reducing it."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q317","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP Planning (Single Points of Failure)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A BIA reveals a payroll application depends on a single on-prem database server with no redundancy. Which remediation MOST directly reduces this single point of failure?","options":[{"text":"Implement database high availability with replication and automated failover for that dependency.","correct":true,"why":"Redundancy and automated failover address availability risk from single points of failure directly."},{"text":"Move the payroll application to a new subnet so a local host failure affects fewer users.","correct":false,"why":"Moving to a new subnet changes network placement but doesn't add any redundancy to the single database server itself, so the single point of failure remains."},{"text":"Increase database monitoring frequency so administrators are warned sooner before a crash occurs.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing monitoring frequency helps detect a failure sooner but doesn't add redundancy or eliminate the underlying single point of failure."},{"text":"Schedule more frequent full backups so the single database server can be rebuilt after failure.","correct":false,"why":"More frequent backups shorten recovery time after a failure but don't prevent the outage itself since there's still only one database server."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q318","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP Governance (Plan Ownership)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"During an outage, teams are unsure who can authorize failing over to the secondary site. What BCP element is MOST clearly missing?","options":[{"text":"Document failover authority, escalation paths, and activation criteria in the continuity plan.","correct":true,"why":"BCP/DR must define decision authority, roles, communications, and escalation paths for failover actions."},{"text":"Add quarterly vulnerability scans for the secondary site so technical risk is more visible.","correct":false,"why":"Adding vulnerability scans for the secondary site addresses technical risk visibility, not the missing decision authority and escalation process for failover."},{"text":"Enforce stronger admin passwords so only senior personnel can approve major recovery actions.","correct":false,"why":"Stronger admin passwords address authentication security, not the actual governance gap of who is authorized to make the failover decision."},{"text":"Create stricter firewall rules so failover requests originate from an approved management network.","correct":false,"why":"Stricter firewall rules control network access paths, not who has the authority to approve and trigger failover during an incident."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q319","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR Testing (Tabletop vs Functional)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"An organization wants to validate its incident communications and decision-making steps without impacting production. Which exercise type BEST fits?","options":[{"text":"Run a tabletop exercise focused on roles, communications, and decision points.","correct":true,"why":"Tabletops validate procedures and communications with minimal risk; full interruption tests are highest risk."},{"text":"Perform a full interruption test that cuts production services to measure actual failover timing.","correct":false,"why":"A full interruption test actually cuts production services, which directly conflicts with the stated goal of validating steps without impacting production."},{"text":"Conduct a red team assessment to simulate adversary behavior during the outage scenario.","correct":false,"why":"A red team assessment simulates adversary behavior and tests detection/response, not specifically the continuity communications and decision-making process being validated here."},{"text":"Launch a phishing campaign to confirm employees know how to report continuity issues.","correct":false,"why":"A phishing campaign tests security awareness, not the incident communications and decision-making steps the organization wants to validate."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q320","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP Communications (Crisis Comms)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A regional outage impacts customer-facing services. Social media rumors spread quickly. Which BCP component MOST directly addresses consistent external messaging?","options":[{"text":"Use a crisis communication plan with approved spokespeople, channels, and prepared messages.","correct":true,"why":"Crisis comms defines who speaks, what to say, how to notify customers/regulators, and keeps messaging consistent."},{"text":"Create a patching calendar for public web systems so rumors are less likely to spread.","correct":false,"why":"A patching calendar addresses technical vulnerability management, not the consistent external messaging needed during an active incident with spreading rumors."},{"text":"Route all executive communications through the SOC so incident updates remain centralized.","correct":false,"why":"Routing communications through the SOC centralizes technical incident updates but doesn't establish the approved external spokespeople and messaging the situation requires."},{"text":"Add social media monitoring alerts so external messaging can be developed after posts appear.","correct":false,"why":"Social media monitoring alerts help detect rumors as they spread but don't themselves provide the prepared, consistent messaging needed to respond to them."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q321","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Work Area Recovery)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A flood makes a headquarters building unusable for weeks. The organization needs to keep operations running with minimal delay. Which strategy BEST supports this?","options":[{"text":"Use work area recovery through remote operations and alternate facilities for essential staff.","correct":true,"why":"Alternate sites and remote work enablement support continuity when facilities are unavailable."},{"text":"Increase endpoint malware scanning so the damaged building can reopen with fewer delays.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing malware scanning doesn't address getting the building back into usable condition or restoring operations elsewhere in the meantime."},{"text":"Require staff to remain on-premises so coordination stays centralized during the disruption.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring staff to remain on-premises in an unusable, flooded building directly conflicts with the goal of keeping operations running with minimal delay."},{"text":"Rotate workstation encryption keys before relocation so alternate offices inherit trusted devices.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating encryption keys before relocation is a security housekeeping step, not a strategy for actually resuming operations at an alternate site."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q322","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR (Hot/Warm/Cold Sites)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A business requires near-immediate recovery with minimal data loss. Budget is high, and downtime must be minutes. Which site strategy BEST matches?","options":[{"text":"Deploy a hot site with current data and ready systems for rapid cutover.","correct":true,"why":"Hot sites are fully equipped and support rapid recovery; warm is partial; cold is minimal and slowest."},{"text":"Maintain a cold site and ship hardware after the declaration so costs stay low.","correct":false,"why":"A cold site requires shipping and setting up hardware after declaration, which introduces far more delay than the minutes-level recovery required."},{"text":"Use a warm site with baseline infrastructure but rebuild current data after activation.","correct":false,"why":"A warm site still requires rebuilding current data after activation, which doesn't meet the near-immediate, minimal-data-loss requirement."},{"text":"Rely on local backups only and rebuild in place because site redundancy is unnecessary.","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on local backups with no alternate site means the business must rebuild in place, which cannot achieve minutes-level recovery."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q323","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BIA Dependencies (Third Parties)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A critical application relies on a SaaS provider. The BIA shows this dependency is a major risk. What is the BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Review the vendor’s resiliency commitments, recovery capabilities, and fallback procedures.","correct":true,"why":"Third-party risk includes resiliency and recovery assurances; plan contingencies and validate SLA/DR capabilities."},{"text":"Assume the provider’s multitenant design already satisfies every continuity requirement.","correct":false,"why":"Assuming a multitenant SaaS design already covers every continuity need skips actually verifying the vendor's specific resiliency and recovery commitments."},{"text":"Reduce application logging to minimize visible evidence when the provider has an outage.","correct":false,"why":"Reducing application logging doesn't address the underlying dependency risk; it only reduces visibility into what's happening during an outage."},{"text":"Hide the SaaS endpoint behind internal DNS so external dependency risk is reduced.","correct":false,"why":"Hiding the endpoint behind internal DNS doesn't change the actual dependency on the provider's availability or its recovery capabilities."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q324","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Backups (3-2-1)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A continuity plan calls for “3-2-1” backups. Which description BEST matches this rule?","options":[{"text":"Maintain three data copies on two media types with one copy kept offsite or offline.","correct":true,"why":"3-2-1 is a backup resilience rule: multiple copies, different media, and offsite/offline storage."},{"text":"Store three backup sets in two cloud regions with one administrator assigned to both.","correct":false,"why":"Storing sets across cloud regions with one shared administrator doesn't reflect the 3-2-1 rule's requirement for different media types and an offline/offsite copy."},{"text":"Retain three years of archives on two servers with one set encrypted for compliance.","correct":false,"why":"Retaining years of archives on two servers with one encrypted set addresses retention and encryption, not the specific 3-2-1 combination of copies, media types, and offsite storage."},{"text":"Create three recovery teams on two shifts with one shared repository for restoration scripts.","correct":false,"why":"Creating recovery teams and shifts describes staffing structure, not the actual backup copy, media, and offsite storage rule the 3-2-1 principle describes."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q325","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Resilience (Redundancy vs Diversity)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"An organization has two data centers in the same city. A regional power event takes both offline. What design principle was MOST lacking?","options":[{"text":"Geographic diversity was missing, allowing a single regional event to affect both sites.","correct":true,"why":"Sites in the same region share risk."},{"text":"Administrative diversity was missing, because shared privileged accounts caused the simultaneous outage.","correct":false,"why":"Shared privileged accounts causing an outage would be a security control issue, not what caused two data centers to go down together from a regional power event."},{"text":"Patch diversity was missing, because identical software versions create region-wide power failures.","correct":false,"why":"Identical software versions don't cause power failures; the actual cause here is both sites sharing the same regional power grid."},{"text":"Logging diversity was missing, because separate collectors would have prevented correlated downtime.","correct":false,"why":"Separate logging collectors wouldn't have prevented the actual outage, which was caused by both data centers sharing the same regional power infrastructure."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q326","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Criticality Tiering)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A business has limited DR budget. It can’t provide the same recovery speed for all systems. What is the BEST approach?","options":[{"text":"Tier services by business impact and align recovery spend to the most critical functions.","correct":true,"why":"BCP aligns recovery investment with business priorities and impact; tiering is common and practical."},{"text":"Apply identical recovery objectives to every system so each department receives equal treatment.","correct":false,"why":"Applying identical recovery objectives to every system ignores the limited budget and fails to prioritize the systems that matter most to the business."},{"text":"Fund whichever systems handle the highest data volume because storage size defines continuity priority.","correct":false,"why":"Funding based on data volume conflates storage size with business criticality, which isn't the same thing as prioritizing by actual business impact."},{"text":"Recover the least complex services first so the program can report quick technical wins.","correct":false,"why":"Recovering the least complex services first for quick wins doesn't align spending with which systems are actually most critical to the business."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q327","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR (Failover vs Failback)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"After failing over to the secondary site, the team needs to return services to the primary site once it is restored. What is this process called?","options":[{"text":"Failback is the controlled return of operations from the alternate site to the primary site.","correct":true,"why":"Failover moves operations to alternate; failback returns them to primary once stable."},{"text":"Rollback is the decision to discard secondary-site processing after the disruption closes.","correct":false,"why":"Rollback implies discarding processing rather than describing the controlled, deliberate return of operations to the primary site once it's stable."},{"text":"Warm restoration is the process of restarting workloads on the rebuilt primary environment.","correct":false,"why":"Warm restoration isn't a standard term for this process; the concept described — returning operations to the primary site — is specifically called failback."},{"text":"Rotation is the handoff step where traffic is shifted between two synchronized production regions.","correct":false,"why":"Rotation describes shifting traffic between synchronized regions in an active-active setup, not the return-to-primary process being described here."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q328","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR Documentation (Runbooks)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"During an outage, a junior admin needs step-by-step recovery instructions for a critical application. What document BEST provides this?","options":[{"text":"Use a disaster recovery runbook with ordered steps, dependencies, contacts, and validation tasks.","correct":true,"why":"Runbooks provide detailed procedures, sequencing, dependencies, and verification steps needed during recovery."},{"text":"Review the acceptable use policy because it defines how employees handle systems during events.","correct":false,"why":"An acceptable use policy governs general system behavior, not the specific step-by-step recovery procedure a junior admin needs during an outage."},{"text":"Open the latest vulnerability report because it lists the assets needing the fastest technical action.","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability report identifies security weaknesses, not the ordered recovery steps and dependencies needed to restore a specific application."},{"text":"Reference the network diagram alone because topology views imply the correct recovery order.","correct":false,"why":"A network diagram shows topology but doesn't provide the explicit sequencing, contacts, and validation steps a runbook would include."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q329","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Change Management)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A continuity test fails because a critical app dependency changed months ago, but the DR plan was not updated. What is the BEST long-term fix?","options":[{"text":"Tie BCP and DR updates to change management so dependencies stay accurate over time.","correct":true,"why":"BCP/DR must be living documents, updated via change management and validated through regular exercises."},{"text":"Freeze changes to critical systems so documented recovery steps do not need further revision.","correct":false,"why":"Freezing changes to critical systems isn't practical long-term and doesn't address keeping the DR plan itself synchronized with legitimate future changes."},{"text":"Reduce exercise frequency so outdated dependencies are less likely to surface during testing.","correct":false,"why":"Reducing exercise frequency would make outdated dependencies less likely to be caught, worsening rather than fixing the underlying gap."},{"text":"Restrict plan access to a smaller team so fewer people act on stale recovery documentation.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting plan access to fewer people doesn't address the actual problem, which is that the plan's content became outdated when the dependency changed."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q330","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Incident vs Disaster (Activation)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A minor outage affects one noncritical service for 15 minutes. The DR manager wants to activate full DR. What is the BEST response?","options":[{"text":"Use the documented activation thresholds and escalate proportionally before declaring full DR.","correct":true,"why":"BCP/DR activation should follow criteria (impact, duration, scope) to avoid unnecessary disruption and cost."},{"text":"Declare full disaster recovery for every outage so teams gain more operational practice.","correct":false,"why":"Declaring full DR for every outage, including a minor 15-minute issue on a noncritical service, causes unnecessary disruption and cost."},{"text":"Reserve DR activation only for confirmed cyberattacks because availability events use separate plans.","correct":false,"why":"Reserving DR activation only for confirmed cyberattacks ignores that availability events can also warrant proportional activation based on documented criteria."},{"text":"Wait for public reporting before escalation because media attention is the clearest severity trigger.","correct":false,"why":"Waiting for public/media reporting is an unreliable and delayed signal, not a documented activation threshold based on impact, duration, and scope."}],"sub":"3.2"},{"id":"q331","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Manual Workarounds)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A key service cannot meet the required RTO due to legacy constraints. The business still needs continuity. What option BEST supports operations?","options":[{"text":"Document manual workarounds and alternate processing steps for the critical business function.","correct":true,"why":"Manual workarounds/alternate processes are legitimate BCP strategies when technical recovery can’t meet targets."},{"text":"Retire the service so the organization no longer has to meet the stated recovery target.","correct":false,"why":"Retiring the service to avoid the recovery target doesn't address that the business still needs the function to keep operating."},{"text":"Rely on end users to adapt informally because operational teams will improvise during the outage.","correct":false,"why":"Relying on informal, ad hoc improvisation by end users doesn't provide the documented, repeatable process a formal continuity approach requires."},{"text":"Increase vulnerability scans against the legacy platform to improve availability during disruptions.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing vulnerability scans addresses security posture, not the operational gap of meeting the required recovery time for this legacy service."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q332","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Backups (Restore Testing)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"Backups are taken nightly, but no restores have been tested. What is the MOST significant risk?","options":[{"text":"The backups may not restore cleanly, so recoverability remains unverified until tested.","correct":true,"why":"Untested backups are a common failure point."},{"text":"Nightly backups are sufficient evidence because successful jobs imply successful recovery.","correct":false,"why":"A successful backup job completing doesn't guarantee the data can actually be restored; job success and restore success are not the same thing."},{"text":"Restore testing weakens backup security because mounted recovery jobs expose encryption material.","correct":false,"why":"Restore testing doesn't inherently weaken backup security; the actual significant risk here is simply not knowing whether backups can be restored at all."},{"text":"Testing restorations is optional when checksums are present because integrity proves usability.","correct":false,"why":"Checksums verify data wasn't corrupted in storage, not that the backup can actually be restored and used successfully."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q333","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Data Prioritization)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A BIA identifies customer orders as the most critical data set. During a DR event, what should the recovery team prioritize first?","options":[{"text":"Restore the order-processing service stack and its dependencies before lower-priority workloads.","correct":true,"why":"Prioritize business-critical processes and dependencies identified in the BIA to meet RTO/RPO for key operations."},{"text":"Bring back the simplest applications first so the recovery team can clear tasks quickly.","correct":false,"why":"Restoring the simplest applications first ignores the BIA's finding that customer order data specifically is the most business-critical to recover."},{"text":"Restore systems according to user demand as business units raise complaints during the outage.","correct":false,"why":"Restoring based on which business units complain loudest doesn't reflect the BIA's documented priority ranking of what's actually most critical."},{"text":"Start every system simultaneously because parallel recovery always shortens the total outage window.","correct":false,"why":"Starting every system simultaneously ignores dependencies and doesn't ensure the most critical order-processing stack is prioritized appropriately."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q334","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR (Replication Modes)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A company uses asynchronous replication to a DR site. After a sudden failure, some transactions are missing at the DR site. Which concept explains this?","options":[{"text":"Asynchronous replication can leave a lag window, so recent transactions may be absent after failover.","correct":true,"why":"Async replication trades some potential data loss for performance and distance; missing transactions align with RPO risk."},{"text":"Asynchronous replication mirrors every write instantly, so missing data indicates the wrong site was used.","correct":false,"why":"Asynchronous replication does not mirror every write instantly; that describes synchronous replication, and the missing transactions actually confirm the lag inherent to async replication."},{"text":"Replication gaps occur only when malware tampers with journals, so compromise is the primary explanation.","correct":false,"why":"Malware tampering with journals is a possible but far less likely explanation than the expected data-loss window inherent to asynchronous replication."},{"text":"This is mainly a time-synchronization issue because clock drift discards writes during DR activation.","correct":false,"why":"Clock drift or time-sync issues wouldn't cause transactions to be missing after failover; the missing data instead reflects the inherent replication lag window."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q335","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Supply Chain)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A critical supplier outage stops manufacturing even though IT systems are available. What BCP lesson is MOST relevant?","options":[{"text":"Continuity planning must cover supplier dependencies and alternate sourcing, not just internal IT.","correct":true,"why":"Continuity includes business operations and supply chain dependencies; alternate sourcing and contractual resilience matter."},{"text":"Cybersecurity controls alone are sufficient because vendor outages usually begin as security incidents.","correct":false,"why":"Cybersecurity controls address security incidents, not the different problem of a supplier's operational outage disrupting the supply chain."},{"text":"External suppliers sit outside the continuity program because the business cannot influence their operations.","correct":false,"why":"External suppliers are very much part of the continuity program since their outages can directly halt business operations, as shown here."},{"text":"Improved monitoring solves the issue because early detection removes the need for sourcing contingencies.","correct":false,"why":"Improved monitoring would help detect an outage sooner but doesn't provide the alternate sourcing needed to keep manufacturing running during one."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q336","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Exercises Types)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"The organization wants to validate technical recovery steps and actually bring services up in the DR site without shutting production down. What exercise BEST fits?","options":[{"text":"Run a functional exercise that executes recovery steps in the DR environment without taking production down.","correct":true,"why":"Functional exercises test technical recovery steps in a controlled way, without necessarily causing production interruption."},{"text":"Perform a checklist review because documented procedures provide enough assurance without live validation.","correct":false,"why":"A checklist review only verifies documentation exists; it doesn't actually execute recovery steps or prove the DR environment works technically."},{"text":"Use a full interruption test since lower-impact exercises do not prove any meaningful recovery capability.","correct":false,"why":"A full interruption test takes production down entirely, which conflicts with the stated goal of testing without disrupting production."},{"text":"Launch a phishing simulation to confirm personnel can recognize continuity-related communications.","correct":false,"why":"A phishing simulation tests security awareness, not the technical recovery steps and DR environment functionality the organization wants to validate."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q337","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Critical Records)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A natural disaster destroys on-site paper contracts and records needed for legal operations. Which control MOST reduces future impact?","options":[{"text":"Digitize essential records and maintain protected offsite copies with retention controls.","correct":true,"why":"Critical records protection includes digitization, offsite storage, access control, and retention management."},{"text":"Store the paper originals in more accessible cabinets so staff can evacuate them faster.","correct":false,"why":"Storing paper originals in more accessible cabinets still leaves them vulnerable to the same physical disaster that destroyed the records in the first place."},{"text":"Reduce record volume by disposing of older contracts whenever storage space becomes limited.","correct":false,"why":"Disposing of older contracts to save space doesn't address protecting essential records; it risks losing records that may still be needed."},{"text":"Depend on institutional knowledge because key agreements can be reconstructed after the event.","correct":false,"why":"Relying on institutional knowledge to reconstruct agreements is unreliable and doesn't provide the documented, verifiable copies legal operations require."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q338","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR (Order of Operations)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"After a data center outage, teams restore application servers first, but the app still fails because the database and IAM are down. What continuity concept does this illustrate?","options":[{"text":"Recovery sequencing and dependency mapping were missing from the restoration order.","correct":true,"why":"Recovery must follow dependencies and sequence."},{"text":"The issue reflects patch prioritization, because unpatched systems should never be restored first.","correct":false,"why":"Patch prioritization concerns which systems get security updates first, not the actual sequencing and dependency issue that caused the application to fail despite being restored."},{"text":"This is primarily a logging problem, since normalized telemetry allows applications to reconnect correctly.","correct":false,"why":"Normalized telemetry is a logging concern and doesn't address the actual dependency-ordering problem that left the database and IAM down when the app needed them."},{"text":"Certificate rotation should precede infrastructure recovery because trust services determine service availability.","correct":false,"why":"Certificate rotation is unrelated to the actual issue here, which is that dependencies (database, IAM) weren't restored before the application that needs them."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q339","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Alternate Communications)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"During a major outage, corporate email and chat are unavailable. The team cannot coordinate response actions. What BCP control BEST prevents this failure?","options":[{"text":"Provide out-of-band communications and offline contact procedures for responders and leaders.","correct":true,"why":"BCP should include out-of-band comms and offline-accessible contact lists to coordinate when primary systems fail."},{"text":"Increase mailbox quotas so the primary email platform remains usable during large disruptions.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing mailbox quotas doesn't help if the primary email platform itself is unavailable during the outage; it doesn't provide an alternate channel."},{"text":"Require everyone to work from headquarters so coordination depends on a single physical location.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring everyone to work from headquarters creates a single point of failure for coordination rather than providing a resilient alternate communication method."},{"text":"Use social messaging apps as the primary fallback because they are always available and appropriate.","correct":false,"why":"Relying on consumer social messaging apps as the primary fallback lacks the reliability, security, and appropriateness needed for official incident coordination."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q340","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Policy and Compliance)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A regulated organization must prove its continuity plans are current and effective. Which evidence BEST supports this claim?","options":[{"text":"Show current plans, revision history, exercise results, and tracked remediation from lessons learned.","correct":true,"why":"Auditors want evidence: updated plans, tests/exercises, results, lessons learned, and corrective actions tracked to closure."},{"text":"Provide an attestation that testing is planned because intent demonstrates program maturity.","correct":false,"why":"An attestation of planned future testing doesn't provide evidence that testing has actually occurred or that the plans are currently effective."},{"text":"Capture screenshots of the DR login portal because visible access confirms operational readiness.","correct":false,"why":"Screenshots of a login portal only show the portal exists; they don't demonstrate that the continuity plans have been tested or are effective."},{"text":"Submit a recent vulnerability scan because security testing also proves continuity effectiveness.","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability scan assesses security weaknesses, not whether the organization's continuity plans have been tested and kept current."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q341","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Personnel Resilience)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A pandemic reduces staff availability for critical operations. What continuity planning element MOST directly addresses this risk?","options":[{"text":"Cross-train staff and maintain succession coverage for critical roles and minimum staffing needs.","correct":true,"why":"Personnel continuity includes cross-training, succession, staffing models, and documented procedures for critical roles."},{"text":"Add more physical security personnel so key workers can reach the office during disruptions.","correct":false,"why":"Adding physical security personnel doesn't address staff shortages caused by a pandemic reducing available personnel for critical operations."},{"text":"Suspend leave approvals for critical teams to preserve enough staffing during extended events.","correct":false,"why":"Suspending leave approvals may temporarily increase headcount but doesn't build the cross-training and succession coverage needed for sustained resilience."},{"text":"Rotate privileged credentials more often so essential responsibilities can be reassigned quickly.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating privileged credentials more often is a security practice unrelated to ensuring critical roles have adequate staffing and backup coverage."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q342","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP (Recovery Validation)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"After restoring from backups, what is the BEST way to confirm the recovered system meets continuity requirements?","options":[{"text":"Validate service functionality, data integrity, and whether recovery objectives were actually met.","correct":true,"why":"Recovery validation requires testing function + integrity, plus verifying RTO/RPO targets were achieved."},{"text":"Treat a successful boot as sufficient confirmation that the restored workload is production-ready.","correct":false,"why":"A successful boot only confirms the system started; it doesn't verify that data integrity is intact or that recovery objectives like RTO/RPO were actually met."},{"text":"Close the event once systems respond so recovery metrics reflect a shorter outage duration.","correct":false,"why":"Closing the event once systems respond, without validating function and data integrity, risks reporting recovery as complete when it may not actually meet requirements."},{"text":"Silence monitoring temporarily because a quiet dashboard indicates stability after restoration.","correct":false,"why":"Silencing monitoring doesn't validate anything about the recovered system; a quiet dashboard doesn't confirm functionality or data integrity."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q343","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"DR Strategy (Active-Active vs Active-Passive)","source":"CySA_Day_7.html","q":"A global application needs high availability and can tolerate near-zero downtime. The organization deploys two regions serving traffic simultaneously. Which architecture is this?","options":[{"text":"This is an active-active design with multiple regions serving production traffic at the same time.","correct":true,"why":"Active-active serves traffic from multiple sites simultaneously; it offers strong availability but increases complexity."},{"text":"This is active-passive because one region will assume full load only after the other fails.","correct":false,"why":"Active-passive means one region only takes over after the other fails; this scenario describes both regions actively serving traffic simultaneously, which is active-active."},{"text":"This is a warm-site arrangement because both regions are available but not fully synchronized.","correct":false,"why":"A warm-site arrangement describes partially ready infrastructure requiring some setup before use, not two regions already actively serving live production traffic together."},{"text":"This is a cold-site strategy because failover capacity exists only when traffic must be rerouted.","correct":false,"why":"A cold-site strategy means capacity exists only after failover is triggered; this scenario describes both regions handling traffic continuously right now."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q344","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Log Sources (Coverage)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A SOC has strong endpoint telemetry but repeatedly misses privileged changes to firewall rules and switch configurations. Which logging improvement MOST directly closes the gap?","options":[{"text":"Enable centralized network device logging and AAA accounting forwarded to the SIEM for change attribution","correct":true,"why":"Network device syslog plus AAA accounting provides direct visibility into privileged actions and configuration changes."},{"text":"Collect periodic configuration snapshots from network devices and compare them offline each week","correct":false,"why":"Periodic offline snapshot comparisons only catch changes after the fact on a weekly cycle, missing timely attribution of who made privileged changes."},{"text":"Increase endpoint audit detail so host events can infer network control changes more precisely","correct":false,"why":"Increasing endpoint audit detail only covers host-level events; it can't directly capture privileged changes made on network devices like firewalls and switches."},{"text":"Expand vulnerability scanner coverage to flag drift in exposed network services after changes","correct":false,"why":"Expanding vulnerability scanning detects resulting exposure from changes, but doesn't provide the direct attribution of who made the privileged configuration change."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q345","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Time Sync (Correlation)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"An incident timeline is unreliable because logs from servers and cloud services appear out of order by minutes. What control MOST directly fixes this?","options":[{"text":"Implement consistent time synchronization and standardized timezone handling across all log sources","correct":true,"why":"Accurate correlation depends on synchronized clocks and consistent timestamp handling across sources."},{"text":"Increase retention so out-of-sequence events can still be reviewed after the fact","correct":false,"why":"Increasing retention lets analysts review more history, but doesn't fix the underlying timestamp inconsistency causing events to appear out of order."},{"text":"Tag alerts by severity so analysts can manually reorder important events first","correct":false,"why":"Tagging alerts by severity for manual reordering doesn't correct the actual timestamp misalignment causing the sequencing problem."},{"text":"Rotate logs more frequently so ingestion delays do not affect event sequence views","correct":false,"why":"Rotating logs more frequently changes how logs are stored, not whether their timestamps are synchronized and consistently ordered."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q346","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Normalization (Parsing)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A SIEM ingests syslog from multiple vendors, but correlation rules fail because fields like source IP and username appear in different formats. What is the BEST fix?","options":[{"text":"Normalize events into a common schema and validate parser accuracy for the key fields","correct":true,"why":"A consistent schema is essential for reliable correlation across heterogeneous sources."},{"text":"Separate vendors into different dashboards and tune rules per device family instead","correct":false,"why":"Separating vendors into different dashboards and tuning per device family avoids the correlation problem rather than fixing the underlying field format inconsistency."},{"text":"Retain raw logs only and build keyword searches around each vendor message format","correct":false,"why":"Retaining only raw logs with keyword search doesn't resolve the inconsistent field formats preventing reliable cross-source correlation."},{"text":"Increase ingestion priority for firewall logs so the most common fields dominate matching","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing ingestion for one vendor's logs doesn't fix the format inconsistency affecting correlation across all the other vendor sources."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q347","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Windows Logs (Authentication)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"You need to detect password spraying against Azure AD and on-prem AD. Which log signal BEST indicates spraying rather than brute force?","options":[{"text":"Failures distributed across many accounts with limited password variation in a short interval","correct":true,"why":"Spraying targets many accounts with one or a few passwords to avoid lockouts, while brute force targets one account with many passwords."},{"text":"Repeated failures against one privileged account followed by lockout and password reset","correct":false,"why":"Repeated failures against one privileged account followed by lockout describes a targeted brute-force pattern against a single account, not the broad spread across many accounts seen in spraying."},{"text":"A sequence of successful sign-ins from the same workstation across a shared kiosk session","correct":false,"why":"Successful sign-ins from a shared kiosk session reflect legitimate device use, not the failed-login pattern associated with password spraying."},{"text":"High authentication volume from a service account during a scheduled maintenance window","correct":false,"why":"High authentication volume from a service account during scheduled maintenance is expected legitimate activity, not evidence of spraying across many accounts."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q348","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Audit Logs (Control Plane)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A cloud account experiences unexpected security group changes and new API keys created after hours. Endpoint tools show nothing. What data source is MOST critical?","options":[{"text":"Cloud control-plane audit logs that record API activity, principals, and permission changes","correct":true,"why":"Control-plane logs capture administrative and API activity and are the primary source for cloud account abuse investigation."},{"text":"Cloud flow logs that summarize accepted and rejected network paths for affected workloads","correct":false,"why":"Cloud flow logs show network path activity, not the administrative API actions and permission changes needed to investigate account-level abuse here."},{"text":"Container runtime logs from the instances attached to the modified security groups","correct":false,"why":"Container runtime logs reflect what's happening inside the instances, not the control-plane security group and API key changes that occurred."},{"text":"Object storage access logs for buckets in the same account and region","correct":false,"why":"Object storage access logs only cover bucket activity; they wouldn't reveal the security group changes or new API key creation described."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q349","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Retention (Compliance vs Detection)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A company wants to reduce SIEM costs by cutting log retention from 180 days to 7 days. What is the MOST significant security downside?","options":[{"text":"Investigations lose historical context for slow attacks, delayed discovery, and threat hunting","correct":true,"why":"Short retention reduces visibility for long-dwell intrusions and investigations that require historical context."},{"text":"Recent alerts become harder to search because hot storage tiers require longer retention periods","correct":false,"why":"Search performance in hot storage tiers is an operational/cost consideration, not the significant security downside of losing historical data needed for investigations."},{"text":"Parser quality declines because field extraction models need months of source data to function","correct":false,"why":"Parser models don't require months of retained data to function; retention length and parsing quality are unrelated concerns."},{"text":"Endpoint agents stop forwarding events when the SIEM keeps less than one month of history","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint agents don't stop forwarding events based on SIEM retention settings; retention and active log forwarding are independent of each other."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q350","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Log Integrity (Tamper Resistance)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"Attackers are suspected of deleting local logs on compromised hosts. Which control MOST directly preserves trustworthy evidence?","options":[{"text":"Forward logs off-host to a centralized immutable store with restricted write permissions","correct":true,"why":"Centralized, immutable logging reduces attacker ability to tamper with evidence and supports investigations."},{"text":"Mirror each host log locally to a second partition protected by endpoint access controls","correct":false,"why":"Mirroring logs to a second local partition still keeps them on the same host, where an attacker with sufficient access could still tamper with both copies."},{"text":"Increase local log size so more deleted events can be recovered from disk slack later","correct":false,"why":"Increasing local log size to recover deleted events from disk slack is unreliable and doesn't proactively prevent tampering the way off-host forwarding does."},{"text":"Back up logs nightly to standard file storage managed by desktop support teams","correct":false,"why":"Nightly backups to standard file storage still leave a gap where recent logs could be deleted before that backup runs, and standard storage may not resist tampering."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q351","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Alert Tuning (False Positives)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A detection rule triggers thousands of alerts for “suspicious PowerShell” because IT uses scripts for management. What is the BEST tuning approach?","options":[{"text":"Baseline approved admin usage and refine the rule around risky behaviors and uncommon context","correct":true,"why":"Tune by baselining and narrowing detections while preserving high-signal patterns such as encoded commands suspicious parents and unusual destinations."},{"text":"Scope the alert to privileged workstations only and suppress all script activity elsewhere","correct":false,"why":"Scoping the alert to only privileged workstations while suppressing all script activity elsewhere would miss malicious PowerShell use on regular endpoints."},{"text":"Raise the threshold so the rule fires only when multiple hosts execute PowerShell together","correct":false,"why":"Raising the threshold to only fire when multiple hosts run PowerShell together would miss genuinely malicious single-host activity that doesn't involve multiple systems."},{"text":"Split the rule into separate alerts for encoded commands remoting and unsigned launches","correct":false,"why":"Splitting into separate alerts for specific behaviors is a reasonable step but doesn't itself establish the baseline of normal admin usage needed to reduce the noise."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q352","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"NetFlow/IPFIX (Encrypted Traffic)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"TLS prevents payload inspection, but you suspect data exfiltration. Which monitoring data BEST helps quantify scope?","options":[{"text":"Flow telemetry with bytes duration direction and endpoint context for large transfers","correct":true,"why":"Flows help identify large transfers unusual destinations and timing even when payload is encrypted."},{"text":"DNS resolution history for the endpoints involved in the suspected transfer path","correct":false,"why":"DNS resolution history shows which domains were queried, not the actual volume, duration, or direction of the suspected data transfer itself."},{"text":"Proxy category logs showing the application class of the destination service only","correct":false,"why":"Proxy category logs show only the application class of a destination, not the size or timing details needed to quantify how much data was transferred."},{"text":"ARP and switch MAC tables tied to the subnet where the workstation resides","correct":false,"why":"ARP and switch MAC tables show local network mappings, not the volume or scope of a data transfer to an external destination."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q353","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"DNS Logs (Tunneling/Beaconing)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"DNS logs show long, high-entropy subdomain queries to a single domain every 60 seconds from one host. What is the MOST likely concern?","options":[{"text":"Possible DNS tunneling or beaconing that should be validated with endpoint and domain context","correct":true,"why":"Regular high-entropy queries can indicate tunneling or command-and-control."},{"text":"Dynamic service discovery by an internal application using randomized host labels for resilience","correct":false,"why":"Dynamic service discovery using randomized labels for resilience wouldn't typically involve consistent 60-second interval queries with long, high-entropy subdomains to one destination."},{"text":"Content delivery optimization where a resolver rotates cache-busting tokens on fixed intervals","correct":false,"why":"Content delivery cache-busting tokens don't typically follow the pattern of high-entropy DNS labels at strict, regular intervals to a single domain."},{"text":"Cloud workload registration traffic from an orchestration agent renewing instance metadata","correct":false,"why":"Cloud orchestration metadata renewal traffic wouldn't typically use long, random subdomain labels queried against an external domain at fixed short intervals."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q354","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"EDR (Process Context)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"An alert shows powershell.exe launching rundll32.exe with a long base64 command. Which enrichment MOST increases confidence?","options":[{"text":"Process lineage full command lines signer details and related network connections","correct":true,"why":"Process lineage plus command line signing and network telemetry are core for validating script abuse and LOLBAS activity."},{"text":"Recent patch deployment records for the host and other systems in the same device group","correct":false,"why":"Patch deployment records reflect update status, not the process behavior or command-line content needed to assess whether this specific execution is malicious."},{"text":"User VPN history and geolocation for the account logged in to that workstation","correct":false,"why":"VPN history and geolocation relate to the user's access location, not the process chain and command-line details needed to validate this specific alert."},{"text":"File system change journals showing which documents were opened before the alert","correct":false,"why":"File change journals show document activity, not the process lineage and network context needed to confirm malicious script or LOLBAS behavior."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q355","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SIEM Correlation (Impossible Travel)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A user logs in to a cloud app from Arizona, then two minutes later from Europe, both successful. Which monitoring rule concept BEST detects this?","options":[{"text":"Geo-velocity correlation that compares session timing with improbable travel distance","correct":true,"why":"Impossible travel correlates geography and timing anomalies and is common for stolen sessions tokens or proxy abuse."},{"text":"Concurrent session detection that flags overlapping use from unmanaged and managed devices","correct":false,"why":"Concurrent session detection flags overlapping device use, not the specific geographic-impossibility pattern of two logins from distant locations minutes apart."},{"text":"Adaptive authentication that raises challenges when sign-ins deviate from learned behavior","correct":false,"why":"Adaptive authentication reacts to behavioral deviations generally; it isn't the specific geo-velocity concept that directly explains this impossible-travel pattern."},{"text":"Source IP reputation matching that prioritizes logins from anonymization infrastructure","correct":false,"why":"Reputation matching flags known-bad infrastructure, but wouldn't specifically catch this pattern if the second login came from a clean, non-flagged IP."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q356","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Web Logs (WAF/App)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A WAF shows repeated 403s followed by a single 200 with an unusual User-Agent, then the app begins generating outbound connections. What is the BEST interpretation?","options":[{"text":"An exploit attempt may have succeeded and should be correlated with server and outbound telemetry","correct":true,"why":"403 bursts can indicate probing and a later success with an unusual user agent may indicate exploit delivery."},{"text":"Application reconnaissance likely shifted into authenticated misuse through a valid session token","correct":false,"why":"Framing this as reconnaissance shifting into authenticated misuse assumes a valid session token was used, which isn't established by 403s followed by a single 200 and new outbound connections."},{"text":"A tuning gap in the WAF may be allowing crafted requests to bypass earlier signature matches","correct":false,"why":"A WAF tuning gap is a plausible contributing factor but doesn't itself describe the full picture of probing followed by apparent successful exploitation and outbound activity."},{"text":"A backend feature integration may have introduced new server-side callbacks tied to that path","correct":false,"why":"New legitimate backend integrations wouldn't typically follow a pattern of repeated 403 blocks and an unusual User-Agent right before the callbacks begin."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q357","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Syslog Severity (Signal)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A SIEM ingestion pipeline drops “informational” logs to save cost. Analysts later miss early recon indicators. What is the BEST adjustment?","options":[{"text":"Filter by event value and use case instead of relying on vendor severity labels alone","correct":true,"why":"Severity labels vary widely."},{"text":"Retain informational logs only for high-risk assets and privileged account activity","correct":false,"why":"Retaining informational logs only for high-risk assets still misses early recon indicators that could appear on other, non-privileged assets."},{"text":"Route low-severity events to cold storage and search them only during investigations","correct":false,"why":"Routing low-severity events to cold storage still delays access to them during active investigations rather than making them available for real-time detection."},{"text":"Normalize source severities so equivalent messages map consistently across platforms","correct":false,"why":"Normalizing severities across platforms helps consistency but doesn't address that vendor severity labels themselves are an unreliable basis for filtering important events."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q358","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Gaps (East-West)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"An IDS at the internet edge shows no alerts, but you suspect lateral movement. What is the BEST monitoring change?","options":[{"text":"Add internal visibility at east-west choke points and correlate it with endpoint telemetry","correct":true,"why":"Edge-only monitoring misses internal movement."},{"text":"Expand firewall logging between internal segments and alert on unusual administrative ports","correct":false,"why":"Expanding firewall logging between segments helps but doesn't provide the same depth of process-level correlation with endpoint telemetry needed to confirm lateral movement."},{"text":"Deploy host firewall analytics to capture remote service creation and management traffic","correct":false,"why":"Host firewall analytics capture some remote service activity but don't provide the broader east-west network visibility across all internal choke points."},{"text":"Collect switch flow records from core aggregation paths used by server-to-server communication","correct":false,"why":"Switch flow records from core aggregation paths provide network-level visibility but don't include the endpoint telemetry correlation needed for full confirmation."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q359","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"Analysts spend hours enriching alerts with IP reputation, WHOIS, and sandbox lookups. Which solution BEST reduces time-to-triage?","options":[{"text":"Use SOAR playbooks to automate enrichment steps with approvals and evidence capture","correct":true,"why":"SOAR reduces repetitive manual work and standardizes triage and enrichment improving speed and consistency."},{"text":"Build SIEM dashboards that pre-stage the most common context for analyst review","correct":false,"why":"Pre-staged SIEM dashboards present context faster but still require the analyst to manually pull and interpret it, unlike automated SOAR enrichment."},{"text":"Move reputation and sandbox checks into endpoint agents so alerts arrive more complete","correct":false,"why":"Moving checks into endpoint agents adds complexity per-agent and doesn't provide the centralized, standardized automation and approval workflow SOAR offers."},{"text":"Create analyst runbooks with standardized links to the same intelligence sources","correct":false,"why":"Standardized runbooks with links still require analysts to manually visit each source, rather than automating the enrichment steps entirely."}],"sub":"1.9"},{"id":"q360","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Data Quality (Duplicate Events)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A SIEM rule double-counts events because the same logs are ingested through an agent and also via syslog forwarding. What is the BEST fix?","options":[{"text":"Establish one authoritative collection path per source type and deduplicate by event identity","correct":true,"why":"Duplicate ingestion skews metrics and triggers."},{"text":"Tune the rule to require a larger event threshold before generating an alert","correct":false,"why":"Raising the alert threshold masks the symptom of inflated event counts but doesn't fix the actual duplicate ingestion causing the double-counting."},{"text":"Normalize duplicate fields into a shared schema so repeated messages collapse more cleanly","correct":false,"why":"Normalizing fields into a shared schema helps correlate messages but doesn't eliminate the duplicate ingestion paths causing events to be counted twice."},{"text":"Tag agent and syslog events separately so analysts can compare both during investigations","correct":false,"why":"Tagging agent and syslog events separately helps analysts distinguish them but doesn't stop the duplicate counting from skewing detection logic."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q361","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication Logs (MFA Fatigue)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A user receives repeated MFA push prompts, and then one is approved, followed by a new-device login. Which monitoring pattern BEST detects this attack?","options":[{"text":"Repeated push activity followed by an approval and anomalous session attributes in a short window","correct":true,"why":"MFA fatigue often shows repeated prompts or denials then an approval followed by anomalous session device or IP characteristics."},{"text":"A sudden increase in successful MFA use from a previously registered corporate laptop","correct":false,"why":"A sudden increase in successful MFA from an already-registered corporate laptop is expected normal behavior, not the anomalous pattern indicating a fatigue attack."},{"text":"A new device enrollment event that occurs before the first sign-in from a remote location","correct":false,"why":"A new device enrollment before the first remote sign-in is a different setup sequence, not the repeated-prompt-then-approval pattern characteristic of push fatigue."},{"text":"Several failed password attempts followed by a password reset and standard MFA registration","correct":false,"why":"Failed password attempts followed by a reset and standard MFA registration describes normal account recovery, not the repeated push approval pattern of a fatigue attack."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q362","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Firewall Logs (Rule Shadowing)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A deny rule for a known-bad IP range exists, but traffic is still allowed to a web server. Review shows an “allow any to web 443” rule above it. Why?","options":[{"text":"The broader allow rule shadows the later deny because it matches the traffic first","correct":true,"why":"First-match rulebases can shadow later rules."},{"text":"The connection is already established so later policy changes apply only to new sessions","correct":false,"why":"Established connection state doesn't explain why new connections were allowed; the issue is which rule matches first for new traffic, not existing session handling."},{"text":"The web rule uses an application object that evaluates before network-based deny criteria","correct":false,"why":"Application object evaluation order doesn't change the fact that a broader rule listed first still matches before the later deny rule is ever reached."},{"text":"A NAT policy rewrites the source and causes the specific deny to miss the translated address","correct":false,"why":"A NAT rewrite could affect which address is evaluated, but the described scenario is specifically about rule order, where the broad allow matches before the deny."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q363","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Windows Auditing (Privilege Use)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"You want to monitor privilege escalation attempts on Windows endpoints. Which log category is MOST relevant?","options":[{"text":"Security auditing for group changes elevation events and admin rights assignments","correct":true,"why":"Monitor group membership changes privilege assignments elevation events and admin token activity with user attribution."},{"text":"PowerShell transcription tied to administrative shells and run-as activity on endpoints","correct":false,"why":"PowerShell transcription captures command activity but doesn't specifically center on the group membership and privilege assignment events that reveal escalation attempts."},{"text":"Application compatibility logs that record installer behavior and driver changes","correct":false,"why":"Application compatibility logs track installer and driver behavior, not privilege escalation activity like group changes or elevation events."},{"text":"RDP session history for privileged users connecting into jump hosts and admin consoles","correct":false,"why":"RDP session history shows connection activity but doesn't directly capture privilege assignment changes or elevation events on the endpoint."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q364","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Application Logs (AuthZ Failures)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"An API begins returning many 403 responses for object access, and then a sudden increase in 200 responses for the same resources from a new token. What might this indicate?","options":[{"text":"Authorization probing followed by abuse of a stolen mis-scoped or over-privileged token","correct":true,"why":"403 bursts can indicate probing or enumeration and a new token succeeding may indicate token theft scope abuse or misconfiguration."},{"text":"A user session migrating between clients that present different cached authorization claims","correct":false,"why":"A user's session migrating between clients with different cached claims wouldn't typically produce a burst of 403s followed by 200s from a distinctly new token."},{"text":"An access-control policy change that propagated unevenly across API nodes and validators","correct":false,"why":"An unevenly propagated policy change could cause inconsistent responses, but wouldn't typically follow the specific pattern of probing then a new token succeeding."},{"text":"Object enumeration that later succeeded after the client refreshed to a broader service scope","correct":false,"why":"Object enumeration succeeding after a scope refresh assumes a benign explanation without considering the more concerning possibility of token theft or misconfiguration."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q365","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring Metrics (KPIs)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"Leadership wants to measure SOC improvements after a new SIEM deployment. Which metric BEST reflects operational detection performance?","options":[{"text":"Mean time to detect and mean time to respond measured with consistent incident criteria","correct":true,"why":"MTTD and MTTR are practical SOC effectiveness measures when defined consistently and tracked over time."},{"text":"True-positive rate for prioritized detections tracked alongside analyst review volume","correct":false,"why":"True-positive rate and review volume reflect detection quality and workload, not the operational speed metrics leadership specifically wants after the SIEM deployment."},{"text":"Case backlog age by severity compared across identical reporting periods and business units","correct":false,"why":"Case backlog age reflects workload management, not the detection and response speed the new SIEM deployment is meant to improve."},{"text":"Coverage growth across log sources and detections mapped to critical business systems","correct":false,"why":"Coverage growth reflects visibility expansion, not the actual operational detection and response performance leadership wants measured."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q366","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Threat Hunting (Hypothesis)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A hunter suspects credential dumping. Which telemetry MOST directly supports the hypothesis?","options":[{"text":"Endpoint evidence of LSASS access suspicious memory reads and related tool behaviors","correct":true,"why":"Credential dumping often touches LSASS or similar secrets stores."},{"text":"Kerberos service ticket requests that spike from a server handling many user sessions","correct":false,"why":"A spike in Kerberos ticket requests from a busy server reflects normal authentication load, not the memory-access behavior specific to credential dumping."},{"text":"Privileged logons followed by SAM or SECURITY hive access from an administrative shell","correct":false,"why":"Privileged logons followed by SAM/SECURITY hive access is a plausible credential-dumping indicator but is a different technique than the LSASS memory access being hypothesized."},{"text":"Process launches of common archive utilities on systems with many cached credentials","correct":false,"why":"Archive utility launches on systems with cached credentials could support exfiltration staging but don't directly confirm the memory-access technique the hunter suspects."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q367","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Data Protection (PII in Logs)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"Developers log full customer SSNs for troubleshooting. Compliance flags this as high risk. What is the BEST remediation?","options":[{"text":"Mask or scrub sensitive fields minimize what is logged and enforce access and retention controls","correct":true,"why":"Follow least-data principles avoid logging sensitive data scrub or mask it and enforce access controls and retention policies."},{"text":"Tokenize the field before writing logs and restrict detokenization to approved support workflows","correct":false,"why":"Tokenizing the field still requires storing and reversing tokens for support, which doesn't address the core issue of full SSNs being unnecessarily logged in the first place."},{"text":"Move detailed troubleshooting logs to a separate repository with tighter reviewer access","correct":false,"why":"Moving logs to a separate repository with tighter access still retains the full SSNs in logs rather than eliminating unnecessary sensitive data collection."},{"text":"Replace full identifiers with hashed values and log cleartext only during break-glass cases","correct":false,"why":"Hashing values while still logging cleartext during break-glass cases still permits full SSNs to appear in logs under certain conditions, which the remediation should avoid entirely."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q368","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Endpoint vs Network (Encrypted LM)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"Lateral movement uses encrypted channels, and network IDS alerts drop. Which monitoring source is MOST reliable for detection?","options":[{"text":"Host telemetry focused on process creation remote execution and credential-related behavior","correct":true,"why":"Encrypted traffic reduces payload visibility while endpoint telemetry captures the behavior of tools and remote execution mechanisms."},{"text":"Network flow analysis that highlights unusual east-west session volume and service patterns","correct":false,"why":"Network flow analysis shows volume and connection patterns but can't reveal the specific process and credential-related behaviors happening on the host."},{"text":"Authentication logs that show remote logon types and account reuse across hosts","correct":false,"why":"Authentication logs show logon types and reuse but don't capture the process-level execution details needed to confirm the specific lateral movement technique."},{"text":"Server message and remote management logs tied to lateral administration protocols in use","correct":false,"why":"Remote administration protocol logs show connection activity but don't provide the process creation and credential access detail that host telemetry offers."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q369","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Log Pipelines (Reliability)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"During peak hours, the SIEM drops logs due to ingestion limits, causing blind spots. Which design BEST improves reliability?","options":[{"text":"Use resilient queues and scalable collectors with prioritization for critical log sources","correct":true,"why":"Queues or brokers and scalable collectors prevent drops during bursts prioritize critical logs and add resilience to pipelines."},{"text":"Shard collectors by source class so bursts from one domain do not starve the others","correct":false,"why":"Sharding collectors by source class helps distribute load but doesn't itself add the queuing and buffering needed to prevent drops during traffic bursts."},{"text":"Pre-filter verbose sources upstream and forward summaries during the highest load periods","correct":false,"why":"Pre-filtering and summarizing verbose sources reduces data volume but risks losing detail needed for investigations rather than actually preventing ingestion drops."},{"text":"Move low-priority analytics to delayed processing so search and ingestion compete less directly","correct":false,"why":"Delaying low-priority analytics processing doesn't address the root ingestion bottleneck causing logs to be dropped during peak load."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q370","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Detection Engineering (Rule Logic)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A rule alerts on “10 failed logins” but triggers constantly for shared kiosks. What is the BEST rule improvement?","options":[{"text":"Add user host and follow-on context so failures matter only with higher-risk supporting signals","correct":true,"why":"Improve signal with context and correlation."},{"text":"Set separate thresholds for kiosks remote access systems and privileged account populations","correct":false,"why":"Setting separate thresholds for different populations helps somewhat but doesn't add the broader contextual correlation that distinguishes malicious failures from routine kiosk noise."},{"text":"Correlate failures with a later success from a new device or unusual source location","correct":false,"why":"Correlating failures with a later new-device success is a useful signal but narrower than adding the fuller set of contextual factors that reduce false positives across all failure causes."},{"text":"Suppress expected service-desk and training-lab systems from the rule during business hours","correct":false,"why":"Suppressing known service-desk and lab systems only addresses specific known-noisy sources rather than adding the general contextual signal needed for the rule broadly."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q371","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Incident Workflow (Evidence Preservation)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A host is suspected of active compromise. You want to contain quickly while preserving evidence. Which action BEST aligns?","options":[{"text":"Use EDR containment while keeping the system available for volatile evidence collection","correct":true,"why":"Contain with minimal disruption and preserve volatile evidence."},{"text":"Disable the suspected account first and then triage the host after live access is restored","correct":false,"why":"Disabling the account first still allows the host itself to remain compromised and active while waiting to restore live access before triaging."},{"text":"Block the host at the network edge and begin remote log and memory collection immediately","correct":false,"why":"Blocking at the network edge is a valid containment step, but starting remote collection immediately without addressing containment on the host itself risks continued activity in the interim."},{"text":"Quarantine the system to a restricted VLAN that still permits response tooling and telemetry","correct":false,"why":"Quarantining to a restricted VLAN while still allowing many tools access is close, but the EDR-based containment approach more directly balances quick isolation with evidence preservation."}],"sub":"3.2"},{"id":"q372","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Honeypots/Honeytokens","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"Security places a fake database credential in a monitored location. Any use triggers an alert. What is this called?","options":[{"text":"Honeytoken a decoy artifact meant to generate a high-signal alert when used","correct":true,"why":"Honeytokens are decoys that should never be used legitimately producing high-signal alerts when accessed."},{"text":"Canary account a controlled identity created to detect misuse in privileged workflows","correct":false,"why":"A canary account is a real, usable identity meant to detect misuse of privileged access, not a fake credential specifically planted as bait like the one described."},{"text":"Deception credential a seeded secret intended to expose unauthorized access attempts","correct":false,"why":"Describing this generically as a 'deception credential' misses the specific, standard term (honeytoken) used for this exact decoy artifact technique."},{"text":"Synthetic indicator a fabricated value inserted to validate alerting and pipeline fidelity","correct":false,"why":"A synthetic indicator implies testing pipeline fidelity, not specifically serving as bait to detect unauthorized use of a fake credential."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q373","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Program Strategy (Defense in Depth)","source":"CySA_Day_8.html","q":"A team claims continuous monitoring is unnecessary if controls are “preventive.” What is the BEST response?","options":[{"text":"Monitoring confirms control effectiveness finds misuse and catches failures prevention misses","correct":true,"why":"Prevention fails is bypassed or is misconfigured."},{"text":"Monitoring provides compensating visibility when coverage varies across systems and workflows","correct":false,"why":"Framing monitoring as merely compensating for inconsistent coverage understates its core role in confirming whether preventive controls are actually working at all."},{"text":"Monitoring shortens dwell time by surfacing behavior changes after controls are bypassed","correct":false,"why":"Shortening dwell time is a valuable benefit of monitoring, but it doesn't capture the broader point that monitoring also validates control effectiveness and catches failures prevention misses."},{"text":"Monitoring supplies feedback needed to tune prevention rules as tactics and environments change","correct":false,"why":"Tuning prevention rules is a downstream benefit of monitoring feedback, but doesn't capture the more fundamental point that monitoring itself catches what preventive controls fail to stop."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q374","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Segmentation)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, ransomware spread from a user VLAN to server subnets using SMB/RDP. Which control MOST reduces blast radius without breaking all workflows?","options":[{"text":"Enforce zone-to-zone allowlists, limit remote admin paths to hardened jump points, and log exception traffic.","correct":true,"why":"Segmentation + controlled admin paths limits lateral movement and restricts high-risk protocols to monitored choke points."},{"text":"Rotate privileged secrets, require phishing-resistant MFA, and review failed logons from administrative groups.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating secrets and requiring stronger MFA addresses authentication security but doesn't restrict the actual SMB/RDP paths that let the ransomware spread across subnets."},{"text":"Disable legacy file-sharing features, review lateral-tool artifacts, and hunt for recent service-creation events.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling legacy file-sharing and hunting for service-creation events helps investigate and reduce some exposure but doesn't establish the zone-based path restrictions needed to contain blast radius broadly."},{"text":"Quarantine affected endpoints, preserve volatile evidence, and compare encryption scope across impacted business units.","correct":false,"why":"Quarantining affected endpoints and comparing encryption scope addresses the current incident's aftermath but doesn't establish the ongoing segmentation control to prevent future lateral spread."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q375","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Logging & Monitoring (SIEM)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"An attacker cleared local Windows logs. What is the BEST way to reconstruct the timeline?","options":[{"text":"Rebuild the sequence from remote collectors and corroborate with endpoint, DNS, proxy, and firewall records.","correct":true,"why":"Centralized logs and other sources remain available even if local logs are cleared, enabling defensible timelines."},{"text":"Capture volatile artifacts from the suspect workstation and compare running services against the gold image baseline.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing volatile artifacts and comparing services to baseline can help investigate the host itself but doesn't reconstruct the broader timeline once local logs are gone."},{"text":"Review time-sync drift and ingestion latency to explain gaps before concluding events were intentionally removed.","correct":false,"why":"Reviewing time-sync drift and ingestion latency addresses a different potential cause of gaps, not the actual situation where logs were deliberately cleared."},{"text":"Check case notes and maintenance windows to separate analyst activity from adversary actions on the affected host.","correct":false,"why":"Checking case notes and maintenance windows helps rule out benign explanations but doesn't itself rebuild the timeline from independent external sources."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q376","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Beaconing)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, proxy logs show HTTPS connections every 60 seconds to a newly registered domain with consistent sizes. What is MOST likely?","options":[{"text":"Periodic command-and-control traffic; tie the session to the parent process, account, and neighboring host activity.","correct":true,"why":"Periodic, uniform connections to new domains are common C2 patterns; validate with process-to-connection mapping."},{"text":"Routine software updates; validate signed binaries, approved vendor endpoints, and change-ticket timing first.","correct":false,"why":"Routine software updates wouldn't typically connect to a newly registered domain at strict 60-second intervals with consistent packet sizes."},{"text":"Federation token refreshes; compare identity logs, device posture, and conditional-access events for alignment.","correct":false,"why":"Federation token refreshes are tied to identity and access events, not the pattern of periodic HTTPS beacon-like connections to a new external domain."},{"text":"Load-balancer health checks; review service ownership, probe cadence, and expected destination inventories.","correct":false,"why":"Load-balancer health checks target known, expected internal or approved service endpoints, not a newly registered external domain."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q377","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Management (Prioritization)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"You have 30 “High” CVSS findings. Only 5 are internet-facing on mission-critical apps with active exploitation. BEST prioritization?","options":[{"text":"Rank work by exploit path, business impact, exposure, and live-threat pressure instead of severity labels alone.","correct":true,"why":"Risk-based prioritization blends severity with business impact, exposure, and active exploitation intelligence."},{"text":"Patch every externally reachable finding first, then address the remaining issues strictly by descending score.","correct":false,"why":"Patching every externally reachable finding first regardless of exploitation status wastes effort on issues that may pose less real risk than the actively exploited ones."},{"text":"Close anything with a public proof of concept before considering whether the asset actually matters to operations.","correct":false,"why":"Focusing only on public proof-of-concept availability without considering whether the asset is actually critical to operations risks misallocating remediation effort."},{"text":"Sort by scanner confidence and ticket age, since older findings usually present the highest real-world risk.","correct":false,"why":"Sorting by scanner confidence and ticket age doesn't reflect actual risk; older findings aren't inherently higher risk than newer, actively exploited ones."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q378","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR (Containment)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, eDR confirms ransomware-like encryption behavior and shadow copy deletion. BEST immediate action?","options":[{"text":"Sever the affected system from the network through host isolation while preserving power and evidence for scoping.","correct":true,"why":"Containment stops spread while keeping artifacts for scoping/root-cause; eradication and recovery follow."},{"text":"Disable file sharing across the estate immediately, then force reauthentication to break any active spread paths.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling file sharing estate-wide and forcing reauthentication is broader and more disruptive than isolating the specific affected host while investigation continues."},{"text":"Restore the most critical servers first so business operations resume before root-cause analysis begins.","correct":false,"why":"Restoring critical servers before completing root-cause analysis risks reintroducing the same vulnerability or reinfecting freshly restored systems."},{"text":"Shut down the infected endpoint to stop encryption quickly, then begin collecting disk artifacts afterward.","correct":false,"why":"Shutting down the endpoint immediately would stop encryption but also destroys volatile evidence needed for scoping and root-cause analysis."}],"sub":"3.2"},{"id":"q379","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"IAM (Authorization)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A user can access an application but sees “403 Forbidden” when requesting admin endpoints. Which concept BEST explains this?","options":[{"text":"The identity check passed, but the account lacks the rights required for that protected function.","correct":true,"why":"403 indicates the user is identified but not permitted to perform that action—an authorization control."},{"text":"The request was rejected because the browser failed to present a valid session cookie to the application tier.","correct":false,"why":"A missing or invalid session cookie would typically produce an authentication failure (401), not a 403 indicating the user is recognized but lacks sufficient permission."},{"text":"The action was blocked because the client device no longer met health requirements defined by access policy.","correct":false,"why":"Device health/posture policy violations are a device-compliance concept, not the same as an authenticated user lacking the specific rights for an admin endpoint."},{"text":"The transaction failed because the backend service could not impersonate the caller to the downstream API.","correct":false,"why":"Backend impersonation failures are a service-to-service delegation issue, not what a straightforward 403 response to an authenticated user's own request represents."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q380","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Security (Firewall Policy)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A broad allow rule sits above a narrow deny for a malicious IP range, and traffic is still allowed. Why?","options":[{"text":"The broader match is evaluated first, so the later restriction is not reached during policy evaluation.","correct":true,"why":"Many firewalls process top-down; first match wins."},{"text":"The deny object is malformed, so any overlapping permit statements automatically take precedence by design.","correct":false,"why":"A malformed deny object wouldn't cause a properly formed, unrelated allow rule listed earlier to take precedence; the real cause is rule order, not malformed syntax."},{"text":"The destination range is cached by the firewall, preventing policy updates from affecting current traffic flows.","correct":false,"why":"Destination caching doesn't override rule evaluation order; the actual explanation is that the broader allow rule is matched before the deny rule is reached."},{"text":"The rule compiles correctly, but encrypted sessions bypass address-based filtering until certificate inspection is enabled.","correct":false,"why":"Encrypted sessions bypassing address-based filtering isn't relevant here; the deny rule targets IP addresses, which apply regardless of encryption, and the real issue is rule order."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q381","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Cloud Security","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A public cloud storage bucket is accidentally set to world-readable. BEST immediate mitigation?","options":[{"text":"Remove anonymous exposure immediately, tighten the resource policy, and review access records to size the leak.","correct":true,"why":"Fix the misconfiguration first, then assess impact via logs and enforce preventive controls."},{"text":"Rotate all cloud credentials at once, then rebuild the bucket so inherited permissions cannot reappear.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating all cloud credentials and rebuilding the bucket doesn't address the actual root cause (misconfigured public access) as directly as fixing the policy and reviewing access first."},{"text":"Move the dataset behind private networking controls and rely on routing isolation as the primary fix for the exposure.","correct":false,"why":"Moving data behind private networking is a good longer-term step but doesn't immediately fix the current world-readable exposure or assess what may have already leaked."},{"text":"Delete the affected object store and restore from backup to guarantee no public metadata remains accessible.","correct":false,"why":"Deleting and restoring the object store is a drastic, unnecessary step compared to simply correcting the misconfigured access policy and reviewing exposure."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q382","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Container Security","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A container is running as root and can write to the host filesystem via a mounted path. BEST hardening?","options":[{"text":"Drop privileges inside the workload, minimize runtime capabilities, and constrain mounts to only what is required.","correct":true,"why":"Least privilege for containers: non-root, minimal capabilities, restrictive mounts, and policy enforcement reduce breakout risk."},{"text":"Increase image scanning frequency and sign releases so unapproved packages cannot be introduced into deployment flows.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing image scanning and signing releases addresses supply-chain risk, not the specific runtime misconfiguration of running as root with a writable host mount."},{"text":"Place the orchestrator API behind a bastion host and require step-up authentication for cluster administration.","correct":false,"why":"Bastion host and step-up auth for the orchestrator API protects cluster administration access, not the container's own excessive runtime privileges and mount permissions."},{"text":"Rotate node credentials and segregate tenant namespaces so east-west traffic cannot traverse the overlay network.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating node credentials and segmenting namespaces addresses lateral network risk, not the container's own root privileges and host filesystem write access."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q383","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (SQLi)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"An API concatenates untrusted input into SQL strings. BEST prevention?","options":[{"text":"Use bound parameters so supplied values stay data, paired with validation and restricted database rights.","correct":true,"why":"Parameterized queries prevent user input from being interpreted as code; validation and least privilege reduce impact."},{"text":"Encode output in the browser context and add a strict policy header to reduce script execution opportunities.","correct":false,"why":"Output encoding and CSP headers address cross-site scripting in browser contexts, not the SQL injection risk from unparameterized queries described here."},{"text":"Add per-user rate limits and anomaly alerts so repeated malformed requests are blocked before the database layer.","correct":false,"why":"Rate limiting and anomaly alerts might slow down repeated attack attempts but don't prevent a single malicious request from still being interpreted as SQL code."},{"text":"Move secrets to a vault and rotate the service account so compromised repository history cannot expose access.","correct":false,"why":"Moving secrets to a vault addresses credential exposure, not the actual SQL injection vulnerability from concatenating untrusted input into queries."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q384","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (XSS)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A page reflects user input into HTML without encoding. BEST mitigation?","options":[{"text":"Render untrusted content with the proper contextual escaping rules and add policy-based browser safeguards.","correct":true,"why":"Output encoding is primary; CSP adds defense-in-depth."},{"text":"Adopt bound SQL parameters and stronger database roles so user input cannot alter backend query structure.","correct":false,"why":"Parameterized SQL queries prevent SQL injection, not the reflected XSS vulnerability described here, which stems from unencoded HTML output."},{"text":"Require anti-forgery tokens and origin validation so cross-site requests cannot trigger state-changing actions.","correct":false,"why":"Anti-forgery tokens and origin validation defend against CSRF, a different vulnerability class than the reflected XSS caused by unencoded output."},{"text":"Restrict server-side fetch destinations and metadata access so backend requests cannot pivot internally.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting server-side fetch destinations defends against SSRF, not the client-side reflected XSS vulnerability from unencoded user input in HTML."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q385","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Threat Hunting (Process Lineage)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, WINWORD.EXE spawns PowerShell.exe, then rundll32.exe with encoded arguments and outbound connections. What is the BEST triage step?","options":[{"text":"Trace the parent-child chain, inspect the encoded invocation, and map the child process to its network activity.","correct":true,"why":"Lineage + command line + network mapping quickly confirms macro/LOLBAS activity and helps scope."},{"text":"Check whether the same user recently authenticated from a second host, indicating possible token or ticket misuse.","correct":false,"why":"Checking for authentication from a second host addresses a different concern (credential/ticket misuse) rather than directly triaging this specific process chain and its network activity."},{"text":"Review DHCP leases and switch telemetry to identify where the workstation was physically connected at the time.","correct":false,"why":"DHCP and switch telemetry show physical network location, not the process behavior and network connections needed to triage this specific malicious execution chain."},{"text":"Enable deeper packet capture on the user segment to compare this host against normal office productivity traffic.","correct":false,"why":"Broader packet capture across the segment is a reasonable follow-up but doesn't provide the immediate process lineage and command-line detail needed for fast triage."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q386","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"TTPs (Credential Access)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A process attempts to open many handles to LSASS.exe and read its memory. What is the MOST likely objective?","options":[{"text":"Harvesting authentication material from memory for reuse, escalation, or movement across additional systems.","correct":true,"why":"LSASS access is a classic credential dumping indicator; correlate with privileges and subsequent auth events."},{"text":"Enumerating open shares so a worm can choose the most efficient path for remote file replication.","correct":false,"why":"Enumerating open shares for lateral file replication doesn't involve reading LSASS memory; that's a different reconnaissance technique unrelated to credential harvesting from memory."},{"text":"Disabling endpoint visibility by modifying protected logging services and local audit configurations.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling logging services would target different system components, not involve opening handles to and reading memory from LSASS specifically."},{"text":"Preparing the workstation for encryption by deleting restore data and staging a ransom message on disk.","correct":false,"why":"Preparing for ransomware encryption involves deleting backups and staging ransom notes, not opening handles to read LSASS process memory."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q387","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"BCP/DR","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A critical system must be restored within 2 hours and can tolerate 15 minutes of data loss. Which metrics do those values represent?","options":[{"text":"Two hours defines the service restoration target, while fifteen minutes defines the tolerated data rollback window.","correct":true,"why":"RTO = time to restore service."},{"text":"Two hours is the maximum outage before declaring disaster, and fifteen minutes is the acceptable notification delay.","correct":false,"why":"These values don't represent a disaster declaration threshold or notification delay; they specifically define the restoration time target and tolerable data loss window."},{"text":"Two hours measures the backup interval, and fifteen minutes measures how quickly failover must begin after detection.","correct":false,"why":"These values aren't about backup interval or failover initiation speed; they define the overall restoration time target and the acceptable data loss window instead."},{"text":"Two hours reflects the time to investigate root cause, and fifteen minutes reflects the time to reimage a host.","correct":false,"why":"These values don't represent root-cause investigation or reimaging time; they specifically define the service restoration target and the tolerable data loss window."}],"sub":"3.3"},{"id":"q388","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Digital Forensics (Chain of Custody)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, evidence may be used legally. What MOST supports admissibility and integrity?","options":[{"text":"Document custody, preserve hashes, record every handler, and secure the item whenever possession changes.","correct":true,"why":"Chain of custody + hashing + controlled access demonstrates integrity and accountability."},{"text":"Write a detailed analyst narrative first so later technical handling steps can be aligned to the response timeline.","correct":false,"why":"Writing an analyst narrative first doesn't itself establish or preserve the technical chain-of-custody documentation required for legal admissibility."},{"text":"Acquire volatile evidence before disk evidence because courts typically prioritize the most recent artifacts.","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing volatile evidence collection first is generally good forensic practice, but it isn't what specifically establishes legal admissibility — chain of custody and hashing do."},{"text":"Store the evidence with the incident ticket so operational staff can reference it during restoration activities.","correct":false,"why":"Storing evidence with an operational incident ticket for staff reference doesn't provide the controlled custody and access documentation needed for legal admissibility."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q389","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Scanning (Credentialed Scans)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A scan shows few findings, but patch/config posture is unknown. BEST improvement?","options":[{"text":"Use authenticated inspection so the scanner can verify local package, patch, and configuration state directly.","correct":true,"why":"Credentialed scans provide local evidence and reduce blind spots from remote-only checks."},{"text":"Increase the scan frequency so timing gaps do not allow recently disclosed weaknesses to evade detection.","correct":false,"why":"Increasing scan frequency doesn't provide the local, authenticated visibility needed to actually see patch and configuration state; it just repeats the same limited remote-only check more often."},{"text":"Run the scanner from multiple network segments to improve banner collection from filtered internal services.","correct":false,"why":"Scanning from multiple network segments still relies on external, remote-only visibility and doesn't query the host's actual local package or patch state."},{"text":"Lower the detection threshold so informational findings expose configuration weaknesses that severe checks missed.","correct":false,"why":"Lowering detection thresholds surfaces more informational findings but doesn't provide the authenticated local access needed to actually verify patch and config posture."}],"sub":"2.1"},{"id":"q390","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Rules of Engagement)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, client needs clarity on allowed methods, scope, and sensitive data handling. Which document BEST defines this?","options":[{"text":"The authorization package that sets boundaries, approved techniques, timing, and data-handling constraints.","correct":true,"why":"RoE formalizes authorization and boundaries for safe, agreed testing."},{"text":"The final report, because it becomes the formal record of what testers were allowed to do during execution.","correct":false,"why":"The final report documents what happened after testing; it doesn't itself define or authorize the boundaries and permitted methods before testing begins."},{"text":"The vulnerability register, because any tested asset must be prelisted there before reconnaissance can begin.","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability register tracks known findings; it doesn't establish the authorized scope, methods, and data-handling rules for a penetration test."},{"text":"The service-level agreement, because it governs acceptable downtime and therefore all security testing scope.","correct":false,"why":"A service-level agreement governs uptime and service commitments; it doesn't define the specific security testing scope, methods, or data-handling rules."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q391","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network (NAT Attribution)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, outbound traffic uses PAT. You see a suspicious public connection. What data is MOST needed to identify the internal host?","options":[{"text":"The translation records that pair inside address and source port with the observed public tuple over time.","correct":true,"why":"PAT hides many hosts behind one IP; port mappings over time map sessions back to the source host."},{"text":"Endpoint command history showing which browser or service opened a connection near the observed timestamp.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint command history could help but isn't the specific data needed to map a public IP:port session back through PAT translation to the source host."},{"text":"DHCP lease history alone, because a single internal address is sufficient to determine the originator behind PAT.","correct":false,"why":"DHCP lease history alone doesn't resolve which specific internal host used a shared public IP at a given time under PAT; the actual mapping data is needed."},{"text":"Proxy logs only, since outbound address sharing does not affect user attribution when web filtering is enabled.","correct":false,"why":"Proxy logs alone don't resolve which specific internal host initiated a given outbound session when many hosts share one public IP under PAT."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q392","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Monitoring (IDS Placement)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, IDS watches only the internet edge. Lateral movement is suspected internally. What is the BEST improvement?","options":[{"text":"Add visibility at internal transit points so movement between trusted segments is observable and attributable.","correct":true,"why":"Edge-only monitoring misses internal lateral movement; internal visibility at key segments is required."},{"text":"Push the edge signatures into prevention mode so blocked internet traffic cannot establish the initial foothold.","correct":false,"why":"Pushing edge signatures to prevention mode only strengthens perimeter blocking; it doesn't provide visibility into lateral movement already occurring between internal segments."},{"text":"Increase endpoint alert severity for remote administration tools so later movement is inferred from host telemetry alone.","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on endpoint alert severity for remote tools provides partial signal but doesn't establish the network-level internal visibility needed to directly observe lateral movement."},{"text":"Mirror only the server farm uplinks, since user-to-user pivots are less relevant than north-south traffic paths.","correct":false,"why":"Mirroring only server farm uplinks would miss the user-to-user lateral movement paths that are actually relevant to the suspected internal activity."}],"sub":"1.8"},{"id":"q393","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Malware (Sandbox Evasion)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A file detonates cleanly in a sandbox but later behaves maliciously on a real endpoint. Why?","options":[{"text":"The sample likely withheld behavior until real-user context, timing, or environment checks were satisfied.","correct":true,"why":"Evasion and delayed execution can cause sandbox false negatives; correlate with endpoint behavior and telemetry."},{"text":"The sandbox failed because encrypted traffic cannot be inspected without installing a trusted root certificate.","correct":false,"why":"TLS inspection requiring a trusted root certificate is a general network monitoring limitation, not specifically why a sandbox detonation showed clean behavior that later turned malicious on a real endpoint."},{"text":"The file probably became malicious only after download, indicating corruption by the endpoint storage subsystem.","correct":false,"why":"Storage subsystem corruption wouldn't cause a file to become malicious after download; this doesn't explain the sandbox-clean-but-endpoint-malicious pattern."},{"text":"The behavior was missed because the detonation environment restricted outbound traffic in a way the sample checked for.","correct":false,"why":"Restricted outbound traffic in the sandbox is a plausible evasion trigger, but the broader explanation covers withheld behavior from any environment or timing check, not just network restrictions specifically."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q394","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Secure Protocols)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A legacy app uses Telnet and FTP for admin and transfers. BEST security change?","options":[{"text":"Move administrative and file-transfer functions to encrypted protocols and tightly controlled management paths.","correct":true,"why":"SSH/SFTP provide encrypted channels, preventing credential capture common with Telnet/FTP."},{"text":"Keep the legacy services but tunnel them through a VPN so the plaintext risk is removed without changing tooling.","correct":false,"why":"Tunneling Telnet/FTP through a VPN still leaves the same unencrypted, weak-authentication protocols in use at the endpoint, rather than replacing them with secure ones."},{"text":"Retain the current design and rotate passwords more frequently because credential freshness offsets protocol weakness.","correct":false,"why":"Rotating passwords more frequently doesn't address that Telnet and FTP transmit credentials in cleartext; the protocol weakness itself remains unresolved."},{"text":"Expose the services only on an internal VLAN since unencrypted administration is acceptable when it stays on-premises.","correct":false,"why":"Keeping unencrypted administration internal-only still leaves cleartext credentials exposed to anyone with internal network access, which doesn't resolve the fundamental weakness."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q395","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Secrets)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, developers store API keys in code repositories. BEST remediation?","options":[{"text":"Store secrets in a managed vault, rotate exposed values, and add controls that stop future commits of sensitive data.","correct":true,"why":"Secrets belong in vaults with rotation and least privilege; repos need scanning to prevent recurrence."},{"text":"Require developers to encrypt configuration files locally before commits so repository history contains protected keys.","correct":false,"why":"Encrypting configuration files locally before committing still leaves keys embedded in the repository history in some encrypted form, rather than removing secrets from source control."},{"text":"Move the repositories to a private network segment because exposure occurs only when source control is internet-facing.","correct":false,"why":"Moving repositories to a private network segment doesn't change that secrets are stored in the repository; internal exposure risk (e.g., insider access) still remains."},{"text":"Replace all API keys with long-lived certificates in code, since certificate material is safer to keep in repositories.","correct":false,"why":"Replacing keys with long-lived certificates still stores long-lived sensitive credential material directly in code, rather than moving secrets to a managed vault."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q396","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Volatility)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A live system may have memory-resident malware. What evidence should be collected FIRST?","options":[{"text":"Capture memory and active connection state first, before any action can erase what only exists on the live system.","correct":true,"why":"Order of volatility: memory and live connections vanish on reboot/shutdown—capture them early."},{"text":"Acquire the disk image immediately, because persistent evidence is more complete and can reproduce volatile state later.","correct":false,"why":"Acquiring the disk image first risks losing memory-resident and connection-state evidence that only exists while the system remains running."},{"text":"Restart the system into a trusted environment so malicious memory artifacts cannot interfere with collection tools.","correct":false,"why":"Restarting into a trusted environment destroys the exact volatile memory state that needs to be captured before any interruption occurs."},{"text":"Export event logs before anything else, since they provide the broadest timeline and are least affected by shutdown.","correct":false,"why":"Exporting event logs first is useful but doesn't capture the memory-resident artifacts that are lost the moment the system reboots or shuts down."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q397","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authorization (Zero Trust)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, which statement BEST represents zero trust network access?","options":[{"text":"Access decisions are re-evaluated continually using identity, device, and context, with narrowly scoped entitlements.","correct":true,"why":"Zero trust removes implicit trust based on network location and enforces continuous, contextual access decisions."},{"text":"Users remain broadly connected after sign-in, but sensitive actions prompt additional verification when risk rises.","correct":false,"why":"Remaining broadly connected after initial sign-in with only occasional step-up checks still reflects implicit trust based on the initial authentication, not zero trust's continuous re-evaluation."},{"text":"All remote access must traverse a full-tunnel VPN so central inspection can determine which internal paths to allow.","correct":false,"why":"Requiring a full-tunnel VPN for all access still relies on network-based trust rather than the identity- and context-based continuous evaluation zero trust requires."},{"text":"Resources are protected primarily by network location, with stronger checks applied only on high-value subnets.","correct":false,"why":"Protecting resources primarily by network location with stronger checks only on high-value subnets is exactly the implicit network-based trust model zero trust is designed to remove."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q398","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Virtualization Security","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A VM host shares management network with tenant traffic. BEST hardening?","options":[{"text":"Isolate the administrative plane from tenant paths and restrict it with strong authentication and audit controls.","correct":true,"why":"Management plane isolation and strong access controls reduce hypervisor compromise risk and lateral movement."},{"text":"Place all virtual machines on a common trunk so east-west monitoring can inspect both management and workload traffic.","correct":false,"why":"Placing all VMs on a common trunk for unified monitoring actually increases exposure by keeping management and tenant traffic on the same shared path."},{"text":"Rely on host-based firewalls inside each guest, since separating the hypervisor network adds little practical security.","correct":false,"why":"Relying only on host-based firewalls inside each guest doesn't protect the hypervisor's own management plane from being reached via the shared network."},{"text":"Expose management services through the same load balancer as tenant workloads to simplify certificate handling.","correct":false,"why":"Exposing management services through the same load balancer as tenant workloads increases exposure of sensitive administrative interfaces rather than isolating them."}],"sub":"1.7"},{"id":"q399","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Threat Intel (IOC vs TTP)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, attackers recompile malware frequently and bypass hash blocks. BEST detection improvement?","options":[{"text":"Detect stable adversary behaviors across execution, persistence, and communications instead of relying on static artifacts.","correct":true,"why":"TTP-based detections are more resilient than static IOCs, especially against polymorphism and rapid changes."},{"text":"Expand the hash blocklist daily so newly compiled binaries are covered before analysts can study their behavior.","correct":false,"why":"Expanding the hash blocklist daily still relies on static file signatures, which recompiled binaries will continue to evade regardless of how often the list updates."},{"text":"Prioritize file reputation feeds because malware families usually preserve enough code structure for signature matching.","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing file reputation feeds still depends on recognizable code structure, which frequent recompilation is specifically designed to defeat."},{"text":"Use stronger perimeter deny lists, since recompilation mainly affects inbound delivery and not post-execution activity.","correct":false,"why":"Stronger perimeter deny lists only address delivery; they don't help detect the post-execution behavior that persists even after recompiled malware gets past initial defenses."}],"sub":"1.2"},{"id":"q400","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Incident Response (Eradication)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"After containment, what is the BEST eradication step to prevent re-entry?","options":[{"text":"Eliminate the foothold and persistence, rotate exposed identities, remediate the weakness, and verify the result.","correct":true,"why":"Eradication is root-cause removal + credential hygiene + patching + validation, not just restoring systems."},{"text":"Restore from known-good backups first, because a clean operating image is enough to remove any chance of re-entry.","correct":false,"why":"Restoring from backups alone doesn't remove the original attack vector or exposed credentials that let the attacker in, risking the same re-entry path."},{"text":"Close the incident once monitoring quiets down, then schedule patching during the next regular maintenance cycle.","correct":false,"why":"Closing the incident once monitoring quiets down and deferring patching to the next cycle leaves the underlying weakness exploitable in the meantime."},{"text":"Block the observed indicators permanently, since successful containment means the underlying access path no longer matters.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking observed indicators permanently doesn't address the underlying access path or exposed credentials the attacker used, which could still enable re-entry through other means."}],"sub":"3.2"},{"id":"q401","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Web Security (WAF)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A web app is targeted by injection attempts and needs HTTP-level blocking. BEST control?","options":[{"text":"Place an application-aware filter in front of the site to inspect requests and enforce attack-specific protections.","correct":true,"why":"WAFs operate at the application layer to block web attack patterns like injection and protocol misuse."},{"text":"Deploy a network intrusion sensor at the perimeter so malicious web payloads are blocked before reaching the server.","correct":false,"why":"A network intrusion sensor at the perimeter inspects traffic generically but lacks the application-layer understanding needed to recognize web-specific attack patterns like injection."},{"text":"Harden browser policy headers, since client-enforced controls are the most direct way to stop hostile requests.","correct":false,"why":"Client-enforced browser policy headers can't be relied upon since an attacker controls their own request tooling and won't respect them."},{"text":"Use endpoint application control on the web server, because HTTP abuse is best prevented by restricting local binaries.","correct":false,"why":"Endpoint application control restricts which binaries run on the server; it doesn't inspect or block malicious HTTP requests themselves."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q402","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Wireless Security","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, company wants per-user Wi-Fi authentication with central control (not WPA2-PSK). BEST solution?","options":[{"text":"Use enterprise wireless authentication with centralized identity-backed access decisions for each individual user.","correct":true,"why":"Enterprise Wi-Fi uses 802.1X/RADIUS to authenticate users individually and apply policy-based access."},{"text":"Adopt a stronger shared passphrase standard, because rotating the key often provides equivalent accountability.","correct":false,"why":"A stronger shared passphrase, even rotated often, is still one credential shared by everyone, without the per-user accountability and centralized control the requirement calls for."},{"text":"Require captive-portal sign-in before network access, since browser-based identity prompts replace 802.1X controls.","correct":false,"why":"A captive portal only gates initial access via a browser prompt; it doesn't provide the per-user, policy-based 802.1X authentication needed for ongoing centralized control."},{"text":"Hide the SSID and filter device addresses, as those measures allow centrally managed user-level authentication.","correct":false,"why":"Hiding the SSID and filtering device addresses are weak, easily bypassed measures that don't provide real per-user identity-based authentication or centralized control."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q403","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS Process Mgmt (Linux Persistence)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A Linux user’s ~/.bashrc is modified to run a binary at login, and a user crontab is added. What does this MOST indicate?","options":[{"text":"Startup hooks in the shell profile and scheduled user tasks are being used to survive reboots and logins.","correct":true,"why":"Attackers commonly persist by editing shell profiles and adding cron jobs for recurring execution."},{"text":"A memory-only implant is executing without persistence, so the observed files are likely unrelated user customization.","correct":false,"why":"The scenario describes concrete file-based changes (bashrc, crontab), which directly indicates persistence mechanisms rather than a memory-only implant with no persistence."},{"text":"The account is preparing for privilege escalation by replacing PAM modules, which commonly appears first in shell history.","correct":false,"why":"PAM module replacement is a different technique aimed at credential capture or backdoor access, not what bashrc edits and crontab entries specifically indicate."},{"text":"The changes mainly indicate data staging, because cron is usually chosen to compress files before exfiltration.","correct":false,"why":"Cron jobs used for data staging would typically involve compression or transfer commands, not the login-triggered binary execution pattern described here."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q404","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Email Security (Phishing)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, email urges users to open a macro-enabled “invoice.” BEST preventive control combination?","options":[{"text":"Layer delivery filtering with detonation, script-control restrictions, and awareness measures that reduce user execution.","correct":true,"why":"Layered controls reduce delivery and execution: filtering, sandboxing, macro hardening, and awareness training."},{"text":"Block all external spreadsheets at the gateway, because invoices delivered as documents are the main phishing vector.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking all external spreadsheets is overly broad and doesn't address macro-enabled documents specifically, while still disrupting legitimate business use of spreadsheets."},{"text":"Require users to open attachments only from virtual desktops, eliminating the need for mail-layer inspection controls.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting attachments to virtual desktops adds a containment layer but doesn't replace the value of layered mail-level filtering and detonation before execution."},{"text":"Rely on sender reputation alone, since macro-enabled attachments are obvious enough for trained users to avoid.","correct":false,"why":"Relying on sender reputation alone assumes users can identify malicious documents, which doesn't address that convincing phishing lures can still deceive trained users."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q405","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Honeypots / Deception","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A SOC deploys a honeypot in a DMZ. What is the PRIMARY security benefit?","options":[{"text":"A decoy provides early, high-confidence insight into adversary interest and methods when someone interacts with it.","correct":true,"why":"Honeypots are detection/deception tools that provide high-fidelity alerts and intelligence, not primary prevention."},{"text":"It diverts all malicious traffic away from production assets, functioning as the primary containment control in the DMZ.","correct":false,"why":"A honeypot doesn't divert all malicious traffic away from production; it's a decoy that may attract some attention but isn't a containment mechanism for the whole DMZ."},{"text":"It creates legally admissible evidence by automatically preserving full packet capture for every hostile interaction.","correct":false,"why":"A honeypot doesn't automatically guarantee legally admissible full packet capture; its primary value is early detection and threat intelligence, not evidentiary capture."},{"text":"It patches visibility gaps by replacing the need for endpoint telemetry on servers exposed to the internet.","correct":false,"why":"A honeypot doesn't replace the need for endpoint telemetry on actual production servers; it's a separate decoy system for detection, not a visibility substitute."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q406","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Compliance/Data Standards","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, which control MOST directly supports PCI DSS requirements for cardholder data transmission?","options":[{"text":"Protect transmissions with strong session encryption and controlled access to systems that handle payment data.","correct":true,"why":"PCI emphasizes protecting cardholder data with strong encryption in transit and access controls with monitoring."},{"text":"Retain transaction records for at least one year, because storage duration is the primary safeguard for payment traffic.","correct":false,"why":"Retaining transaction records for a year addresses data retention, not the specific requirement to protect cardholder data during transmission."},{"text":"Tokenize account numbers at rest only, since transmission channels fall outside the scope of cardholder protections.","correct":false,"why":"Tokenizing only at rest doesn't address protecting data while it's actively being transmitted, which is the specific requirement here."},{"text":"Restrict database administrator access, as network protections are secondary once payment systems are segmented.","correct":false,"why":"Restricting database administrator access addresses data-at-rest access control, not the transmission security requirement being asked about."}],"sub":"4.2"},{"id":"q407","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Network Concepts (DNS Security)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, which data source BEST helps identify newly registered suspicious domains used for C2?","options":[{"text":"Resolver and query records paired with domain-age context and endpoint attribution best expose suspicious new lookups.","correct":true,"why":"DNS telemetry plus reputation/age and endpoint mapping supports detection of suspicious new domains and C2 patterns."},{"text":"Full packet capture alone is sufficient, because resolver logging rarely includes enough detail to spot fresh domains.","correct":false,"why":"Full packet capture alone doesn't provide the domain registration age and reputation context needed to specifically flag newly registered suspicious domains."},{"text":"Email gateway telemetry is most effective, since newly registered command domains usually arrive through phishing links.","correct":false,"why":"Email gateway telemetry only captures phishing-delivered links; it wouldn't reveal C2 domains contacted through other channels like malware callbacks."},{"text":"Authentication logs are enough, because hosts contacting attacker infrastructure typically also show failed logons.","correct":false,"why":"Authentication logs show login activity, not domain registration age or DNS query patterns needed to identify newly registered malicious domains."}],"sub":"1.1"},{"id":"q408","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vuln Validation (Backports)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A scanner flags an old vulnerable version by banner, but the OS uses backported security fixes. BEST action?","options":[{"text":"Confirm package and patch reality with authenticated evidence and vendor guidance rather than trusting version banners.","correct":true,"why":"Backports can keep version strings while patching vulnerabilities."},{"text":"Treat the banner as authoritative unless exploitation succeeds, because backported fixes do not change risk posture.","correct":false,"why":"Treating the banner as authoritative unless exploitation succeeds ignores that backported fixes can already have patched the vulnerability despite the banner data."},{"text":"Ignore the finding if the package name matches the vendor build, since distribution releases remove version ambiguity.","correct":false,"why":"Ignoring the finding just because the package name matches the vendor build still doesn't confirm whether the specific fix was actually backported and applied."},{"text":"Prioritize the issue for immediate patching, because scanners underreport risk more often than they overreport it.","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing for immediate patching without verification risks wasted remediation effort if the vulnerability was already fixed via backport."}],"sub":"2.2"},{"id":"q409","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Out-of-Scope)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During a test you find a new subnet not listed in scope. BEST next step?","options":[{"text":"Pause activity and obtain explicit written approval before touching anything outside the authorized boundary.","correct":true,"why":"Operate only within authorized scope."},{"text":"Perform only passive discovery on the subnet, since observation does not count as testing against out-of-scope assets.","correct":false,"why":"Passive discovery on an unauthorized subnet still constitutes interacting with unauthorized infrastructure without approval, even if not overtly intrusive."},{"text":"Continue if the new range appears related to an in-scope environment, documenting the assumption in the final report.","correct":false,"why":"Continuing because a new range 'appears related' assumes authorization based on the tester's own judgment rather than obtaining actual written approval."},{"text":"Validate one non-intrusive proof of concept first, then request scope expansion only if a weakness is confirmed.","correct":false,"why":"Validating a proof of concept first before requesting scope expansion still means testing occurred on an unauthorized subnet before permission was granted."}],"sub":"2.3"},{"id":"q410","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Process Injection","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A new unsigned DLL is injected into browser processes and outbound connections to low-reputation domains begin. MOST likely function?","options":[{"text":"Interfering with browser activity to steal session material or redirect traffic while maintaining external communications.","correct":true,"why":"Browser injection is common for credential theft/session hijack, often paired with suspicious outbound communications."},{"text":"Adding redundancy to the user’s web stack so encrypted sessions can survive browser restarts without data loss.","correct":false,"why":"This behavior doesn't add redundancy for session data; DLL injection into a browser combined with suspicious outbound traffic points to malicious credential or session theft, not resilience."},{"text":"Performing local privilege escalation through browser sandbox escape, which does not require any network callback.","correct":false,"why":"Local privilege escalation through sandbox escape wouldn't explain the observed outbound connections to low-reputation domains, which suggest external communication."},{"text":"Enumerating installed extensions for inventory purposes before a software-updater process verifies their signatures.","correct":false,"why":"Extension enumeration for inventory purposes wouldn't require injecting a DLL into the browser process or generating outbound connections to suspicious domains."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q411","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (CSRF)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A web app relies only on cookies for state-changing actions. Users can be tricked into actions. BEST mitigation?","options":[{"text":"Require request-specific anti-forgery validation in addition to browser cookie controls for state-changing actions.","correct":true,"why":"CSRF requires request validation beyond cookies: tokens and same-site/origin checks reduce cross-site abuse."},{"text":"Escape untrusted output before rendering so browser-delivered scripts cannot alter the page and submit hidden forms.","correct":false,"why":"Escaping untrusted output prevents XSS, not CSRF; it doesn't stop a forged request from a different origin from being submitted using the victim's existing cookies."},{"text":"Use prepared statements on the backend because forged requests succeed only when input reaches the database unsafely.","correct":false,"why":"Prepared statements prevent SQL injection; they don't validate whether an incoming request was legitimately initiated by the user versus forged cross-site."},{"text":"Inspect inbound payloads with a web filter, since browser-initiated cross-site actions are mainly a request-signature issue.","correct":false,"why":"A web filter inspecting payload content doesn't verify request origin or authenticity, which is what's actually needed to stop forged cross-site requests."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q412","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Hardening (Egress Controls)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, blocking known malicious domains fails because attackers rotate domains fast. BEST control improvement?","options":[{"text":"Constrain outbound paths with policy-backed broker controls and telemetry so rapid domain rotation is less useful.","correct":true,"why":"Egress controls reduce outbound abuse and provide visibility."},{"text":"Increase perimeter deny-list updates, because rotation speed is mainly a feed-latency problem rather than a design issue.","correct":false,"why":"Simply updating the deny-list faster still relies on already-known-bad domains, which doesn't help against newly registered domains not yet on any list."},{"text":"Force all endpoints onto full-tunnel remote access, since domain churn is most effective only when users split tunnel.","correct":false,"why":"Forcing full-tunnel remote access addresses split-tunneling risk specifically, not the broader problem of restricting and monitoring what any endpoint can reach outbound."},{"text":"Harden password policy for service accounts, because outbound domain changes usually accompany credential spraying.","correct":false,"why":"Hardening service account passwords addresses credential security, not the actual problem of attackers evading domain-based blocking through rapid rotation."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q413","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"OS/Endpoint Hardening (Allowlisting)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, which control BEST reduces malware execution from user-writable paths like %TEMP% and Downloads?","options":[{"text":"Permit only approved code paths and prevent launches from user-controlled locations where malware commonly lands.","correct":true,"why":"Attackers often execute from user-writable paths; allowlisting and execution controls reduce initial execution vectors."},{"text":"Increase antivirus signature updates, because execution from temporary folders mainly succeeds when definitions are stale.","correct":false,"why":"More frequent antivirus signature updates still relies on recognizing known malware; it doesn't prevent execution from user-writable paths in the first place."},{"text":"Remove local administrator rights, since user-writable directories cannot launch code once elevation is unavailable.","correct":false,"why":"Removing admin rights limits what malware can do once running, but doesn't itself prevent a non-privileged process from launching in a user-writable folder."},{"text":"Disable browser downloads by policy, because that fully addresses executable content appearing in temporary folders.","correct":false,"why":"Disabling browser downloads addresses one delivery method but doesn't cover other ways malicious files could land in user-writable directories like Downloads or %TEMP%."}],"sub":"1.4"},{"id":"q414","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Imaging)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, what is the BEST practice for acquiring a suspect drive without altering evidence?","options":[{"text":"Use a write-protected acquisition path, capture a full forensic image, and validate it with cryptographic digests.","correct":true,"why":"Write blockers prevent modifications; bit-level imaging preserves sectors; hashes validate integrity."},{"text":"Copy only user files of interest to minimize handling risk, then hash the archive so evidence remains admissible.","correct":false,"why":"Copying only files of interest misses unallocated space and other data across the disk that a full forensic image would capture."},{"text":"Mount the drive read-only within the operating system and export folders, since sector-level imaging is rarely necessary.","correct":false,"why":"Mounting read-only within the OS and exporting folders still misses a full sector-level image, which can matter for deleted or hidden data."},{"text":"Boot the suspect device into a trusted environment and compress the disk contents to preserve storage space.","correct":false,"why":"Booting into a trusted environment and compressing contents doesn't use a write blocker and risks altering the original evidence during the process."}],"sub":"3.1"},{"id":"q415","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"Authentication (Kerberos)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, many Kerberos service ticket requests (TGS) target a service account, and offline cracking is suspected. Which technique does this MOST likely indicate?","options":[{"text":"Requesting service tickets tied to service principals so their encrypted material can be cracked offline.","correct":true,"why":"Kerberoasting abuses service tickets for offline cracking of service account credentials."},{"text":"Reusing ticket-granting tickets across hosts after disabling preauthentication on the user account.","correct":false,"why":"Reusing TGTs across hosts after disabling preauthentication describes a different attack technique (AS-REP roasting variant), not requesting service tickets for offline cracking."},{"text":"Forging interdomain referral tickets to impersonate administrators without interacting with service accounts.","correct":false,"why":"Forging interdomain referral tickets describes a different, more advanced attack (like a golden/silver ticket variant) that doesn't involve requesting numerous service tickets tied to one service account."},{"text":"Capturing NTLM challenge-response pairs from network flows after an authentication path shifted away from service-ticket use.","correct":false,"why":"Capturing NTLM challenge-response pairs is a different technique entirely, unrelated to requesting Kerberos service tickets for offline cracking."}],"sub":"1.5"},{"id":"q416","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"DDoS","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A public site is hit by volumetric DDoS saturating bandwidth. BEST mitigation at scale?","options":[{"text":"Use provider-side absorption and traffic scrubbing capabilities rather than relying only on local edge devices.","correct":true,"why":"Volumetric DDoS requires upstream mitigation since local devices cannot handle saturated circuits."},{"text":"Block the top source addresses at the firewall, because volumetric attacks depend on a small number of persistent senders.","correct":false,"why":"Blocking top source addresses assumes a small number of persistent senders, but volumetric DDoS typically comes from many distributed sources, making this ineffective at scale."},{"text":"Increase web-application filtering, since bandwidth exhaustion is mainly driven by malformed HTTP request payloads.","correct":false,"why":"Web-application filtering addresses application-layer attacks, not the raw bandwidth-saturating volume of a volumetric DDoS attack."},{"text":"Fail over to another region without coordination, because attack traffic rarely follows a site once DNS changes propagate.","correct":false,"why":"Failing over to another region without coordination doesn't stop attack traffic from simply following the new destination once discovered, and lacks upstream mitigation."}],"sub":"1.3"},{"id":"q417","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Password Storage)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"During an investigation, passwords are stored using unsalted MD5. BEST fix?","options":[{"text":"Move to adaptive password hashing with unique salts and tuned cost parameters, then migrate accounts safely.","correct":true,"why":"Passwords should be hashed with slow, salted algorithms resistant to offline cracking (not encryption/encoding)."},{"text":"Encrypt the password table with a server-held key, because reversible protection is easier to integrate with legacy logins.","correct":false,"why":"Encrypting the password table with a server-held key is reversible and still allows plaintext recovery if the key is compromised, unlike properly salted one-way hashing."},{"text":"Keep MD5 but add transport encryption, since offline cracking risk comes primarily from weak session protection.","correct":false,"why":"Adding transport encryption protects data in transit but doesn't address that stored passwords remain weakly hashed and vulnerable to offline cracking if the database is breached."},{"text":"Store a second unhashed backup copy temporarily so users can be migrated to the stronger scheme without resets.","correct":false,"why":"Storing a second unhashed backup copy temporarily creates an additional, even more exposed copy of plaintext-equivalent passwords, worsening the security risk."}],"sub":"2.4"},{"id":"q418","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance (Exception Handling)","source":"CySA_Final_Review.html","q":"A team requests a patch exception for a critical vuln on a customer-facing server. BEST process?","options":[{"text":"Approve only a time-bounded exception with justification, compensating measures, ownership, and follow-up verification.","correct":true,"why":"Exceptions must be governed: time-bound approvals, compensating controls, documented rationale, and monitoring."},{"text":"Delay patching informally while the application team prepares a maintenance window, then close the risk if no incidents occur.","correct":false,"why":"Delaying patching informally without documented justification, compensating controls, or a defined timeline lacks the governance structure a proper exception requires."},{"text":"Accept the risk permanently once leadership signs off, because customer-facing systems often cannot tolerate repeated changes.","correct":false,"why":"Accepting the risk permanently, even with sign-off, skips establishing the time-bound nature and follow-up verification a proper exception process requires."},{"text":"Lower the scanner severity for that asset so reporting better reflects operational constraints while remediation is deferred.","correct":false,"why":"Lowering the scanner severity to reflect operational constraints hides the actual risk rather than governing it through a proper documented exception process."}],"sub":"4.3"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A SOC receives dozens of nearly identical phishing reports from employees within a 10-minute window, all referencing the same sender domain. Rather than having an analyst manually process each ticket, the security team wants the platform to automatically extract indicators, check them against threat intelligence, and quarantine matching emails across all mailboxes. Which capability BEST describes this workflow?","options":[{"text":"A SOAR playbook orchestrating indicator extraction, enrichment, and automated remediation across connected tools","correct":true,"why":"This is a textbook SOAR (security orchestration, automation, and response) use case: a defined playbook chains together extraction, threat intel enrichment, and remediation actions across multiple integrated tools without manual step-by-step intervention."},{"text":"A SIEM correlation rule that simply raises the severity of related alerts without performing any indicator lookups or automated remediation actions","correct":false,"why":"SIEM correlation rules can group related alerts together, but they don't independently perform enrichment lookups or execute remediation actions like mailbox quarantine across systems the way an orchestrated playbook does."},{"text":"A vulnerability scanner configured to run on a recurring schedule and report newly discovered weaknesses across scanned systems","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability scanning identifies weaknesses in systems and has no role in processing phishing reports or coordinating an automated mailbox remediation response."},{"text":"A manual runbook that the on-call analyst must follow step-by-step without any automated extraction, enrichment, or remediation support","correct":false,"why":"A manual runbook still requires a human to execute each step; the scenario specifically describes removing that manual burden through automation, which is the defining feature of orchestration."}],"id":"q419","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A newly deployed automation playbook is intended to block any IP address flagged by three or more threat intelligence feeds. Shortly after activation, it begins blocking IP addresses belonging to a major cloud provider used by several legitimate internal services, causing an outage. What is the MOST likely root cause of this incident?","options":[{"text":"The playbook was deployed to production without adequate testing or an allowlist for shared infrastructure ranges","correct":true,"why":"Automation that acts on third-party intelligence without validation, staging, or exclusion lists for known-shared address ranges (like large cloud provider CIDR blocks) is likely to produce false-positive blocks with wide blast radius, which is exactly what proper pre-production testing and allowlisting are meant to catch."},{"text":"The threat intelligence feeds were outdated and needed a subscription renewal to keep pace with new threats","correct":false,"why":"An outdated feed would more likely cause missed detections, not an aggressive over-blocking pattern tied specifically to shared cloud provider address space; the failure described is about validation and scoping, not feed freshness."},{"text":"The SIEM was not configured to ingest logs from the affected internal services during the outage window","correct":false,"why":"Missing log ingestion would limit visibility into the outage's cause, but it does not explain why the automation took the blocking action in the first place."},{"text":"The analyst who built the playbook lacked administrator credentials needed to configure it correctly in production","correct":false,"why":"A credential or permissions issue would typically prevent the playbook from executing actions at all, not cause it to execute overly broad actions successfully."}],"id":"q420","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A security engineer designs a playbook where a critical server will be automatically isolated from the network the moment ransomware-indicative behavior is detected, with no analyst review required before the action executes. A colleague argues this specific action should instead require analyst approval before executing. What is the STRONGEST justification for the colleague's position?","options":[{"text":"Automatically isolating a critical production server on a single detection could cause significant business disruption if the detection turns out to be a false positive","correct":true,"why":"High-impact, hard-to-reverse actions on critical systems benefit from a human-in-the-loop approval step specifically because the cost of a false positive (unplanned downtime on a critical server) can outweigh the speed benefit of full automation, unlike lower-impact actions."},{"text":"SOAR platforms are technically incapable of taking network isolation actions against production servers regardless of configuration","correct":false,"why":"SOAR platforms are technically capable of executing network isolation actions against any integrated asset, including production servers; the concern here is about risk and impact, not technical capability."},{"text":"Ransomware indicators can only ever be detected by dedicated antivirus software, never by automation or detection platforms","correct":false,"why":"SOAR and detection platforms routinely ingest and act on ransomware-indicative behavioral signals from EDR and other sources; this isn't a technical limitation of automation."},{"text":"Human-in-the-loop approval steps are required by law for every single security automation action taken anywhere","correct":false,"why":"There is no blanket legal requirement mandating human approval for all automated security actions; the appropriate use of approval gates is a risk-based design decision, not a universal legal mandate."}],"id":"q421","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A SOC team notices that their SIEM generates 40 separate alerts for a single brute-force login attempt because each failed authentication event triggers its own alert. The team wants an automated solution that groups these into a single incident ticket before an analyst ever sees it. Which automation concept addresses this specifically?","options":[{"text":"Alert deduplication and correlation logic within the orchestration workflow","correct":true,"why":"Automated deduplication/correlation logic is designed exactly for this situation: grouping many related low-level events (repeated failed logins from the same pattern) into a single actionable ticket, reducing analyst alert fatigue."},{"text":"Increasing the SIEM's log retention period so older brute-force events remain searchable for longer","correct":false,"why":"Retention period controls how long logs are stored for later search, but it has no effect on how many alerts are generated in real time for a burst of related events."},{"text":"Disabling authentication logging for the affected system to reduce the volume of generated alerts","correct":false,"why":"Disabling logging would eliminate visibility into the brute-force attempt entirely, which removes the ability to detect and respond to the actual threat rather than solving the alert volume problem."},{"text":"Increasing the account lockout threshold so more failed attempts are tolerated before a lockout occurs","correct":false,"why":"Changing the lockout threshold affects how many attempts are permitted before an account locks, but it does not address the underlying issue of a single event triggering many duplicate alerts."}],"id":"q422","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"An organization integrates its chat platform with its SOAR tool so that analysts can type a command such as 'isolate host WKS-042' directly into a shared channel and have the action executed automatically, with the result posted back to the channel for the whole team to see. What is this practice commonly known as?","options":[{"text":"ChatOps","correct":true,"why":"ChatOps is the specific practice of triggering operational or security actions through chat-based commands, with results posted back for team visibility, which matches the scenario exactly."},{"text":"Threat hunting","correct":false,"why":"Threat hunting is a proactive, hypothesis-driven search for hidden threats within an environment, not a method of triggering automated actions via chat commands."},{"text":"Vulnerability scanning","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability scanning identifies weaknesses in systems; it has no relationship to executing response actions through a chat interface."},{"text":"Digital forensics","correct":false,"why":"Digital forensics involves the structured investigation and preservation of evidence, which is unrelated to issuing operational commands through a chat platform."}],"id":"q423","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A playbook is configured to automatically collect a memory dump, relevant log files, and a list of running processes the instant an EDR agent reports a critical alert on any endpoint. What is the PRIMARY benefit of automating this specific step?","options":[{"text":"Volatile evidence such as memory contents can be lost quickly, so immediate automated collection preserves it before it degrades or is overwritten","correct":true,"why":"Volatile data like RAM contents changes constantly and can be lost the moment a system is rebooted, crashes, or simply continues running; automating collection the instant an alert fires captures that evidence before an analyst could manually respond in time."},{"text":"It eliminates the need for a chain of custody during the investigation since the collection was automated","correct":false,"why":"Automated evidence collection still requires a properly documented chain of custody; automation does not remove that legal and procedural requirement."},{"text":"It guarantees the alert is a true positive rather than a false positive simply because evidence was collected","correct":false,"why":"Automated evidence collection does not validate whether an alert is accurate; it simply preserves data for later analysis regardless of whether the underlying alert turns out to be a false positive."},{"text":"It automatically identifies the attacker's real-world identity from the collected memory dump and log files","correct":false,"why":"Collecting memory dumps and logs supports later analysis and attribution efforts, but the collection step itself does not identify who the attacker is."}],"id":"q424","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A confirmed compromised laptop needs to be simultaneously removed from the network, have its associated user account disabled, and have a ticket opened with full context for the on-call analyst. Which approach accomplishes all three actions in a single, coordinated automated action?","options":[{"text":"A single orchestrated playbook that calls the EDR, identity provider, and ticketing system APIs in sequence","correct":true,"why":"Coordinating multiple distinct tools (EDR for isolation, identity provider for account disablement, and a ticketing system for case creation) through one triggered workflow is precisely what orchestration platforms are designed to do, replacing several separate manual tasks with one automated sequence."},{"text":"Manually logging into each of the three systems one at a time","correct":false,"why":"Manually performing each action individually is the slower, error-prone process that orchestration is specifically meant to replace; it does not represent a coordinated automated action."},{"text":"Relying on the identity provider to automatically notify the EDR platform without any integration configured","correct":false,"why":"Without an actual configured integration or workflow connecting these systems, there is no mechanism for one platform to automatically trigger actions in another."},{"text":"Waiting for the next scheduled vulnerability scan to detect the compromised host","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability scans run on a scheduled cadence and are designed to find weaknesses, not to perform real-time incident containment actions across multiple systems."}],"id":"q425","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"Before rolling a new automated remediation playbook into the production SOC environment, the automation engineer runs it against a set of simulated alerts in an isolated environment and reviews every action it would have taken. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this step?","options":[{"text":"To validate that the playbook behaves as intended and does not take unintended or harmful actions before it can affect real systems","correct":true,"why":"Testing automation logic in a staging or simulated environment before production deployment is a standard safeguard to catch flawed logic, unintended side effects, or overly broad actions before they can impact live systems."},{"text":"To satisfy a mandatory annual compliance audit requirement that has nothing to do with the playbook's actual logic","correct":false,"why":"While testing can support audit and compliance goals broadly, the primary and immediate purpose of pre-production testing is to catch functional problems in the automation logic itself, not to check a specific audit box."},{"text":"To reduce the number of threat intelligence feeds the platform needs to subscribe to going forward","correct":false,"why":"Staging tests validate playbook behavior; they have no relationship to the number of threat intelligence feeds an organization subscribes to."},{"text":"To permanently disable the playbook after a single use so it can never run again in production","correct":false,"why":"Testing is meant to validate a playbook so it CAN be used safely going forward, not to disable it; disabling it after one use would defeat the purpose of building reusable automation."}],"id":"q426","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"An organization's SOAR platform automatically ingests indicators from five external threat intelligence feeds and adds any IP address, domain, or file hash appearing on two or more feeds to the enterprise blocklist. What is the MAIN advantage of automating this specific process instead of having an analyst manually cross-reference feeds each day?","options":[{"text":"It applies protective blocking far faster and more consistently than a manual daily review process could achieve","correct":true,"why":"Automating the cross-referencing and blocklist update means new threats are blocked within minutes of appearing on multiple feeds rather than waiting for a scheduled manual review, and it removes the risk of human error or fatigue in the comparison process."},{"text":"It eliminates the possibility of any indicator ever being a false positive once it appears on two feeds","correct":false,"why":"Automation does not guarantee accuracy; indicators from threat feeds can still be false positives regardless of whether the cross-referencing process is manual or automated."},{"text":"It removes the need to maintain any threat intelligence subscriptions going forward since the blocklist is built","correct":false,"why":"The feeds themselves are still required as the data source for the automation; automating the comparison process does not eliminate the need for the underlying subscriptions."},{"text":"It guarantees the blocklist will never need to be reviewed again once entries are added automatically","correct":false,"why":"Automated blocklists still require periodic review to catch stale entries, false positives, or drift over time; automation reduces manual effort but does not eliminate the need for oversight."}],"id":"q427","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A security automation workflow depends on a third-party vendor's API to pull vulnerability data into the SIEM every night. One morning, analysts notice that no new vulnerability data has appeared for three days, but no error alert was ever generated. What is the MOST likely underlying issue with the automation design?","options":[{"text":"The workflow lacks monitoring or alerting for its own failure conditions, such as an API outage or authentication failure","correct":true,"why":"Automated workflows that depend on external APIs need their own health monitoring; without alerting on failure conditions like a broken API call or expired credentials, the automation can silently stop working while everyone assumes it is still functioning."},{"text":"The vulnerability scanner has reached its maximum license count and silently stopped scanning new hosts","correct":false,"why":"A license limit would typically produce an explicit error rather than a silent multi-day gap with no alerting at all, and it doesn't explain the complete absence of failure notification."},{"text":"The SIEM's storage has become fully saturated and cannot accept any further incoming vulnerability data","correct":false,"why":"Storage saturation would typically generate its own distinct alerts or errors related to storage capacity, not a silent, unnoticed failure of a single automated data feed."},{"text":"The vendor discontinued the vulnerability data product entirely without notifying any of its customers","correct":false,"why":"While possible, this is a much less likely and unverified explanation compared to the more fundamental design gap: the automation has no self-monitoring to surface any failure, regardless of its root cause."}],"id":"q428","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A patch automation tool deploys an update to a fleet of servers and is configured to automatically monitor each server's health metrics for 15 minutes afterward, reverting the patch on any server that fails to come back online or reports critical service errors. What automation concept does this describe?","options":[{"text":"Automated rollback triggered by post-deployment health validation","correct":true,"why":"Automatically checking system health after a change and reverting on failure is the definition of automated rollback tied to health validation, which limits the blast radius of a bad patch without requiring a human to notice and intervene manually."},{"text":"Credentialed vulnerability scanning that authenticates to the host for a deeper assessment of installed packages","correct":false,"why":"Credentialed scanning refers to authenticating to a system to get a deeper vulnerability assessment; it is unrelated to monitoring patch deployment health and triggering rollback."},{"text":"Manual change advisory board review conducted by human stakeholders before the change is approved and scheduled","correct":false,"why":"A change advisory board involves human reviewers evaluating and approving a change before it happens; the scenario describes an automated post-deployment safety mechanism, not a pre-change human review process."},{"text":"Static application security testing performed against source code during the development pipeline stage","correct":false,"why":"Static application security testing analyzes source code for vulnerabilities during development; it has no role in monitoring the health of already-deployed servers after a patch."}],"id":"q429","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"After enabling an automation that instantly blocks any host generating more than 100 outbound connections per minute, the SOC begins seeing dozens of blocking actions fire within seconds during a routine software deployment that legitimately generates high connection volume. What design change would BEST address this without disabling the automation entirely?","options":[{"text":"Add rate-limiting or a cooldown window to the automation, and create an exception for recognized maintenance windows or known-legitimate high-volume processes","correct":true,"why":"Tuning the automation with rate limits, cooldown periods, and exceptions for known legitimate high-volume activity (like scheduled deployments) preserves its usefulness for real threats while preventing it from firing on predictable, sanctioned bursts of activity."},{"text":"Permanently disable all outbound connection monitoring so the automation can never fire on any traffic again, including genuinely malicious activity","correct":false,"why":"Removing the monitoring entirely would eliminate detection of genuinely malicious high-volume outbound activity, such as data exfiltration, which is a much larger loss than the disruption caused by the false positives."},{"text":"Increase the connection threshold to 100,000 connections per minute so almost nothing ever triggers the rule, even truly malicious bursts","correct":false,"why":"Setting the threshold unreasonably high would likely prevent the automation from ever firing on real malicious activity, effectively neutering its detection value rather than tuning it appropriately."},{"text":"Require every future software deployment across the organization to be scheduled for after business hours only, regardless of business need","correct":false,"why":"Changing organizational deployment scheduling practices does not address the underlying automation tuning problem and is a much larger and less targeted change than adjusting the automation's own logic."}],"id":"q430","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A CISO is evaluating whether to invest in a SOAR platform. A board member asks what the primary value proposition is, given that the organization already has skilled analysts capable of performing the same response steps manually. What is the BEST answer?","options":[{"text":"Automation performs repetitive response steps consistently and far faster than manual execution, freeing analysts to focus on complex investigation and judgment-based work","correct":true,"why":"The core value of SOAR is not replacing analyst judgment but eliminating the time and inconsistency involved in repetitive, well-defined tasks, allowing skilled analysts to spend their time on higher-value investigative and decision-making work instead."},{"text":"Automation eliminates the need for the organization to employ any security analysts at all going forward, since every task becomes automated","correct":false,"why":"SOAR platforms are designed to augment analysts by automating repetitive steps, not to fully replace the human judgment, investigation, and decision-making that skilled analysts provide."},{"text":"Automation guarantees that no security incident will ever occur again once the platform is fully deployed across the environment","correct":false,"why":"No automation platform can guarantee the prevention of all future incidents; SOAR improves response speed and consistency, but it does not eliminate risk entirely."},{"text":"Automation removes the organization's obligation to maintain a documented incident response plan entirely once playbooks exist","correct":false,"why":"An incident response plan is still required to define processes, roles, and escalation paths; SOAR automates the execution of certain steps within that plan, it does not replace the need for the plan itself."}],"id":"q431","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A SOC integrates its EDR, SIEM, and ticketing platform through an orchestration layer so that a single detection can trigger enrichment lookups, generate a ticket with full context, and notify the on-call analyst, all without manual data entry between tools. Six months later, a new analyst notices the automation is pulling outdated asset ownership data because the source system's data format changed and the integration was never updated. What does this scenario illustrate?","options":[{"text":"Automation requires ongoing maintenance, since upstream changes in integrated systems can cause it to silently produce inaccurate results over time","correct":true,"why":"Automations are only as reliable as their integrations; when a connected system's data format or API changes and the automation isn't updated to match, it can keep running without errors while quietly producing stale or inaccurate output, which is why ongoing maintenance and periodic validation are essential."},{"text":"Orchestration platforms are inherently unreliable and should never be used for asset ownership data at all, regardless of how well maintained","correct":false,"why":"The issue described is a maintenance and change-management gap, not an inherent flaw in orchestration technology itself; well-maintained integrations can remain accurate over time."},{"text":"The SIEM has reached its maximum data retention limit and can no longer store any new asset ownership records going forward","correct":false,"why":"Retention limits govern how long historical data is stored, which is unrelated to an integration pulling outdated but still-present asset ownership data due to a format change."},{"text":"The ticketing system requires a license upgrade before it can continue creating new tickets from incoming detection alerts","correct":false,"why":"A licensing issue would typically prevent ticket creation entirely rather than cause tickets to be created successfully with outdated data."}],"id":"q432","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"An organization's HR system automatically notifies the identity and access management platform the moment an employee's termination is processed, which in turn immediately disables the employee's accounts, revokes VPN access, and notifies the security team, all without any manual ticket being filed. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this automated integration?","options":[{"text":"It minimizes the window of time a terminated employee could retain unauthorized access to organizational systems","correct":true,"why":"Manual deprovisioning processes can be delayed by staffing gaps, missed communications, or backlog, leaving a window where a terminated employee retains access; automating the trigger directly from the authoritative HR event closes that gap as tightly as possible."},{"text":"It eliminates the need for exit interviews to be conducted with employees who are being terminated","correct":false,"why":"Exit interviews serve HR and organizational purposes unrelated to technical account deprovisioning; automating account revocation does not affect whether exit interviews are conducted."},{"text":"It guarantees the employee will not attempt to access company data or systems after termination occurs","correct":false,"why":"Automated deprovisioning reduces the technical access window significantly, but it cannot guarantee behavioral intent; it addresses access control, not the individual's actions or motivations."},{"text":"It removes the requirement for a formal offboarding policy to exist within the organization at all","correct":false,"why":"A formal offboarding policy still defines what should happen, who is responsible, and how exceptions are handled; the automation implements part of that policy but does not replace the need for it to exist."}],"id":"q433","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A team is comparing two designs for an automated incident response playbook. Design A takes action immediately with no logging of what it did. Design B takes the same actions but logs every decision point, input, and output to an audit trail. Which design is preferable from a security operations standpoint, and why?","options":[{"text":"Design B, because a documented audit trail supports post-incident review, troubleshooting, and accountability for automated actions","correct":true,"why":"Automated actions still need to be reviewable after the fact, whether to confirm they behaved correctly, to support an investigation, or to satisfy compliance requirements; a design with no logging removes the ability to verify or troubleshoot what the automation actually did."},{"text":"Design A, because logging every decision point slows down the overall speed of the automated response","correct":false,"why":"While logging does add a small amount of overhead, the security and operational value of an auditable record of automated actions far outweighs a negligible speed difference, especially for actions with real business impact."},{"text":"Both designs are equally acceptable since the underlying response actions taken are identical either way","correct":false,"why":"Even though the response actions are the same, the lack of an audit trail in Design A leaves the organization unable to verify, troubleshoot, or defend those actions later, which is a meaningful operational and compliance gap."},{"text":"Design A, because unlogged actions cannot be challenged or reviewed later by internal or external auditors","correct":false,"why":"The inability for auditors or reviewers to examine unlogged actions is a weakness, not a benefit; being unreviewable undermines trust and accountability rather than supporting it."}],"id":"q434","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A security team wants to reduce analyst fatigue caused by hundreds of low-severity alerts each day that almost always turn out to be benign after a five-minute manual check. Which automation approach would BEST address this without losing visibility into genuinely suspicious activity?","options":[{"text":"Build a playbook that automatically performs the same five-minute enrichment checks the analyst does, and only escalates to a human when the results are inconclusive or suspicious","correct":true,"why":"Automating the routine, well-defined enrichment steps an analyst already performs mirrors human judgment on the easy cases while preserving human review specifically for cases that are ambiguous or genuinely concerning, which directly reduces fatigue without sacrificing coverage."},{"text":"Disable all low-severity alerts entirely so analysts never have to see or manually triage any of them ever again, even the rare genuinely malicious ones","correct":false,"why":"Simply suppressing low-severity alerts removes visibility entirely, meaning a genuinely malicious event that happens to generate a low-severity alert would go completely unnoticed rather than being triaged appropriately."},{"text":"Require two separate analysts to independently review every single low-severity alert instead of just one analyst doing it, doubling the manual review workload","correct":false,"why":"Doubling the number of people reviewing each alert increases total analyst workload rather than reducing fatigue, and does nothing to address the root inefficiency of manually repeating the same routine checks."},{"text":"Increase the frequency of the vulnerability scanning schedule so even more findings are generated for analysts to manually review each day","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability scanning frequency is unrelated to the volume of low-severity alerts being manually triaged; adjusting it would not reduce analyst fatigue from this specific workflow."}],"id":"q435","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.1","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Credentialed vs Non-credentialed)","q":"A vulnerability management team runs an external scan against a public-facing web server without providing any login credentials to the scanner, intentionally simulating what an outside attacker could see. What type of scan is this?","options":[{"text":"An uncredentialed (unauthenticated) scan","correct":true,"why":"An uncredentialed scan intentionally omits login credentials to approximate an external attacker's view, identifying only vulnerabilities visible without authenticated access, which matches the described intent exactly."},{"text":"A credentialed scan","correct":false,"why":"A credentialed scan uses valid login credentials to authenticate to the target and inspect it from an internal, logged-in perspective, which is the opposite of the external, no-login approach described here."},{"text":"A penetration test","correct":false,"why":"A penetration test goes beyond automated scanning to include active exploitation attempts by a human tester; the scenario describes only a scan, not an exploitation engagement."},{"text":"A static code analysis","correct":false,"why":"Static code analysis examines application source code directly rather than scanning a live running server from the network, which is not what is described in this scenario."}],"id":"q436","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.1","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Scanning Methods (Safe Scanning in Production)","q":"A vulnerability management team needs to scan a set of production database servers that support a customer-facing application with strict uptime requirements. Leadership is concerned an aggressive scan could cause service disruption. Which approach BEST balances thorough coverage with production stability?","options":[{"text":"Schedule a credentialed scan during an approved maintenance window with throttled scan intensity and prior stakeholder notification","correct":true,"why":"Combining a maintenance window, notification to stakeholders, and throttled (rate-limited) scan settings directly addresses the stability concern while still achieving deep, authenticated visibility into the servers, which is the standard way to safely scan sensitive production systems."},{"text":"Run the most aggressive scan settings available during peak business hours to maximize overall coverage speed","correct":false,"why":"Running an aggressive scan during peak hours on production database servers directly conflicts with the stated uptime concern and risks causing exactly the disruption leadership is worried about."},{"text":"Skip scanning these servers entirely since leadership considers them too sensitive and important to test","correct":false,"why":"Excluding critical production systems from vulnerability scanning entirely leaves them without visibility into their security posture, which creates a much larger long-term risk than a carefully scheduled, throttled scan."},{"text":"Only scan a single representative server and assume the results apply equally to all the others","correct":false,"why":"Assuming uniform configuration across all servers without verification risks missing vulnerabilities unique to individual systems, such as configuration drift, and does not address the original concern about scan impact."}],"id":"q437","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.2","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Vulnerability Analysis (CVSS vs Risk)","q":"A vulnerability scanner reports a finding with a CVSS base score of 9.8 on a server, but that server sits on an isolated lab network with no internet access, no sensitive data, and is scheduled for decommission next week. How should this finding MOST appropriately be prioritized relative to a CVSS 6.5 finding on an internet-facing production server handling customer payment data?","options":[{"text":"The CVSS 6.5 finding should be prioritized higher, because environmental context and exposure significantly affect actual risk beyond the base score alone","correct":true,"why":"CVSS base scores measure theoretical severity in isolation; actual prioritization must account for environmental factors like exposure, data sensitivity, and compensating controls, meaning a lower base score on a highly exposed, sensitive production system can represent greater real-world risk than a higher base score on an isolated, soon-to-be-retired system."},{"text":"The CVSS 9.8 finding should always be prioritized higher regardless of context, since it has a numerically higher raw score","correct":false,"why":"Prioritizing purely by raw CVSS base score ignores critical context like network exposure, data sensitivity, and the system's remaining lifecycle, which can make a lower-scored finding on a more exposed and valuable asset the more urgent issue in practice."},{"text":"Both findings should be given identical priority since they were both identified by the exact same scanner tool","correct":false,"why":"Treating findings as equally urgent regardless of business context and exposure ignores the fundamental purpose of risk-based prioritization, which is to focus remediation effort where actual risk is highest."},{"text":"Neither finding needs remediation at all since both systems will eventually be replaced or decommissioned anyway","correct":false,"why":"The production payment system handling customer data is not described as being decommissioned and remains actively exposed, making it inappropriate to deprioritize remediation entirely."}],"id":"q438","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.3","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Rules of Engagement)","q":"Before a penetration test begins, the client and testing firm agree on a document specifying which systems are in scope, which testing techniques are prohibited (such as denial-of-service attacks), the testing window, and emergency contact procedures. What is this document called?","options":[{"text":"Rules of engagement","correct":true,"why":"Rules of engagement is the specific pre-engagement document that defines scope boundaries, permitted and prohibited techniques, timing, and escalation contacts for a penetration test, exactly matching what's described."},{"text":"A vulnerability scan report","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability scan report is a results document produced after scanning activity has occurred; it does not define the boundaries or permitted techniques for a test before it begins."},{"text":"A service level agreement","correct":false,"why":"A service level agreement typically defines performance and availability expectations for an ongoing service relationship, not the specific scope and constraints of a time-boxed penetration test."},{"text":"An incident response plan","correct":false,"why":"An incident response plan defines how an organization responds to security incidents after they occur; it is unrelated to defining the pre-agreed boundaries of an authorized penetration test."}],"id":"q439","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.3","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Black/Gray/White Box)","q":"A client wants a penetration test that most closely simulates what an external attacker with zero prior knowledge or access could accomplish, providing the testing team with nothing more than the company name to start from. Which testing approach BEST matches this requirement?","options":[{"text":"Black box testing","correct":true,"why":"Black box testing provides the tester with no internal knowledge, credentials, or documentation, forcing them to discover everything from the outside, which best simulates a real external attacker starting from zero information."},{"text":"White box testing","correct":false,"why":"White box testing provides the tester with full internal knowledge, such as source code, network diagrams, and credentials, which is the opposite of the zero-knowledge simulation the client requested."},{"text":"Gray box testing","correct":false,"why":"Gray box testing provides the tester with partial knowledge, such as limited credentials or documentation, which still gives more information than the zero-knowledge starting point described in the scenario."},{"text":"Vulnerability scanning","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability scanning is an automated technique for identifying known weaknesses, not a testing methodology defined by how much prior knowledge the tester is given."}],"id":"q440","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.3","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Pen Testing (Post-Exploitation Boundaries)","q":"During an authorized penetration test, a tester successfully gains administrative access to a domain controller. The rules of engagement explicitly prohibit modifying production data or disrupting services. The tester wants to demonstrate the impact of the access obtained. What is the MOST appropriate next step?","options":[{"text":"Document the level of access achieved and simulate further impact in a non-destructive way, such as listing accessible sensitive files without altering them","correct":true,"why":"Respecting the rules of engagement means demonstrating impact without crossing into prohibited actions like modifying data or disrupting services; documenting access and non-destructively showing what could be reached achieves the demonstration goal while staying within authorized boundaries."},{"text":"Delete a few non-critical files on the domain controller to prove that data destruction is technically possible","correct":false,"why":"Deleting files, even non-critical ones, violates the explicit prohibition on modifying production data and exceeds the authorized scope of the engagement, which could expose the tester and firm to serious liability."},{"text":"Immediately stop the entire engagement and refuse to document any findings gathered from the access obtained","correct":false,"why":"Stopping the engagement and withholding findings is unnecessary and unhelpful; the appropriate response is to continue working within the agreed boundaries and document findings, not abandon the test entirely."},{"text":"Use the access to reset the domain administrator password, locking out legitimate administrators from their accounts","correct":false,"why":"Resetting the domain administrator password would directly disrupt production services and administrative access, which is explicitly prohibited by the stated rules of engagement."}],"id":"q441","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.4","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (SSRF)","q":"A cloud-hosted web application allows users to submit a URL, which the server then fetches and displays a preview of. An attacker submits a URL pointing to the cloud provider's internal metadata service instead of a normal website, and the server dutifully fetches and returns sensitive instance credentials in the response. What type of vulnerability does this describe?","options":[{"text":"Server-side request forgery (SSRF)","correct":true,"why":"SSRF occurs when an attacker manipulates a server into making requests to unintended destinations, such as an internal cloud metadata endpoint, on the attacker's behalf; the server fetching and exposing internal metadata based on attacker-supplied input is a classic SSRF outcome."},{"text":"Cross-site scripting (XSS)","correct":false,"why":"Cross-site scripting involves injecting malicious script that executes in another user's browser; this scenario involves the server itself making an unintended request, not a script running in a victim's browser."},{"text":"SQL injection","correct":false,"why":"SQL injection involves manipulating database queries through unsanitized input; this scenario involves the server fetching an attacker-controlled URL, which is unrelated to database query manipulation."},{"text":"Cross-site request forgery (CSRF)","correct":false,"why":"CSRF tricks an authenticated user's browser into submitting unwanted requests to a site they're logged into; this scenario involves the server itself fetching a URL on the attacker's behalf, not a victim's browser being manipulated."}],"id":"q442","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.4","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Broken Access Control)","q":"A web application displays invoice details when a user visits a URL like example.com/invoice?id=1042. A tester changes the number in the URL to a different value and successfully views another customer's invoice without any additional authentication. What category of vulnerability does this represent?","options":[{"text":"Broken access control, specifically an insecure direct object reference","correct":true,"why":"This is a textbook insecure direct object reference: the application fails to verify that the logged-in user is actually authorized to view the specific record being requested, allowing simple ID manipulation to access other users' data."},{"text":"A race condition arising from two threads modifying the same resource without proper synchronization","correct":false,"why":"A race condition involves timing-dependent behavior when multiple operations occur concurrently; this scenario is about missing authorization checks on a direct object reference, not a timing issue."},{"text":"A buffer overflow caused by writing more data into memory than the allocated buffer can hold","correct":false,"why":"A buffer overflow involves writing data beyond the bounds of allocated memory, typically in lower-level code; this scenario is a web application authorization flaw, unrelated to memory handling."},{"text":"A denial-of-service vulnerability that exhausts server resources through repeated malicious requests","correct":false,"why":"Denial-of-service vulnerabilities impact system availability; this scenario describes unauthorized data disclosure, not an availability impact."}],"id":"q443","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.4","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Race Conditions / TOCTOU)","q":"An online store's checkout process checks whether an item is in stock, and then, in a separate step a moment later, decrements the inventory count after payment succeeds. A user discovers that submitting many simultaneous purchase requests for the last item in stock allows several of them to succeed, resulting in oversold inventory. What type of vulnerability does this illustrate?","options":[{"text":"A time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","correct":true,"why":"This is a classic TOCTOU race condition: the gap between checking stock availability and actually committing the decrement allows multiple concurrent requests to pass the check before any of them updates the count, resulting in an inconsistent, oversold state."},{"text":"Cross-site scripting caused by unescaped user input being rendered directly in the browser","correct":false,"why":"Cross-site scripting involves injecting malicious script into pages viewed by other users; this scenario involves a timing flaw in concurrent inventory processing, unrelated to script injection."},{"text":"An insecure direct object reference allowing access to another user's data by changing an identifier","correct":false,"why":"An insecure direct object reference involves accessing another user's data by manipulating an identifier; this scenario involves a timing gap in inventory logic, not unauthorized data access via an identifier."},{"text":"A weak password policy that allows attackers to guess credentials through repeated online attempts","correct":false,"why":"Password policy is unrelated to this scenario, which describes a logic flaw in how concurrent purchase requests interact with inventory checks, not an authentication weakness."}],"id":"q444","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.4","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Insecure Deserialization)","q":"A Java application accepts serialized objects from client input and deserializes them directly without validation. A security researcher demonstrates that a specially crafted serialized object can trigger arbitrary code execution on the server the moment it is deserialized. What vulnerability class does this represent?","options":[{"text":"Insecure deserialization","correct":true,"why":"Insecure deserialization occurs when an application processes untrusted serialized data without validation, allowing an attacker to craft objects that trigger unintended and potentially dangerous behavior, including remote code execution, exactly as described."},{"text":"Cross-site request forgery","correct":false,"why":"Cross-site request forgery tricks an authenticated user's browser into submitting unwanted requests; this scenario involves the server directly processing malicious serialized input, not a browser-based attack against a user."},{"text":"Weak session management","correct":false,"why":"Weak session management concerns how session tokens are generated, stored, or validated; this scenario is about unsafe processing of serialized object data, not session handling."},{"text":"Clickjacking","correct":false,"why":"Clickjacking tricks a user into clicking something different from what they perceive using deceptive UI layering; this scenario involves server-side deserialization of malicious data, unrelated to UI manipulation."}],"id":"q445","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"2.4","objective":"2.0","objectiveName":"Vulnerability Management","topic":"Secure Coding (Input Validation)","q":"A developer builds a form field that accepts a customer's phone number and passes it directly into a backend command without checking its length, format, or content. A tester enters a string containing shell metacharacters and successfully executes an unintended system command on the server. What is the MOST fundamental root cause of this vulnerability?","options":[{"text":"The application failed to validate and sanitize user input before using it in a sensitive operation","correct":true,"why":"Nearly all injection-style vulnerabilities, including this command injection example, trace back to a failure to properly validate, sanitize, or safely handle untrusted input before it is used in a sensitive context like a system command."},{"text":"The web server was running an outdated version of its operating system that lacked recent security patches","correct":false,"why":"While outdated systems can carry their own risks, the vulnerability described is specifically tied to how unvalidated input was passed into a command, which is an application-layer coding flaw rather than an OS patching issue."},{"text":"The database was not encrypted at rest, exposing stored records if the underlying disk was ever accessed","correct":false,"why":"Encryption at rest protects stored data confidentiality but has no bearing on whether unvalidated input can be used to execute unintended commands on the server."},{"text":"The phone number field was not marked as a required field on the customer-facing form","correct":false,"why":"Whether a field is required or optional has nothing to do with whether its contents are validated and safely handled before being used in a backend operation."}],"id":"q446","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Digital Forensics (Order of Volatility)","q":"A forensic analyst arrives at a compromised server that is still powered on and connected to the network. Following proper forensic procedure, which of the following should generally be collected FIRST, before any other evidence?","options":[{"text":"The contents of system memory (RAM)","correct":true,"why":"The order of volatility principle dictates collecting the most volatile evidence first; RAM contents change constantly and are lost entirely on power-off, making it the highest priority to capture before anything less volatile, like disk contents or archived logs."},{"text":"Backup tapes stored in an offsite facility","correct":false,"why":"Backup tapes are among the least volatile forms of evidence and will remain intact regardless of what happens to the live system, so they do not need to be prioritized ahead of rapidly-changing live memory contents."},{"text":"Printed physical security logs from the building's front desk","correct":false,"why":"Physical printed logs are static and non-volatile; while they may be relevant to the investigation, they aren't at risk of being lost imminently the way live system memory is."},{"text":"Archived log files from six months ago","correct":false,"why":"Older archived logs are already stored and stable; they are not at risk of disappearing the way active system memory is on a still-running compromised host."}],"id":"q447","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Chain of Custody)","q":"An analyst removes a hard drive from a compromised workstation as evidence and hands it to a colleague to transport to a secure evidence locker. What must be created and maintained throughout this process to ensure the evidence remains legally admissible?","options":[{"text":"A chain of custody record documenting who handled the evidence, when, and why, at every transfer point","correct":true,"why":"Chain of custody is the unbroken, documented record of every person who has handled a piece of evidence and when, which is essential to proving the evidence wasn't tampered with and remains admissible in legal or disciplinary proceedings."},{"text":"A vulnerability scan report of the affected workstation identifying weaknesses present on the system","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability scan identifies weaknesses in a system's configuration; it has no bearing on documenting the physical handling and transfer of a piece of evidence like a hard drive."},{"text":"A network topology diagram of the affected segment showing how devices are connected","correct":false,"why":"A network diagram describes infrastructure layout and is useful for investigation context, but it does not serve the specific legal function of documenting evidence handling and transfer."},{"text":"An updated asset inventory listing the workstation's specifications and assigned owner","correct":false,"why":"An asset inventory records device details for management purposes; it does not track who physically handled a specific piece of evidence throughout an investigation."}],"id":"q448","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Write Preservation)","q":"A forensic analyst needs to create a bit-for-bit image of a suspect's hard drive for analysis while guaranteeing the original drive's contents cannot be accidentally altered during the imaging process. What hardware tool is specifically designed to accomplish this?","options":[{"text":"A write blocker","correct":true,"why":"A write blocker is a hardware device connected between the original drive and the imaging system that physically prevents any write commands from reaching the original media, ensuring the source evidence remains unaltered during the imaging process."},{"text":"A network tap","correct":false,"why":"A network tap passively captures network traffic passing between two points; it has no role in preventing writes to a hard drive during forensic imaging."},{"text":"A KVM switch","correct":false,"why":"A KVM switch allows one keyboard, video display, and mouse to control multiple computers; it has no function related to protecting a drive from writes during forensic imaging."},{"text":"A protocol analyzer","correct":false,"why":"A protocol analyzer captures and inspects network communications; it does not provide any physical write protection for a hard drive being imaged."}],"id":"q449","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Hashing Use)","q":"After creating a forensic image of a hard drive, an analyst calculates a cryptographic hash value of both the original drive and the image file and records both values. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this step?","options":[{"text":"To later prove the image is an exact, unaltered copy of the original evidence","correct":true,"why":"Matching hash values between the original drive and the image serve as mathematical proof that the image is a perfect, unmodified copy, which is essential for establishing the integrity and admissibility of forensic evidence during analysis or in legal proceedings."},{"text":"To encrypt the image file so unauthorized parties cannot open it","correct":false,"why":"Hashing produces a fixed-size fingerprint of data for integrity verification; it does not encrypt or restrict access to the file's contents."},{"text":"To compress the image file so it takes up less storage space","correct":false,"why":"Hashing does not reduce file size or compress data; its purpose is integrity verification, not storage optimization."},{"text":"To automatically remove any malware present on the imaged drive","correct":false,"why":"Hashing is a verification technique and has no capability to detect, remove, or otherwise act on malware present within the imaged data."}],"id":"q450","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (Timeline Building)","q":"An investigator is trying to determine the exact sequence of events during a breach, correlating firewall logs, authentication logs, and endpoint detection alerts from three different systems with different clock settings. What must be verified and corrected FIRST to ensure the resulting timeline is accurate?","options":[{"text":"That all systems' clocks are synchronized to a common, accurate time source, or that timestamps are normalized to account for any discrepancies","correct":true,"why":"If the systems being correlated have clocks that drift or are set to different time zones without normalization, events that actually happened in one order could appear to have happened in a different, misleading order, undermining the entire timeline's accuracy."},{"text":"That all three systems are running the exact same operating system version, patch level, and vendor build configuration","correct":false,"why":"The operating system each log source runs on has no bearing on whether their reported timestamps can be accurately correlated; the critical factor is time synchronization, not OS uniformity."},{"text":"That the firewall's firmware has been updated to the latest version available from the vendor before proceeding further","correct":false,"why":"Firmware version does not affect whether historical log timestamps can be accurately correlated across systems; the priority is verifying and normalizing time sources, not patch levels."},{"text":"That a completely new vulnerability scan is run against all three systems before any timeline can be built from their logs","correct":false,"why":"Running a vulnerability scan identifies current weaknesses in the systems but does nothing to help correlate historical timestamps from existing log data for timeline reconstruction."}],"id":"q451","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Forensics (EDR Containment vs Evidence)","q":"An EDR platform detects active ransomware encryption in progress on a workstation and offers a one-click 'kill and quarantine' response that immediately terminates the malicious process and isolates the host. The incident response lead hesitates before clicking it. What forensic consideration MOST justifies this hesitation?","options":[{"text":"Immediately killing the process could eliminate volatile evidence in memory that would otherwise help determine the attack's full scope and origin","correct":true,"why":"Abruptly terminating a malicious process can wipe out volatile forensic artifacts, such as in-memory indicators of the initial access vector or command-and-control communication, that would otherwise be invaluable for understanding how the attacker got in and what else they may have touched."},{"text":"The EDR platform does not have sufficient permissions configured to terminate the malicious process running on this workstation","correct":false,"why":"Modern EDR platforms are specifically designed with the necessary permissions to terminate malicious processes; this isn't a technical limitation relevant to the hesitation described."},{"text":"Quarantining the host will automatically delete all of the organization's stored backup copies across every connected system","correct":false,"why":"Isolating a single compromised host from the network has no direct effect on the organization's separate backup systems or their contents."},{"text":"Ransomware cannot be stopped once encryption has begun, making any further response action at this point entirely pointless","correct":false,"why":"Stopping the malicious process, even mid-encryption, can limit the number of files affected, so the response is not pointless; the hesitation is about preserving evidence, not about the futility of containment."}],"id":"q452","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.1","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"Digital Forensics (Legal Hold)","q":"During an active investigation into a data breach potentially involving regulated customer data, legal counsel issues a formal notice requiring that all related emails, logs, and system backups be preserved and excluded from routine deletion schedules until further notice. What is this notice called?","options":[{"text":"A legal hold","correct":true,"why":"A legal hold is the formal notice issued to suspend normal data destruction or retention schedules for information relevant to actual or anticipated litigation or investigation, exactly matching what is described."},{"text":"A vulnerability disclosure","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability disclosure is a notification about a discovered security weakness, typically to affected vendors or the public, and is unrelated to preserving evidence for an investigation."},{"text":"A service level agreement","correct":false,"why":"A service level agreement defines performance expectations between parties for an ongoing service; it has no relationship to suspending data retention schedules for litigation purposes."},{"text":"A penetration test authorization form","correct":false,"why":"A penetration test authorization form grants permission for security testing activities; it is unrelated to preserving evidence during an active breach investigation."}],"id":"q453","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Preparation)","q":"An organization conducts quarterly reviews of its incident response runbooks, ensures contact lists for the response team are current, and verifies that forensic tools are installed and licensed on response laptops, all before any incident has occurred. Which phase of the incident response lifecycle does this activity belong to?","options":[{"text":"Preparation","correct":true,"why":"Preparation is the proactive phase of incident response focused on ensuring tools, documentation, contact lists, and team readiness are all in place before an incident happens, exactly matching the activities described."},{"text":"Containment","correct":false,"why":"Containment refers to actions taken during an active incident to limit its spread, such as isolating affected systems, which is distinct from the proactive readiness activities described here."},{"text":"Eradication","correct":false,"why":"Eradication involves removing the root cause of an incident, such as malware, after it has been identified, not the proactive readiness work done before any incident occurs."},{"text":"Lessons learned","correct":false,"why":"Lessons learned is a post-incident review activity focused on improving future response based on a specific incident that already occurred, not general ongoing readiness maintenance."}],"id":"q454","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Identification)","q":"A SOC analyst receives an alert indicating unusual outbound traffic from a server. Before declaring a formal security incident, the analyst spends 20 minutes reviewing logs, checking whether the traffic matches a known scheduled backup job, and confirming with the system owner whether any legitimate changes were recently made. What phase of incident response does this activity represent?","options":[{"text":"Identification (triage), which distinguishes true incidents from false positives before formal response begins","correct":true,"why":"Identification involves investigating an alert to determine whether it represents a genuine security incident or a false positive/benign explanation, which is exactly what the analyst is doing by checking logs and confirming context before escalating."},{"text":"Eradication, since the analyst is actively removing the threat from the affected server at this stage","correct":false,"why":"Eradication involves actively removing a confirmed threat's root cause; the analyst here has not yet confirmed an incident is occurring and is not taking any removal action."},{"text":"Recovery, since the analyst is restoring the system to normal business operations at this point","correct":false,"why":"Recovery involves restoring affected systems to normal operation after a confirmed incident has been contained and eradicated, which is not what is happening during this initial investigative triage."},{"text":"Lessons learned, since the analyst is documenting findings from a completed response effort","correct":false,"why":"Lessons learned is a formal post-incident review process that happens after an incident has been fully resolved, not the initial triage investigation of a new alert."}],"id":"q455","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Containment Strategy)","q":"During a confirmed ransomware incident, the response team disables the compromised server's network connection immediately to stop the malware from spreading further, while leaving the server itself running so evidence can still be gathered. What term BEST describes this specific action?","options":[{"text":"Short-term (or segmentation-based) containment","correct":true,"why":"Isolating a compromised system from the network while keeping it running to preserve evidence is a classic short-term containment tactic, which limits spread quickly without taking the more disruptive step of full system shutdown or long-term rebuilding."},{"text":"Eradication, since the malicious process and any related artifacts are being permanently removed from the host","correct":false,"why":"Eradication refers to removing the actual root cause of the compromise, such as deleting malware or closing an exploited vulnerability, which is a separate later step from simply isolating the system from the network."},{"text":"Recovery, since the server is being restored to normal production operation after the incident","correct":false,"why":"Recovery involves restoring the system to normal, trusted operation after the threat has been fully removed, which has not yet happened in this scenario where the server is still isolated and under investigation."},{"text":"Lessons learned, since the team is documenting what happened for future process improvement","correct":false,"why":"Lessons learned is a post-incident review activity conducted after the incident is fully resolved, not an in-the-moment containment action taken during active response."}],"id":"q456","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Eradication)","q":"After containing a malware infection on a server by isolating it from the network, the response team identifies the specific malicious executable and the vulnerability that allowed initial access, then removes the malware and applies the missing patch. What incident response phase does this describe?","options":[{"text":"Eradication","correct":true,"why":"Eradication is the phase focused on removing the actual root cause of the compromise, including malicious files and the vulnerability that enabled the attack, which matches removing the executable and patching the exploited flaw."},{"text":"Identification","correct":false,"why":"Identification is the earlier phase of confirming that an incident is actually occurring; this scenario describes actions taken after containment to actively remove the threat's cause, which is eradication, not identification."},{"text":"Preparation","correct":false,"why":"Preparation refers to proactive readiness activities conducted before any incident occurs, not the active removal of malware and patching that happens during response to a confirmed incident."},{"text":"Containment","correct":false,"why":"Containment, described earlier in the scenario as isolating the server, is distinct from eradication, which is the subsequent step of actually removing the malicious code and closing the vulnerability."}],"id":"q457","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Recovery)","q":"After a compromised server has had its malware removed and the exploited vulnerability patched, the team restores the server from a known-clean backup, closely monitors it for several days for any signs of reinfection, and gradually returns it to normal production traffic. What phase does this represent?","options":[{"text":"Recovery","correct":true,"why":"Recovery is the phase focused on restoring affected systems to normal, trusted operation, typically including restoring from clean backups and closely monitoring for signs the threat has returned, exactly matching this scenario."},{"text":"Containment","correct":false,"why":"Containment refers to the earlier action of limiting the spread of an active threat, such as isolating a system, which has already been completed by the time restoration and monitoring for reinfection begins."},{"text":"Identification","correct":false,"why":"Identification is the initial phase of confirming an incident is occurring, which happens well before the later steps of restoring a system from backup and monitoring it during recovery."},{"text":"Preparation","correct":false,"why":"Preparation involves proactive readiness activities conducted before any incident occurs, not the post-eradication restoration and monitoring activities described in this scenario."}],"id":"q458","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Lessons Learned)","q":"Two weeks after a significant security incident has been fully resolved, the response team holds a meeting to review what happened, identify what worked well, pinpoint gaps in detection or process, and update the incident response plan accordingly. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this meeting?","options":[{"text":"To improve future incident response effectiveness by turning the experience into concrete process and documentation improvements","correct":true,"why":"The lessons learned meeting exists specifically to convert the experience of a real incident into actionable improvements, such as closing detection gaps or refining runbooks, so the organization responds more effectively to future incidents."},{"text":"To assign formal blame to the individual analyst who happened to miss the initial detection alert","correct":false,"why":"A well-run lessons learned process focuses on improving processes and systems rather than assigning personal blame, since a blame-focused culture discourages honest reporting and reduces the meeting's actual value."},{"text":"To restore the affected systems to production use following completion of the incident response","correct":false,"why":"Restoring systems to production is part of the earlier recovery phase, which is completed well before a lessons learned meeting is held after the incident is fully resolved."},{"text":"To formally notify regulators about the incident as required under applicable data breach law","correct":false,"why":"Regulatory notification is a distinct compliance and communication obligation that occurs on its own timeline, separate from the internal lessons learned review meeting focused on process improvement."}],"id":"q459","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Escalation Criteria)","q":"An organization's incident response plan defines specific criteria for when an incident must be escalated to executive leadership, such as confirmed exposure of regulated data, expected downtime exceeding four hours, or media inquiries. What is the PRIMARY benefit of defining these criteria in advance?","options":[{"text":"It ensures consistent, timely escalation decisions rather than relying on ad hoc judgment calls during the stress of an active incident","correct":true,"why":"Predefined escalation criteria remove ambiguity and pressure-driven guesswork during a live incident, ensuring that severe incidents reliably reach the right decision-makers quickly and consistently, regardless of which analyst is handling the response."},{"text":"It eliminates the need for the organization to maintain any documented incident response plan altogether","correct":false,"why":"Escalation criteria are one component within a broader incident response plan, not a replacement for it; the plan still needs to cover identification, containment, eradication, and other phases."},{"text":"It guarantees that no security incident will ever be severe enough to reach executive leadership","correct":false,"why":"The purpose of escalation criteria is the opposite of avoiding executive involvement; it ensures that incidents meeting specific severity thresholds DO reach leadership promptly and reliably."},{"text":"It removes the need for any technical containment or eradication steps during a real incident","correct":false,"why":"Escalation criteria govern communication and decision-making thresholds; they have no bearing on whether technical containment and eradication steps are still required to actually resolve the incident."}],"id":"q460","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Tabletop Exercise)","q":"A security team gathers stakeholders from IT, legal, communications, and executive leadership in a conference room to walk through a simulated ransomware scenario, discussing decisions and responses at each stage without touching any actual production systems. What is the PRIMARY value of this exercise?","options":[{"text":"It identifies gaps in the response plan, communication paths, and decision-making authority in a low-risk setting before a real incident occurs","correct":true,"why":"Tabletop exercises let an organization discover confusion about roles, missing escalation paths, or unclear decision authority in a safe, discussion-based setting, which is far cheaper and less risky than discovering those gaps for the first time during an actual live incident."},{"text":"It permanently patches all of the technical vulnerabilities that happened to be discussed during the tabletop exercise itself","correct":false,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based simulation with no interaction with real systems; it does not involve or result in any actual technical patching of vulnerabilities."},{"text":"It satisfies the organization's formal compliance requirement to perform an annual penetration test against production","correct":false,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based planning activity, fundamentally different from a penetration test, which involves actively attempting to exploit real systems; one does not substitute for the other."},{"text":"It replaces the ongoing organizational need to maintain a written, up-to-date incident response plan document","correct":false,"why":"A tabletop exercise tests and improves an existing incident response plan; it does not replace the need for the plan to exist and be documented in writing."}],"id":"q461","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Incident Commander Role)","q":"During a multi-system security incident involving several response team members working in parallel, one individual is designated to make final decisions, coordinate communication between technical teams and leadership, and ensure the overall response stays on track. What role does this person hold?","options":[{"text":"Incident commander","correct":true,"why":"The incident commander is the designated individual responsible for overall coordination, final decision-making authority, and communication management during an incident, exactly matching the role described."},{"text":"Threat hunter","correct":false,"why":"A threat hunter proactively searches for hidden threats within an environment using hypothesis-driven techniques; this is a distinct specialist role, not the overall coordination and decision-making role described."},{"text":"Penetration tester","correct":false,"why":"A penetration tester conducts authorized simulated attacks to find vulnerabilities; this role is unrelated to coordinating a live incident response effort."},{"text":"Compliance auditor","correct":false,"why":"A compliance auditor evaluates adherence to regulatory or policy requirements; this is a distinct function from the real-time coordination and decision-making role of an incident commander during an active incident."}],"id":"q462","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Scope Determination)","q":"After discovering a compromised workstation, an analyst is trying to determine whether the attacker moved laterally to other systems before being detected. Which activity is MOST directly focused on answering this specific question?","options":[{"text":"Reviewing authentication and network connection logs across other systems for activity originating from the compromised host or using stolen credentials","correct":true,"why":"Determining lateral movement requires tracing whether the compromised host's credentials or network connections touched other systems, which is done by correlating authentication and connection logs across the broader environment, directly answering the scope question."},{"text":"Updating the organization's acceptable use policy to reflect newly identified employee behaviors observed elsewhere","correct":false,"why":"Updating a policy document is an administrative and governance task with no direct bearing on investigating whether an attacker moved laterally within the environment."},{"text":"Scheduling the organization's next quarterly vulnerability scan across all business units and remote office locations","correct":false,"why":"A future scheduled scan does not help determine what already happened during an active compromise; scope determination requires reviewing existing logs and evidence from the relevant timeframe."},{"text":"Renewing the organization's cyber insurance policy well ahead of the upcoming annual coverage expiration date","correct":false,"why":"Insurance renewal is a business and risk transfer activity unrelated to the technical investigative work of determining how far an attacker's access actually spread."}],"id":"q463","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Communication with Legal/PR)","q":"During a confirmed breach involving customer personal data, the incident response lead ensures that legal counsel and the communications team are looped in early, before any public statement or regulatory notification is drafted. What is the MOST important reason for involving these teams early rather than after technical remediation is complete?","options":[{"text":"Legal and regulatory notification obligations often have strict timelines that start from the moment of discovery, and premature or inaccurate public statements can create legal and reputational risk","correct":true,"why":"Many data breach notification laws start the compliance clock from the moment a breach is discovered, not from when remediation finishes, and statements made without legal and communications input can be inaccurate or create additional liability, making early involvement essential rather than optional."},{"text":"Legal and communications teams are primarily responsible for actually patching the specific technical vulnerability that attackers exploited during the breach","correct":false,"why":"Patching the technical vulnerability is a responsibility of the technical response team, not legal or communications staff; their role is managing regulatory, legal, and public messaging obligations, not technical remediation."},{"text":"Involving them early in the process eliminates the need for any further technical investigation into exactly how the breach occurred in the first place","correct":false,"why":"Legal and communications involvement runs in parallel with, not instead of, the technical investigation and remediation work, both of which are still fully required regardless of when these teams are looped in."},{"text":"Regulatory notification requirements only apply once the media independently becomes aware of the breach and chooses to report on it publicly themselves","correct":false,"why":"Regulatory notification obligations are generally triggered by the nature and scope of the breach itself, not by whether the media has learned about it, making early legal involvement important regardless of media attention."}],"id":"q464","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Multiple Simultaneous Incidents)","q":"A SOC is simultaneously handling a low-severity phishing report, a confirmed malware infection on a single non-critical workstation, and unconfirmed but suspicious activity suggesting active exfiltration from a database containing regulated customer records. With limited analyst staff available, how should the team prioritize these three situations?","options":[{"text":"Prioritize the suspected database exfiltration first, given its potential severity and regulated data exposure, even though it is not yet fully confirmed","correct":true,"why":"Prioritization should be driven by potential business impact and data sensitivity, not just by confirmation status; a plausible active exfiltration event involving regulated data carries far greater potential consequence than a confirmed but contained low-severity malware case or a routine phishing report, justifying immediate attention despite some uncertainty."},{"text":"Prioritize strictly in the order the three reports were originally received, regardless of their relative severity","correct":false,"why":"First-come, first-served handling ignores relative severity and potential impact, which can leave a high-consequence event like potential data exfiltration under-resourced while lower-impact issues are addressed first."},{"text":"Ignore the phishing report and the malware infection entirely until the database issue is fully resolved first","correct":false,"why":"Completely ignoring the other incidents risks allowing the malware infection to spread further or the phishing campaign to claim more victims; proper prioritization means allocating more resources to the highest-impact issue, not abandoning the others."},{"text":"Assign all three issues to a single available analyst to handle sequentially, one at a time, in any order","correct":false,"why":"Handling significant, differently-natured incidents strictly sequentially with a single analyst wastes available team capacity and delays response to the more severe potential data exfiltration issue; available staff should be allocated based on relative priority."}],"id":"q465","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Post-Incident Report)","q":"Following the resolution of a significant security incident, the response team produces a formal document detailing the timeline of events, root cause, systems affected, actions taken, and recommendations for preventing recurrence. Who is this document PRIMARILY intended to inform?","options":[{"text":"A range of stakeholders including leadership, technical teams, and potentially auditors or regulators, depending on the incident's severity and requirements","correct":true,"why":"A formal post-incident report serves multiple audiences: leadership needs the business impact summary, technical teams need the root cause and remediation details to prevent recurrence, and depending on severity and regulatory context, auditors or regulators may also require the documentation."},{"text":"Only the single analyst who initially detected the incident and opened the original investigation ticket in the queue","correct":false,"why":"A formal post-incident report is a shared organizational document meant for broader distribution to relevant stakeholders, not a private record intended solely for the individual who happened to first notice the incident."},{"text":"Only the vendor whose product was exploited during the incident, so their engineers alone can patch the underlying software","correct":false,"why":"While a report might reference a vendor's product, it is an internal (and sometimes regulatory) organizational document, not a deliverable created specifically and solely for an external vendor."},{"text":"No one; the document is created purely to satisfy an internal filing requirement and is never actually reviewed by anyone","correct":false,"why":"Post-incident reports are meant to be actively used to drive improvements in security posture and inform stakeholders, not simply filed away unread; treating them as a pure formality defeats their core purpose."}],"id":"q466","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.1","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","q":"After a vulnerability assessment identifies a newly discovered flaw in a critical but hard-to-patch legacy system, the security team adds it to a centralized document tracking its likelihood, potential impact, current mitigation status, and assigned owner. What is this document called?","options":[{"text":"A risk register","correct":true,"why":"A risk register is the centralized tracking document used to record identified risks along with their likelihood, impact, mitigation status, and ownership, exactly matching what's described for the newly discovered vulnerability."},{"text":"An incident response plan","correct":false,"why":"An incident response plan defines how the organization responds to active security incidents; it does not function as an ongoing tracking log for identified risks and their mitigation status."},{"text":"A penetration test report","correct":false,"why":"A penetration test report documents findings from a specific testing engagement; it is a point-in-time deliverable, not the centralized, ongoing risk-tracking document described."},{"text":"A business continuity plan","correct":false,"why":"A business continuity plan defines how the organization maintains operations during a disruption; it is not the specific tool used to track individual risk items like a newly found vulnerability."}],"id":"q467","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.1","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","q":"A CISO presents two options to the executive team for addressing a moderate risk: spend $200,000 to fully remediate it, or formally accept the risk with documented sign-off given its low likelihood of exploitation and limited potential impact. The executive team chooses to formally accept the risk. What must happen NEXT to properly manage this decision?","options":[{"text":"The risk acceptance decision should be documented, including the rationale, decision-maker, and a scheduled date to revisit the decision","correct":true,"why":"Formally accepting a risk isn't a one-time, informal choice; it needs to be documented with clear ownership and rationale, and revisited periodically, since circumstances (likelihood, impact, or available mitigations) can change over time and the acceptance should be reevaluated."},{"text":"The risk should be immediately removed from the risk register entirely since it has now been formally accepted","correct":false,"why":"Accepting a risk does not mean it disappears or should be untracked; it should remain in the risk register with its accepted status clearly noted so it continues to be monitored and periodically reevaluated."},{"text":"The $200,000 remediation budget should be spent anyway despite the executive decision to accept the risk instead","correct":false,"why":"Spending the remediation budget after the executive team has explicitly decided to accept the risk instead contradicts the decision that was just made and wastes the resources the acceptance was meant to avoid spending."},{"text":"No further action is needed since executives are not required to justify or revisit their risk decisions later","correct":false,"why":"Executive risk decisions still need to be documented and justified for accountability, audit, and future reevaluation purposes; treating the decision as needing no further action or documentation undermines proper risk governance."}],"id":"q468","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.1","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","q":"A security manager describes an organization's risk appetite as 'moderate' but its risk tolerance for any risk affecting regulated customer data as 'very low.' A new vendor integration is proposed that would give a third party direct access to regulated financial records, carrying a risk level the team considers 'moderate.' How should this be evaluated given the stated tolerances?","options":[{"text":"The integration should be flagged for additional scrutiny or rejected, since it involves regulated data where the organization's specific tolerance is far stricter than its general risk appetite","correct":true,"why":"Risk appetite is the organization's general willingness to accept risk, while risk tolerance defines acceptable variation for specific risk categories; when a specific category like regulated data has a much lower tolerance than the general appetite, a 'moderate' risk affecting that category should be evaluated against the stricter, category-specific tolerance, not the general appetite."},{"text":"The integration should proceed without modification, since a 'moderate' risk rating fits within the organization's stated general 'moderate' risk appetite","correct":false,"why":"Applying only the general risk appetite ignores the organization's own stated, stricter tolerance specifically for risks touching regulated customer data, which should govern this particular decision instead."},{"text":"Risk appetite and risk tolerance are simply the same underlying concept described using different words, so this distinction doesn't matter here","correct":false,"why":"Risk appetite and risk tolerance are related but distinct concepts; appetite is the broad, general risk-taking stance, while tolerance defines acceptable boundaries for specific categories, and conflating them can lead to inappropriate risk decisions like this one."},{"text":"The integration should be approved automatically since the access request originates from an external vendor rather than an internal system team","correct":false,"why":"The source of the risk (vendor versus internal) does not change the fact that it involves regulated data subject to a specific, stricter tolerance; vendor relationships still need to be evaluated against the same risk criteria."}],"id":"q469","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.1","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","q":"A security analyst prepares a report for the board of directors summarizing the organization's top risks. Rather than presenting raw CVSS scores and technical vulnerability counts, the analyst translates the risks into potential financial impact, likelihood expressed in plain terms, and business consequences. What is the PRIMARY reason for this translation?","options":[{"text":"Board members typically need risk communicated in business and financial terms to make informed strategic decisions, rather than raw technical metrics","correct":true,"why":"Effective risk communication is tailored to the audience; board members are generally responsible for strategic and financial decisions, not technical remediation, so translating technical risk data into business impact and financial terms allows them to make informed governance decisions."},{"text":"CVSS scores are classified information under federal law that legally cannot be shared with board members under any circumstances at all","correct":false,"why":"CVSS scores are a standard, publicly documented scoring system and are not classified; the reason for translating them isn't confidentiality, but ensuring the board can understand and act on the information in business terms."},{"text":"Technical vulnerability counts are always fundamentally inaccurate and therefore should never be reported to any audience whatsoever","correct":false,"why":"Vulnerability counts and CVSS scores are legitimate and useful technical metrics for technical teams; the issue isn't their accuracy, but that they aren't the most effective format for a board-level, business-focused audience."},{"text":"The board of directors is legally prohibited from receiving any security-related information whatsoever, regardless of its sensitivity level","correct":false,"why":"Boards of directors generally have both the authority and, in many governance frameworks, a responsibility to receive security risk information; there is no prohibition, only a need to present it in an appropriately business-oriented format."}],"id":"q470","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.1","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Managing Risk","q":"A department head wants to bypass the standard risk assessment process and immediately deploy a new third-party application that would have access to sensitive employee data, citing an urgent business need. What is the MOST appropriate way for the security team to handle this request?","options":[{"text":"Perform an expedited but still documented risk assessment, and escalate the decision to appropriate risk owners if the timeline genuinely cannot accommodate a full review","correct":true,"why":"Urgent business needs don't eliminate the need for risk evaluation and proper escalation; an expedited, documented review with appropriate sign-off balances the legitimate time pressure with the organization's responsibility to understand and formally accept whatever risk is being taken on."},{"text":"Approve the deployment immediately with absolutely no review at all, since the department head already has the authority to make this specific request","correct":false,"why":"Bypassing risk assessment entirely, even under time pressure, risks deploying a system with sensitive data access without any understanding or formal acceptance of the associated risk, which undermines the organization's risk management process."},{"text":"Deny the request permanently and refuse to ever revisit it under any future circumstances, regardless of any additional justification provided","correct":false,"why":"An outright permanent denial without any expedited review process fails to balance legitimate business needs with risk management, and doesn't offer a constructive path forward for a genuinely urgent situation."},{"text":"Let the department head decide unilaterally whether the risk is acceptable, without involving security or any designated risk owners at all","correct":false,"why":"Allowing a single department head to make an isolated risk acceptance decision, especially one involving sensitive employee data, bypasses the proper risk governance structure that should involve appropriate risk owners and documented sign-off."}],"id":"q471","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (PCI DSS)","q":"A retail company wants to reduce the scope of systems subject to PCI DSS compliance requirements. Which approach would MOST directly achieve this goal?","options":[{"text":"Use a third-party, PCI-compliant payment processor so cardholder data never touches the company's own systems","correct":true,"why":"PCI DSS scope is determined by which systems store, process, or transmit cardholder data; outsourcing payment handling entirely to a compliant processor so card data never enters the company's own environment is the most direct way to shrink that scope."},{"text":"Store all cardholder data in a single, well-documented database to simplify ongoing compliance reporting efforts","correct":false,"why":"Consolidating cardholder data into one database may simplify management, but every system that stores, processes, or transmits that data still falls within PCI DSS scope; it doesn't reduce the scope itself, and could even concentrate risk."},{"text":"Encrypt all cardholder data using a weak, outdated cipher in order to reduce processing overhead on servers","correct":false,"why":"Using outdated or weak encryption does not reduce compliance scope and directly conflicts with PCI DSS requirements for strong cryptography to protect cardholder data."},{"text":"Increase the number of employees who have direct access to cardholder data in order to provide staffing redundancy","correct":false,"why":"Expanding the number of people with access to cardholder data increases risk and typically increases compliance burden and scope, rather than reducing it."}],"id":"q472","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (HIPAA / Privacy)","q":"A healthcare provider discovers that an employee's laptop containing unencrypted patient records was stolen from their car. Under HIPAA, what is the organization generally required to do regarding this event?","options":[{"text":"Assess whether the incident constitutes a reportable breach and, if so, notify affected individuals and regulators within required timeframes","correct":true,"why":"HIPAA requires covered entities to assess incidents involving protected health information for breach notification obligations, and if the assessment confirms a reportable breach, notify affected individuals and the Department of Health and Human Services within specific mandated timeframes."},{"text":"Wait until the organization's next annual security review before taking any action to address the incident","correct":false,"why":"HIPAA breach notification has specific, much shorter mandated timeframes than an annual review cycle; waiting for an annual review would violate those requirements if the incident is determined to be a reportable breach."},{"text":"Only notify law enforcement about the theft, since HIPAA does not require notifying the affected patients directly","correct":false,"why":"HIPAA specifically requires notifying affected individuals (patients) in addition to regulators when a reportable breach of protected health information occurs; notifying only law enforcement would not satisfy this obligation."},{"text":"Take no action at all since the stolen laptop was the employee's personal property, not the organization's","correct":false,"why":"HIPAA obligations are tied to whether protected health information was involved and exposed, not to who owned the physical device; a covered entity is still responsible for assessing and responding to this exposure regardless of device ownership."}],"id":"q473","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (GDPR / Data Minimization)","q":"A European customer emails a company requesting a copy of all personal data the company holds about them, as well as deletion of that data. Under GDPR, what are these requests known as?","options":[{"text":"Data subject rights (specifically, the right of access and the right to erasure)","correct":true,"why":"GDPR grants individuals specific data subject rights, including the right of access (to obtain a copy of their data) and the right to erasure (commonly called the 'right to be forgotten'), which directly match the two requests described."},{"text":"A penetration test request submitted through the company's standard security testing intake process","correct":false,"why":"A penetration test request would involve authorization for security testing of systems; it has no relationship to an individual requesting access to or deletion of their own personal data under privacy law."},{"text":"A change management request submitted through the company's standard IT change control process","correct":false,"why":"A change management request relates to proposed modifications to IT systems or infrastructure; it is unrelated to an individual exercising personal data rights under GDPR."},{"text":"A vulnerability disclosure request submitted through the company's responsible disclosure program","correct":false,"why":"A vulnerability disclosure request concerns reporting a security weakness in a product or system; it is unrelated to an individual's request to access or delete their personal data."}],"id":"q474","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Data Classification)","q":"An organization labels its documents as Public, Internal, Confidential, or Restricted, with each label dictating specific handling rules such as encryption requirements, approved storage locations, and who may access the data. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this labeling system?","options":[{"text":"To ensure data is handled, stored, and protected according to its sensitivity, applying stronger controls to more sensitive information","correct":true,"why":"Data classification systems exist to tie the level of protection applied to information directly to its sensitivity, ensuring highly sensitive data (like Restricted) receives stronger controls than low-sensitivity data (like Public), which is efficient and risk-appropriate."},{"text":"To make internal documents easier for employees to locate quickly using the company's internal search engine and indexing tool","correct":false,"why":"While labels can aid searchability as a side effect, the core security purpose of a data classification scheme is to drive appropriate handling and protection controls based on sensitivity, not to optimize search functionality."},{"text":"To determine which employees receive performance bonuses based specifically on how they handled sensitive data during the year","correct":false,"why":"Data classification labels govern how information should be handled and protected; they have no connection to employee performance evaluation or compensation decisions."},{"text":"To reduce the total amount of storage space that a labeled document consumes on the company's shared network servers","correct":false,"why":"Classification labeling does not affect file size or storage consumption; its purpose is governing handling and protection requirements based on sensitivity level, not optimizing storage."}],"id":"q475","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Retention / Disposal)","q":"A company's data retention policy states that customer support tickets should be deleted after three years. However, a legal hold has been issued covering a specific set of tickets related to an ongoing lawsuit. What should happen to the tickets covered by the legal hold when the standard three-year retention period expires?","options":[{"text":"They must be preserved and excluded from deletion until the legal hold is formally lifted, regardless of the standard retention schedule","correct":true,"why":"A legal hold overrides normal retention and deletion schedules for the specific data it covers; deleting held records simply because a routine retention period expired could constitute unlawful spoliation of evidence and expose the organization to serious legal consequences."},{"text":"They should be deleted on schedule exactly as required by the company's standard three-year retention policy","correct":false,"why":"Following the standard retention schedule and deleting data actively under legal hold would violate the preservation obligation the hold created, regardless of what the normal policy states."},{"text":"They should be immediately handed over to the opposing party named in the ongoing lawsuit without delay","correct":false,"why":"A legal hold requires preservation of the data, not automatic disclosure to an opposing party; actual production of evidence follows separate legal discovery procedures, not automatic transfer upon a hold being issued."},{"text":"They should be anonymized so that they technically no longer count as the same records under the hold","correct":false,"why":"Altering or anonymizing records under legal hold would compromise their evidentiary value and could itself be viewed as improper tampering with evidence subject to a preservation obligation."}],"id":"q476","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (NIST / Control Families)","q":"An organization adopts a well-known framework that organizes security requirements into control families such as Access Control, Incident Response, and Risk Assessment, and uses it to structure its overall security program and assess maturity. What is this an example of?","options":[{"text":"Adopting a security control framework (such as NIST) to structure and benchmark the security program","correct":true,"why":"Organizing a security program around a structured set of control families and using it to assess maturity is exactly how frameworks like NIST are used in practice, providing a standardized structure for building and measuring a security program."},{"text":"Performing a penetration test against the organization's production network and internet-facing systems","correct":false,"why":"A penetration test is a specific technical testing activity; adopting a broad structural framework to organize an entire security program is a governance activity, not a testing engagement."},{"text":"Conducting a tabletop exercise that walks stakeholders through a simulated incident response scenario","correct":false,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based incident response simulation; it is unrelated to adopting a structural framework of control families to organize a security program."},{"text":"Performing digital forensics on a compromised system as part of an active incident investigation","correct":false,"why":"Digital forensics involves investigating specific security incidents through evidence collection and analysis; it is unrelated to adopting a broad governance framework to structure a security program."}],"id":"q477","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.2","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Data Standards (Cross-Border Transfer)","q":"A US-based company plans to transfer European customers' personal data to a data center located outside the European Economic Area for processing. What compliance concern is MOST directly raised by this plan?","options":[{"text":"GDPR restrictions on international data transfers, which may require specific safeguards or legal mechanisms before the transfer can occur","correct":true,"why":"GDPR places specific restrictions on transferring personal data of EU residents outside the European Economic Area, generally requiring approved safeguards (such as standard contractual clauses or an adequacy decision) before such a transfer is permitted, making this the most directly relevant concern."},{"text":"The data center's physical building must be certified LEED Gold for environmental sustainability standards","correct":false,"why":"Environmental building certifications relate to sustainability standards and have no relevance to the legal compliance concerns around transferring personal data across international borders."},{"text":"The transfer will automatically void the company's existing cyber insurance policy coverage terms","correct":false,"why":"While cross-border data handling might be a factor an insurer considers in some circumstances, it does not automatically void a policy, and this isn't the primary or most directly applicable compliance concern for this scenario."},{"text":"US companies are legally prohibited from operating any data centers located outside the United States","correct":false,"why":"There is no blanket US legal prohibition on companies operating data centers outside the country; the relevant concern here is the destination jurisdiction's data protection requirements (GDPR), not a US-side restriction on overseas operations."}],"id":"q478","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"An organization's security team publishes a high-level document stating that 'all employees must protect the confidentiality of customer data,' without specifying exact technical steps. A separate, more detailed document then explains the exact configuration steps required to encrypt customer databases. What are these two documents called, respectively?","options":[{"text":"A policy, followed by a procedure","correct":true,"why":"A policy states a high-level mandatory requirement or intent ('must protect confidentiality') without prescribing specific steps, while a procedure provides the detailed, step-by-step instructions for how to actually accomplish that requirement, matching the two documents described."},{"text":"A guideline, followed by a standard","correct":false,"why":"A guideline offers optional, recommended advice rather than a mandatory requirement, and a standard specifies mandatory technical parameters; neither label fits as precisely as policy (mandatory high-level requirement) and procedure (detailed steps) for the documents described."},{"text":"A procedure, followed by a policy","correct":false,"why":"This reverses the actual relationship; the high-level mandatory statement is the policy, and the detailed step-by-step instructions are the procedure, not the other way around."},{"text":"A risk register, followed by an incident response plan","correct":false,"why":"Neither document described is a risk register (which tracks specific risk items) or an incident response plan (which defines incident handling); they are a governance policy and its supporting procedure."}],"id":"q479","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A security exception request is submitted asking to bypass the organization's standard patching policy for a legacy system that cannot be patched without breaking a critical business process. Which governance structure is MOST appropriate for evaluating and approving this exception?","options":[{"text":"A formal exception process reviewed by a governance body (such as a risk or change advisory committee) that documents the exception, required compensating controls, and an expiration or review date","correct":true,"why":"Legitimate exceptions to security policy should go through a formal, documented governance process rather than an informal one-off decision, ensuring the risk is understood, compensating controls (like additional network isolation) are applied, and the exception is periodically reevaluated rather than becoming permanent by default."},{"text":"The system administrator should quietly disable patching on the legacy system without informing anyone else in the organization at all about the change","correct":false,"why":"Making an undocumented, unilateral decision to bypass policy removes any organizational visibility into the risk being accepted and eliminates accountability, which defeats the purpose of having a governance process at all."},{"text":"The exception should be automatically denied with absolutely no review process whatsoever, regardless of the actual business impact or urgency involved","correct":false,"why":"A blanket automatic denial without any review process fails to account for legitimate business constraints and doesn't provide a path to formally accept and manage a necessary risk with appropriate compensating controls."},{"text":"Any single employee should be able to grant themselves a permanent policy exception without any oversight, approval, or documentation whatsoever","correct":false,"why":"Allowing an individual to self-approve a permanent exception with no oversight removes the accountability and periodic reevaluation that proper governance requires, especially for something as significant as bypassing standard patching."}],"id":"q480","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"In a well-designed change management process, the person who develops and tests a code change is generally not the same person who has final authority to approve and deploy it to production. What governance principle does this separation reflect?","options":[{"text":"Segregation of duties","correct":true,"why":"Segregation of duties is the governance principle of splitting critical tasks (like developing and approving a change) between different individuals so that no single person has unchecked control over the entire process, reducing the risk of error or malicious action going undetected."},{"text":"Risk acceptance","correct":false,"why":"Risk acceptance refers to a formal decision to tolerate a known risk rather than mitigate it; it is a distinct concept from structurally separating who performs a task from who approves it."},{"text":"Data minimization","correct":false,"why":"Data minimization is the principle of collecting and retaining only the data necessary for a specific purpose; it is unrelated to separating development and approval responsibilities in a change process."},{"text":"Business impact analysis","correct":false,"why":"A business impact analysis evaluates the consequences of a disruption to business functions; it does not describe the structural separation of development and approval roles in change management."}],"id":"q481","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"An organization's information security policy has not been reviewed or updated in seven years, despite significant changes in the threat landscape, adopted cloud services, and regulatory requirements during that time. What governance practice was MOST clearly neglected?","options":[{"text":"Periodic policy review and revision on a defined cadence to keep governance documents current with the organization's actual environment and risk landscape","correct":true,"why":"Effective governance requires that policies be reviewed and updated on a defined, recurring schedule to remain relevant as the organization, its technology, and the surrounding threat and regulatory landscape evolve; a seven-year gap indicates this review cadence was not maintained."},{"text":"Encrypting data at rest across all company systems using industry-standard, currently approved encryption algorithms and key lengths","correct":false,"why":"Data encryption is a specific technical control, not the governance practice of periodically reviewing and updating policy documents, which is the gap actually described in this scenario."},{"text":"Conducting a penetration test against the organization's production network and all internet-facing systems and applications","correct":false,"why":"Penetration testing evaluates technical security posture through simulated attacks; it does not address the separate governance issue of policies going years without formal review and revision."},{"text":"Issuing multi-factor authentication tokens or app-based push prompts to every employee across the entire organization","correct":false,"why":"MFA deployment is an access control implementation detail, not the governance practice of maintaining a regular policy review cycle, which is the specific gap highlighted in the scenario."}],"id":"q482","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A company's security policy states that only the Chief Information Security Officer can approve exceptions to the encryption standard, while the IT operations team is responsible for actually implementing approved exceptions. Later, an auditor discovers the CISO's direct report has been both requesting and approving their own exceptions without any additional oversight. What governance issue does this represent?","options":[{"text":"A conflict of interest resulting from inadequate segregation of duties in the exception approval process","correct":true,"why":"When the same individual can both request and approve their own exceptions, there is no independent check on that decision, creating a conflict of interest and a breakdown in the segregation of duties the governance structure was meant to enforce."},{"text":"A properly functioning governance process, since the CISO's direct report has been given delegated approval authority","correct":false,"why":"The policy explicitly assigns exception approval authority to the CISO specifically, not to their direct reports; self-approval by someone who should only be requesting exceptions is a governance failure, not a properly functioning delegated process."},{"text":"An issue that only affects the organization's physical security posture and building access controls","correct":false,"why":"This is a governance and process integrity issue related to how encryption exceptions are approved, not a physical security matter like building access or environmental controls."},{"text":"A data classification labeling error found during the same audit that reviewed the exception process","correct":false,"why":"Data classification concerns how information is labeled and handled based on sensitivity; this scenario is about who has authority to approve policy exceptions, an unrelated governance control issue."}],"id":"q483","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A newly hired compliance officer is confused about the difference between the organization's information security governance function and its day-to-day security operations function. Which example BEST illustrates the distinction between governance and operations?","options":[{"text":"Governance sets the policy requiring quarterly access reviews and approves the overall access control strategy; operations actually performs the reviews and adjusts individual user permissions","correct":true,"why":"Governance is about setting direction, policy, and strategic oversight (deciding that reviews must happen and approving the approach), while operations is about the hands-on execution of that direction (actually conducting the reviews and making the permission changes), which is the core distinction between the two functions."},{"text":"Governance and operations are actually the exact same function, performed by the same team with no meaningful distinction between the two roles at all","correct":false,"why":"Governance and operations are distinct functions in a mature security program; governance focuses on policy, oversight, and strategic direction, while operations focuses on the tactical, day-to-day execution of security tasks, and conflating them undermines proper oversight."},{"text":"Governance only applies to the organization's physical security guards, while operations applies to all of the company's digital systems instead entirely","correct":false,"why":"Governance and operations both apply broadly across physical and digital security domains; the distinction is about the nature of the activity (strategic oversight versus tactical execution), not which domain (physical versus digital) it applies to."},{"text":"Governance is performed exclusively by external auditors hired periodically, and is never handled by any internal staff members at the company at all","correct":false,"why":"While external auditors may assess governance effectiveness, governance itself (setting policy, risk appetite, and oversight structures) is typically performed by internal leadership and dedicated governance bodies, not exclusively by outside auditors."}],"id":"q484","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A board of directors requests that the CISO present a security governance update at every quarterly board meeting, covering key risk indicators, policy exceptions granted, and progress against the security roadmap. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this recurring reporting cadence?","options":[{"text":"To maintain ongoing executive-level visibility and accountability over the organization's security posture and governance decisions","correct":true,"why":"Regular governance reporting to the board ensures that security risk, exceptions, and strategic progress remain visible at the highest level of the organization on an ongoing basis, supporting informed oversight and accountability rather than leaving security governance invisible until a crisis forces attention."},{"text":"To replace the need for the CISO to have any communication with the security team between board meetings","correct":false,"why":"Quarterly board reporting is a high-level oversight mechanism; it does not replace the CISO's ongoing, much more frequent operational communication and engagement with their own security team."},{"text":"To satisfy a requirement that boards must approve every individual security patch before deployment","correct":false,"why":"Boards are not typically involved in approving individual technical actions like specific patches; their governance role is strategic oversight, not granular technical decision-making, which remains with operational teams."},{"text":"To eliminate the need for the organization to maintain a written risk register","correct":false,"why":"Board reporting on key risk indicators actually depends on having an underlying risk register or similar tracking mechanism to draw from; it does not eliminate the need for that documentation to exist."}],"id":"q485","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"An organization is evaluating its security governance maturity and finds that policies exist and are followed inconsistently across departments, with no formal metrics tracking compliance or effectiveness. According to common governance maturity models, what would be the NEXT logical improvement step?","options":[{"text":"Standardize policy enforcement across departments and introduce measurable metrics to track compliance and effectiveness consistently","correct":true,"why":"Moving from inconsistent, ad hoc policy application toward standardized, consistently enforced, and measured governance is the typical next maturity step, since introducing metrics and consistency allows the organization to actually assess whether its governance is working and improve it over time."},{"text":"Eliminate all written policies entirely since they are not being followed consistently across departments anyway","correct":false,"why":"Removing policy documentation entirely would move the organization backward in maturity, not forward; the appropriate response to inconsistent enforcement is standardizing and measuring compliance, not abandoning governance altogether."},{"text":"Immediately outsource the entire security function to a third-party provider instead of fixing internal process","correct":false,"why":"Outsourcing the security function doesn't inherently solve inconsistent policy enforcement or a lack of metrics; the underlying governance maturity issue would need to be addressed with the vendor as well, making this a non-answer to the specific gap identified."},{"text":"Stop conducting any further governance maturity assessments going forward since the results were disappointing","correct":false,"why":"Discontinuing maturity assessments would remove the very mechanism that identified this gap in the first place, making it impossible to track whether future improvements are actually effective."}],"id":"q486","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"1.9","objective":"1.0","objectiveName":"Security Operations","topic":"SOAR (Automation)","q":"A security team measures the average time between an alert firing and containment action being taken. Before implementing SOAR automation, this averaged 45 minutes; after implementing automated containment playbooks for well-defined scenarios, it dropped to under two minutes for those same scenarios. Which metric is being used to demonstrate the automation's value?","options":[{"text":"Mean time to respond (or contain)","correct":true,"why":"Mean time to respond/contain measures the average elapsed time between detection and response action, which is exactly the before-and-after comparison being used here to demonstrate the automation playbook's impact."},{"text":"CVSS base score","correct":false,"why":"CVSS base score measures the theoretical severity of a specific vulnerability; it has no relationship to measuring how quickly an organization responds to and contains an alert."},{"text":"Risk appetite","correct":false,"why":"Risk appetite describes an organization's general willingness to accept risk; it is a governance concept, not a time-based operational metric like the one being measured here."},{"text":"Data retention period","correct":false,"why":"Data retention period defines how long records are kept before disposal; it is unrelated to measuring the speed of incident response actions."}],"id":"q487","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Communication Plan)","q":"An organization's incident response plan includes a predefined communication matrix specifying exactly who needs to be notified, through what channel, and within what timeframe for incidents of varying severity, ranging from a simple internal email for low-severity events to an emergency conference bridge for critical ones. What is the PRIMARY benefit of defining this in advance?","options":[{"text":"It removes ambiguity about who to contact and how during the stress of an active incident, ensuring timely and appropriate communication","correct":true,"why":"Pre-defining communication paths and timeframes for each severity level ensures that during the pressure of a real incident, the response team doesn't have to figure out communication logistics from scratch, reducing delays and the chance of key stakeholders being missed."},{"text":"It eliminates the need for anyone in the organization to be on call outside of normal business hours","correct":false,"why":"A communication matrix defines who to contact and how, but it does not eliminate the underlying need for on-call coverage to actually respond to incidents that occur outside business hours."},{"text":"It guarantees that no future incident will ever be classified as critical severity going forward","correct":false,"why":"A communication plan defines how to respond to incidents of any severity, including critical ones; it does not influence or reduce the actual severity classification of an incident that occurs."},{"text":"It replaces the need for a documented containment and eradication process during a real incident","correct":false,"why":"A communication plan addresses notification and escalation; it is a separate component from the technical containment and eradication procedures, which are still required regardless of how well communication is planned."}],"id":"q488","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"3.2","objective":"3.0","objectiveName":"Incident Response and Management","topic":"IR Process (Detection Method)","q":"One security incident is discovered when an EDR platform automatically flags a known malicious file hash on an endpoint. A second, unrelated incident is discovered only after a threat hunter notices an employee account authenticating from two geographically distant locations within an implausibly short time window, a pattern with no predefined rule. What distinguishes how these two incidents were detected?","options":[{"text":"The first was detected through signature-based detection; the second was detected through anomaly-based (behavioral) analysis","correct":true,"why":"Matching a known malicious file hash is a classic signature-based detection method relying on a pre-existing indicator, while identifying an implausible travel pattern with no predefined rule is anomaly-based detection, relying on recognizing behavior that deviates from an established baseline rather than matching a known signature."},{"text":"Both incidents were detected using identical signature-based detection methods run by the same platform","correct":false,"why":"The second incident had no predefined signature or rule triggering it; it was identified through behavioral analysis of an unusual pattern, which is fundamentally different from matching a known malicious indicator."},{"text":"The first was detected through digital forensics, while the second was detected through a penetration test engagement","correct":false,"why":"Neither scenario describes a forensic investigation of already-collected evidence or an authorized simulated attack; both describe real-time detection methods (signature matching and behavioral anomaly detection), not forensics or pen testing."},{"text":"Both incidents were discovered purely by chance, with no detection technology involved in either case","correct":false,"why":"Both incidents involved specific detection mechanisms, either an automated EDR signature match or a threat hunter's behavioral analysis; neither was a random, technology-free discovery."}],"id":"q489","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A newly formed security governance committee is deciding whether it should be responsible for approving individual firewall rule changes on a daily basis, or whether it should instead focus on approving the overall network security architecture and policy while delegating rule-level changes to the network operations team. Which approach reflects appropriate governance-level scope?","options":[{"text":"The committee should focus on approving architecture and policy, delegating day-to-day rule changes to operations","correct":true,"why":"Governance bodies are meant to provide strategic oversight and policy direction rather than perform tactical, high-volume operational tasks; approving every individual firewall rule change would overwhelm the committee and blur the distinction between governance and operations."},{"text":"The committee should personally approve every individual firewall rule change to maintain maximum control","correct":false,"why":"Requiring a governance committee to approve every low-level operational change is impractical at scale and conflates governance's strategic oversight role with the tactical execution responsibilities that belong to operations."},{"text":"The committee should have no involvement in network security decisions at all","correct":false,"why":"Governance still needs to set the overall policy and architectural direction that guides network security decisions; having no involvement at all would leave the organization without strategic oversight of this critical area."},{"text":"The committee should dissolve itself and let each engineer set their own individual security policy","correct":false,"why":"Allowing individual engineers to independently set their own policies removes consistent organizational oversight and direction entirely, which defeats the purpose of having a governance function."}],"id":"q490","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"An organization's data governance council includes representatives from legal, IT, compliance, and business units, and meets monthly to make decisions about data classification standards, retention rules, and access policies affecting the whole organization. What is the PRIMARY reason for including representatives from multiple different functions rather than having IT make these decisions alone?","options":[{"text":"Data governance decisions affect legal, regulatory, and business considerations beyond pure technical implementation, so cross-functional input leads to more complete and defensible decisions","correct":true,"why":"Decisions like data classification and retention rules have legal, regulatory, and business impact well beyond technical feasibility; involving legal, compliance, and business stakeholders ensures those dimensions are properly considered rather than having decisions made in a purely technical vacuum."},{"text":"IT staff are simply not permitted to make any decisions about organizational data whatsoever under any circumstances at all, according to this view","correct":false,"why":"IT is typically a core participant in data governance decisions, not excluded from them; the point of a cross-functional council is broader representation, not the exclusion of IT."},{"text":"Having more people present in the monthly council meeting simply guarantees that decisions will always be made much faster overall than with fewer people","correct":false,"why":"Cross-functional governance bodies with more stakeholders often take longer to reach consensus than a single team acting alone; the benefit is more complete and well-rounded decisions, not speed."},{"text":"Legal and compliance representatives are only present in the council meeting to take notes for the official minutes, and nothing more than that","correct":false,"why":"Legal and compliance representatives on a data governance council serve as substantive decision-making stakeholders bringing essential regulatory and legal perspective, not administrative note-takers."}],"id":"q491","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"An organization discovers during an internal review that its written security policies reference a 'Data Protection Officer' role that was eliminated in a reorganization two years ago, and several procedures still point to systems that have since been decommissioned. What governance failure does this MOST clearly illustrate?","options":[{"text":"A lack of a process to keep governance documentation synchronized with organizational and technical changes over time","correct":true,"why":"Governance documents like policies and procedures need a defined process to be updated whenever the organization changes, whether that's a role being eliminated or a system being decommissioned; without that upkeep process, documentation drifts out of sync with reality, as demonstrated here."},{"text":"A missing multi-factor authentication requirement that was never implemented across the organization's systems","correct":false,"why":"Multi-factor authentication is a specific technical access control; the issue described is about outdated governance documentation referencing eliminated roles and decommissioned systems, which is a document maintenance failure, not an authentication gap."},{"text":"An improperly configured firewall rule that was left open on a production network segment","correct":false,"why":"A firewall misconfiguration is a technical network security issue; it is unrelated to written policy and procedure documents referencing roles and systems that no longer exist."},{"text":"A missing disaster recovery site that the organization never established for its critical systems","correct":false,"why":"A disaster recovery site relates to business continuity infrastructure; it has no connection to the scenario, which is specifically about stale, unmaintained governance documentation."}],"id":"q492","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A security policy states that access to the customer database requires manager approval, but an audit reveals that for the past year, approvals have been granted verbally and never logged or documented anywhere. What governance gap does this represent?","options":[{"text":"A lack of enforceable, auditable evidence that the required approval control is actually being followed","correct":true,"why":"A policy requirement is only meaningfully enforced if compliance can be demonstrated and audited; verbal, undocumented approvals leave no evidence trail, making it impossible to verify the control was actually applied consistently, which undermines the entire point of having the requirement."},{"text":"An issue with the physical security of the server room where the customer database is hosted","correct":false,"why":"This scenario is about undocumented approval decisions for database access, which is a process and audit trail issue, not a physical security concern about server room access."},{"text":"A weakness in the organization's encryption algorithm selection for data stored in the database","correct":false,"why":"Encryption algorithm choice is a distinct technical control; the gap described is specifically about the lack of documented evidence for an approval process, unrelated to cryptography."},{"text":"A failure to patch a known vulnerability affecting the customer database application","correct":false,"why":"Patch management concerns remediating known software vulnerabilities; it is unrelated to the described gap in documenting and auditing manager approvals for database access."}],"id":"q493","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"After a significant security incident, a post-incident review determines that a key control failure went undetected for months because no one in the organization was formally accountable for monitoring that specific control's effectiveness. What governance concept was missing that would have prevented this gap?","options":[{"text":"Clearly assigned roles and responsibilities, including a designated control owner accountable for monitoring its ongoing effectiveness","correct":true,"why":"Effective governance requires that every significant control have a clearly designated owner responsible for monitoring it; without that explicit accountability, gaps like this one can persist unnoticed for extended periods since no single person is tasked with catching them."},{"text":"A stronger password complexity requirement enforced across all employee accounts in the organization","correct":false,"why":"Password complexity is a specific technical control; the root gap described here is about accountability and ownership for monitoring control effectiveness broadly, not a password policy weakness."},{"text":"A larger physical security budget allocated to guards and access control at company facilities","correct":false,"why":"Physical security budget has no bearing on this scenario, which concerns a lack of assigned accountability for monitoring a control's effectiveness, an organizational governance issue rather than a funding issue."},{"text":"A faster internet connection provisioned for the SOC team's monitoring and analysis workstations","correct":false,"why":"Network bandwidth is unrelated to the described governance failure, which is about the absence of a clearly accountable owner for monitoring a specific control over time."}],"id":"q494","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A CISO wants to demonstrate to the board that the organization's security governance program is not just a set of static documents but an active, functioning process. Which piece of evidence would BEST support this claim?","options":[{"text":"Records showing regular policy reviews, tracked exceptions with expiration dates, and documented governance committee meeting decisions over time","correct":true,"why":"Ongoing, dated records of policy reviews, tracked and time-bound exceptions, and documented committee decisions demonstrate that governance is an active, continuously functioning process rather than a one-time document creation exercise, which is exactly the evidence needed to support this claim."},{"text":"A single printed copy of the original security policy document from five years ago, kept in a binder in someone's desk drawer","correct":false,"why":"A static, unrevised document from years ago is actually evidence against an active governance process; it doesn't demonstrate any ongoing review, decision-making, or adaptation over time."},{"text":"The total number of employees currently working at the company across all departments, offices, and geographic locations","correct":false,"why":"Headcount has no bearing on whether a governance program is actively functioning; it is an unrelated organizational statistic, not evidence of governance activity."},{"text":"A list of every software vendor the company has ever purchased a product or license from throughout its entire history","correct":false,"why":"A vendor purchase history does not demonstrate whether governance processes like policy review, exception tracking, or committee decision-making are actively occurring."}],"id":"q495","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"An organization is deciding between a centralized governance model, where a single corporate security team sets and enforces policy across all business units, and a decentralized model, where each business unit sets its own security policy independently. A large, highly diversified conglomerate with very different regulatory environments across its divisions is evaluating which model fits best. What is the KEY tradeoff to consider?","options":[{"text":"Centralized governance offers more consistency and easier oversight, while decentralized governance allows more flexibility to address each division's unique regulatory and operational needs, at the cost of overall consistency","correct":true,"why":"This is the fundamental tradeoff between the two models: centralization provides uniform standards and simpler enterprise-wide oversight, while decentralization allows each division to tailor policy to its specific regulatory and business context, but at the cost of consistency and potentially harder enterprise-wide risk visibility."},{"text":"There is no meaningful practical difference at all between centralized and decentralized governance models in any real-world organizational scenario whatsoever, according to this flawed view","correct":false,"why":"Centralized and decentralized governance models have genuinely different strengths and weaknesses around consistency, oversight, and flexibility, making the choice a meaningful strategic decision rather than one with no real difference."},{"text":"Centralized governance is legally prohibited for conglomerates that operate across multiple distinct regulatory environments and jurisdictions worldwide, which is not actually true","correct":false,"why":"There is no legal prohibition on centralized governance for diversified conglomerates; many large organizations successfully use centralized models, though it may require careful accommodation of differing regulatory requirements across divisions."},{"text":"Decentralized governance always results in meaningfully lower overall security costs, regardless of the organization size, structure, or industry it operates within","correct":false,"why":"Decentralized governance can actually increase overall costs due to duplicated effort, inconsistent tooling, and redundant processes across business units, so lower cost is not a guaranteed or inherent outcome of this model."}],"id":"q496","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A company's executive sponsor for the security program actively champions security initiatives in leadership meetings, secures budget approval, and ensures security is considered in major business decisions. What is the PRIMARY value this executive sponsor role provides to the organization's security governance?","options":[{"text":"It ensures security has visibility, authority, and resourcing at the highest organizational levels, rather than being siloed as a purely technical concern","correct":true,"why":"An engaged executive sponsor elevates security from being viewed as a narrow technical function to being treated as a genuine business priority with the organizational authority and budget needed to be effective, which is difficult to achieve without high-level sponsorship."},{"text":"It eliminates the need for a dedicated security team to perform any hands-on technical work at all going forward","correct":false,"why":"An executive sponsor provides organizational backing and resourcing; they do not perform or replace the hands-on technical work still required from the dedicated security team."},{"text":"It guarantees that the organization will never experience a security incident of any kind ever again going forward","correct":false,"why":"No level of executive sponsorship can guarantee the complete prevention of security incidents; its value is in ensuring the security program has adequate support, visibility, and resources, not in providing an absolute guarantee against all risk."},{"text":"It replaces the organization's need to maintain a documented, up-to-date risk register altogether once sponsorship exists","correct":false,"why":"Executive sponsorship supports the security program's authority and resourcing; it does not replace the actual operational documentation, such as a risk register, needed to track and manage identified risks."}],"id":"q497","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"Following a major security incident that revealed several governance gaps, including unclear ownership of key controls and outdated policies, the organization commits to a formal review of its entire governance structure. What should this review PRIMARILY focus on?","options":[{"text":"Identifying and correcting the specific structural and procedural gaps that contributed to the incident, and updating governance documentation and ownership accordingly","correct":true,"why":"A post-incident governance review should directly address the specific weaknesses that were exposed, such as unclear control ownership and outdated policy, translating the incident's lessons into concrete governance structure and documentation improvements rather than a generic, unfocused review."},{"text":"Firing every single employee who happened to be working at the company at the exact time the incident occurred, regardless of their actual role","correct":false,"why":"A governance review should focus on structural and procedural improvements rather than punitive staffing actions; a blame-focused response does not address the actual root governance gaps that allowed the incident to occur."},{"text":"Purchasing new office furniture and equipment for the security team's workspace, break room, and shared meeting rooms across the building","correct":false,"why":"Physical office amenities have no relationship to correcting governance structure gaps like unclear control ownership or outdated policy documentation."},{"text":"Discontinuing all governance activities entirely since the previous organizational structure was found to have failed during the incident","correct":false,"why":"Abandoning governance entirely in response to identified gaps would leave the organization with even less oversight and structure; the appropriate response is to correct and strengthen the existing governance framework, not eliminate it."}],"id":"q498","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A mid-sized company's only security policy document is a single page stating 'employees must act securely,' with no supporting standards, procedures, defined roles, or review process. Using a governance maturity model perspective, how would this organization's governance maturity BEST be described?","options":[{"text":"Initial or ad hoc maturity, characterized by minimal, vague documentation with no supporting structure or defined processes","correct":true,"why":"A single vague policy statement with no supporting standards, procedures, defined roles, or review cadence is characteristic of the lowest, most immature governance stage in common maturity models, where security governance exists in name only without real structure or enforcement mechanisms."},{"text":"Optimized maturity, since the single-page policy is simple and easy for employees to remember day to day","correct":false,"why":"Simplicity alone does not indicate governance maturity; optimized maturity involves well-defined, actively managed, and continuously improved processes with clear metrics, none of which are present in this bare, unsupported policy statement."},{"text":"Fully compliant maturity, since a written policy document technically exists somewhere in the company","correct":false,"why":"The mere existence of a document does not equate to meaningful compliance or maturity; without supporting standards, procedures, defined roles, and a review process, the policy provides little actual governance structure or enforceability."},{"text":"Governance maturity cannot be assessed at all without first conducting a full penetration test","correct":false,"why":"Governance maturity assessment evaluates the structure, documentation, and process maturity of the governance program itself; it does not require a penetration test, which is a separate technical testing activity focused on system vulnerabilities."}],"id":"q499","source":"original-2026-batch"},{"sub":"4.3","objective":"4.0","objectiveName":"Reporting and Communication","topic":"Governance","q":"A security governance framework assigns 'policy owner' responsibilities to specific individuals for each major policy, distinct from the 'control owner' responsible for implementing the technical measures the policy requires. Why is this distinction between policy ownership and control ownership useful?","options":[{"text":"It clarifies accountability at both the strategic (what is required) and operational (how it is implemented) levels, preventing gaps where no one feels responsible for either dimension","correct":true,"why":"Separating policy ownership (defining and maintaining what is required) from control ownership (implementing and maintaining the technical measures) ensures both the strategic requirement and its practical execution have clear, distinct accountability, preventing situations where each side assumes the other is responsible for a given gap."},{"text":"It ensures that only one single person in the entire organization can ever be held accountable for any security failure that occurs anywhere","correct":false,"why":"The distinction actually creates multiple points of clear accountability across different roles and responsibilities, rather than concentrating all accountability in a single individual for every possible failure."},{"text":"It removes the need for any technical staff to be involved at all in actually implementing the required security measures day to day","correct":false,"why":"Control owners are specifically the individuals responsible for the technical implementation of security requirements; this distinction does not remove technical staff from the process, it clarifies their specific role within it."},{"text":"It is purely an internal naming convention with no practical impact whatsoever on how the organization actually operates on a daily basis","correct":false,"why":"This distinction has real practical impact on accountability and gap prevention, as described; it is not merely a naming convention without operational consequence."}],"id":"q500","source":"original-2026-batch"}];
